WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.100
[Amit Varma]: One thing I have learnt while doing this show is how constrained our vision can be.

00:00:09.100 --> 00:00:11.660
[Amit Varma]: They say where you stand depends on where you sit.

00:00:11.660 --> 00:00:13.300
[Amit Varma]: And we may need to watch out for that.

00:00:13.300 --> 00:00:15.660
[Amit Varma]: We are products of our time and circumstance.

00:00:15.660 --> 00:00:19.880
[Amit Varma]: So I may look around at the people around me, fall for selection bias, and think this

00:00:19.880 --> 00:00:20.880
[Amit Varma]: is the world.

00:00:20.880 --> 00:00:23.220
[Amit Varma]: Or I may look further and see a bit more.

00:00:23.220 --> 00:00:25.520
[Amit Varma]: I may be informed by books or movies.

00:00:25.520 --> 00:00:29.840
[Amit Varma]: But to truly get a picture of the world where everything is now interconnected, I need to

00:00:29.840 --> 00:00:34.640
[Amit Varma]: travel not only through geography and look outside of my own setting, but also through

00:00:34.640 --> 00:00:35.640
[Amit Varma]: time.

00:00:35.640 --> 00:00:39.680
[Amit Varma]: The world as it is now has been shaped by everything that came before and everything

00:00:39.680 --> 00:00:40.960
[Amit Varma]: that exists elsewhere.

00:00:40.960 --> 00:00:44.860
[Amit Varma]: Reality, in a sense, is everything everywhere all at once.

00:00:44.860 --> 00:00:48.500
[Amit Varma]: So to understand the full sweep of any subject is impossible.

00:00:48.500 --> 00:00:49.760
[Amit Varma]: Is the effort worth making?

00:00:49.760 --> 00:00:50.840
[Amit Varma]: Yes, it is.

00:00:50.840 --> 00:00:56.080
[Amit Varma]: We understand because some brave soul took one for the team and made the effort of gathering

00:00:56.080 --> 00:01:01.480
[Amit Varma]: dots and joining them.

00:01:01.480 --> 00:01:06.680
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioural

00:01:06.680 --> 00:01:07.680
[Unknown]: science.

00:01:07.680 --> 00:01:14.280
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:14.280 --> 00:01:15.460
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen.

00:01:15.460 --> 00:01:19.640
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is Alice Evans, who teaches at the King's College in London, is a faculty

00:01:19.640 --> 00:01:23.880
[Amit Varma]: associate at the Centre for International Development at Harvard, and is writing a grand

00:01:23.880 --> 00:01:26.900
[Amit Varma]: book called The Great Gender Divergence.

00:01:26.900 --> 00:01:32.240
[Amit Varma]: She looks across time and space to examine, in her words, quote, the origins and evolution

00:01:32.240 --> 00:01:37.600
[Amit Varma]: of patriarchy, the drivers of gender equality and regional variations, stop quote.

00:01:37.600 --> 00:01:42.280
[Amit Varma]: She tries to understand the local factors at play that are causing different parts of

00:01:42.280 --> 00:01:47.480
[Amit Varma]: the world to move towards gender equality at a different pace, as well as a global current

00:01:47.480 --> 00:01:48.820
[Amit Varma]: should affect us all.

00:01:48.820 --> 00:01:54.280
[Amit Varma]: She takes an interdisciplinary approach, brings prisms from many fields, and is unafraid to

00:01:54.280 --> 00:01:57.320
[Amit Varma]: question conventions, or indeed to question her own priors.

00:01:57.320 --> 00:02:00.400
[Amit Varma]: Her podcast is called Rocking Our Priors.

00:02:00.400 --> 00:02:03.680
[Amit Varma]: She also uses Twitter in interesting and bold ways.

00:02:03.680 --> 00:02:08.480
[Amit Varma]: She not only writes about her work, but she also thinks aloud, asks questions, engages

00:02:08.480 --> 00:02:09.680
[Amit Varma]: in dialogue.

00:02:09.680 --> 00:02:13.360
[Amit Varma]: And this conversation that you will hear now is eye-opening on its own.

00:02:13.360 --> 00:02:18.800
[Amit Varma]: But it's also, in my view, part of a longer conversation that she has had across various

00:02:18.800 --> 00:02:24.920
[Amit Varma]: fora and part of a longer conversation that I have had across episodes with many experts

00:02:24.920 --> 00:02:25.920
[Amit Varma]: on gender.

00:02:25.920 --> 00:02:28.520
[Amit Varma]: I will link all those episodes in the show notes.

00:02:28.520 --> 00:02:33.340
[Amit Varma]: That's why I get to learn so much over time by having conversations like this.

00:02:33.340 --> 00:02:38.680
[Amit Varma]: Before we begin this one, though, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:02:38.680 --> 00:02:41.760
[Amit Varma]: Have you always wanted to be a writer but never quite gotten down to it?

00:02:41.760 --> 00:02:43.160
[Amit Varma]: Well, I'd love to help you.

00:02:43.160 --> 00:02:48.040
[Amit Varma]: Since April 2020, I've taught 20 cohorts of my online course, The Art of Clear Writing,

00:02:48.040 --> 00:02:51.200
[Amit Varma]: and online community has now sprung up of all my past students.

00:02:51.200 --> 00:02:55.560
[Amit Varma]: We have workshops, a newsletter to showcase the work of students, and vibrant community

00:02:55.560 --> 00:02:56.560
[Amit Varma]: interaction.

00:02:56.560 --> 00:03:00.640
[Amit Varma]: In the course itself, through four webinars spread over four weekends, I share all I know

00:03:00.640 --> 00:03:02.840
[Amit Varma]: about the craft and practice of clear writing.

00:03:02.840 --> 00:03:06.800
[Amit Varma]: There are many exercises, much interaction, a lovely and lively community at the end of

00:03:06.800 --> 00:03:07.800
[Amit Varma]: it.

00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:11.840
[Amit Varma]: The course costs Rs. 10,000 plus GST, or about $150, and is a monthly thing.

00:03:11.840 --> 00:03:16.760
[Amit Varma]: So if you're interested, head on over to register at indiauncut.com slash clearwriting.

00:03:16.760 --> 00:03:24.360
[Amit Varma]: Being a good writer doesn't require God-given talent, just the willingness to work hard

00:03:24.360 --> 00:03:27.920
[Amit Varma]: and a clear idea of what you need to do to refine your skills.

00:03:27.920 --> 00:03:28.920
[Amit Varma]: I can help you.

00:03:28.920 --> 00:03:32.280
[Amit Varma]: Alice, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:03:32.280 --> 00:03:33.280
[Guest]: Thank you for having me.

00:03:33.280 --> 00:03:34.280
[Guest]: This is a real joy.

00:03:34.280 --> 00:03:35.280
[Guest]: I'm excited.

00:03:35.280 --> 00:03:38.640
[Amit Varma]: You know, when I met you earlier, we were both at this conference in Udaipur.

00:03:38.640 --> 00:03:42.440
[Amit Varma]: And the first thought that struck me, and I told you this, was that you are the most

00:03:42.440 --> 00:03:44.680
[Amit Varma]: energetic person I have ever met.

00:03:44.680 --> 00:03:47.320
[Amit Varma]: You were just bouncing off the walls.

00:03:47.320 --> 00:03:48.820
[Amit Varma]: And I'm kind of the opposite.

00:03:48.820 --> 00:03:53.800
[Amit Varma]: So I've often had this contrast with my guests, where, you know, the contrast, very often,

00:03:53.800 --> 00:03:57.800
[Amit Varma]: the most common place for the contrast is that I tend to be pessimistic, and my guests

00:03:57.800 --> 00:04:00.280
[Amit Varma]: tend to be optimistic, and so on and so forth.

00:04:00.280 --> 00:04:03.800
[Amit Varma]: But here, I think it's a high energy, low energy contrast, especially because I've just

00:04:03.800 --> 00:04:06.300
[Amit Varma]: recovered from something which was just like COVID.

00:04:06.300 --> 00:04:10.320
[Amit Varma]: But I kept testing negative, which was really irritating, because I mean, I didn't want

00:04:10.320 --> 00:04:11.320
[Amit Varma]: it to be COVID.

00:04:11.320 --> 00:04:13.920
[Amit Varma]: But what the hell was it, you really want to know.

00:04:13.920 --> 00:04:17.720
[Amit Varma]: So the last few days, I've been feeling a little low on energy.

00:04:17.720 --> 00:04:22.420
[Amit Varma]: But it's really great, I think, therefore, that I'm starting my series of recordings

00:04:22.420 --> 00:04:23.880
[Amit Varma]: in Delhi with you.

00:04:23.880 --> 00:04:27.780
[Amit Varma]: Because hopefully, you can inject some of your energy into me and we can everything

00:04:27.780 --> 00:04:29.680
[Amit Varma]: can start off well that way.

00:04:29.680 --> 00:04:37.560
[Amit Varma]: I want to start by asking about your enthusiasm for life, which is a sort of a separate thing

00:04:37.560 --> 00:04:39.120
[Amit Varma]: from energy.

00:04:39.120 --> 00:04:44.200
[Amit Varma]: But you are always rushing to talk to people find out new things, even when you post things

00:04:44.200 --> 00:04:49.080
[Amit Varma]: on Twitter, you're asking for criticism, and you mean it, you know, what I've noticed

00:04:49.080 --> 00:04:52.560
[Amit Varma]: about you is that, you know, earlier, before we started recording, you were saying you

00:04:52.560 --> 00:04:55.480
[Amit Varma]: don't feel things like jealousy and all those petty things.

00:04:55.480 --> 00:05:00.760
[Amit Varma]: But what I noticed is that there's an there's that absence of ego also, where you're perfectly

00:05:00.760 --> 00:05:04.320
[Amit Varma]: happy for someone to tell you that you're wrong about something if they're doing it

00:05:04.320 --> 00:05:08.520
[Amit Varma]: in good faith, and you go out of your way to kind of solicit that.

00:05:08.520 --> 00:05:14.920
[Amit Varma]: So tell me how you sort of came to this approach, like what were you as a kid, you know, when

00:05:14.920 --> 00:05:15.920
[Amit Varma]: you were 11?

00:05:15.920 --> 00:05:18.040
[Amit Varma]: Were you also like bouncing off walls?

00:05:18.040 --> 00:05:22.080
[Amit Varma]: And you also mentioned you've never fallen sick in your life, you've traveled through

00:05:22.080 --> 00:05:24.200
[Amit Varma]: India and never got the loosies.

00:05:24.200 --> 00:05:28.760
[Amit Varma]: So so tell me a little bit about the young Alice and as you're growing up, and what made

00:05:28.760 --> 00:05:35.720
[Amit Varma]: you you know, not become an Olympic athlete, but instead, come towards wherever you are.

00:05:35.720 --> 00:05:41.600
[Guest]: Okay, I think that I'm jolly and upbeat, maybe for three reasons.

00:05:41.600 --> 00:05:44.760
[Guest]: And let me summarize those before we go into my childhood.

00:05:44.760 --> 00:05:47.480
[Guest]: One is age 17.

00:05:47.480 --> 00:05:54.680
[Guest]: After a number of adversities, I mean, I taught myself how to become happy, I thought, I need

00:05:54.680 --> 00:05:59.560
[Guest]: to identify and work out what makes me happy and to pursue it, regardless of what other

00:05:59.560 --> 00:06:03.120
[Guest]: people say, because yes, there'll always be criticism, but I need to pursue what makes

00:06:03.120 --> 00:06:04.480
[Guest]: me happy.

00:06:04.480 --> 00:06:08.920
[Guest]: And then I also thought to myself, I need to celebrate every single victory, you know,

00:06:08.920 --> 00:06:12.200
[Guest]: so often we're on this ladder, and we're always looking up, you know, we're climbing up the

00:06:12.200 --> 00:06:14.800
[Guest]: mountain, and we're looking at how far we have to climb.

00:06:14.800 --> 00:06:18.080
[Guest]: And what I need to do is celebrate every accomplishment.

00:06:18.080 --> 00:06:20.760
[Guest]: So that's one aspect of teaching myself how to become happy.

00:06:20.760 --> 00:06:22.240
[Guest]: And I always see the silver lining.

00:06:22.240 --> 00:06:23.720
[Guest]: Now it just comes naturally.

00:06:23.720 --> 00:06:32.520
[Guest]: A second aspect is that what enables me to be happy is that I've emancipated and liberated

00:06:32.520 --> 00:06:38.280
[Guest]: myself from people who might try to confine me, from gatekeepers who would support a very

00:06:38.280 --> 00:06:39.440
[Guest]: narrow objective.

00:06:39.440 --> 00:06:43.200
[Guest]: Now I do what I love, and I pursue it, you know, I love my project.

00:06:43.200 --> 00:06:48.040
[Guest]: I think the great gender divergence is the most fundamental fact about humanity that

00:06:48.040 --> 00:06:49.200
[Guest]: we cannot answer.

00:06:49.200 --> 00:06:53.480
[Guest]: And I've got this tremendous curiosity to find out the answer, and I jump out of bed

00:06:53.480 --> 00:06:55.960
[Guest]: every day excited to know the answer.

00:06:55.960 --> 00:06:58.840
[Guest]: And I will look through every single piece of evidence so I can work that out.

00:06:58.840 --> 00:07:02.640
[Guest]: So that's the second part, this curiosity about the world.

00:07:02.640 --> 00:07:10.920
[Guest]: And then I'd say the third part is some of the adversities that I have overcome.

00:07:10.920 --> 00:07:12.960
[Guest]: And I can share these with you now.

00:07:12.960 --> 00:07:13.960
[Guest]: Yeah?

00:07:13.960 --> 00:07:14.960
[Guest]: Okay.

00:07:14.960 --> 00:07:19.480
[Guest]: So I was born to great economic privilege, right?

00:07:19.480 --> 00:07:23.160
[Guest]: My parents, you know, were professionals.

00:07:23.160 --> 00:07:28.920
[Guest]: We lived in a lovely house, big garden, went to a very nice school, very well educated.

00:07:28.920 --> 00:07:34.520
[Guest]: But then age 10, my father decided he was bored of family life.

00:07:34.520 --> 00:07:39.520
[Guest]: He went off on motorbikes, holidays, sailing, and he basically abandoned us.

00:07:39.520 --> 00:07:44.200
[Guest]: We had no idea where he was for several years, really, we just had no clue.

00:07:44.200 --> 00:07:47.520
[Guest]: But my mother, my mother persevered, she was a lawyer.

00:07:47.520 --> 00:07:50.440
[Guest]: And one Christmas, he invited his entire family over.

00:07:50.440 --> 00:07:54.080
[Guest]: We cooked, we cleaned, we waited on them hand and foot.

00:07:54.080 --> 00:07:58.760
[Guest]: We disappeared after the Christmas, he came back, he issued divorce proceedings.

00:07:58.760 --> 00:07:59.760
[Guest]: And I was delighted.

00:07:59.760 --> 00:08:03.040
[Guest]: I mean, he was this hot tempered bully.

00:08:03.040 --> 00:08:04.400
[Guest]: He was ex-army.

00:08:04.400 --> 00:08:08.520
[Guest]: He would just, you know, shout and bully and scold.

00:08:08.520 --> 00:08:09.680
[Guest]: He was a nasty man.

00:08:09.680 --> 00:08:13.560
[Guest]: He was even fired from one of his jobs because he was too aggressive.

00:08:13.560 --> 00:08:17.600
[Guest]: So when he announced these divorce proceedings, I thought this was the most fantastic thing

00:08:17.600 --> 00:08:18.600
[Guest]: in the world.

00:08:18.600 --> 00:08:25.600
[Guest]: And then there's a saying in Urdu, the major fights and struggles and problems in life

00:08:25.600 --> 00:08:28.400
[Guest]: over wealth, women and property.

00:08:28.400 --> 00:08:30.240
[Guest]: And that was certainly the issue for my father.

00:08:30.240 --> 00:08:34.560
[Guest]: So when there were the court proceedings, my mother got a share of the house.

00:08:34.560 --> 00:08:35.680
[Guest]: My father resented that.

00:08:35.680 --> 00:08:40.240
[Guest]: He bitterly resented the amount of money she got over dividing the property.

00:08:40.240 --> 00:08:41.820
[Guest]: And then he was fueled with venom.

00:08:41.820 --> 00:08:45.360
[Guest]: He never gave any money in financial support to my mother.

00:08:45.360 --> 00:08:50.040
[Guest]: And every time my brother went to visit my father, he would return that weekend with

00:08:50.040 --> 00:08:54.760
[Guest]: this poisonous venom and hatred against my mother that my father had instilled.

00:08:54.760 --> 00:08:59.160
[Guest]: And I didn't want anything to do with my father, to be honest.

00:08:59.160 --> 00:09:01.040
[Guest]: And I distanced myself from him.

00:09:01.040 --> 00:09:05.040
[Guest]: And every time we went to pick up my brother, my father would be abusive to my mother.

00:09:05.040 --> 00:09:06.200
[Guest]: He would treat her with contempt.

00:09:06.200 --> 00:09:07.680
[Guest]: He would not allow her in.

00:09:07.680 --> 00:09:14.400
[Guest]: And yet my mother, she always wanted to be polite, to be, you know, to maintain the moral

00:09:14.400 --> 00:09:20.360
[Guest]: high ground, you know, to whatever they say to us, we'll be polite and we'll be courteous.

00:09:20.360 --> 00:09:26.160
[Guest]: And so she was saddled with two kids in this economically privileged environment.

00:09:26.160 --> 00:09:29.160
[Guest]: I went to the same school as Shahrukh Khan's son.

00:09:29.160 --> 00:09:30.880
[Unknown]: So a very nice school, very nice.

00:09:30.880 --> 00:09:32.560
[Guest]: That's my India connection early on.

00:09:32.560 --> 00:09:35.360
[Guest]: So we went to this very nice school and my mother was worried financially, but she worked

00:09:35.360 --> 00:09:36.360
[Guest]: incredibly hard.

00:09:36.360 --> 00:09:40.120
[Guest]: I didn't realize at the time, but her field is very male dominated, international financial

00:09:40.120 --> 00:09:41.120
[Guest]: law.

00:09:41.120 --> 00:09:45.280
[Guest]: She was an entrepreneur, incredibly successful, and she made sure we had absolutely everything.

00:09:45.280 --> 00:09:47.160
[Guest]: So she worked very long hours.

00:09:47.160 --> 00:09:48.540
[Guest]: She was economically independent.

00:09:48.540 --> 00:09:50.400
[Guest]: She was focused on work.

00:09:50.400 --> 00:09:55.360
[Guest]: And I think through that, I realized the importance of pursuing my studies.

00:09:55.360 --> 00:09:58.760
[Guest]: You know, marriage would be weak insurance for me.

00:09:58.760 --> 00:10:01.720
[Guest]: I was going to make sure I was totally fine.

00:10:01.720 --> 00:10:05.080
[Guest]: And she and she, she was incredibly entrepreneurial.

00:10:05.080 --> 00:10:08.160
[Guest]: She bought this ramshackle house in a nice environment.

00:10:08.160 --> 00:10:09.160
[Guest]: She did it up.

00:10:09.160 --> 00:10:10.220
[Guest]: She made it spectacular.

00:10:10.220 --> 00:10:11.220
[Guest]: She made it magnificent.

00:10:11.220 --> 00:10:14.040
[Guest]: We had absolutely everything we could ever want.

00:10:14.040 --> 00:10:18.240
[Guest]: And so and I benefited from that great education, just as I'm sure Shahrukh Khan's son did.

00:10:18.240 --> 00:10:19.720
[Guest]: And so I went to debate clubs.

00:10:19.720 --> 00:10:21.280
[Guest]: I was, you know, discussing literature.

00:10:21.280 --> 00:10:24.040
[Guest]: I was really interested in philosophy and history.

00:10:24.040 --> 00:10:26.320
[Guest]: I was winning academic prizes.

00:10:26.320 --> 00:10:27.880
[Guest]: I was successful at school.

00:10:27.880 --> 00:10:29.120
[Guest]: I was chirpy at school.

00:10:29.120 --> 00:10:30.840
[Guest]: I mean, you ask about my cheerfulness.

00:10:30.840 --> 00:10:35.240
[Guest]: I was jolly and playful and, you know, was one of the popular kids.

00:10:35.240 --> 00:10:37.040
[Guest]: I had the parties were at my house.

00:10:37.040 --> 00:10:40.520
[Guest]: You know, I was fun and outgoing.

00:10:40.520 --> 00:10:45.280
[Guest]: That said, my brother always wanted to see my father.

00:10:45.280 --> 00:10:48.260
[Guest]: And he was sort of treated as the golden boy.

00:10:48.260 --> 00:10:49.400
[Guest]: And I never did.

00:10:49.400 --> 00:10:51.400
[Guest]: And yet I was always pushed to spend time with him.

00:10:51.400 --> 00:10:54.920
[Guest]: You know, my mother wanted to make things normal for my brother, wanted to thought it

00:10:54.920 --> 00:10:58.760
[Guest]: was thought that family mattered and we should spend time with our family.

00:10:58.760 --> 00:11:02.280
[Guest]: And so like, for example, I was pushed to go on holidays with him.

00:11:02.280 --> 00:11:05.440
[Guest]: And the following year, I would be so upset and cross about that because my father was

00:11:05.440 --> 00:11:07.820
[Guest]: a bully and horrific that the next year I wasn't good.

00:11:07.820 --> 00:11:11.600
[Guest]: But I was pushed, you know, for the sake of my brother, that my brother's welfare was

00:11:11.600 --> 00:11:12.600
[Guest]: prioritised.

00:11:12.600 --> 00:11:18.080
[Guest]: Anyway, so at school, I did well.

00:11:18.080 --> 00:11:24.440
[Guest]: And then, but I was, you know, I was in a very, you know, to be critical of my childhood,

00:11:24.440 --> 00:11:29.760
[Guest]: I was in a very elitist parochial environment, you know, I surrounded by a bunch of rich

00:11:29.760 --> 00:11:30.760
[Guest]: other kids.

00:11:30.760 --> 00:11:32.400
[Guest]: I had no clue about the rest of the world.

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:35.480
[Guest]: I was absolutely clueless, totally clueless.

00:11:35.480 --> 00:11:44.220
[Guest]: But anyway, so another important stage of my life was that age 16, I never had any periods.

00:11:44.220 --> 00:11:47.960
[Guest]: And so I went to the doctors to discuss this to understand what was going on.

00:11:47.960 --> 00:11:48.960
[Guest]: And they didn't know.

00:11:48.960 --> 00:11:54.440
[Guest]: They thought that everything externally was normal, but something wasn't happening.

00:11:54.440 --> 00:11:56.780
[Guest]: So they thought, well, maybe she just hasn't fully developed.

00:11:56.780 --> 00:11:59.100
[Guest]: Maybe she hasn't fully gone through puberty.

00:11:59.100 --> 00:12:04.280
[Guest]: So they gave me more progesterone and estrogen, even though the levels were totally normal.

00:12:04.280 --> 00:12:05.760
[Guest]: So they put me on the pill.

00:12:05.760 --> 00:12:06.760
[Guest]: That didn't work.

00:12:06.760 --> 00:12:12.360
[Guest]: So age 16, they doubled the dose, which I'm sure is a great thing to give a teenage girl.

00:12:12.360 --> 00:12:13.360
[Guest]: And then that didn't work.

00:12:13.360 --> 00:12:16.840
[Guest]: So they thought, well, let's bypass the digestive system.

00:12:16.840 --> 00:12:18.760
[Guest]: They put me on the patch pill.

00:12:18.760 --> 00:12:19.760
[Guest]: That didn't work.

00:12:19.760 --> 00:12:24.880
[Guest]: So anyway, so then they did a number of ultrasounds and they discovered I had only one kidney,

00:12:24.880 --> 00:12:28.020
[Guest]: only one ovary, no uterus, no vagina.

00:12:28.020 --> 00:12:30.320
[Guest]: This is a syndrome called Rokitansky.

00:12:30.320 --> 00:12:33.200
[Guest]: It affects one in 5,000 women.

00:12:33.200 --> 00:12:35.640
[Guest]: And the nurse told me, OK, so this is what you need to do.

00:12:35.640 --> 00:12:39.240
[Guest]: She highlighted, she showed me a series of plastic dilators.

00:12:39.240 --> 00:12:41.120
[Guest]: One is the size of your little finger.

00:12:41.120 --> 00:12:44.000
[Guest]: One is the size of a much larger.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:45.000
[Guest]: That was interesting.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:49.320
[Guest]: She just basically told, so I had what was like a cute, like a dimple.

00:12:49.320 --> 00:12:55.160
[Guest]: My vagina was like a dimple and you're basically supposed to ram these plastic dilators inside

00:12:55.160 --> 00:12:56.960
[Guest]: me to build my own vagina.

00:12:56.960 --> 00:13:01.800
[Guest]: And I think because of my childhood, having seen my mother being very pragmatic, you know,

00:13:01.800 --> 00:13:05.640
[Guest]: just dealing with things, getting the job done, you know, my mother never showed any

00:13:05.640 --> 00:13:06.860
[Guest]: weakness about my father.

00:13:06.860 --> 00:13:07.860
[Guest]: She never cried.

00:13:07.860 --> 00:13:10.280
[Guest]: I never saw her express despair.

00:13:10.280 --> 00:13:12.920
[Guest]: She's not a warm or she's not a warm or jolly person.

00:13:12.920 --> 00:13:14.200
[Guest]: She's pragmatic.

00:13:14.200 --> 00:13:16.960
[Guest]: And so I had that same approach when I discovered I had no vagina.

00:13:16.960 --> 00:13:19.480
[Guest]: I like here is the medical solution.

00:13:19.480 --> 00:13:20.680
[Guest]: This is what I need to do.

00:13:20.680 --> 00:13:22.920
[Guest]: So, you know, I do this therapy every night.

00:13:22.920 --> 00:13:26.880
[Guest]: It's incredibly painful, you know, tearing a hole in yourself.

00:13:26.880 --> 00:13:27.880
[Guest]: And but I did it.

00:13:27.880 --> 00:13:32.160
[Guest]: You know, I go to the three months later, I go to the nurse, she's like 2.2 centimetres.

00:13:32.160 --> 00:13:33.760
[Guest]: Six months later, 4.4 centimetres.

00:13:33.760 --> 00:13:34.760
[Guest]: Anyway, I did it.

00:13:34.760 --> 00:13:36.760
[Guest]: I made my own vagina.

00:13:36.760 --> 00:13:42.360
[Guest]: And then I went to some of the there was a use of the hospital where I was affiliated

00:13:42.360 --> 00:13:43.360
[Guest]: with in London.

00:13:43.360 --> 00:13:46.200
[Guest]: They organised an event for many women with the same condition.

00:13:46.200 --> 00:13:47.880
[Guest]: And we don't know the cause of this condition.

00:13:47.880 --> 00:13:52.240
[Guest]: So there were women in hijabs, women in hot pants, you know, all typically around like

00:13:52.240 --> 00:13:55.560
[Guest]: 17, 18, recently diagnosed.

00:13:55.560 --> 00:14:00.800
[Guest]: And I then realised that my response to this diagnosis was totally unusual.

00:14:00.800 --> 00:14:05.200
[Guest]: I mean, the rest of the women were depressed, traumatised, anxious, upset.

00:14:05.200 --> 00:14:06.880
[Guest]: You know, they felt like they weren't proper women.

00:14:06.880 --> 00:14:10.680
[Guest]: They didn't, you know, even though my even though externally I'm totally normal, even

00:14:10.680 --> 00:14:16.800
[Guest]: though my chromosomes totally normal for females, they felt they weren't proper women.

00:14:16.800 --> 00:14:19.440
[Guest]: They were incredibly distressed.

00:14:19.440 --> 00:14:26.080
[Guest]: And so what I did is I got up and I said, Hey, I'm Alice Evans, and I made my own vagina

00:14:26.080 --> 00:14:27.740
[Guest]: and you can too.

00:14:27.740 --> 00:14:33.760
[Guest]: And that's probably one of the my greatest, my greatest contributions to public welfare.

00:14:33.760 --> 00:14:38.960
[Guest]: Because after that, women, you know, contacted me, and they said, you've changed how I see

00:14:38.960 --> 00:14:42.480
[Guest]: myself, you know, for so long, and, you know, so long.

00:14:42.480 --> 00:14:47.520
[Guest]: And this is a broader point that whenever there is a stigma, whenever there is a taboo,

00:14:47.520 --> 00:14:51.720
[Guest]: people stay silent, and they stay ashamed, and they don't speak to people.

00:14:51.720 --> 00:14:54.880
[Guest]: And that can create that cultivates a negative feedback loop.

00:14:54.880 --> 00:14:58.540
[Guest]: Because people feel alone, they don't have the support, they feel bad in themselves.

00:14:58.540 --> 00:15:02.980
[Guest]: And that's just a mental construction, a repeat of beliefs and behaviour.

00:15:02.980 --> 00:15:05.840
[Guest]: So what I saw is me speaking out was a public good.

00:15:05.840 --> 00:15:10.280
[Guest]: So when I was at school, I would tell anyone who was interested, Hey, I have no vagina,

00:15:10.280 --> 00:15:11.280
[Guest]: but I made it.

00:15:11.280 --> 00:15:16.800
[Guest]: Because I thought people should know because if I can reach just one person, because it's

00:15:16.800 --> 00:15:20.160
[Guest]: not in 5000 women, it's not that rare, but it doesn't get discussed.

00:15:20.160 --> 00:15:23.480
[Guest]: So I went on BBC News about that, etc, etc.

00:15:23.480 --> 00:15:28.780
[Guest]: Around that same period, and this is just the week before I went to university, my father's

00:15:28.780 --> 00:15:31.400
[Guest]: ex girlfriend contacted me.

00:15:31.400 --> 00:15:33.440
[Guest]: And she said, How's your father?

00:15:33.440 --> 00:15:36.040
[Guest]: And I said, I don't know.

00:15:36.040 --> 00:15:37.040
[Guest]: She said, Well, how's his wife?

00:15:37.040 --> 00:15:39.800
[Guest]: Well, I said, I don't know about that either.

00:15:39.800 --> 00:15:44.800
[Guest]: So anyway, so she I asked my mother to drive me to the ex girlfriend's house.

00:15:44.800 --> 00:15:51.640
[Guest]: I discovered that my father had taken a BMW tour to Morocco, met a young woman a little

00:15:51.640 --> 00:15:56.640
[Guest]: bit older than me, from a poor part of Marrakesh living in a two room flat with her 10 brothers

00:15:56.640 --> 00:15:58.440
[Guest]: or whatever.

00:15:58.440 --> 00:16:05.520
[Guest]: And he converted to Islam, paid for her with sugar, chickens and olive oil.

00:16:05.520 --> 00:16:07.160
[Guest]: And she was going to come to England.

00:16:07.160 --> 00:16:12.500
[Guest]: The ex girlfriend also told me that while living with my father, my father had given

00:16:12.500 --> 00:16:14.920
[Guest]: her a black eye and ruptured her kidneys.

00:16:14.920 --> 00:16:18.680
[Guest]: Now, my father had never been physically violent to us.

00:16:18.680 --> 00:16:19.680
[Guest]: But I believe this.

00:16:19.680 --> 00:16:21.240
[Guest]: And I was given my father's history.

00:16:21.240 --> 00:16:22.240
[Guest]: I didn't think that was crazy.

00:16:22.240 --> 00:16:27.200
[Guest]: And my the ex girlfriend also told me that my father had stalked her.

00:16:27.200 --> 00:16:28.400
[Guest]: So I believe this.

00:16:28.400 --> 00:16:32.320
[Guest]: And I was really worried about this Moroccan woman, especially you know, she she didn't

00:16:32.320 --> 00:16:33.320
[Guest]: really speak English.

00:16:33.320 --> 00:16:39.760
[Guest]: But anyway, so they my Moroccan wife came over, subsequently met her, they had a child.

00:16:39.760 --> 00:16:41.520
[Guest]: Anyway, so that that's one issue.

00:16:41.520 --> 00:16:45.480
[Guest]: And then my father, but then oh, yes, so I'll give you a brief story about that.

00:16:45.480 --> 00:16:51.200
[Guest]: So they had they might they moved to France because land is cheaper there, I'm part French.

00:16:51.200 --> 00:16:53.280
[Guest]: Then they had a child together.

00:16:53.280 --> 00:16:57.640
[Guest]: But they were so incompatible, they called the child separate names.

00:16:57.640 --> 00:17:01.960
[Guest]: Then my father tells us, and I don't know if this is true, the Moroccan wife violently

00:17:01.960 --> 00:17:02.960
[Guest]: attacked him.

00:17:02.960 --> 00:17:06.240
[Guest]: He claims this is because she wanted a greater share of the divorce proceedings because she

00:17:06.240 --> 00:17:08.200
[Guest]: was trying to trigger violence in him.

00:17:08.200 --> 00:17:12.580
[Guest]: They had five custody battles because my father did not want to pay the maintenance to her.

00:17:12.580 --> 00:17:15.960
[Guest]: He did not want her to get the money, five custody battles over this child.

00:17:15.960 --> 00:17:18.480
[Guest]: And at one point, my father kidnapped the child.

00:17:18.480 --> 00:17:22.720
[Guest]: So she is in England, she moved back to England because she thought French people are racist

00:17:22.720 --> 00:17:24.440
[Guest]: and she wanted to live in England.

00:17:24.440 --> 00:17:27.960
[Guest]: She was a forget somewhere in England.

00:17:27.960 --> 00:17:32.520
[Guest]: Then the police knocked on the door of my mother's house at 2am and asked to search

00:17:32.520 --> 00:17:34.780
[Guest]: the property just in case the child was there.

00:17:34.780 --> 00:17:38.520
[Guest]: My father was apprehended at Portsmouth in England and my brother had to pay the bail

00:17:38.520 --> 00:17:39.520
[Guest]: of £5,000.

00:17:39.520 --> 00:17:41.480
[Guest]: Anyway, we can move on from that story.

00:17:41.480 --> 00:17:45.280
[Guest]: So that's just one, that's just one, you know, adventure.

00:17:45.280 --> 00:17:46.280
[Guest]: Shall I go on to the...

00:17:46.280 --> 00:17:47.280
[Guest]: So, so, okay.

00:17:47.280 --> 00:17:48.280
[Guest]: So are we happy to continue?

00:17:48.280 --> 00:17:49.280
[Amit Varma]: Please continue Emma.

00:17:49.280 --> 00:17:50.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:17:50.280 --> 00:17:51.280
[Amit Varma]: Okay.

00:17:51.280 --> 00:17:52.280
[Guest]: So then at university...

00:17:52.280 --> 00:17:57.200
[Guest]: Oh no, I want to tell you another story that I think is an important part of the process.

00:17:57.200 --> 00:18:07.040
[Guest]: When I was 16, we went on holiday to South Africa, Mozambique, Lesotho and Swaziland.

00:18:07.040 --> 00:18:10.480
[Guest]: And that was my first encounter with extreme poverty.

00:18:10.480 --> 00:18:16.280
[Guest]: That was the first time that I'd seen slums and rural deprivation.

00:18:16.280 --> 00:18:22.040
[Guest]: And I remember we stopped, we stopped the car at one point, and we got out and my brother

00:18:22.040 --> 00:18:25.200
[Guest]: and I and these other kids we were with, and we played with some kids, we like just playing

00:18:25.200 --> 00:18:26.240
[Guest]: football.

00:18:26.240 --> 00:18:30.460
[Guest]: And that was the first time that I'd seen extreme deprivation.

00:18:30.460 --> 00:18:32.760
[Guest]: And after that, I just cried.

00:18:32.760 --> 00:18:33.760
[Guest]: Because I'd never...

00:18:33.760 --> 00:18:34.760
[Guest]: And it really shocked me.

00:18:34.760 --> 00:18:36.440
[Guest]: It really shocked me.

00:18:36.440 --> 00:18:37.440
[Amit Varma]: And...

00:18:37.440 --> 00:18:38.440
[Amit Varma]: What was extreme deprivation?

00:18:38.440 --> 00:18:39.440
[Guest]: What did you see?

00:18:39.440 --> 00:18:47.320
[Guest]: Like seeing slums, seeing sewage, seeing kids with living in ramshackle houses, you know,

00:18:47.320 --> 00:18:52.320
[Guest]: just dilapidated houses, having very, very little, you know, we, we had, you know, we

00:18:52.320 --> 00:18:55.920
[Guest]: had friendship, we had humanity, we had solid, you know, we played together just as kids

00:18:55.920 --> 00:18:57.040
[Guest]: do.

00:18:57.040 --> 00:19:00.960
[Guest]: But I just had never encountered that level of deprivation before.

00:19:00.960 --> 00:19:04.800
[Guest]: And I cried, I really cried.

00:19:04.800 --> 00:19:09.360
[Guest]: I just didn't know that kind of, that kind of deprivation existed at all.

00:19:09.360 --> 00:19:11.840
[Guest]: So I think, I think that was, that was an important point.

00:19:11.840 --> 00:19:15.400
[Guest]: So then I went to university and I studied philosophy.

00:19:15.400 --> 00:19:19.680
[Guest]: And that was incredibly important to my mental development.

00:19:19.680 --> 00:19:24.560
[Guest]: So I think philosophy, I studied, you know, free will.

00:19:24.560 --> 00:19:29.840
[Guest]: And through studying that, I realized that free will is impossible because it's luck

00:19:29.840 --> 00:19:33.720
[Guest]: what kind of personality we have, you know, whether you're the person who works hard,

00:19:33.720 --> 00:19:34.720
[Guest]: that's luck.

00:19:34.720 --> 00:19:38.400
[Guest]: Whether you're a person, if you're born in an environment in which hard work pays off,

00:19:38.400 --> 00:19:39.400
[Guest]: that's luck.

00:19:39.400 --> 00:19:43.880
[Guest]: I also came to question personal identity that I realized there is no constant thing.

00:19:43.880 --> 00:19:45.680
[Guest]: That's just a mental construction.

00:19:45.680 --> 00:19:49.160
[Guest]: I also became skeptical the external world existed.

00:19:49.160 --> 00:19:51.280
[Guest]: You know, we studied the arguments about the brain and the vat.

00:19:51.280 --> 00:19:52.920
[Guest]: And I realized that I could be a brain and a vat.

00:19:52.920 --> 00:19:55.920
[Guest]: There's no evidence that these aren't just mental stimulations.

00:19:55.920 --> 00:20:02.820
[Guest]: I studied meta ethics and the idea that we actually, that actually our claims about right

00:20:02.820 --> 00:20:05.760
[Guest]: and wrong and good and bad are just social constructs.

00:20:05.760 --> 00:20:08.520
[Guest]: There's nothing in the external world that is a moral fact.

00:20:08.520 --> 00:20:12.880
[Guest]: This is something that we've made up to and that has enabled our societies to thrive.

00:20:12.880 --> 00:20:18.680
[Guest]: I also studied philosophy and I, before I, before I became a nihilist, I was very interested

00:20:18.680 --> 00:20:21.680
[Guest]: in utilitarianism and I found that very persuasive.

00:20:21.680 --> 00:20:26.720
[Guest]: And when I became a utilitarian, I became a vegan and I gave away vast sums of money

00:20:26.720 --> 00:20:29.600
[Guest]: because I was concerned, you know, extreme poverty, et cetera.

00:20:29.600 --> 00:20:33.920
[Guest]: So what was also in pursuit, I became, you know, that philosophy, I was continually questioning

00:20:33.920 --> 00:20:35.160
[Guest]: everything.

00:20:35.160 --> 00:20:38.940
[Guest]: So it's that intense questioning, no, there were no sacred truths.

00:20:38.940 --> 00:20:40.560
[Guest]: There was nothing that would be taken for given.

00:20:40.560 --> 00:20:43.440
[Guest]: I would, from now on, I would be questioning absolutely everything.

00:20:43.440 --> 00:20:47.480
[Guest]: I should say I started philosophy in school, but it was exaggerated at university.

00:20:47.480 --> 00:20:51.200
[Guest]: And I was also madly in love with formal logic.

00:20:51.200 --> 00:20:53.440
[Guest]: I would spend my evenings studying formal.

00:20:53.440 --> 00:20:55.480
[Guest]: I found it, I found it thrilling.

00:20:55.480 --> 00:21:00.440
[Guest]: I found logical propositions, just, just sledgehammer logic.

00:21:00.440 --> 00:21:01.440
[Guest]: I loved it.

00:21:01.440 --> 00:21:06.580
[Guest]: I mean, I should say, I did dabble in university life.

00:21:06.580 --> 00:21:10.600
[Guest]: So my first week of university, they have this thing called Freshers Week where people

00:21:10.600 --> 00:21:14.000
[Guest]: go, and I thought, right, I'm going to try this out.

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:17.960
[Guest]: I will go out every single night and party until 5.30am.

00:21:17.960 --> 00:21:22.120
[Guest]: I will try the student experience, and this is my sort of empirical experiment.

00:21:22.120 --> 00:21:24.600
[Guest]: At the end of the week, I reviewed it.

00:21:24.600 --> 00:21:26.800
[Guest]: I decided it did not make me happy.

00:21:26.800 --> 00:21:32.280
[Guest]: And I never went out in the entire university life, but yet, I just loved philosophy and

00:21:32.280 --> 00:21:35.120
[Guest]: formal logic and, and this analytical rigor.

00:21:35.120 --> 00:21:36.120
[Guest]: I enjoyed that.

00:21:36.120 --> 00:21:41.920
[Guest]: I was also, I also did a couple of courses in the philosophy of sex, in feminist philosophy.

00:21:41.920 --> 00:21:49.280
[Guest]: So yeah, that was all important for my mental development, analytical rigor, questioning

00:21:49.280 --> 00:21:50.280
[Guest]: everything.

00:21:50.280 --> 00:21:55.900
[Guest]: Also at university, I joined university debate clubs.

00:21:55.900 --> 00:21:58.920
[Guest]: So I would train twice a week in debate.

00:21:58.920 --> 00:22:03.080
[Guest]: Every weekend, we would go to debate tournaments, and I went to European debate championships,

00:22:03.080 --> 00:22:04.080
[Guest]: world debate tournaments.

00:22:04.080 --> 00:22:06.040
[Guest]: I became president of the debate society.

00:22:06.040 --> 00:22:07.880
[Guest]: I did that for a year.

00:22:07.880 --> 00:22:12.840
[Guest]: But then I decided that actually, debate was not good for my mental development because

00:22:12.840 --> 00:22:16.160
[Guest]: it forces, the goal is to destroy the other person.

00:22:16.160 --> 00:22:22.720
[Guest]: The goal is to demonstrate such oratory that you just destroy them, embarrass them so that

00:22:22.720 --> 00:22:23.840
[Guest]: people think you're right.

00:22:23.840 --> 00:22:26.320
[Guest]: It's not about working out the correct answer.

00:22:26.320 --> 00:22:29.200
[Guest]: It's not about you and I learning from each other.

00:22:29.200 --> 00:22:31.760
[Guest]: And just before this, you and I were discussing something controversial.

00:22:31.760 --> 00:22:32.760
[Guest]: We had a nice discussion.

00:22:32.760 --> 00:22:34.480
[Guest]: It wasn't about working out the truth.

00:22:34.480 --> 00:22:36.880
[Guest]: It was just this artistry.

00:22:36.880 --> 00:22:39.720
[Guest]: And so I decided that no, this wasn't what I wanted to pursue.

00:22:39.720 --> 00:22:40.720
[Guest]: This wasn't good for me.

00:22:40.720 --> 00:22:42.560
[Guest]: So I was going to move on from it.

00:22:42.560 --> 00:22:46.200
[Guest]: But it did, that practice definitely strengthened my skills.

00:22:46.200 --> 00:22:50.600
[Guest]: And this is one thing I've come to learn, that no one is born with any innate skills,

00:22:50.600 --> 00:22:55.040
[Guest]: but we develop them through practice, through good guidance, and also social recognition

00:22:55.040 --> 00:22:56.040
[Guest]: and reward.

00:22:56.040 --> 00:22:58.200
[Guest]: You know, the more that those are appreciated.

00:22:58.200 --> 00:23:03.200
[Guest]: So I was in an environment where I was praised and rewarded through doing well in debate.

00:23:03.200 --> 00:23:04.200
[Guest]: So that was important.

00:23:04.200 --> 00:23:11.320
[Guest]: I would say one more thing, what helped me become more confident, because I am confident,

00:23:11.320 --> 00:23:14.600
[Guest]: is also working in different environments.

00:23:14.600 --> 00:23:18.160
[Guest]: Like from age 15, I was a waitress, and that teaches you know how to get along with different

00:23:18.160 --> 00:23:19.160
[Guest]: people.

00:23:19.160 --> 00:23:20.160
[Guest]: So I was, you know, quite confident about that.

00:23:20.160 --> 00:23:25.800
[Guest]: I also had a couple of characters in my own family, you know, I talked about my abusive

00:23:25.800 --> 00:23:26.800
[Guest]: father.

00:23:26.800 --> 00:23:29.640
[Guest]: There were other characters who gave me other sources of inspiration.

00:23:29.640 --> 00:23:32.800
[Guest]: My uncle is an interesting character.

00:23:32.800 --> 00:23:38.200
[Guest]: Age 30, so he was doing an office job, age 30, he decided that didn't make him happy.

00:23:38.200 --> 00:23:40.640
[Guest]: What he really loved was skiing and hang gliding.

00:23:40.640 --> 00:23:44.760
[Guest]: So he quit his job, he went off to be a ski rep, because that way he could do as much

00:23:44.760 --> 00:23:45.760
[Guest]: skiing as possible.

00:23:45.760 --> 00:23:48.680
[Guest]: He lived in a caravan in the summer doing hang gliding.

00:23:48.680 --> 00:23:49.680
[Guest]: And I love that.

00:23:49.680 --> 00:23:53.320
[Guest]: You know, this is someone who thinks, I'm happy if I'm skiing and hang gliding.

00:23:53.320 --> 00:23:56.120
[Guest]: So whatever social convention, let me do that.

00:23:56.120 --> 00:23:58.880
[Guest]: Age 45, he then realized he needed a pension.

00:23:58.880 --> 00:24:01.840
[Guest]: So he started up a business and they did tremendously well.

00:24:01.840 --> 00:24:02.840
[Guest]: He's fine.

00:24:02.840 --> 00:24:06.280
[Guest]: Then we have my grandfather, who was this pioneering physicist.

00:24:06.280 --> 00:24:09.840
[Guest]: He was at Cambridge, then developed radar during the Second World War.

00:24:09.840 --> 00:24:11.920
[Guest]: My grandmother was a historian.

00:24:11.920 --> 00:24:17.680
[Guest]: She is probably the one person in my family who showed warmth and care.

00:24:17.680 --> 00:24:21.480
[Guest]: You know, you would enter a room and she would make you feel valued.

00:24:21.480 --> 00:24:23.280
[Guest]: She would make you feel cherished.

00:24:23.280 --> 00:24:32.400
[Guest]: And actually, when she died five years ago, I had a, this is, I'll be interested in your

00:24:32.400 --> 00:24:33.800
[Guest]: thoughts on this.

00:24:33.800 --> 00:24:40.080
[Guest]: So often at funerals, at least in England, people mourn the dead and mourn their departure

00:24:40.080 --> 00:24:41.540
[Guest]: and that loss.

00:24:41.540 --> 00:24:45.080
[Guest]: And they also say nice things about them after they've died.

00:24:45.080 --> 00:24:47.640
[Guest]: And so people never get to hear those nice things.

00:24:47.640 --> 00:24:50.760
[Guest]: But I took a different approach to my grandmother's death.

00:24:50.760 --> 00:24:57.360
[Guest]: I thought, well, let me identify her virtues and let me try to inculcate them in myself

00:24:57.360 --> 00:25:01.120
[Guest]: so the wonderful things that she did can live on through me.

00:25:01.120 --> 00:25:07.600
[Guest]: And so I try in my interactions, albeit imperfectly, to make people feel valued.

00:25:07.600 --> 00:25:11.960
[Guest]: Like one thing I like to do is give credible compliments.

00:25:11.960 --> 00:25:17.800
[Guest]: So I like, I think so many people, they're trying their best, but might not feel appreciated

00:25:17.800 --> 00:25:20.240
[Guest]: or recognized.

00:25:20.240 --> 00:25:25.040
[Guest]: And I can give several, for example, earlier this year, I was in Morocco, where I was doing

00:25:25.040 --> 00:25:27.160
[Guest]: research for my book.

00:25:27.160 --> 00:25:32.640
[Guest]: And this wonderful family invited me for iftar, to break the Ramadan.

00:25:32.640 --> 00:25:36.800
[Guest]: And the mother made the most glorious spread, you know, there were so many different dishes

00:25:36.800 --> 00:25:38.600
[Guest]: and they were all delicious.

00:25:38.600 --> 00:25:40.280
[Guest]: And I sat there with her family.

00:25:40.280 --> 00:25:46.720
[Guest]: And I noticed that not one of the, not her husband or either of her sons said anything

00:25:46.720 --> 00:25:47.720
[Guest]: nice.

00:25:47.720 --> 00:25:49.640
[Guest]: They didn't say how delicious the food was.

00:25:49.640 --> 00:25:50.640
[Guest]: They didn't praise it.

00:25:50.640 --> 00:25:56.960
[Guest]: And that's common the world over, that women's care workers not recognized is not valued.

00:25:56.960 --> 00:26:02.000
[Guest]: And I was, and I wanted to tell her how much I enjoyed the food and this is delicious.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:05.200
[Guest]: And this is like, and not just to say it's delicious, but to explain why.

00:26:05.200 --> 00:26:10.280
[Guest]: And afterwards, when we were washing up in the kitchen, I said to her, I noticed that

00:26:10.280 --> 00:26:13.120
[Guest]: other people didn't comment on the food.

00:26:13.120 --> 00:26:16.720
[Guest]: And she said, yeah, they treat me like a maid.

00:26:16.720 --> 00:26:22.280
[Guest]: And I think that's not a uniquely gendered issue, but there are so many people, whatever

00:26:22.280 --> 00:26:28.600
[Guest]: they do, they're trying, but people might not say what we appreciate and what we recognize.

00:26:28.600 --> 00:26:31.520
[Guest]: And I like to, I like to compliment people.

00:26:31.520 --> 00:26:36.600
[Unknown]: And I don't do it in an insincere, it's not just a fake claim, but I like to identify

00:26:36.600 --> 00:26:41.360
[Guest]: and highlight and explain what I see in the other person that's brilliant and fascinating,

00:26:41.360 --> 00:26:43.200
[Guest]: because everyone has these unique draws.

00:26:43.200 --> 00:26:45.520
[Guest]: And that very much comes from my grandmother.

00:26:45.520 --> 00:26:48.640
[Guest]: And so that's something that I try to inculcate.

00:26:48.640 --> 00:26:52.200
[Guest]: And I want everyone to leave an interaction with me feeling better about themselves and

00:26:52.200 --> 00:26:54.200
[Guest]: feeling happy about that interaction.

00:26:54.200 --> 00:26:55.200
[Guest]: So that's important for me.

00:26:55.200 --> 00:27:01.840
[Guest]: So even though I'm a nihilist, I do try to, you know, spread joy, in a sense, okay.

00:27:01.840 --> 00:27:06.680
[Guest]: So, so, okay, so now we come to, okay, so let's say we've done the undergraduate degree

00:27:06.680 --> 00:27:12.400
[Guest]: in philosophy, then I did a three month internship with an NGO working on poverty reduction,

00:27:12.400 --> 00:27:14.000
[Guest]: because I'm now interested in that.

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:16.840
[Guest]: I initially wanted to be a human rights lawyer.

00:27:16.840 --> 00:27:22.640
[Guest]: But through this experience, I realized, actually, I wanted to understand the causes of underdevelopment.

00:27:22.640 --> 00:27:28.000
[Guest]: So I was going to the LSE, and I switched to master's to study international development.

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:30.840
[Guest]: They would allow me to come, but I had to wait a year.

00:27:30.840 --> 00:27:34.120
[Guest]: In that intervening time, I had a year to kill, what was I going to do?

00:27:34.120 --> 00:27:40.280
[Guest]: So in walks the country director of ActionAid, the Gambia, she walks in, and I introduce

00:27:40.280 --> 00:27:43.080
[Guest]: myself to her, I say, Hi, I'm Alice Evans.

00:27:43.080 --> 00:27:44.600
[Guest]: And I'd like to come and work for you.

00:27:44.600 --> 00:27:46.560
[Guest]: And so off I go to the Gambia.

00:27:46.560 --> 00:27:47.560
[Guest]: And that was that.

00:27:47.560 --> 00:27:50.880
[Guest]: And while I go to the Gambia, I do a search of all the professors at the LSE.

00:27:50.880 --> 00:27:52.240
[Guest]: Is there anyone who's studying the Gambia?

00:27:52.240 --> 00:27:55.960
[Guest]: And I find a professor who is, I volunteer to be her research assistant, we do a research

00:27:55.960 --> 00:27:59.680
[Guest]: project on gender, and I realized the importance of social esteem.

00:27:59.680 --> 00:28:04.600
[Guest]: So I, so I even before my master's, I was doing this six month qualitative research

00:28:04.600 --> 00:28:06.600
[Guest]: project, then I went to the LSE.

00:28:06.600 --> 00:28:11.880
[Guest]: And I was so excited, I thought now I'm going to find some brilliant minds who will be able

00:28:11.880 --> 00:28:15.480
[Guest]: to discuss these topics as we talked, you know, I'm very curious, I'm eager to discuss.

00:28:15.480 --> 00:28:18.000
[Guest]: So I went in and I had read everything.

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:20.720
[Unknown]: You know, I had studied everything and I was eager to chat.

00:28:20.720 --> 00:28:23.680
[Guest]: And I was so disappointed.

00:28:23.680 --> 00:28:28.320
[Guest]: You know, people could regurgitate the two basic readings.

00:28:28.320 --> 00:28:29.320
[Guest]: So that was disappointing.

00:28:29.320 --> 00:28:33.800
[Guest]: You know, I think throughout my life, I've always wanted to find people who might want

00:28:33.800 --> 00:28:36.000
[Guest]: to share and discuss these ideas.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:38.560
[Guest]: But you know, that wasn't at the LSE.

00:28:38.560 --> 00:28:45.840
[Guest]: Then, so then, after my master's, I decided I want to pursue a PhD now, because I was

00:28:45.840 --> 00:28:50.960
[Guest]: and I chose to continue with Professor Sylvia Chant, because I knew her, we had a nice relationship.

00:28:50.960 --> 00:28:55.240
[Guest]: So I was interested in gender, merely because of she was interested in gender, it wasn't

00:28:55.240 --> 00:28:58.640
[Guest]: like I had this strong feminist zeal.

00:28:58.640 --> 00:29:03.640
[Guest]: Many of the studies on gender at the time were often short term studies, you know, micro

00:29:03.640 --> 00:29:06.960
[Guest]: finance, does it change gender relations in six months?

00:29:06.960 --> 00:29:07.960
[Guest]: No.

00:29:07.960 --> 00:29:12.600
[Guest]: So I thought, well, actually, you know, gender relations take a long time to change generations.

00:29:12.600 --> 00:29:15.960
[Guest]: And so what we need to study is the lingerie.

00:29:15.960 --> 00:29:21.320
[Guest]: So I thought, where is a good place for me to study 100 years of how gender relations

00:29:21.320 --> 00:29:22.320
[Guest]: change?

00:29:22.320 --> 00:29:27.720
[Guest]: And I picked Zambia, because from the 1930s, there have been ethnographic anthropological

00:29:27.720 --> 00:29:28.720
[Guest]: studies.

00:29:28.720 --> 00:29:32.720
[Guest]: So 1930s, 1950s, 1970s, so that was a great place for me to go to.

00:29:32.720 --> 00:29:35.960
[Guest]: One hitch is that people will be speaking Bemba.

00:29:35.960 --> 00:29:40.040
[Guest]: So obviously, I need to teach myself Bemba, how am I going to do this?

00:29:40.040 --> 00:29:46.200
[Guest]: Well, I contacted a professor of languages at SOAS, who, but then we couldn't find a

00:29:46.200 --> 00:29:48.680
[Guest]: deal, we really couldn't find many resources.

00:29:48.680 --> 00:29:52.080
[Guest]: So I found on eBay, a colonial missionaries drama book.

00:29:52.080 --> 00:29:56.080
[Guest]: And I also found a sort of dictionary from the 1960s.

00:29:56.080 --> 00:29:57.080
[Guest]: And I studied this.

00:29:57.080 --> 00:30:01.960
[Guest]: And then I went to Zambia, I just went to some event, I met a school girl, and I said

00:30:01.960 --> 00:30:02.960
[Guest]: she was 16.

00:30:02.960 --> 00:30:03.960
[Guest]: Her name's Esther.

00:30:03.960 --> 00:30:05.320
[Guest]: And I said, Can I come and stay with you?

00:30:05.320 --> 00:30:06.560
[Guest]: And she said, Yes.

00:30:06.560 --> 00:30:08.680
[Guest]: So I lived with that family.

00:30:08.680 --> 00:30:12.960
[Guest]: And every morning, I woke up at 4am, I studied my grammar book, I soon realized that the

00:30:12.960 --> 00:30:15.720
[Guest]: dictionary I was using was totally antiquated.

00:30:15.720 --> 00:30:19.400
[Guest]: I mean, these were like, deep rural Bemba that missionaries were using.

00:30:19.400 --> 00:30:21.720
[Guest]: So no one was using these words.

00:30:21.720 --> 00:30:23.960
[Guest]: So what I did is I wrote my own dictionary.

00:30:23.960 --> 00:30:28.080
[Guest]: Every time I heard a word, I drew a picture of it, because that's a form of active learning

00:30:28.080 --> 00:30:33.580
[Guest]: that the more we creatively engage with a concept, the more we it aids our learning.

00:30:33.580 --> 00:30:38.200
[Guest]: So I wrote this dictionary, I wrote my own dictionary, I became fluent in Bemba, and

00:30:38.200 --> 00:30:45.080
[Guest]: I also lived with I also, in that period, one day I was interviewed, I mean, it's this,

00:30:45.080 --> 00:30:50.960
[Guest]: it's my intense curiosity that pushes me to take to pushes me to be bold and take risks,

00:30:50.960 --> 00:30:52.560
[Guest]: because all I want to do is learn.

00:30:52.560 --> 00:30:54.080
[Guest]: And so nothing else matters.

00:30:54.080 --> 00:30:56.560
[Guest]: So I wanted to interview a local government counselor.

00:30:56.560 --> 00:30:59.160
[Guest]: So I the day and she's living in a slum.

00:30:59.160 --> 00:31:02.640
[Guest]: So the day I meet her, I say, you know, we have a nice chat, we have a fantastic interview,

00:31:02.640 --> 00:31:04.960
[Guest]: we get along, I say, well, can I come and live with you?

00:31:04.960 --> 00:31:07.840
[Guest]: So then after that, I lived in the slum for six months.

00:31:07.840 --> 00:31:15.140
[Guest]: Another time, I went to interview an MP in the same area, and she invited me to stay

00:31:15.140 --> 00:31:16.140
[Guest]: with her.

00:31:16.140 --> 00:31:20.520
[Guest]: And then off I went to live with MPs and, and while I so in Zambia, all the MPs live

00:31:20.520 --> 00:31:24.760
[Guest]: together in a sort of BNB type event type affair.

00:31:24.760 --> 00:31:28.760
[Guest]: And so while I was staying there, I was invited to go on national TV and was interviewed about

00:31:28.760 --> 00:31:30.080
[Guest]: my research in Bemba.

00:31:30.080 --> 00:31:31.680
[Guest]: So I was on state TV.

00:31:31.680 --> 00:31:35.840
[Guest]: And then here's this young white woman, I was what, 24 at the time, who's fluent in

00:31:35.840 --> 00:31:36.840
[Guest]: Bemba.

00:31:36.840 --> 00:31:39.120
[Guest]: And so I became famous across the country.

00:31:39.120 --> 00:31:43.080
[Guest]: So I would, anywhere I would walk, I would get on a bus, I would get in a taxi, I would

00:31:43.080 --> 00:31:46.720
[Guest]: be in a supermarket 200 miles away, and people would know who I was.

00:31:46.720 --> 00:31:51.280
[Guest]: One time I was even deep, deep in the bush, and I was giving all my official papers to

00:31:51.280 --> 00:31:53.960
[Guest]: this person, you know, showing I had approval.

00:31:53.960 --> 00:31:58.280
[Unknown]: So she was like, I know who you are, I've seen you on TV.

00:31:58.280 --> 00:32:01.040
[Unknown]: So that was all very helpful that people felt that they knew me.

00:32:01.040 --> 00:32:07.240
[Guest]: That study, so that study in Zambia, was really important.

00:32:07.240 --> 00:32:12.840
[Guest]: So what I learned is, in Zambia, there's now a saying you can hear in markets, in schools,

00:32:12.840 --> 00:32:16.760
[Guest]: in homes, they say, banamayo, kutibaa bomba inshitao shaabaomei.

00:32:16.760 --> 00:32:20.240
[Guest]: And what that means is, women can do what men can do.

00:32:20.240 --> 00:32:26.640
[Guest]: And this has emerged as a result of economic behaviour and cultural changes in that from

00:32:26.640 --> 00:32:32.920
[Guest]: the 1980s, there was worsening economic insecurity as a result of the plummeting price of copper,

00:32:32.920 --> 00:32:38.200
[Guest]: state cutbacks, HIV AIDS, and men could no longer provide for their families single handedly.

00:32:38.200 --> 00:32:43.280
[Guest]: And so women surged into the labour force to provide for their children, to make ends

00:32:43.280 --> 00:32:44.280
[Guest]: meet.

00:32:44.280 --> 00:32:48.160
[Guest]: And initially, this was just adding to their drudgery, you know, they weren't being recognised,

00:32:48.160 --> 00:32:49.200
[Guest]: they weren't being valued.

00:32:49.200 --> 00:32:53.720
[Guest]: But through prolonged exposure, as people saw women fighting to provide for their children,

00:32:53.720 --> 00:33:00.240
[Guest]: to pay the electricity, as widows were demonstrating equal competence alongside men, then people

00:33:00.240 --> 00:33:05.360
[Guest]: and through public discussions, you know, people discussing, talking in the marketplaces,

00:33:05.360 --> 00:33:10.120
[Guest]: sharing stories about these women pioneers, sharing stories about women mechanics, women

00:33:10.120 --> 00:33:14.240
[Guest]: professors, women doing all these great things, people came to recognise and revere women

00:33:14.240 --> 00:33:16.720
[Guest]: and that encouraged social change.

00:33:16.720 --> 00:33:20.040
[Guest]: So that was my PhD, broadly.

00:33:20.040 --> 00:33:25.840
[Guest]: And then I realised another conundrum, well, why is this social change being faster in

00:33:25.840 --> 00:33:27.960
[Guest]: cities than in rural areas?

00:33:27.960 --> 00:33:31.340
[Guest]: And that's a global phenomenon, that in cities, people are generally much more liberal, much

00:33:31.340 --> 00:33:33.360
[Guest]: more gender equal, etc.

00:33:33.360 --> 00:33:36.900
[Guest]: So I thought, right, I want to test, I want to understand this.

00:33:36.900 --> 00:33:39.800
[Guest]: So let me do a comparative rural urban ethnography.

00:33:39.800 --> 00:33:44.960
[Guest]: So I returned to Zambia, I interviewed some rural urban traders, and they invite me to

00:33:44.960 --> 00:33:47.240
[Guest]: go back to their village.

00:33:47.240 --> 00:33:54.080
[Guest]: So we were talking about and so to get there, I was going to board a coach, take a shortcut

00:33:54.080 --> 00:33:57.920
[Guest]: through the Democratic Republic of Congo.

00:33:57.920 --> 00:34:07.040
[Guest]: And on the way, these Congolese border officials stop me and tell me to disembark the coach.

00:34:07.040 --> 00:34:13.480
[Guest]: These eight soldiers take me into a room, and they shout at me in the local language.

00:34:13.480 --> 00:34:16.320
[Guest]: And you can understand this, you know, they haven't been paid in a long time, they want

00:34:16.320 --> 00:34:18.240
[Guest]: to intimidate the white person.

00:34:18.240 --> 00:34:20.560
[Guest]: I totally understand that.

00:34:20.560 --> 00:34:25.640
[Guest]: As luck would have it, colonial borders were arbitrarily imposed.

00:34:25.640 --> 00:34:27.280
[Guest]: I already knew their language.

00:34:27.280 --> 00:34:33.440
[Guest]: So I reply in my polite and fluent Bemba, and I explain myself, I explain my purpose,

00:34:33.440 --> 00:34:35.760
[Guest]: I'm perfectly calm.

00:34:35.760 --> 00:34:36.880
[Guest]: This frustrated them.

00:34:36.880 --> 00:34:41.440
[Guest]: So they took me to another room, where they shouted and texted me in French.

00:34:41.440 --> 00:34:45.080
[Guest]: As luck would have it, I'm part French.

00:34:45.080 --> 00:34:50.760
[Guest]: So they eventually released me, off I go, back on the coach, through this 10 hour drive

00:34:50.760 --> 00:34:56.080
[Guest]: through the muddy parts of Congo, I arrive in the village.

00:34:56.080 --> 00:34:57.720
[Guest]: And that was wonderful.

00:34:57.720 --> 00:35:01.480
[Guest]: This is a place of no electricity, no running water, no phone signal.

00:35:01.480 --> 00:35:06.500
[Guest]: But you know, I talked to people, I tried to understand why many of these traditions

00:35:06.500 --> 00:35:08.440
[Guest]: had persisted in the village.

00:35:08.440 --> 00:35:12.680
[Guest]: And I learned that, you know, this is a place that's, this was a swamp.

00:35:12.680 --> 00:35:17.560
[Guest]: So it's much more socially isolated, many of the, the vast majority of the women there

00:35:17.560 --> 00:35:18.840
[Guest]: were wives and mothers.

00:35:18.840 --> 00:35:21.800
[Guest]: And that's, you know, people grew up anticipating that.

00:35:21.800 --> 00:35:26.640
[Guest]: So even if, even if, and also there's this, and I realized how negative feedback loops

00:35:26.640 --> 00:35:27.640
[Guest]: can persist.

00:35:27.640 --> 00:35:30.200
[Guest]: So even because of fear of social condemnation.

00:35:30.200 --> 00:35:35.700
[Guest]: So for example, one woman, Mavis, she was a trader in town.

00:35:35.700 --> 00:35:39.400
[Guest]: And through trading in town, she heard that in town, women kept their own money.

00:35:39.400 --> 00:35:40.440
[Guest]: And she wanted that.

00:35:40.440 --> 00:35:42.300
[Guest]: She definitely wanted that.

00:35:42.300 --> 00:35:44.240
[Guest]: But she couldn't push for that at home.

00:35:44.240 --> 00:35:45.640
[Guest]: And that frustrated her.

00:35:45.640 --> 00:35:49.480
[Guest]: And I asked her why is because people in her community wouldn't support that.

00:35:49.480 --> 00:35:51.760
[Guest]: And she didn't want to fight that battle.

00:35:51.760 --> 00:35:56.040
[Guest]: And similarly, I was talking to a man in town who, through coming to town, he realized that

00:35:56.040 --> 00:35:59.080
[Guest]: gender based violence was wrong, that was wrong to be your wife, he was definitely opposed

00:35:59.080 --> 00:36:00.080
[Guest]: to it.

00:36:00.080 --> 00:36:05.660
[Guest]: But back in the village, he would not intervene in such cases, because he anticipated social

00:36:05.660 --> 00:36:06.660
[Guest]: condemnation.

00:36:06.660 --> 00:36:10.360
[Guest]: And I think that's an important point about what I call our norm perception.

00:36:10.360 --> 00:36:16.160
[Guest]: So even if we are privately critical of something, if we anticipate social disapproval, we often

00:36:16.160 --> 00:36:17.620
[Guest]: choose not to rock the boat.

00:36:17.620 --> 00:36:20.560
[Guest]: And that can create what I call a despondency trap.

00:36:20.560 --> 00:36:25.800
[Guest]: Because if we never see successful resistance, people may not push back.

00:36:25.800 --> 00:36:27.840
[Guest]: And so then they never see successful resistance.

00:36:27.840 --> 00:36:32.320
[Guest]: And so these places remain caught in a negative feedback loop, and that impedes social change.

00:36:32.320 --> 00:36:37.760
[Guest]: So it's the isolation, the death of economic opportunities, leads to cultural persistence.

00:36:37.760 --> 00:36:40.640
[Guest]: So that rural study was that's really important.

00:36:40.640 --> 00:36:42.680
[Guest]: And then I had another conundrum.

00:36:42.680 --> 00:36:47.520
[Guest]: Well, I wanted to test my hypothesis, because what I'm ultimately saying is that it's cities

00:36:47.520 --> 00:36:52.000
[Guest]: catalyzing social change, it's the diversity, the heterogeneity of people, or it's you know,

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:57.000
[Guest]: that myriad exposure, you know, in a Zambian copper belt, you're bored of bus, and you'll

00:36:57.000 --> 00:37:02.160
[Guest]: see a woman going off to her office, you'll see a woman driving a truck to the mind, it's

00:37:02.160 --> 00:37:07.120
[Guest]: all those myriad exposures, those associations, seeing the different different things going

00:37:07.120 --> 00:37:09.360
[Guest]: on talking about them debating things.

00:37:09.360 --> 00:37:13.240
[Guest]: Just yesterday, I was at JNU chatting with female students about their same experience

00:37:13.240 --> 00:37:14.240
[Guest]: that they're sharing ideas.

00:37:14.240 --> 00:37:19.000
[Guest]: And I was thinking that cities themselves are catalysts of social change.

00:37:19.000 --> 00:37:20.300
[Guest]: But maybe I got it wrong.

00:37:20.300 --> 00:37:25.120
[Guest]: Maybe it was just about women having economic opportunities.

00:37:25.120 --> 00:37:28.040
[Guest]: So I thought, well, let me test this hypothesis.

00:37:28.040 --> 00:37:34.720
[Guest]: What I need to do is look for a rural labor demand shock, I need to find a village where

00:37:34.720 --> 00:37:39.040
[Guest]: there's suddenly been female employment does, you know, in a rural environment with this

00:37:39.040 --> 00:37:44.440
[Guest]: isolated that doesn't have those diverse experiences and exposure, could female employment catalyze

00:37:44.440 --> 00:37:46.560
[Guest]: a change of its own accord.

00:37:46.560 --> 00:37:52.180
[Guest]: So I think where in the world is a rural labor demand shock, I know, Cambodia, because of

00:37:52.180 --> 00:37:57.800
[Guest]: rising labor costs and land costs in China, many factories have relocated to rural Cambodia.

00:37:57.800 --> 00:38:03.240
[Guest]: So off I go to Cambodia, and I start learning Khmer, I contact a family and I do rural urban

00:38:03.240 --> 00:38:07.800
[Guest]: comparative ethnographic research in Cambodia.

00:38:07.800 --> 00:38:09.160
[Guest]: And that was enormously fascinating.

00:38:09.160 --> 00:38:13.480
[Guest]: So every morning at 5.30am, I'm chatting with the factory workers.

00:38:13.480 --> 00:38:18.520
[Guest]: And through this, again, you know, the rural factory workers were saying how, you know,

00:38:18.520 --> 00:38:22.680
[Guest]: they feel pride that they're able to support their families, just like sons, they feel

00:38:22.680 --> 00:38:27.040
[Guest]: pride that they're able to support their parents, but it's not like they have their own, you

00:38:27.040 --> 00:38:31.360
[Guest]: know, incredible autonomy, they're not like they're challenging gender barriers, you know,

00:38:31.360 --> 00:38:34.240
[Guest]: it's that they're gaining status, they're gaining pride, they're gaining esteem, but

00:38:34.240 --> 00:38:40.880
[Guest]: it's far more, there's far more radical disruption in cities, you know, I talked to garment workers,

00:38:40.880 --> 00:38:46.800
[Guest]: and they said, and one told me how, in the apartment next to her, the husband was sharing

00:38:46.800 --> 00:38:48.200
[Guest]: the care work.

00:38:48.200 --> 00:38:52.560
[Guest]: And she realized that, hey, hey, yeah, you know, if I'm working, my husband's working,

00:38:52.560 --> 00:38:54.520
[Guest]: my husband could also be doing the washing up.

00:38:54.520 --> 00:38:56.000
[Guest]: So she pushed for that, too.

00:38:56.000 --> 00:38:57.000
[Guest]: Her husband refused.

00:38:57.000 --> 00:38:58.160
[Guest]: And so she divorced him.

00:38:58.160 --> 00:39:01.760
[Guest]: And I talked to students, too, and they saw, and they said, well, you know, the other day,

00:39:01.760 --> 00:39:06.200
[Guest]: I saw a woman driving a tuk tuk, which is their equivalent of an auto rickshaw.

00:39:06.200 --> 00:39:08.560
[Guest]: And they were like, women can do what men can do.

00:39:08.560 --> 00:39:12.640
[Guest]: And I talked to male students, and they'd say, yeah, I came from the village, getting

00:39:12.640 --> 00:39:15.200
[Guest]: a scholarship or bursary, you know, subsidies for education.

00:39:15.200 --> 00:39:19.760
[Guest]: And I saw these women administrators, I saw these women managers, and I realized that

00:39:19.760 --> 00:39:21.160
[Guest]: women can do stuff, too.

00:39:21.160 --> 00:39:26.320
[Guest]: So again, I see the same theme, that cities enable this diversity, this exposure, these

00:39:26.320 --> 00:39:27.740
[Guest]: critical discussions.

00:39:27.740 --> 00:39:33.080
[Guest]: So that helped me realize something about the broader process of structural transformation,

00:39:33.080 --> 00:39:39.260
[Guest]: that cities, combined with relatively high rates of female employment and public spaces

00:39:39.260 --> 00:39:42.520
[Guest]: of open discussion, can enable cultural change.

00:39:42.520 --> 00:39:49.240
[Guest]: But in this process, so what I've told you, it's basically like Alice having a dialogue

00:39:49.240 --> 00:39:50.480
[Guest]: with Alice, right?

00:39:50.480 --> 00:39:53.400
[Guest]: All these things have been like me testing my own hypotheses.

00:39:53.400 --> 00:39:55.320
[Guest]: There's very little engagement with the outside world.

00:39:55.320 --> 00:40:00.040
[Guest]: I mean, all these articles that I publish, they always publish well.

00:40:00.040 --> 00:40:04.760
[Guest]: I never felt that there was a strong appetite or interest in my research.

00:40:04.760 --> 00:40:07.840
[Guest]: Whenever I went to conferences, people were doing radically different things, you know,

00:40:07.840 --> 00:40:11.560
[Guest]: there might be an RCT or there might be something.

00:40:11.560 --> 00:40:16.720
[Guest]: I never found there was an audience that was interested in what I was doing.

00:40:16.720 --> 00:40:22.200
[Guest]: It was just me by myself, interested in it, interested in it for my own sake.

00:40:22.200 --> 00:40:30.320
[Guest]: And I think there, Twitter in part has helped me because I'm able to reach out to a broader

00:40:30.320 --> 00:40:31.320
[Guest]: audience.

00:40:31.320 --> 00:40:34.080
[Guest]: I do find some people who are interested in these bigger questions.

00:40:34.080 --> 00:40:38.040
[Guest]: And so I think that has been liberating in itself.

00:40:38.040 --> 00:40:46.360
[Guest]: But I think also, so often you hear academics complain that there are disciplinary gatekeepers.

00:40:46.360 --> 00:40:50.940
[Guest]: And you know, in economics, for example, they might say, you know, journals want to publish

00:40:50.940 --> 00:40:53.920
[Guest]: these kinds of research or this is popular.

00:40:53.920 --> 00:41:02.080
[Guest]: And I think of that as a little bit like an abusive marriage, that if people try to please

00:41:02.080 --> 00:41:06.680
[Guest]: one person, then they're beholden to that narrow gatekeeper, whether it's journal gatekeepers

00:41:06.680 --> 00:41:08.680
[Guest]: or whether it's the abusive husband.

00:41:08.680 --> 00:41:13.760
[Guest]: But that's contingent on your desire to please that one narrow group.

00:41:13.760 --> 00:41:17.440
[Guest]: We can, we each have the opportunity to step back and liberate ourselves and say, actually,

00:41:17.440 --> 00:41:18.960
[Guest]: no, I don't want to.

00:41:18.960 --> 00:41:20.800
[Guest]: That isn't the audience that I want to please.

00:41:20.800 --> 00:41:25.040
[Guest]: So my PhD happened to be in geography because I'd followed Sylvia Chant.

00:41:25.040 --> 00:41:27.560
[Guest]: I didn't like what the geography journals were pushing me to do.

00:41:27.560 --> 00:41:28.760
[Guest]: They let me to theorise space.

00:41:28.760 --> 00:41:30.040
[Guest]: I thought that was pointless.

00:41:30.040 --> 00:41:32.400
[Guest]: So I stopped publishing geography.

00:41:32.400 --> 00:41:38.680
[Guest]: So I think I've always had this, I've cultivated over time, incrementally, this sense of what

00:41:38.680 --> 00:41:40.040
[Guest]: makes me happy?

00:41:40.040 --> 00:41:43.240
[Guest]: What do I think is important intrinsically?

00:41:43.240 --> 00:41:44.440
[Guest]: Let me pursue that.

00:41:44.440 --> 00:41:49.200
[Guest]: I'm not going to be beholden to whatever kind of social policing or social convention.

00:41:49.200 --> 00:41:52.000
[Guest]: I'm going to do what I think is important.

00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:57.160
[Guest]: So I think that's a consequence of, you know, gaining knowledge.

00:41:57.160 --> 00:42:04.080
[Guest]: But I think then another, in terms of continuing this theme about my research, 2019 was a major

00:42:04.080 --> 00:42:11.480
[Guest]: step change because that's when I really engaged deeply with a debate around what's called

00:42:11.480 --> 00:42:12.680
[Guest]: the Great Divergence.

00:42:12.680 --> 00:42:17.200
[Guest]: So this is the rise of the West, the economic divergence in how some nations became rich

00:42:17.200 --> 00:42:19.320
[Guest]: and democratic and others didn't.

00:42:19.320 --> 00:42:20.600
[Guest]: And I found this fascinating.

00:42:20.600 --> 00:42:23.360
[Guest]: I like these big comparative questions.

00:42:23.360 --> 00:42:26.680
[Guest]: I was totally engrossed.

00:42:26.680 --> 00:42:32.760
[Guest]: And through maybe three months of reading this literature, reading absolutely everything,

00:42:32.760 --> 00:42:36.120
[Guest]: I was struck by something.

00:42:36.120 --> 00:42:45.200
[Guest]: I realised there was also what I call the Great Gender Divergence in that all countries

00:42:45.200 --> 00:42:51.960
[Guest]: are patriarchal, but we also see, if we look at objective, nationally representative indicators,

00:42:51.960 --> 00:42:56.160
[Guest]: that in the Middle East, North Africa and South Asia, it is men who grow out of their

00:42:56.160 --> 00:43:00.840
[Guest]: homes primarily to run family businesses, organise politically and make the laws of

00:43:00.840 --> 00:43:01.840
[Guest]: the land.

00:43:01.840 --> 00:43:07.360
[Guest]: In post-communist countries, Russia and China, women do work, but they're excluded from politics.

00:43:07.360 --> 00:43:12.600
[Guest]: Russian government and Chinese politics are almost exclusively male, whereas in Latin

00:43:12.600 --> 00:43:17.080
[Guest]: America, there's been this radical feminist transformation, soaring rates of female employment,

00:43:17.080 --> 00:43:21.760
[Guest]: massive feminist rallies against gender-based violence, 11 legislatures now have gender

00:43:21.760 --> 00:43:22.760
[Guest]: parity.

00:43:22.760 --> 00:43:26.080
[Guest]: So it's converging with Europe, even though it was much more patriarchal.

00:43:26.080 --> 00:43:31.960
[Guest]: And now today, Scandinavia is one of the most gender equal places in the world.

00:43:31.960 --> 00:43:37.140
[Guest]: But for much of human history, it was far more patriarchal than bilateral and matrilineal

00:43:37.140 --> 00:43:41.700
[Guest]: Southeast Asia, the Andes, the Gulf of Guinea and Southern Africa.

00:43:41.700 --> 00:43:46.980
[Guest]: And so this, this is what I call the great gender divergence, this cultural heterogeneity

00:43:46.980 --> 00:43:53.200
[Guest]: across the world, notwithstanding, you know, and so and so I started to study why exactly

00:43:53.200 --> 00:43:54.240
[Guest]: that had happened.

00:43:54.240 --> 00:43:58.640
[Guest]: And so broadly, my argument is that the great gender divergence occurred primarily in the

00:43:58.640 --> 00:44:04.000
[Guest]: 20th century as a result of the enormous economic and political divergence, because with technology

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:08.800
[Guest]: and technological change and job creating economic growth, women seize those economic

00:44:08.800 --> 00:44:09.800
[Guest]: opportunities.

00:44:09.800 --> 00:44:15.160
[Guest]: We see soaring rates of female employment and advancement in both Europe, North America,

00:44:15.160 --> 00:44:16.440
[Guest]: and also East Asia.

00:44:16.440 --> 00:44:23.040
[Guest]: And by going out to factories, to jobs, women form friendships, and they start to challenge

00:44:23.040 --> 00:44:29.520
[Guest]: and criticise many of these patriarchal ideas and traditions, they develop a politics of

00:44:29.520 --> 00:44:30.520
[Guest]: solidarity.

00:44:30.520 --> 00:44:35.320
[Guest]: And these female friendships are the, the foundations of feminist activism, and women

00:44:35.320 --> 00:44:39.840
[Guest]: also seize political opportunities, so where there's democratisation, in South Korea, for

00:44:39.840 --> 00:44:44.360
[Guest]: example, women organise for Me Too, they organise in Latin America, they challenge these, their

00:44:44.360 --> 00:44:47.000
[Guest]: stigma and shame around rape.

00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:54.160
[Guest]: But the rate at which women seize those political economic opportunities is mediated by their

00:44:54.160 --> 00:44:55.160
[Guest]: culture.

00:44:55.160 --> 00:45:02.680
[Guest]: And so then I wanted to understand the enormous divergence and causes of why in some cultures,

00:45:02.680 --> 00:45:06.720
[Guest]: male labour supply rises weakly with economic jobs and opportunities, and so I can talk

00:45:06.720 --> 00:45:08.360
[Guest]: about that if you'd like.

00:45:08.360 --> 00:45:12.480
[Guest]: And so then I decided, I wrote to Princeton, and I had this big book proposal.

00:45:12.480 --> 00:45:19.240
[Guest]: And I said, listen, here is the most fundamental fact about humanity that we cannot answer.

00:45:19.240 --> 00:45:20.860
[Guest]: I want to study it.

00:45:20.860 --> 00:45:22.160
[Guest]: This is what I propose.

00:45:22.160 --> 00:45:26.400
[Guest]: I propose to study a history of every single country in the world.

00:45:26.400 --> 00:45:30.600
[Guest]: This has not been done before, but I believe I can do it.

00:45:30.600 --> 00:45:34.480
[Guest]: And at that time, you know, people did not believe that was possible.

00:45:34.480 --> 00:45:39.680
[Guest]: But you know, I'm someone who's made my own vagina, who's taught myself to become fluent

00:45:39.680 --> 00:45:44.880
[Guest]: in Bemba, and I pretty much believe I can do anything I want to, anything I put my mind

00:45:44.880 --> 00:45:45.880
[Guest]: to.

00:45:45.880 --> 00:45:48.920
[Guest]: I have learnt that with practice and perseverance, I can do it.

00:45:48.920 --> 00:45:53.240
[Guest]: And I thought this was an important project, and I wanted to give it a try.

00:45:53.240 --> 00:45:56.520
[Guest]: And so that's what I've been doing for almost three years now.

00:45:56.520 --> 00:46:00.980
[Guest]: And so I've come to India as part of that study to, you know, try to learn, to listen

00:46:00.980 --> 00:46:02.960
[Guest]: to different people traveling across India.

00:46:02.960 --> 00:46:08.680
[Guest]: You know, so while I've, you know, read much of the literature and understanding, you know,

00:46:08.680 --> 00:46:12.720
[Guest]: different academic perspectives, now I want to talk to people to hear their stories.

00:46:12.720 --> 00:46:19.880
[Guest]: So let me come back to your question, what makes me, what makes me so upbeat and optimistic?

00:46:19.880 --> 00:46:25.200
[Guest]: I think it's, I have pursued what's made me happy.

00:46:25.200 --> 00:46:35.520
[Guest]: I have liberated myself from forces and organizations that would try to restrict me, constrain me.

00:46:35.520 --> 00:46:43.440
[Guest]: I do what I enjoy, but I'm also enabled by incredible generosity, incredible kindness.

00:46:43.440 --> 00:46:50.120
[Guest]: Like I was saying earlier, when I was stuck in Jaipur, the father offered to, you know,

00:46:50.120 --> 00:46:51.120
[Guest]: drive me all the way.

00:46:51.120 --> 00:46:54.360
[Guest]: When I was stuck in Jaipur, the guy offered to drive me all the way to Udaipur.

00:46:54.360 --> 00:47:00.520
[Guest]: So it's people's support and kindness and encouragement, you know, I am not, I do not

00:47:00.520 --> 00:47:02.600
[Guest]: exist in a vacuum, all of this.

00:47:02.600 --> 00:47:09.240
[Guest]: And going back to Twitter, you know, I have received incredible support, encouragement,

00:47:09.240 --> 00:47:15.520
[Guest]: and that social reward, that social recognition has really helped me continue.

00:47:15.520 --> 00:47:18.940
[Guest]: You know, it's a lot of encouragement, a lot of support.

00:47:18.940 --> 00:47:20.440
[Guest]: So I'm happy in that respect.

00:47:20.440 --> 00:47:21.440
[Amit Varma]: Fascinating.

00:47:21.440 --> 00:47:24.640
[Amit Varma]: There's so much to double click on, but I'm just wondering if this gentleman in Jaipur

00:47:24.640 --> 00:47:28.480
[Amit Varma]: who offered to drive you, you should have told him, yeah, okay, drive me, he'd probably

00:47:28.480 --> 00:47:31.880
[Amit Varma]: have driven you to the bus stop and said, there's a bus, take that bus.

00:47:31.880 --> 00:47:33.640
[Amit Varma]: No, I'm kidding.

00:47:33.640 --> 00:47:35.240
[Amit Varma]: Lots to double click on here.

00:47:35.240 --> 00:47:39.200
[Amit Varma]: And I'll, you know, before we get to your work and the great gender divergence and all

00:47:39.200 --> 00:47:43.440
[Amit Varma]: of that, which we'll come to, before we get to that, you know, some more questions about

00:47:43.440 --> 00:47:44.440
[Amit Varma]: your personal journey.

00:47:44.440 --> 00:47:49.520
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things that I'm sort of struck by is how you bookended your wonderful answer

00:47:49.520 --> 00:47:52.760
[Amit Varma]: by talking about happiness.

00:47:52.760 --> 00:47:58.200
[Amit Varma]: And the sort of notion that you looked at it in an intentional way, you started by saying,

00:47:58.200 --> 00:48:01.100
[Amit Varma]: I decided to be happy, right?

00:48:01.100 --> 00:48:02.100
[Amit Varma]: As an act of intentionality.

00:48:02.100 --> 00:48:07.680
[Amit Varma]: Later on, when you speak about college, you spoke about how you realized that any skill

00:48:07.680 --> 00:48:09.000
[Amit Varma]: can be learned.

00:48:09.000 --> 00:48:12.920
[Amit Varma]: So you could almost shape yourself by learning the stuff that you were learning, you know,

00:48:12.920 --> 00:48:16.840
[Amit Varma]: and then you go to Zambia, and you learn Bemba, though, I have to tell you that if I try to

00:48:16.840 --> 00:48:22.600
[Amit Varma]: teach myself a language by drawing something for every word, I would just be babbling,

00:48:22.600 --> 00:48:24.440
[Amit Varma]: because I'm really bad at drawing.

00:48:24.440 --> 00:48:28.120
[Amit Varma]: So I guess you're good at drawing as well, which is, again, in the time that you learn

00:48:28.120 --> 00:48:32.400
[Amit Varma]: philosophy, one of the and I'll ask you about each of them, I won't ask you about freewill,

00:48:32.400 --> 00:48:33.880
[Amit Varma]: I'll ask you about metaethics.

00:48:33.880 --> 00:48:40.080
[Amit Varma]: But one thing that you mentioned was how you sort of realized that identity isn't a fixed

00:48:40.080 --> 00:48:44.180
[Amit Varma]: thing, who you are isn't a fixed thing, you know, which is a theme I keep going back to

00:48:44.180 --> 00:48:51.040
[Amit Varma]: on how it's contingent, not just on perhaps on circumstance, but also on little things

00:48:51.040 --> 00:48:54.880
[Amit Varma]: like the chemical composition of your brain, or what did you have to eat that particular

00:48:54.880 --> 00:48:58.680
[Amit Varma]: morning, if something is off a little bit, you're a different person entirely.

00:48:58.680 --> 00:49:04.680
[Amit Varma]: And that speaks to also this effort you're talking about, of sort of building yourself

00:49:04.680 --> 00:49:09.520
[Amit Varma]: deciding to be happy, deciding to be good at x, deciding to be good at y, deciding to

00:49:09.520 --> 00:49:11.720
[Amit Varma]: follow all of these different things.

00:49:11.720 --> 00:49:17.200
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about that, because sometimes when you know, I think in my, you

00:49:17.200 --> 00:49:22.280
[Amit Varma]: know, extremely negative, pessimistic way about identity, and so on, I sometimes wonder

00:49:22.280 --> 00:49:27.000
[Amit Varma]: if somebody says something good about me, that, you know, that does this person know

00:49:27.000 --> 00:49:30.680
[Amit Varma]: that I'm really winging it, that all this isn't real.

00:49:30.680 --> 00:49:35.080
[Amit Varma]: And then of course, the question at the back of that is that what is real?

00:49:35.080 --> 00:49:41.000
[Amit Varma]: If everything is kind of constructed, either consciously or otherwise, by you, and most

00:49:41.000 --> 00:49:45.960
[Amit Varma]: people, they are who they are kind of by default, they don't think too hard about this stuff.

00:49:45.960 --> 00:49:50.280
[Amit Varma]: They think happiness is something that happens, not something that you can cause yourself

00:49:50.280 --> 00:49:52.120
[Amit Varma]: to be right.

00:49:52.120 --> 00:49:59.120
[Amit Varma]: So what are sort of your thoughts on becoming who you are, you know, especially when you

00:49:59.120 --> 00:50:03.220
[Amit Varma]: realize through your study of philosophy that it's all fragile, you know, that you could

00:50:03.220 --> 00:50:06.040
[Amit Varma]: just grow older and get dementia and forget everything.

00:50:06.040 --> 00:50:10.080
[Amit Varma]: And if you forget everything, who are you, you know, you're back to nothing, except you

00:50:10.080 --> 00:50:12.320
[Amit Varma]: no longer have the tools to build it back.

00:50:12.320 --> 00:50:17.840
[Amit Varma]: So what's your sense of how your identity evolved when you look back at yourself?

00:50:17.840 --> 00:50:18.840
[Amit Varma]: What do you like?

00:50:18.840 --> 00:50:19.840
[Amit Varma]: What do you not like?

00:50:19.840 --> 00:50:23.200
[Amit Varma]: When you think of who you are, you know, sort of what are your feelings?

00:50:23.200 --> 00:50:24.280
[Amit Varma]: What did you want to be?

00:50:24.280 --> 00:50:29.240
[Amit Varma]: How did you see that, you know, perception of yourself sort of changing with time?

00:50:29.240 --> 00:50:32.680
[Guest]: I liked your question, what did I not like about my past?

00:50:32.680 --> 00:50:37.680
[Guest]: You know, what aspects of Alice Evans were less good in the past?

00:50:37.680 --> 00:50:46.040
[Unknown]: I think perhaps in the past, I might have allowed myself to be shy, to be nervous, to

00:50:46.040 --> 00:50:48.960
[Guest]: be easily intimidated.

00:50:48.960 --> 00:50:53.520
[Guest]: And I've overcome that in the way through encouragement from others.

00:50:53.520 --> 00:50:59.800
[Guest]: So I remember after my PhD and postdoc at the LSE, I went to Cambridge, and I was very

00:50:59.800 --> 00:51:00.800
[Guest]: nervous.

00:51:00.800 --> 00:51:02.640
[Guest]: I was very intimidated.

00:51:02.640 --> 00:51:07.200
[Guest]: But I had a wonderful colleague, Emma Maudsley, and she said, listen, there's just this Cambridge

00:51:07.200 --> 00:51:08.200
[Guest]: myth.

00:51:08.200 --> 00:51:11.680
[Guest]: These are just normal people, don't be intimidated.

00:51:11.680 --> 00:51:14.580
[Guest]: And that support and encouragement made me feel okay.

00:51:14.580 --> 00:51:16.320
[Guest]: And so I could engage with them.

00:51:16.320 --> 00:51:21.520
[Guest]: So that I mean, you know, right now, I may strike you as this confident, bubbly person.

00:51:21.520 --> 00:51:24.000
[Guest]: But this has been an incremental journey.

00:51:24.000 --> 00:51:31.720
[Guest]: It's about trying something, taking a risk, being supported by others and realising I

00:51:31.720 --> 00:51:34.540
[Guest]: can do it and then thriving.

00:51:34.540 --> 00:51:38.520
[Guest]: So I think, you know, that so I was not always this confident.

00:51:38.520 --> 00:51:42.400
[Guest]: I mean, there was a period when I think I was about 13.

00:51:42.400 --> 00:51:47.800
[Guest]: And this was a result of my father's bullying, that I barely spoke, all I did really was

00:51:47.800 --> 00:51:48.800
[Guest]: just apologise.

00:51:48.800 --> 00:51:50.480
[Guest]: I just say, I'm sorry.

00:51:50.480 --> 00:51:53.480
[Guest]: You know, that's what happens when you live with a bully, right?

00:51:53.480 --> 00:52:02.280
[Guest]: So it's not like I've always been this, you know, go get in feisty, independent mind.

00:52:02.280 --> 00:52:03.680
[Guest]: I mean, let me give you another example.

00:52:03.680 --> 00:52:06.480
[Guest]: So I run my own podcast.

00:52:06.480 --> 00:52:11.200
[Guest]: Not as successful as yours, but I started it when I was in Cambridge, because even then

00:52:11.200 --> 00:52:16.260
[Guest]: I was relatively confident, but I knew that there were a number of other amazingly brilliant

00:52:16.260 --> 00:52:23.800
[Guest]: minds who might be shyer and more worried about self promotion, they, you know, reluctant

00:52:23.800 --> 00:52:24.920
[Guest]: to put themselves out there.

00:52:24.920 --> 00:52:28.360
[Guest]: And I thought that's a net loss for the world, because we're not hearing their brilliant

00:52:28.360 --> 00:52:29.360
[Guest]: ideas.

00:52:29.360 --> 00:52:31.700
[Guest]: So let me set up a podcast and let me interview them.

00:52:31.700 --> 00:52:35.640
[Guest]: So I was doing all these interviews with academics, and I wanted to highlight their research.

00:52:35.640 --> 00:52:39.760
[Guest]: And this is also part of my, my love and excitement for learning.

00:52:39.760 --> 00:52:46.200
[Guest]: So the other day, I did a very nice, I met at their conference in Udaipur, I met Soumya

00:52:46.200 --> 00:52:48.360
[Guest]: Dhanaraja and Vidya Mahambre.

00:52:48.360 --> 00:52:50.120
[Guest]: They told me about this research they just done.

00:52:50.120 --> 00:52:52.420
[Guest]: And so they that very day, I say, hey, let's do a podcast.

00:52:52.420 --> 00:52:53.480
[Guest]: This is great.

00:52:53.480 --> 00:52:54.480
[Guest]: And they were a little bit nervous.

00:52:54.480 --> 00:52:55.480
[Guest]: You know, they were worried.

00:52:55.480 --> 00:52:57.000
[Guest]: They hadn't done a podcast before.

00:52:57.000 --> 00:52:58.000
[Guest]: But I was encouraged.

00:52:58.000 --> 00:52:59.940
[Guest]: I said, listen, your work is fascinating.

00:52:59.940 --> 00:53:01.920
[Guest]: I want people to hear about this.

00:53:01.920 --> 00:53:06.720
[Guest]: And so that's why I started the podcast to share brilliant ideas.

00:53:06.720 --> 00:53:14.840
[Guest]: But even when I was doing that podcast, I was often deferential to my guests.

00:53:14.840 --> 00:53:22.280
[Guest]: I was, even if I was privately critical, I was reluctant to say, I don't think that's

00:53:22.280 --> 00:53:23.280
[Guest]: possible.

00:53:23.280 --> 00:53:24.280
[Guest]: I don't think that's persuasive.

00:53:24.280 --> 00:53:26.640
[Guest]: I didn't want to embarrass them in that spot.

00:53:26.640 --> 00:53:28.560
[Guest]: I didn't want to be too aggressive.

00:53:28.560 --> 00:53:35.360
[Guest]: I've always been, and this is possibly a consequence of my father, I've been incredibly uncomfortable

00:53:35.360 --> 00:53:36.360
[Guest]: with conflict.

00:53:36.360 --> 00:53:37.920
[Guest]: I don't like personal conflict.

00:53:37.920 --> 00:53:39.320
[Guest]: It makes me tense up.

00:53:39.320 --> 00:53:42.560
[Guest]: If someone is abusive or horrible to me, I'm just silent.

00:53:42.560 --> 00:53:44.040
[Guest]: I'm silent.

00:53:44.040 --> 00:53:45.040
[Guest]: I don't say anything.

00:53:45.040 --> 00:53:46.720
[Guest]: I don't speak back.

00:53:46.720 --> 00:53:54.960
[Guest]: And in my podcast previously, in my earlier episodes of my podcast, I did not challenge

00:53:54.960 --> 00:54:00.240
[Guest]: my guests because I didn't want to be too conflictual, I was worried they wouldn't like

00:54:00.240 --> 00:54:01.240
[Guest]: it.

00:54:01.240 --> 00:54:07.560
[Guest]: And actually some male guests did react, sorry, yeah.

00:54:07.560 --> 00:54:13.720
[Guest]: And so then a kind friend said to me, listen, I was listening to your podcast and I think

00:54:13.720 --> 00:54:16.840
[Guest]: sometimes you disagree with them, but you don't say it.

00:54:16.840 --> 00:54:22.440
[Guest]: And I think that's common for many people, especially women that we're reluctant to challenge.

00:54:22.440 --> 00:54:27.480
[Guest]: And they said to me and they were really encouraging and supportive and they were like, listen,

00:54:27.480 --> 00:54:34.400
[Guest]: you've read this material, you know your stuff, you can express yourself and push them.

00:54:34.400 --> 00:54:38.240
[Guest]: And people enjoy that, people like a feisty podcast.

00:54:38.240 --> 00:54:43.280
[Guest]: And I did that increasingly and I think, but it really depends on the guest.

00:54:43.280 --> 00:54:48.340
[Guest]: So for example, one of my great, one of my very close, my best friends, he's very kind

00:54:48.340 --> 00:54:52.680
[Guest]: and he's very supportive and whatever I say to him, he never is aggressive or hostile,

00:54:52.680 --> 00:54:54.680
[Guest]: but other male guests have been.

00:54:54.680 --> 00:54:59.680
[Guest]: So I once interviewed a professor who I won't name, but, and I challenged him on this podcast

00:54:59.680 --> 00:55:02.880
[Guest]: and afterwards he sent me this hostile email.

00:55:02.880 --> 00:55:08.960
[Guest]: He did not like that, he was like, well, I didn't know about your views and I, why were

00:55:08.960 --> 00:55:09.960
[Guest]: you taking me to task?

00:55:09.960 --> 00:55:11.920
[Guest]: And I was like, well, you could have read about my research.

00:55:11.920 --> 00:55:16.600
[Guest]: Anyway, he was upset and there was a backlash about me challenging him, but anyway.

00:55:16.600 --> 00:55:24.400
[Guest]: So my point is, my rambling point is that I was initially, even despite all those debate

00:55:24.400 --> 00:55:30.760
[Guest]: clubs, despite all that independent travel, I was previously much more cautious, much

00:55:30.760 --> 00:55:36.760
[Guest]: shyer, much less reluctant, more reluctant to rock the boat and challenge things, more,

00:55:36.760 --> 00:55:37.760
[Guest]: you know, quieter.

00:55:37.760 --> 00:55:45.680
[Guest]: But it's something that I've learned that many people may try to, you know, assert themselves.

00:55:45.680 --> 00:55:50.960
[Guest]: And part of, you know, developing an open dialogue and a more egalitarian relationship

00:55:50.960 --> 00:55:53.160
[Guest]: is to assert oneself.

00:55:53.160 --> 00:55:56.400
[Guest]: And so I can draw a brilliant example from the Gulf of Guinea.

00:55:56.400 --> 00:56:03.480
[Guest]: So in the Gulf of Guinea, there was, there were women always had in Yoruba and Igbo,

00:56:03.480 --> 00:56:09.400
[Guest]: Asante and in Cameroon as well, women had their own independent networks and they use

00:56:09.400 --> 00:56:14.640
[Guest]: that female solidarity to challenge men that would try to transgress or try to challenge

00:56:14.640 --> 00:56:16.160
[Guest]: their autonomy and authority.

00:56:16.160 --> 00:56:19.960
[Guest]: In Cameroon, they would even say, you know, a man dare not even steal an egg from his

00:56:19.960 --> 00:56:24.000
[Guest]: wife's chicken coop because these women, you know, gender relations aren't set in stone.

00:56:24.000 --> 00:56:27.400
[Guest]: It depends on women mobilizing, protecting their entitlements.

00:56:27.400 --> 00:56:31.440
[Guest]: And that's, and that is something that I've learned to do.

00:56:31.440 --> 00:56:33.680
[Guest]: It's a skill I've developed.

00:56:33.680 --> 00:56:34.760
[Unknown]: Yes.

00:56:34.760 --> 00:56:41.480
[Guest]: So that's a, so, so to answer your question, what do I not like about the old Alice Evans

00:56:41.480 --> 00:56:48.840
[Guest]: is that not so much to dislike, but I've learned how to be more confident and more assertive

00:56:48.840 --> 00:56:50.560
[Guest]: in myself.

00:56:50.560 --> 00:57:00.160
[Guest]: And I've learned also to be more diplomatic and to learn the ways in which it's possible.

00:57:00.160 --> 00:57:05.480
[Guest]: And I've learned how to get along or cultivate, you know, get along with a diverse group of

00:57:05.480 --> 00:57:06.480
[Guest]: people.

00:57:06.480 --> 00:57:08.680
[Guest]: And that's come through, you know, traveling the world, meeting lots of different people.

00:57:08.680 --> 00:57:16.320
[Unknown]: So I've learned diplomacy and I've learned assertion, I'd say.

00:57:16.320 --> 00:57:20.320
[Amit Varma]: Early on, you know, in your first answer, you spoke about how, when your dad filed for

00:57:20.320 --> 00:57:23.600
[Amit Varma]: divorce, you was just so delighted that this shit is over.

00:57:23.600 --> 00:57:28.400
[Amit Varma]: Later, you spoke about Cambodia and about how these women would go to factories and

00:57:28.400 --> 00:57:34.040
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, they'd be, you know, staying, staying with next to other women like them.

00:57:34.040 --> 00:57:37.200
[Amit Varma]: And they'd hear another woman say that, oh, my husband shares his housework.

00:57:37.200 --> 00:57:41.800
[Amit Varma]: Then you spoke about this young lady who demanded the same of her husband and divorced him,

00:57:41.800 --> 00:57:44.280
[Amit Varma]: you know, which is again, a cause for celebration.

00:57:44.280 --> 00:57:50.440
[Amit Varma]: I once I think 13 years ago, I wrote a column about how the best metric we can use in India

00:57:50.440 --> 00:57:54.640
[Amit Varma]: to show whether women are progressing or not is rising divorce rates, which I felt was

00:57:54.640 --> 00:57:55.640
[Amit Varma]: great.

00:57:55.640 --> 00:57:59.240
[Amit Varma]: The higher they go, the better they are, because it shows that women are getting more empowered.

00:57:59.240 --> 00:58:03.360
[Amit Varma]: But a larger question I have for you, and we'll, of course, talk about all your research

00:58:03.360 --> 00:58:09.120
[Amit Varma]: and all your work in detail, but the larger question that I have is that isn't marriage

00:58:09.120 --> 00:58:10.240
[Amit Varma]: toxic?

00:58:10.240 --> 00:58:12.920
[Amit Varma]: Isn't marriage fundamentally toxic, especially for women?

00:58:12.920 --> 00:58:14.360
[Amit Varma]: It's convenient for men.

00:58:14.360 --> 00:58:15.360
[Amit Varma]: But isn't it toxic?

00:58:15.360 --> 00:58:20.280
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, when you look at the larger arc of history, like what you've done so beautifully

00:58:20.280 --> 00:58:26.040
[Amit Varma]: through all your writings and your essays, is talk about how all our norms, all the ways

00:58:26.040 --> 00:58:31.240
[Amit Varma]: that we behave, the structures in society are shaped by things like geography and economics

00:58:31.240 --> 00:58:33.240
[Amit Varma]: and different kinds of circumstance.

00:58:33.240 --> 00:58:38.720
[Amit Varma]: And so the change that we see through the decades and centuries seems agonizingly slow,

00:58:38.720 --> 00:58:40.160
[Amit Varma]: extremely incremental.

00:58:40.160 --> 00:58:47.000
[Amit Varma]: But I'm going to ask you to take a leap now, and imagine maybe two 300 years later.

00:58:47.000 --> 00:58:51.560
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that marriage in many ways, especially in the ways that we think of it

00:58:51.560 --> 00:58:53.760
[Amit Varma]: is already redundant.

00:58:53.760 --> 00:58:58.260
[Amit Varma]: And there is an acceptance of it, which is a lagging acceptance, and it'll take a long

00:58:58.260 --> 00:59:03.320
[Amit Varma]: time to play out, but it simply doesn't make sense, especially for women, especially in

00:59:03.320 --> 00:59:04.680
[Guest]: the shape that it is now.

00:59:04.680 --> 00:59:07.520
[Guest]: Okay, let me answer that with three points.

00:59:07.520 --> 00:59:08.520
[Guest]: Point number one.

00:59:08.520 --> 00:59:10.080
[Guest]: No, I do not believe that marriage is toxic.

00:59:10.080 --> 00:59:14.280
[Guest]: I've met many people in wonderfully happy, supportive, loving relationships, you know,

00:59:14.280 --> 00:59:16.840
[Guest]: the experience of love, it can be found.

00:59:16.840 --> 00:59:18.400
[Amit Varma]: I don't mean every marriage is toxic.

00:59:18.400 --> 00:59:22.560
[Amit Varma]: I mean, the notion, the concept of marriage, the way people look at it, both men and women.

00:59:22.560 --> 00:59:30.760
[Guest]: I think marriage can cultivate hierarchies and inequalities if several conditions are

00:59:30.760 --> 00:59:31.760
[Guest]: met.

00:59:31.760 --> 00:59:39.360
[Guest]: One is if, one, the cultural valorization of marriage as the most important end point

00:59:39.360 --> 00:59:44.040
[Guest]: for a woman means that women can be constantly striving and desperate for that marriage.

00:59:44.040 --> 00:59:48.400
[Guest]: So, Shrayana has a wonderful book, Desperately Seeking Shahrukh.

00:59:48.400 --> 00:59:53.720
[Guest]: And she highlights how, and also there's a fantastic book on India called Chup, when

00:59:53.720 --> 00:59:57.080
[Guest]: it's about, you know, women being socialized for marriage and believing that, you know,

00:59:57.080 --> 00:59:59.640
[Guest]: going to marriage is the most important thing.

00:59:59.640 --> 01:00:05.600
[Guest]: And if women who fail to achieve that are somehow defunct and flawed, and that can

01:00:05.600 --> 01:00:10.400
[Guest]: trigger, you know, that social policing means that women might, you know, opt for the wrong,

01:00:10.400 --> 01:00:14.720
[Guest]: for someone who doesn't make them happy and remain in an abusive relationship.

01:00:14.720 --> 01:00:17.320
[Guest]: So it's one, the cultural valorization of marriage.

01:00:17.320 --> 01:00:22.280
[Guest]: Two, it's the dearth of economic opportunities that might make women reluctant to leave that

01:00:22.280 --> 01:00:23.960
[Guest]: abusive marriage.

01:00:23.960 --> 01:00:30.160
[Guest]: And three, if divorce rates are very low, then we're, and if there's strong social policing,

01:00:30.160 --> 01:00:32.800
[Guest]: women may believe that they can't exist alone.

01:00:32.800 --> 01:00:39.200
[Guest]: So for, and we see this across, so there's this, Bijou has a great paper on terrorism

01:00:39.200 --> 01:00:44.840
[Guest]: and dowry deaths and his argument, as I recall, it's from Karnataka, he talks about women

01:00:44.840 --> 01:00:50.440
[Guest]: being reluctant, women getting married, then their husband's family exploiting her and

01:00:50.440 --> 01:00:55.080
[Guest]: beating her up to leverage more dowry and her not leaving because of fear of social

01:00:55.080 --> 01:01:01.860
[Guest]: policing, the failure, you know, the condemnation of a divorced woman.

01:01:01.860 --> 01:01:06.600
[Guest]: So it's the condemnation of divorce and the dearth of economic options, and also women's

01:01:06.600 --> 01:01:13.240
[Guest]: fear that they cannot manage alone means that women continue in many of those abusive, unhappy

01:01:13.240 --> 01:01:14.240
[Guest]: relationships.

01:01:14.240 --> 01:01:22.040
[Guest]: So those conditions can cultivate hierarchy, you know, the unquestioned inequalities and

01:01:22.040 --> 01:01:23.280
[Guest]: the lack of exit options.

01:01:23.280 --> 01:01:24.280
[Guest]: And that's it.

01:01:24.280 --> 01:01:28.480
[Guest]: And let me add a third point that even in societies where marriage rates are low and

01:01:28.480 --> 01:01:32.560
[Guest]: where women do divorce, that doesn't get you to gender equality.

01:01:32.560 --> 01:01:38.000
[Guest]: So let me give you the example of the Soviet Union, where as a result of the communist

01:01:38.000 --> 01:01:41.600
[Guest]: model of extensive growth, there's very high female employment, there continues to be very

01:01:41.600 --> 01:01:47.040
[Guest]: high female employment, there continues to be a high number of female headed households.

01:01:47.040 --> 01:01:52.080
[Guest]: So many women have chosen, you know, that many women have chosen to exist independently,

01:01:52.080 --> 01:01:54.440
[Guest]: and they can because they're economically autonomous.

01:01:54.440 --> 01:02:00.920
[Guest]: But still, because totalitarian communism suffocated feminist activism, there is very

01:02:00.920 --> 01:02:06.040
[Guest]: weak feminist activism, and women are not represented in the corridors of power.

01:02:06.040 --> 01:02:08.840
[Guest]: And the Russian government continues to discriminate against women.

01:02:08.840 --> 01:02:11.760
[Guest]: So there are weak protections against gender based violence.

01:02:11.760 --> 01:02:16.400
[Guest]: So a couple of years ago, the Russian parliament actually decriminalized domestic battery.

01:02:16.400 --> 01:02:20.840
[Guest]: So even if a woman is living, it's not about you yourself, whether you choose to get married

01:02:20.840 --> 01:02:21.840
[Guest]: or not.

01:02:21.840 --> 01:02:25.040
[Guest]: It's about the social and political environment that enables gender equality.

01:02:25.040 --> 01:02:28.680
[Guest]: So I will come out and say marriage can be totally fine and loving and wonderful and

01:02:28.680 --> 01:02:29.680
[Guest]: happy.

01:02:29.680 --> 01:02:32.960
[Guest]: There is a range of other social and political conditions that are also important.

01:02:32.960 --> 01:02:37.360
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I'm kind of thinking looking ahead that assuming that the arc of human history goes

01:02:37.360 --> 01:02:39.360
[Guest]: towards progress and goes towards a nicer place.

01:02:39.360 --> 01:02:42.760
[Guest]: Oh yeah, I need to come back to your 300 years question, and I need to play the pessimist

01:02:42.760 --> 01:02:43.760
[Amit Varma]: here.

01:02:43.760 --> 01:02:44.760
[Guest]: Go ahead.

01:02:44.760 --> 01:02:45.760
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:02:45.760 --> 01:02:51.320
[Guest]: Okay, so I think that, so the reason I call my book, The Great Gender Divergence, is that

01:02:51.320 --> 01:02:56.720
[Guest]: some countries have become much more gender equal, whereas in others, we see far slower

01:02:56.720 --> 01:02:58.720
[Guest]: transitions to gender equality.

01:02:58.720 --> 01:03:03.320
[Guest]: So despite rising growth, in much of the Middle East, North Africa and South Asia, we still

01:03:03.320 --> 01:03:05.720
[Guest]: see very low rates of female employment, for example.

01:03:05.720 --> 01:03:08.040
[Guest]: So that is what they call the divergence.

01:03:08.040 --> 01:03:11.280
[Guest]: And there are reasons to think that that divergence might persist.

01:03:11.280 --> 01:03:15.120
[Guest]: And let me highlight three things that pose a risk.

01:03:15.120 --> 01:03:17.840
[Guest]: One is rising authoritarianism.

01:03:17.840 --> 01:03:26.280
[Guest]: So gender equality is partly a matter of challenging patriarchal ideals, challenging ideas that

01:03:26.280 --> 01:03:32.360
[Guest]: women should fast for their husbands, challenging ideas that women should perform subservience

01:03:32.360 --> 01:03:36.040
[Guest]: by doing everything for their husband, doing the housework for their husbands, etc.

01:03:36.040 --> 01:03:41.280
[Guest]: And that happens through debate, you know, what Amartya Sen calls the argumentative Indian.

01:03:41.280 --> 01:03:46.560
[Guest]: And that flourishes in conditions where there is open debate, where there is free thought.

01:03:46.560 --> 01:03:52.040
[Guest]: And so rising authoritarianism, which we now see across much of the world, can stifle that

01:03:52.040 --> 01:03:54.720
[Guest]: public debate because people become more reluctant to speak out.

01:03:54.720 --> 01:04:00.600
[Guest]: And so it's not even suppression of civil debate more broadly, it has a silencing effect

01:04:00.600 --> 01:04:05.200
[Guest]: on feminist activism because it it mutes that culture of resistance, which is hugely important.

01:04:05.200 --> 01:04:09.880
[Guest]: So where we see rising authoritarianism, we should expect to slow any kind of cultural

01:04:09.880 --> 01:04:10.880
[Guest]: change.

01:04:10.880 --> 01:04:12.520
[Guest]: And what's second point.

01:04:12.520 --> 01:04:16.480
[Guest]: And so, for example, in China, even though there are very high rates of female employment,

01:04:16.480 --> 01:04:23.080
[Guest]: even though women are enormously successful in business, crackdowns on Me Too, media blackouts,

01:04:23.080 --> 01:04:28.200
[Guest]: media blackouts on Weibo and WeChat mean that many people regard sexual harassment and abuse

01:04:28.200 --> 01:04:29.440
[Guest]: as inevitable.

01:04:29.440 --> 01:04:31.240
[Guest]: And it is very difficult.

01:04:31.240 --> 01:04:33.760
[Guest]: So debate is absolutely critical.

01:04:33.760 --> 01:04:36.080
[Guest]: Open debate is hugely important.

01:04:36.080 --> 01:04:41.000
[Guest]: Second issue is a primary driver of rising female employment is job creating economic

01:04:41.000 --> 01:04:42.000
[Guest]: growth.

01:04:42.000 --> 01:04:44.360
[Guest]: But there are two obstacles to that.

01:04:44.360 --> 01:04:46.040
[Guest]: One is climate breakdown.

01:04:46.040 --> 01:04:49.280
[Guest]: Climate breakdown, absolutely, as you know, and I don't even need to argue this point

01:04:49.280 --> 01:04:51.460
[Guest]: is going to suppress job creation, right?

01:04:51.460 --> 01:04:56.360
[Guest]: It's going to suppress economic growth through one environmental disasters, destruction of

01:04:56.360 --> 01:05:01.720
[Guest]: physical infrastructure, and also high temperatures, which make it impossible to learn to acquire

01:05:01.720 --> 01:05:03.720
[Guest]: human capital to be productive.

01:05:03.720 --> 01:05:06.320
[Guest]: And so that will make it so much harder.

01:05:06.320 --> 01:05:15.720
[Guest]: Third issue is automation, especially if our institutions continue to allow job killing

01:05:15.720 --> 01:05:16.720
[Guest]: automation.

01:05:16.720 --> 01:05:19.640
[Guest]: Automation doesn't necessarily need to kill jobs, it could augment labor.

01:05:19.640 --> 01:05:25.260
[Guest]: But if our institution, so for example, in India, female labor force participation in

01:05:25.260 --> 01:05:29.480
[Guest]: rural areas has declined as a result of mechanization of agriculture.

01:05:29.480 --> 01:05:37.280
[Guest]: So you know, if you have mechanization in ways that reduce demand for labor in Bangladeshi

01:05:37.280 --> 01:05:42.480
[Guest]: families, we've seen in factories, rather, since 2013, Bangladeshi factories have hired

01:05:42.480 --> 01:05:47.700
[Guest]: fewer laborers, they've hired fewer low skilled laborers, because they've increasingly mechanized.

01:05:47.700 --> 01:05:55.920
[Guest]: So if we have authoritarianism, or job killing automation, and also climate breakdown, then

01:05:55.920 --> 01:06:01.280
[Guest]: that means that we're caught in what I call this patrilineal trap, that if the available

01:06:01.280 --> 01:06:06.580
[Guest]: female earnings do not compensate for male honor, then women will continue to remain

01:06:06.580 --> 01:06:08.080
[Guest]: at home.

01:06:08.080 --> 01:06:12.080
[Guest]: And so that would be the story for South Asia, North Africa, and the Middle East, whereas

01:06:12.080 --> 01:06:18.360
[Guest]: in Africa, which in much of Africa, like in Zambia, where I was, women will be trapped

01:06:18.360 --> 01:06:23.080
[Guest]: in rural poverty, and they will continue to bear many children, their families will not

01:06:23.080 --> 01:06:25.580
[Guest]: have the money to educate them.

01:06:25.580 --> 01:06:30.120
[Guest]: So they will quit school at 16, bear lots of children and struggle to acquire the assets,

01:06:30.120 --> 01:06:33.840
[Guest]: the resources to challenge dominant men to go to the cities where they learn about all

01:06:33.840 --> 01:06:34.840
[Guest]: these different ideas.

01:06:34.840 --> 01:06:38.440
[Guest]: You know, I am not going to, you know, everyone wants to know what will happen in the future.

01:06:38.440 --> 01:06:40.060
[Guest]: And I'm not, and that's alchemy, right?

01:06:40.060 --> 01:06:42.640
[Guest]: We cannot know, there's so much chaos and contingency.

01:06:42.640 --> 01:06:47.620
[Guest]: But there are three reasons to think that great divergence will continue.

01:06:47.620 --> 01:06:48.620
[Amit Varma]: So there I am the pessimist.

01:06:48.620 --> 01:06:53.080
[Amit Varma]: I just, yeah, it's, it's a terrifying moment, because there's great cognitive dissonance,

01:06:53.080 --> 01:06:57.160
[Amit Varma]: because I just realized that I'm optimistic on all three points you mentioned, but optimistic

01:06:57.160 --> 01:06:58.160
[Amit Varma]: in the long term.

01:06:58.160 --> 01:07:03.120
[Amit Varma]: I think in the short term and the medium term, I'm quite, I think the outlook is bleak, but

01:07:03.120 --> 01:07:08.800
[Amit Varma]: I'm optimistic briefly in the long term, because, you know, as far as authoritarianism is concerned,

01:07:08.800 --> 01:07:12.480
[Amit Varma]: I think, I hope that we're not doomed to this forever.

01:07:12.480 --> 01:07:14.520
[Amit Varma]: And technology empowers individuals.

01:07:14.520 --> 01:07:18.720
[Amit Varma]: And hopefully, we'll find a way out of this as far as climate change is concerned.

01:07:18.720 --> 01:07:20.560
[Amit Varma]: I think in the long run, we will solve it.

01:07:20.560 --> 01:07:25.760
[Amit Varma]: I have enough faith in human ingenuity, we've come through other crisis before.

01:07:25.760 --> 01:07:30.080
[Amit Varma]: And if we don't, well, you know, what's a big deal of one species vanishes.

01:07:30.080 --> 01:07:32.560
[Amit Varma]: And you know, adapting nuclear energy would just go a long way.

01:07:32.560 --> 01:07:36.160
[Amit Varma]: I mean, the campaign against nuclear is, you know, utterly daft, and I've spoken about

01:07:36.160 --> 01:07:38.880
[Amit Varma]: it very often on this podcast.

01:07:38.880 --> 01:07:42.000
[Amit Varma]: I'm not so worried about, you know, economic growth, either.

01:07:42.000 --> 01:07:43.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:07:43.000 --> 01:07:46.720
[Amit Varma]: And I'm not, I'm not that worried about automation, either, because that's been a common concern

01:07:46.720 --> 01:07:51.620
[Amit Varma]: throughout history, that, you know, machines will take away the job of humans, but any

01:07:51.620 --> 01:07:53.160
[Amit Varma]: disruption is temporary.

01:07:53.160 --> 01:07:58.920
[Amit Varma]: And in the end, productivity goes up, and it just works out for everybody's better.

01:07:58.920 --> 01:08:01.960
[Amit Varma]: But even if I were to agree with you on all of these,

01:08:01.960 --> 01:08:06.000
[Guest]: I just clarify, I'm not, I would not want to say what I think will happen.

01:08:06.000 --> 01:08:08.080
[Unknown]: All I'm posing is three risks.

01:08:08.080 --> 01:08:09.560
[Unknown]: Those are three risks.

01:08:09.560 --> 01:08:12.040
[Guest]: And other people can assess whether or not they will happen.

01:08:12.040 --> 01:08:16.760
[Guest]: All I'm saying, if those three things happen, then you should not expect a greater gender

01:08:16.760 --> 01:08:17.760
[Amit Varma]: I get it.

01:08:17.760 --> 01:08:20.000
[Amit Varma]: You're not forecasting and neither am I for that matter.

01:08:20.000 --> 01:08:26.040
[Amit Varma]: But even assuming that these risks were to hold us back, it's an argument against, you

01:08:26.040 --> 01:08:29.000
[Amit Varma]: know, that perhaps we may not progress to where we hope to progress.

01:08:29.000 --> 01:08:34.080
[Amit Varma]: But my question was more like, if we do progress to where we progress in a thought experiment

01:08:34.080 --> 01:08:38.720
[Amit Varma]: where you know, the gender divergence sort of ends that you get more or less equality

01:08:38.720 --> 01:08:44.920
[Amit Varma]: between genders, then I think a concept like marriage, the way we look at it today, along

01:08:44.920 --> 01:08:50.480
[Amit Varma]: with various other concepts, just it looks like one fixed template for a relationship,

01:08:50.480 --> 01:08:52.800
[Amit Varma]: which is skewed in one particular way.

01:08:52.800 --> 01:08:55.240
[Amit Varma]: And we need not follow this conventional template.

01:08:55.240 --> 01:08:59.000
[Amit Varma]: There are many other templates for how people relate to each other.

01:08:59.000 --> 01:09:04.060
[Amit Varma]: You know, in India, for example, people talk about the need for there to be a uniform civil

01:09:04.060 --> 01:09:05.060
[Amit Varma]: code.

01:09:05.060 --> 01:09:08.640
[Amit Varma]: And my point is, no matter what you feel of a uniform civil code, your ideal end state

01:09:08.640 --> 01:09:13.080
[Amit Varma]: in a thought experiment is where there is no civil code, where people make voluntary

01:09:13.080 --> 01:09:17.480
[Amit Varma]: contracts with each other with and voluntary agreements and live according to that.

01:09:17.480 --> 01:09:19.160
[Amit Varma]: Obviously, that's never going to happen.

01:09:19.160 --> 01:09:26.560
[Amit Varma]: It's it's at least not in a future I can foresee because society is just structured the way

01:09:26.560 --> 01:09:27.960
[Amit Varma]: that it is right.

01:09:27.960 --> 01:09:34.700
[Amit Varma]: And because of that, you do need protection for for women for different oppressed classes

01:09:34.700 --> 01:09:36.080
[Amit Varma]: within society.

01:09:36.080 --> 01:09:40.800
[Amit Varma]: But leaving that aside, moving on from sort of the question of, you know, marriage, which

01:09:40.800 --> 01:09:44.920
[Amit Varma]: we normalized, tell me a little bit more about your academic journey, that when you you know,

01:09:44.920 --> 01:09:50.120
[Amit Varma]: you get into academics, you've taken a very unconventional route to where you are, in

01:09:50.120 --> 01:09:55.640
[Amit Varma]: the sense that you haven't been formally trained as it were in these fields.

01:09:55.640 --> 01:10:00.160
[Amit Varma]: We'll talk about Twitter later, but you were set upon by a mob and I noticed one tweet

01:10:00.160 --> 01:10:04.400
[Amit Varma]: from somebody saying, Oh, she calls herself an ethnographer, but she hasn't studied ethnography.

01:10:04.400 --> 01:10:09.240
[Amit Varma]: She's done geography and this and that, to which my reaction, I mean, I just hate that

01:10:09.240 --> 01:10:10.840
[Amit Varma]: kind of credentialism.

01:10:10.840 --> 01:10:13.640
[Amit Varma]: My point always is you have to judge people by their work.

01:10:13.640 --> 01:10:16.340
[Amit Varma]: You know, I haven't done a PhD in podcasting either.

01:10:16.340 --> 01:10:21.400
[Amit Varma]: So fucking what and your work in that sense cannot speaks for itself.

01:10:21.400 --> 01:10:25.600
[Amit Varma]: But how did you navigate your way through academia as it were like earlier, you've

01:10:25.600 --> 01:10:29.880
[Amit Varma]: said, like, you know, in different episodes, I've spoken with academics about the great

01:10:29.880 --> 01:10:34.280
[Amit Varma]: academic circle jerk, where it's like you're caught in what Indians would call a chakravu.

01:10:34.280 --> 01:10:38.240
[Amit Varma]: That once you're playing that game, you're stuck in that game, you know, you've got to

01:10:38.240 --> 01:10:42.720
[Amit Varma]: get published in certain journals, speak a certain kind of language, there are topics

01:10:42.720 --> 01:10:44.960
[Amit Varma]: and themes that are fashionable.

01:10:44.960 --> 01:10:48.720
[Amit Varma]: And you know, some subjects will get you funding, other subjects won't.

01:10:48.720 --> 01:10:53.200
[Amit Varma]: And once you get stuck in that, it's just academics talking to other academics, you're

01:10:53.200 --> 01:10:54.800
[Guest]: not going out and engaging with the world.

01:10:54.800 --> 01:10:55.800
[Guest]: Right.

01:10:55.800 --> 01:10:56.800
[Guest]: But that's an active choice.

01:10:56.800 --> 01:10:58.840
[Guest]: So lots of people complain.

01:10:58.840 --> 01:11:00.480
[Guest]: So let me speak to two points.

01:11:00.480 --> 01:11:07.320
[Guest]: Firstly, I would say on the so my three formal degrees are one philosophy to international

01:11:07.320 --> 01:11:12.720
[Guest]: development three geography and the geography was geographies abroad field and then I studied

01:11:12.720 --> 01:11:16.720
[Guest]: qualitative research methods and that entire year was ethnography and I was living with

01:11:16.720 --> 01:11:17.720
[Guest]: families.

01:11:17.720 --> 01:11:18.720
[Guest]: I was fluent about me.

01:11:18.720 --> 01:11:20.480
[Guest]: I think that counts as ethnography.

01:11:20.480 --> 01:11:22.320
[Guest]: Let me say one more point.

01:11:22.320 --> 01:11:28.240
[Guest]: So each of the transition from philosophy to international development, that's a big

01:11:28.240 --> 01:11:33.720
[Guest]: change because you're going from questioning the meaning of life with zero empirical content

01:11:33.720 --> 01:11:36.320
[Guest]: to suddenly starting social science.

01:11:36.320 --> 01:11:37.320
[Guest]: That's a transition.

01:11:37.320 --> 01:11:38.320
[Guest]: Yes.

01:11:38.320 --> 01:11:42.280
[Guest]: But I could do it because I was just going to read absolutely everything.

01:11:42.280 --> 01:11:45.560
[Guest]: I mean, I devour.

01:11:45.560 --> 01:11:50.320
[Guest]: One friend said, you know, you take the books like combine harvester in a field of daisies.

01:11:50.320 --> 01:11:51.320
[Unknown]: Right.

01:11:51.320 --> 01:11:54.200
[Guest]: And it's also important is the way that I read.

01:11:54.200 --> 01:11:55.200
[Guest]: And this is something.

01:11:55.200 --> 01:12:00.160
[Guest]: So I did a postgraduate certificate in higher education where I learned about active learning.

01:12:00.160 --> 01:12:01.160
[Guest]: And this is the idea.

01:12:01.160 --> 01:12:02.680
[Guest]: You know, passive learning is just reading a book.

01:12:02.680 --> 01:12:05.200
[Guest]: But often my students might get to the end of the chapter and have no idea what they

01:12:05.200 --> 01:12:06.200
[Guest]: just read.

01:12:06.200 --> 01:12:12.280
[Guest]: And part of active learning is creatively engaging and questioning and and raising questions

01:12:12.280 --> 01:12:13.280
[Guest]: about it.

01:12:13.280 --> 01:12:16.480
[Guest]: And that's how I try to approach books by asking questions or or thinking what this

01:12:16.480 --> 01:12:17.480
[Guest]: prompts.

01:12:17.480 --> 01:12:18.480
[Guest]: So I've always been actively.

01:12:18.480 --> 01:12:20.320
[Guest]: So it's not just about the volume of the books.

01:12:20.320 --> 01:12:24.920
[Guest]: The volume of books I've read, but also about the way that I read in a in a critical style,

01:12:24.920 --> 01:12:25.920
[Guest]: thinking about it.

01:12:25.920 --> 01:12:29.740
[Guest]: And Twitter really helps because sometimes, you know, I try to explain, et cetera.

01:12:29.740 --> 01:12:33.640
[Guest]: And then to go back to your question about being beholden to narrow gatekeepers.

01:12:33.640 --> 01:12:35.160
[Guest]: Yes, absolutely.

01:12:35.160 --> 01:12:42.520
[Guest]: Some people complain that one, each discipline privilege is a specific kind of research.

01:12:42.520 --> 01:12:46.360
[Guest]: So the geography journals wanted to talk about space, for example.

01:12:46.360 --> 01:12:49.880
[Guest]: And they complain that they're constantly jumping through hoops.

01:12:49.880 --> 01:12:53.960
[Guest]: But that in itself is a choice that we're making.

01:12:53.960 --> 01:12:57.640
[Guest]: We're saying, I want career advancement.

01:12:57.640 --> 01:13:00.480
[Guest]: And so then I will do what these people want.

01:13:00.480 --> 01:13:05.400
[Guest]: And I have decided that what's important to me is not my job title.

01:13:05.400 --> 01:13:09.520
[Guest]: If I'm senior lecturer or reader, so what?

01:13:09.520 --> 01:13:10.520
[Guest]: So what?

01:13:10.520 --> 01:13:12.720
[Guest]: Like, that's not the most important thing to me.

01:13:12.720 --> 01:13:17.960
[Guest]: If my department thinks that I'm it's it's just not important to me.

01:13:17.960 --> 01:13:21.640
[Guest]: And this goes back to, you know, my my fundamental idea that I need to work out what's important

01:13:21.640 --> 01:13:22.640
[Guest]: to me.

01:13:22.640 --> 01:13:27.480
[Guest]: And by pursuing that, I can liberate myself from these social conventions, which we can

01:13:27.480 --> 01:13:29.860
[Guest]: question, which we can emancipate ourselves from.

01:13:29.860 --> 01:13:35.000
[Guest]: So I have incrementally realized that I do not need to be beholden to conventions.

01:13:35.000 --> 01:13:39.540
[Guest]: And it's also other people encouraging me and supporting me.

01:13:39.540 --> 01:13:45.640
[Guest]: So there was this, I saw this prize, this blog prize that I'd never blogged.

01:13:45.640 --> 01:13:47.140
[Guest]: But I saw there was a prize for blogging.

01:13:47.140 --> 01:13:48.600
[Guest]: And so I thought, hey, I'll go for that.

01:13:48.600 --> 01:13:52.840
[Guest]: And then I started blogging and I enjoyed it because that was another way of sharing

01:13:52.840 --> 01:13:53.920
[Guest]: my research with the world.

01:13:53.920 --> 01:13:59.120
[Guest]: And I've increasingly realized that that can have value and a useful because there are

01:13:59.120 --> 01:14:03.640
[Guest]: many economists who might, you know, not read all that huge volume of anthropological of

01:14:03.640 --> 01:14:07.080
[Guest]: quality literature, but can quickly go to my blogs and find something interesting.

01:14:07.080 --> 01:14:11.240
[Guest]: And I can synthesize these literatures and I can share these ideas and I can communicate

01:14:11.240 --> 01:14:12.560
[Guest]: with a far bigger audience.

01:14:12.560 --> 01:14:19.160
[Guest]: And I came to increasingly realize that, you know, journals, you know, are a locked journal

01:14:19.160 --> 01:14:24.200
[Guest]: that one, many people in many parts of the world cannot afford and cannot access.

01:14:24.200 --> 01:14:27.760
[Guest]: And even if they could access, you know, it's only about eight people reading it because

01:14:27.760 --> 01:14:29.880
[Guest]: they need to get the reference or the citation.

01:14:29.880 --> 01:14:36.020
[Guest]: I mean, I don't understand why so many brilliant minds, enormously clever, brilliant minds

01:14:36.020 --> 01:14:40.680
[Guest]: might be spending all their time, all their resources, publishing things that no one's

01:14:40.680 --> 01:14:45.000
[Guest]: going to read, that I don't get that, that model doesn't appear to me.

01:14:45.000 --> 01:14:49.000
[Guest]: But now there's blogging and writing this book, yeah, then I can actually be sharing

01:14:49.000 --> 01:14:57.400
[Guest]: ideas and what I'm trying to do now, you know, this isn't what my goal now is really not

01:14:57.400 --> 01:14:58.880
[Guest]: the mission of Alice Evans.

01:14:58.880 --> 01:15:03.560
[Guest]: I'm trying to build a new field and I will only, and I can't do that alone.

01:15:03.560 --> 01:15:08.460
[Guest]: I absolutely cannot get, I cannot pretend that I will get the answer absolutely right

01:15:08.460 --> 01:15:09.880
[Guest]: by myself.

01:15:09.880 --> 01:15:15.400
[Guest]: So what I really want to do is for others to be excited by this project and join me.

01:15:15.400 --> 01:15:19.440
[Guest]: And, you know, they may, you know, everyone has got their different skills and interests

01:15:19.440 --> 01:15:24.160
[Guest]: and whether it's a comparative study of Bangladesh or India, or whether it's looking at the impact

01:15:24.160 --> 01:15:27.320
[Guest]: of automation or whether it's looking about, you know, marriage, whatever.

01:15:27.320 --> 01:15:31.840
[Guest]: I want to share this research so that other people realise, hey, this is a big fundamental

01:15:31.840 --> 01:15:33.680
[Guest]: question and we want to answer it too.

01:15:33.680 --> 01:15:36.800
[Guest]: We want to take a stab at that bit to look at what's happening in Spain.

01:15:36.800 --> 01:15:41.920
[Guest]: So the more that I, what I'm actually trying to do is lower the barriers to entry.

01:15:41.920 --> 01:15:46.040
[Guest]: I want more people, I want to create this field, create, you know, help people.

01:15:46.040 --> 01:15:50.600
[Guest]: So I'm building the jigsaw, but I want to make it easier for other people to study these

01:15:50.600 --> 01:15:53.920
[Guest]: questions in ways that they find exciting and tantalising.

01:15:53.920 --> 01:15:55.880
[Guest]: So I'm not remotely territorial.

01:15:55.880 --> 01:15:59.760
[Guest]: And this is part of you, I'm de-territorialising my own terrain.

01:15:59.760 --> 01:16:01.360
[Guest]: I'm saying, hey, come with me.

01:16:01.360 --> 01:16:07.400
[Guest]: And so three weeks ago, I was in Boston and I gave a talk with economists who were great

01:16:07.400 --> 01:16:09.280
[Guest]: and we were talking about these ideas.

01:16:09.280 --> 01:16:11.240
[Guest]: And I'm also giving a talk to anthropologists.

01:16:11.240 --> 01:16:14.920
[Guest]: So I want to speak to all these different disciplines, because there are so many people

01:16:14.920 --> 01:16:18.920
[Guest]: with so many brilliant tools and techniques and their own ideas, their own ways of analysing

01:16:18.920 --> 01:16:19.920
[Guest]: these things.

01:16:19.920 --> 01:16:24.440
[Guest]: And I want everyone to jump on board, because there have always been many books on the rise

01:16:24.440 --> 01:16:28.180
[Guest]: of the West, you know, economic divergence, but not on gender.

01:16:28.180 --> 01:16:30.720
[Guest]: And so now I think, hey, let's take a crack at it.

01:16:30.720 --> 01:16:32.120
[Guest]: And I'll take the first step.

01:16:32.120 --> 01:16:35.760
[Guest]: I'll get out the broad outline, but, you know, there'll be a lot of things that I'll get

01:16:35.760 --> 01:16:36.760
[Guest]: wrong.

01:16:36.760 --> 01:16:40.840
[Guest]: So, you know, let's, you know, all hands to the deck, I say.

01:16:40.840 --> 01:16:42.480
[Unknown]: So it is a different model.

01:16:42.480 --> 01:16:44.000
[Guest]: It is a different model of academia.

01:16:44.000 --> 01:16:47.680
[Guest]: And another thing I would say, another way it's different.

01:16:47.680 --> 01:16:52.400
[Guest]: So when I try to reduce the barriers to entry to studying these questions and to share research

01:16:52.400 --> 01:16:56.680
[Guest]: between different brilliant minds, whether that's through my podcasts or through my blogs.

01:16:56.680 --> 01:17:04.600
[Guest]: Another aspect is academics have historically spent a huge amount of time applying for grants.

01:17:04.600 --> 01:17:07.400
[Guest]: So they'll write these long, long, long documents.

01:17:07.400 --> 01:17:12.440
[Guest]: So for example, earlier this year, I spent ages, maybe three months applying for two

01:17:12.440 --> 01:17:17.560
[Guest]: million euros in funding because I wanted to get five PhDs and postdocs to study my

01:17:17.560 --> 01:17:21.160
[Guest]: research question, comparative histories and gender in their own languages.

01:17:21.160 --> 01:17:25.200
[Guest]: So in Arabic, in Mandarin, you know, I thought, hey, let's get more Alice Evanses, but in

01:17:25.200 --> 01:17:29.400
[Guest]: their own languages, because there's a huge amount of data, I can't access it, I'm flawed.

01:17:29.400 --> 01:17:32.640
[Guest]: Let's have other people with their own knowledge doing what I'm doing.

01:17:32.640 --> 01:17:35.400
[Guest]: Let's multiply Alice Evans, but you know, in their way.

01:17:35.400 --> 01:17:39.880
[Guest]: I didn't get that funding, but it was an enormous cost in my time, an enormous cost in my time.

01:17:39.880 --> 01:17:41.280
[Guest]: So that was a total waste of time.

01:17:41.280 --> 01:17:42.480
[Guest]: And I got nothing out of it.

01:17:42.480 --> 01:17:43.760
[Guest]: And many academics do that.

01:17:43.760 --> 01:17:46.160
[Guest]: They spend their time chasing grants that they don't get.

01:17:46.160 --> 01:17:52.440
[Guest]: So now what I'm doing is actually trying to cultivate an alternative way of academic inquiry.

01:17:52.440 --> 01:17:57.560
[Guest]: Let me share this research and other people of their own volition will find it interesting

01:17:57.560 --> 01:17:59.080
[Guest]: and choose to do it.

01:17:59.080 --> 01:18:01.720
[Guest]: So we're not going through some complex bureaucracy.

01:18:01.720 --> 01:18:05.960
[Guest]: It's not that I'm applying for grants, then recruiting and hiring RAs who are then under

01:18:05.960 --> 01:18:07.120
[Guest]: my management.

01:18:07.120 --> 01:18:10.760
[Guest]: What I'm saying is I'm making here are these questions, if you like it, come aboard of

01:18:10.760 --> 01:18:13.000
[Guest]: your own independent volition and we'll do it.

01:18:13.000 --> 01:18:21.160
[Guest]: So there are numbers of ways in which I'm offering or exploring or experimenting with

01:18:21.160 --> 01:18:22.480
[Unknown]: different ways of doing things.

01:18:22.480 --> 01:18:25.640
[Amit Varma]: I love the kind of open source inquiry that this is headed towards.

01:18:25.640 --> 01:18:30.800
[Amit Varma]: And I appreciate what you said earlier about it being a choice, whether you play the academic

01:18:30.800 --> 01:18:31.920
[Amit Varma]: game or not.

01:18:31.920 --> 01:18:35.420
[Amit Varma]: But the incentives are all tailored in one direction.

01:18:35.420 --> 01:18:39.520
[Amit Varma]: And this is a common lament I hear even from people within academics that listen, we don't

01:18:39.520 --> 01:18:41.720
[Amit Varma]: have a choice but to play that game.

01:18:41.720 --> 01:18:47.360
[Amit Varma]: So one, are you an outlier in that sense that you have chosen not to play the game and you

01:18:47.360 --> 01:18:49.600
[Amit Varma]: walked away and you're trying to do something different?

01:18:49.600 --> 01:18:55.240
[Amit Varma]: And two, when you talk about building a new field, do you mean building a new approach

01:18:55.240 --> 01:18:56.920
[Amit Varma]: to doing the kind of work you're doing?

01:18:56.920 --> 01:18:59.520
[Amit Varma]: Or do you also mean building a new field field?

01:18:59.520 --> 01:19:00.640
[Guest]: And can you elaborate upon that?

01:19:00.640 --> 01:19:02.600
[Guest]: So I just mean the great gender divergence.

01:19:02.600 --> 01:19:03.880
[Guest]: So no one has ever.

01:19:03.880 --> 01:19:09.400
[Guest]: So the most fundamental fact about humanity that we don't know is why some countries have

01:19:09.400 --> 01:19:13.560
[Guest]: become so much more gender equal than others, all of patriarchy, but we can't explain that.

01:19:13.560 --> 01:19:17.960
[Guest]: So that's the field that the great gender divergence, that's what I want people to explore

01:19:17.960 --> 01:19:20.040
[Guest]: alongside me.

01:19:20.040 --> 01:19:24.440
[Guest]: Now why am I not beholden to career incentives to such a degree?

01:19:24.440 --> 01:19:25.920
[Guest]: I would say two things.

01:19:25.920 --> 01:19:29.760
[Guest]: One is it's this intrinsic love of learning.

01:19:29.760 --> 01:19:33.440
[Guest]: And that matters more to me than any title people can give me.

01:19:33.440 --> 01:19:34.760
[Guest]: So I just want to know the answer.

01:19:34.760 --> 01:19:40.000
[Guest]: I jump out of bed each morning because I'm excited by a book.

01:19:40.000 --> 01:19:45.280
[Unknown]: So yeah, so what is this intrinsic quest?

01:19:45.280 --> 01:19:50.640
[Guest]: I mean, it's like, you know, sometimes people ask me for productivity hacks, or, you know,

01:19:50.640 --> 01:19:51.640
[Guest]: what's your routine?

01:19:51.640 --> 01:19:54.160
[Guest]: And all that is endogenous.

01:19:54.160 --> 01:19:59.880
[Guest]: Because what's underlying all this is like this intense, creative, obsessive lust and

01:19:59.880 --> 01:20:03.400
[Guest]: passion to understand the answer to stuff.

01:20:03.400 --> 01:20:05.200
[Guest]: So that drives me absolutely.

01:20:05.200 --> 01:20:07.400
[Guest]: And that's what I think is important.

01:20:07.400 --> 01:20:08.400
[Guest]: And that drives me.

01:20:08.400 --> 01:20:10.840
[Guest]: So that's my fuel.

01:20:10.840 --> 01:20:16.120
[Guest]: And the other aspect, so one is my goals may be different.

01:20:16.120 --> 01:20:21.960
[Guest]: Another aspect is perhaps money doesn't matter to me that much.

01:20:21.960 --> 01:20:26.520
[Guest]: And that may be in partly because of my background of economic privilege.

01:20:26.520 --> 01:20:31.240
[Guest]: You know, there are many people for whom they have children, they have financial responsibilities,

01:20:31.240 --> 01:20:33.400
[Guest]: they may want to acquire more wealth.

01:20:33.400 --> 01:20:35.320
[Guest]: But money has never been that important to me.

01:20:35.320 --> 01:20:37.360
[Guest]: Money is not something, I mean, what am I going to do?

01:20:37.360 --> 01:20:38.360
[Guest]: Buy more books?

01:20:38.360 --> 01:20:42.880
[Guest]: I mean, I already get, yeah, I spend a lot of money on books, but you know, there's only

01:20:42.880 --> 01:20:44.960
[Guest]: so many books I can read.

01:20:44.960 --> 01:20:52.080
[Guest]: So one is I'm really, so I have the economic luxury of not caring that much about money.

01:20:52.080 --> 01:20:54.840
[Guest]: And that's a privileged position, I totally accept that.

01:20:54.840 --> 01:21:01.160
[Guest]: The third aspect that I would say is incredibly important, and I keep coming back to this

01:21:01.160 --> 01:21:06.280
[Guest]: is that I have been enabled to do this by other people having faith and confidence in

01:21:06.280 --> 01:21:07.280
[Guest]: me.

01:21:07.280 --> 01:21:12.920
[Guest]: So Princeton University Press, when I explained this project to them, I told them I would

01:21:12.920 --> 01:21:16.960
[Guest]: need eight or nine years to study the global history of gender.

01:21:16.960 --> 01:21:18.640
[Guest]: And they accepted it on my terms.

01:21:18.640 --> 01:21:22.000
[Guest]: And so they gave me a contract with that long time horizon.

01:21:22.000 --> 01:21:26.640
[Guest]: So whereas other academics might be under pressure to publish every single year, I have

01:21:26.640 --> 01:21:27.640
[Guest]: this contract.

01:21:27.640 --> 01:21:30.200
[Guest]: So Princeton University Press, I absolutely thank and support them.

01:21:30.200 --> 01:21:36.640
[Guest]: I've also been able to cultivate a number of grants that, you know, enable me to travel

01:21:36.640 --> 01:21:37.640
[Guest]: around the world.

01:21:37.640 --> 01:21:41.200
[Guest]: So that gives me a sense of financial freedom, financial autonomy, you know, people having

01:21:41.200 --> 01:21:42.760
[Guest]: belief in Alice Evans.

01:21:42.760 --> 01:21:49.640
[Guest]: So it's absolutely, so going back to your point is, me, my love of learning, to me really

01:21:49.640 --> 01:21:52.000
[Guest]: not caring about money.

01:21:52.000 --> 01:21:57.520
[Guest]: And because of my economic privilege, and, and three, other people's faith and support

01:21:57.520 --> 01:21:59.200
[Guest]: in this project.

01:21:59.200 --> 01:22:01.280
[Amit Varma]: So let's double click on the love of learning.

01:22:01.280 --> 01:22:03.560
[Amit Varma]: And at one point, you said you read absolutely everything.

01:22:03.560 --> 01:22:07.600
[Amit Varma]: I think you said that a few times, and I tell my writing students don't use adverbs.

01:22:07.600 --> 01:22:12.280
[Amit Varma]: But in this case, absolutely seems quite apt for how much you do seem to read because almost

01:22:12.280 --> 01:22:15.560
[Amit Varma]: every day on Twitter, you're like recommending a couple of interesting books, and I've bought

01:22:15.560 --> 01:22:19.560
[Amit Varma]: a bunch of books just because I've seen you tweet about them excitedly.

01:22:19.560 --> 01:22:25.360
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about what is your process of what you earlier described as active

01:22:25.360 --> 01:22:26.360
[Amit Varma]: learning?

01:22:26.360 --> 01:22:27.360
[Unknown]: Like, how do you read?

01:22:27.360 --> 01:22:28.920
[Amit Varma]: Do you have a note taking app?

01:22:28.920 --> 01:22:30.920
[Amit Varma]: How do you take notes?

01:22:30.920 --> 01:22:35.360
[Amit Varma]: You know, what what sort of your speed of reading in the sense, one of the things I'm

01:22:35.360 --> 01:22:39.280
[Amit Varma]: kind of blessed with, which enables me to do this podcast is I can read both fast and

01:22:39.280 --> 01:22:44.200
[Amit Varma]: deep at the same time, I don't skim, I can do that I can take notes, but I'm, I have

01:22:44.200 --> 01:22:45.920
[Amit Varma]: a feeling you read much more than me.

01:22:45.920 --> 01:22:51.400
[Amit Varma]: So I'd love to know about what your methods are of assimilating knowledge of giving them

01:22:51.400 --> 01:22:55.520
[Amit Varma]: the time to seep into you and for you to think about them, contextualize them in the light

01:22:55.520 --> 01:22:57.320
[Amit Varma]: of everything else that you've read.

01:22:57.320 --> 01:23:01.720
[Amit Varma]: So take me a bit through that process, like you say, you bounce out of bed in the morning,

01:23:01.720 --> 01:23:03.600
[Amit Varma]: because you're looking forward to reading a book.

01:23:03.600 --> 01:23:08.280
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, so what's a typical day in your life and you know, what is this active learning

01:23:08.280 --> 01:23:09.280
[Amit Varma]: process like?

01:23:09.280 --> 01:23:11.320
[Guest]: Okay, I want to answer that in two parts.

01:23:11.320 --> 01:23:15.880
[Guest]: One is I want to share active learning that might be useful to others.

01:23:15.880 --> 01:23:20.120
[Guest]: So I, as I mentioned earlier, I did this two year qualification in how people learn and

01:23:20.120 --> 01:23:22.360
[Guest]: I was fascinated by that process of learning.

01:23:22.360 --> 01:23:26.560
[Guest]: And I think that's enormously important, because we can be more productive if we if we apply

01:23:26.560 --> 01:23:27.720
[Guest]: active learning.

01:23:27.720 --> 01:23:31.840
[Guest]: And so I tell my students four, four fundamental things.

01:23:31.840 --> 01:23:40.760
[Guest]: So, one is when they read a paper or a book, they should be able to reflect on it and synthesize

01:23:40.760 --> 01:23:42.640
[Guest]: that material in a single sentence.

01:23:42.640 --> 01:23:46.160
[Guest]: So that active synthesis, so what is the main argument?

01:23:46.160 --> 01:23:52.600
[Guest]: Two, they should look what evidence is presented to support that argument.

01:23:52.600 --> 01:23:56.360
[Guest]: So they should look through the book saying, well, where is the evidence does that and

01:23:56.360 --> 01:23:59.800
[Guest]: then three, does that stack up on their read?

01:23:59.800 --> 01:24:03.960
[Guest]: Does it support the argument and to be critical of the evidence or the methodology and for

01:24:03.960 --> 01:24:10.040
[Guest]: them to think, well, how does this approach differ from other perspectives, other literature

01:24:10.040 --> 01:24:11.040
[Guest]: in that field?

01:24:11.040 --> 01:24:16.320
[Guest]: So it's that four prong approach, which I use to which I encourage my students to for

01:24:16.320 --> 01:24:17.560
[Guest]: active learning.

01:24:17.560 --> 01:24:22.360
[Guest]: And then I always, yeah, so that that's what I encourage my students to do.

01:24:22.360 --> 01:24:28.480
[Guest]: Even on my process myself, again, trying to apply my active learning, I sometimes use

01:24:28.480 --> 01:24:35.200
[Guest]: Twitter here, because what I try to do is to present a book in a way that appeals to

01:24:35.200 --> 01:24:36.200
[Guest]: a broader audience.

01:24:36.200 --> 01:24:42.160
[Guest]: And that pushes me to be creative, to think, well, let me make this interesting to a wider

01:24:42.160 --> 01:24:43.160
[Guest]: audience.

01:24:43.160 --> 01:24:46.120
[Guest]: So let me connect this to a bigger, bigger question.

01:24:46.120 --> 01:24:48.840
[Guest]: Let me help people understand this.

01:24:48.840 --> 01:24:50.440
[Guest]: Let me help outsiders understand this.

01:24:50.440 --> 01:24:55.040
[Guest]: So the more that I'm creatively engaging, thinking about how to present that material

01:24:55.040 --> 01:25:02.280
[Guest]: and present that evidence is actually, let me confess, part of my active learning process.

01:25:02.280 --> 01:25:05.560
[Guest]: And I'm thinking about the ideas relating it to the broader question.

01:25:05.560 --> 01:25:08.520
[Guest]: So that public engagement is actually part of my active learning.

01:25:08.520 --> 01:25:12.400
[Guest]: I mean, of course, I don't, I don't tweet about everything that I read, you know, I'll

01:25:12.400 --> 01:25:14.560
[Guest]: tell you a story from.

01:25:14.560 --> 01:25:19.600
[Guest]: So I have this software called Zotero, which is a form of referencing software.

01:25:19.600 --> 01:25:25.080
[Guest]: And so just the number of things that I've cited, so that's not the totality or the totality

01:25:25.080 --> 01:25:26.360
[Guest]: of everything I read.

01:25:26.360 --> 01:25:30.880
[Guest]: But I think in the past three years, it's now up to three and a half thousand books

01:25:30.880 --> 01:25:31.880
[Guest]: and papers.

01:25:31.880 --> 01:25:36.280
[Guest]: I mean, it's a lot, but it's always with this mechanism, always with this mechanism.

01:25:36.280 --> 01:25:37.880
[Amit Varma]: That's three a day, basically.

01:25:37.880 --> 01:25:39.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:25:39.600 --> 01:25:41.560
[Guest]: How many books do you read in a day?

01:25:41.560 --> 01:25:44.480
[Guest]: It might be some combination of books and papers.

01:25:44.480 --> 01:25:47.080
[Guest]: Oh, yes, you asked, you asked about my, my, my day routine.

01:25:47.080 --> 01:25:50.720
[Guest]: So usually I jump out of bed, I do that, I do the book, I have this, you know, the hive

01:25:50.720 --> 01:25:54.720
[Guest]: of activity, and then exercise is very important to me.

01:25:54.720 --> 01:25:58.920
[Guest]: So I usually spend either one or two hours exercising at some sort of middle of the day

01:25:58.920 --> 01:26:00.120
[Guest]: or something like that.

01:26:00.120 --> 01:26:01.120
[Guest]: So I do my exercise.

01:26:01.120 --> 01:26:02.120
[Guest]: And that's really important.

01:26:02.120 --> 01:26:08.160
[Guest]: And I think that can also, I think, you know, there's huge endorphin release, it's important

01:26:08.160 --> 01:26:09.160
[Guest]: to be away from the screen.

01:26:09.160 --> 01:26:13.960
[Guest]: So my best ideas come to me when I'm charging through the countryside, running.

01:26:13.960 --> 01:26:20.040
[Guest]: And I think there's also, and I don't know the the academic research on this, so I present

01:26:20.040 --> 01:26:28.400
[Guest]: this only as an anecdote, there's also a sense of confidence through being athletic and physically

01:26:28.400 --> 01:26:29.400
[Guest]: strong.

01:26:29.400 --> 01:26:35.440
[Guest]: Like, I think one reason why I'm not intimidated when I'm traveling around the world is I can

01:26:35.440 --> 01:26:38.160
[Guest]: see men and not be intimidated by them.

01:26:38.160 --> 01:26:42.120
[Guest]: So I think that that could be one, but the mental health, I have huge mental health benefits

01:26:42.120 --> 01:26:46.480
[Guest]: from being very athletic, going through the countryside, fresh air.

01:26:46.480 --> 01:26:47.480
[Guest]: I love it.

01:26:47.480 --> 01:26:48.480
[Guest]: And I do a range of sports.

01:26:48.480 --> 01:26:54.200
[Guest]: I run, I cycle, I swim, I do yoga, I do Pilates, I lift weights, I do everything.

01:26:54.200 --> 01:26:56.960
[Unknown]: And I get a great joy out of that.

01:26:56.960 --> 01:27:00.440
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, you mentioned before we started recording that you went to a gym with a friend and you

01:27:00.440 --> 01:27:02.480
[Amit Varma]: were stronger than all the men there.

01:27:02.480 --> 01:27:03.480
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

01:27:03.480 --> 01:27:05.640
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I'd be just the other way around.

01:27:05.640 --> 01:27:07.880
[Amit Varma]: If I went to a gym, I'd be weaker than all the women there.

01:27:07.880 --> 01:27:11.320
[Amit Varma]: So there you go, playing to those stereotypes as well.

01:27:11.320 --> 01:27:16.760
[Amit Varma]: Because my next question, there's always a trade off when you get into a subject between

01:27:16.760 --> 01:27:19.760
[Amit Varma]: thinking too broadly and becoming too narrow.

01:27:19.760 --> 01:27:27.380
[Amit Varma]: Now, one of the traps that people in academics have fallen into is they've become what my

01:27:27.380 --> 01:27:31.880
[Amit Varma]: friend Ajay Shah would describe as the prisoners of domain expertise, right?

01:27:31.880 --> 01:27:37.880
[Amit Varma]: So they choose a specialization and they are kind of trapped there, you know, growth in

01:27:37.880 --> 01:27:44.560
[Amit Varma]: GDP in the middle class in Congo between the years 1632 to 1633, and so on and so forth.

01:27:44.560 --> 01:27:45.720
[Amit Varma]: And they're completely trapped there.

01:27:45.720 --> 01:27:48.200
[Amit Varma]: And that's all that they can see.

01:27:48.200 --> 01:27:53.080
[Amit Varma]: And they're not bringing wider insights to bear on their work, even from their own discipline,

01:27:53.080 --> 01:27:55.120
[Amit Varma]: forget other disciplines.

01:27:55.120 --> 01:28:00.320
[Amit Varma]: And the allure of going broad is that you can bring different frames from different

01:28:00.320 --> 01:28:04.360
[Amit Varma]: disciplines to look at a problem that you can, you know, you may look at something that

01:28:04.360 --> 01:28:11.020
[Amit Varma]: is happening in one country and use your insights from other countries and be able to, you know,

01:28:11.020 --> 01:28:16.000
[Amit Varma]: see things that a domain specialist wouldn't do, I think, in, you know, somewhere, I forget

01:28:16.000 --> 01:28:19.760
[Amit Varma]: where you wrote this, but you quoted Fukuyama, where you said that, you know, you don't know

01:28:19.760 --> 01:28:23.100
[Amit Varma]: your own country, if it's the only country, you know, something to that effect, right?

01:28:23.100 --> 01:28:24.560
[Amit Varma]: And that's beautiful.

01:28:24.560 --> 01:28:30.280
[Amit Varma]: The danger, however, of being broad, is that whenever you comment on anything that is narrow

01:28:30.280 --> 01:28:34.920
[Amit Varma]: on any specific thing, a narrow specialist who has studied only that thing will say,

01:28:34.920 --> 01:28:40.240
[Amit Varma]: hey, you're being too broad, you're generalising, you're painting with broad brushstrokes, right?

01:28:40.240 --> 01:28:42.640
[Amit Varma]: And this seems to me to be an insurmountable problem.

01:28:42.640 --> 01:28:43.640
[Guest]: No, it's not.

01:28:43.640 --> 01:28:44.640
[Guest]: Tell me about it.

01:28:44.640 --> 01:28:45.640
[Guest]: I absolutely agree.

01:28:45.640 --> 01:28:49.760
[Guest]: I need to be as expert as every single expert.

01:28:49.760 --> 01:28:55.480
[Guest]: So for every topic, whether it's marriage in medieval Europe, I need to know that literature.

01:28:55.480 --> 01:28:57.480
[Guest]: I need to be absolutely on top of that literature.

01:28:57.480 --> 01:29:02.560
[Guest]: And I don't believe there is a trade-off between breadth and depth, if you have infinite time

01:29:02.560 --> 01:29:04.960
[Guest]: and an absolute passion to understand it.

01:29:04.960 --> 01:29:10.900
[Guest]: So the comparative lens, so for example, by comparing East Asia and South Asia, we can

01:29:10.900 --> 01:29:14.720
[Guest]: understand the massive importance of job creating economic growth.

01:29:14.720 --> 01:29:19.480
[Guest]: So back in 1900, both of these places were extremely patriarchal.

01:29:19.480 --> 01:29:24.840
[Guest]: So South Korea, Korean women, rather, gangban, elite Korean women were veiled.

01:29:24.840 --> 01:29:30.800
[Guest]: They even had this seesaw whereby behind the walls of the household, girls would play so

01:29:30.800 --> 01:29:34.440
[Guest]: that one could jump high and see over the barricades.

01:29:34.440 --> 01:29:37.520
[Guest]: So there were patrilocal marriages in East Asia.

01:29:37.520 --> 01:29:41.760
[Guest]: Women were, yeah, inter-arranged marriages with very little autonomy.

01:29:41.760 --> 01:29:46.440
[Guest]: Confucianism had the three obediences, be subservient to your husband, your father,

01:29:46.440 --> 01:29:47.440
[Guest]: your son.

01:29:47.440 --> 01:29:50.760
[Guest]: You know, Chinese women, their feet were broken and bound.

01:29:50.760 --> 01:29:57.560
[Guest]: Culture in China always celebrated female sacrifice for male honour.

01:29:57.560 --> 01:30:03.240
[Guest]: But through job creating economic growth, mass manufacturing, at first families might

01:30:03.240 --> 01:30:08.120
[Guest]: be reluctant for their daughters to go out to cities because they were worried about

01:30:08.120 --> 01:30:13.040
[Guest]: losing honour, about losing faith that other people would talk and their daughters would

01:30:13.040 --> 01:30:14.040
[Guest]: become unmarriageable.

01:30:14.040 --> 01:30:20.080
[Guest]: And all this resonates with what's happening in India today, right, that families are reluctant

01:30:20.080 --> 01:30:23.680
[Guest]: to allow women to go to the cities because they worry about their daughters becoming

01:30:23.680 --> 01:30:24.680
[Guest]: unmarriageable.

01:30:24.680 --> 01:30:27.120
[Guest]: And they only do it in cases of economic desperation.

01:30:27.120 --> 01:30:32.840
[Guest]: But in East Asia, job creating economic growth was so intensive that girls, the flocks of

01:30:32.840 --> 01:30:37.560
[Guest]: women were going to the cities, that it became a normal expected part of adolescence.

01:30:37.560 --> 01:30:41.760
[Guest]: So no family needed to worry about sticking their neck out and others gossiping because

01:30:41.760 --> 01:30:42.840
[Guest]: it became so normal.

01:30:42.840 --> 01:30:47.200
[Guest]: So that big comparative lens really enabled me to see the importance of job creating economic

01:30:47.200 --> 01:30:48.200
[Guest]: growth.

01:30:48.200 --> 01:30:49.640
[Guest]: So that breadth helped.

01:30:49.640 --> 01:30:53.680
[Guest]: Now I'm in India to understand the depth, right.

01:30:53.680 --> 01:30:59.040
[Guest]: So I've been to Rajasthan, I was in Jaipur, I was in Udaipur, I went to a small village

01:30:59.040 --> 01:31:06.680
[Guest]: near Bharatpur, I'm also going to Bangalore, I'm going to Chennai, Mumbai and Calcutta.

01:31:06.680 --> 01:31:12.880
[Guest]: I'm speaking to, I've been speaking to Dalit journalists, Dalit politicians, Muslim families,

01:31:12.880 --> 01:31:16.640
[Guest]: students at JNU, housewives, domestic workers, all these kinds of people, because I need

01:31:16.640 --> 01:31:18.640
[Guest]: to understand the depth, right.

01:31:18.640 --> 01:31:19.640
[Guest]: This is getting at the depth.

01:31:19.640 --> 01:31:21.080
[Guest]: This is understanding people's stories.

01:31:21.080 --> 01:31:22.520
[Guest]: This is understanding the nuance.

01:31:22.520 --> 01:31:26.680
[Guest]: This is understanding every single life and people's diverse struggles, their aspirations,

01:31:26.680 --> 01:31:28.800
[Guest]: their beliefs, how they see it.

01:31:28.800 --> 01:31:35.040
[Guest]: So I am, and I admit, I mean, you know, I know my project sounds outrageously ambitious.

01:31:35.040 --> 01:31:40.360
[Guest]: You know, I'm trying to do breadth and depth and I believe, and I may not get it perfectly

01:31:40.360 --> 01:31:44.420
[Guest]: right, but I'm trying to do it all because I believe that one should do it all.

01:31:44.420 --> 01:31:47.440
[Guest]: And so that's why I want people to help me too, you know, to help me, you know, where

01:31:47.440 --> 01:31:48.640
[Guest]: I fail, they should try.

01:31:48.640 --> 01:31:51.360
[Guest]: I'd like them to come and help me.

01:31:51.360 --> 01:31:53.320
[Amit Varma]: The two keywords in your answer were infinite time.

01:31:53.320 --> 01:31:55.040
[Amit Varma]: You said it's possible to combine these two.

01:31:55.040 --> 01:31:58.120
[Amit Varma]: There is no trade off if you have infinite time, but of course we don't.

01:31:58.120 --> 01:31:59.920
[Amit Varma]: That is a fundamental scarcity, right?

01:31:59.920 --> 01:32:02.960
[Amit Varma]: Princeton gave you eight years or nine years or whatever, and you think they are being

01:32:02.960 --> 01:32:03.960
[Amit Varma]: generous.

01:32:03.960 --> 01:32:06.480
[Amit Varma]: But when you're in your ninth year and you realise you need another 18 years more and

01:32:06.480 --> 01:32:09.600
[Amit Varma]: they're knocking at the door, that'll be interesting.

01:32:09.600 --> 01:32:17.520
[Amit Varma]: Like one, I would say that, yeah, at some point you can perhaps reach the stage where, while

01:32:17.520 --> 01:32:22.840
[Amit Varma]: you're coming at it from a broad perspective, you're not making major errors on any particular

01:32:22.840 --> 01:32:23.840
[Amit Varma]: domain.

01:32:23.840 --> 01:32:24.840
[Amit Varma]: You can get that kind of depth.

01:32:24.840 --> 01:32:25.840
[Amit Varma]: I accept that.

01:32:25.840 --> 01:32:30.840
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, I think that given that one doesn't have infinite time, you know,

01:32:30.840 --> 01:32:34.600
[Amit Varma]: I would imagine that at some level that there is a trade off.

01:32:34.600 --> 01:32:38.160
[Amit Varma]: But I'm guessing by saying that you can do both breadth and depth, you mean that you

01:32:38.160 --> 01:32:41.840
[Amit Varma]: can get adequately deep, that you're not making any big mistakes?

01:32:41.840 --> 01:32:43.480
[Guest]: Well, let me at least try.

01:32:43.480 --> 01:32:44.480
[Guest]: Let me at least try.

01:32:44.480 --> 01:32:48.560
[Guest]: So I'm not going to pretend that my book is going to be perfect.

01:32:48.560 --> 01:32:52.240
[Guest]: There will be things that I get wrong and other people should rightly call me out.

01:32:52.240 --> 01:32:53.960
[Guest]: And I welcome them calling me out.

01:32:53.960 --> 01:32:58.840
[Guest]: And even in this journey of research in the book, there are major ways in which I've revised

01:32:58.840 --> 01:33:00.920
[Guest]: my beliefs because I'm constantly learning.

01:33:00.920 --> 01:33:04.760
[Guest]: So there were things that I previously didn't understand that I've revised my beliefs.

01:33:04.760 --> 01:33:07.480
[Guest]: Every single day I'm revising my beliefs.

01:33:07.480 --> 01:33:10.280
[Guest]: My learning curves are astronomical.

01:33:10.280 --> 01:33:14.120
[Guest]: So let me not say that I think I can get it perfectly right.

01:33:14.120 --> 01:33:20.640
[Guest]: Let me just say that I agree we should try to master both breadth and depth and I will

01:33:20.640 --> 01:33:21.920
[Guest]: give it my best shot.

01:33:21.920 --> 01:33:22.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, absolutely.

01:33:22.920 --> 01:33:26.720
[Amit Varma]: I mean, one of the things that struck me when I was reading all your essays, I mean, you

01:33:26.720 --> 01:33:30.440
[Amit Varma]: call them blog posts, but they're all these wonderful essays.

01:33:30.440 --> 01:33:34.520
[Amit Varma]: Most of them is that, you know, one that I found that I have something to learn, not

01:33:34.520 --> 01:33:38.960
[Amit Varma]: just from the content of it, which, of course, I do, but also from the approach, which is

01:33:38.960 --> 01:33:43.600
[Amit Varma]: an approach where you're constantly rocking your own priors, as it were, to, you know,

01:33:43.600 --> 01:33:47.680
[Amit Varma]: take the name of your podcast, like you wrote this piece about three things you got wrong

01:33:47.680 --> 01:33:48.680
[Amit Varma]: about patriarchy.

01:33:48.680 --> 01:33:52.080
[Amit Varma]: And the first of them is, quote, when I lack globally comparative knowledge, I was blind

01:33:52.080 --> 01:33:54.920
[Amit Varma]: to country specific characteristics, stop, quote, and there are two others.

01:33:54.920 --> 01:33:57.480
[Amit Varma]: And you're kind of talking about all the things you got wrong.

01:33:57.480 --> 01:34:02.240
[Amit Varma]: And this brings me to your fascinating use of Twitter, which I absolutely love, by the

01:34:02.240 --> 01:34:03.240
[Amit Varma]: way.

01:34:03.240 --> 01:34:07.280
[Amit Varma]: The other thing about Twitter, and a lesson that I learned early, is that not everyone

01:34:07.280 --> 01:34:10.520
[Amit Varma]: is there for the same reasons that you might be there for, right?

01:34:10.520 --> 01:34:14.700
[Amit Varma]: So my imagining of Twitter was that, okay, you go out there, you put your links out there,

01:34:14.700 --> 01:34:17.960
[Amit Varma]: you do all of that any conversations that happen, happen in good faith, and this is

01:34:17.960 --> 01:34:20.120
[Amit Varma]: like a very 12 year old view of it.

01:34:20.120 --> 01:34:24.640
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, it's not like that there are different games being played on Twitter itself,

01:34:24.640 --> 01:34:28.680
[Amit Varma]: there are ideological tribes being formed within which you have people trying to raise

01:34:28.680 --> 01:34:33.280
[Amit Varma]: their own status by attacking others, and you know, passing judgment on others always

01:34:33.280 --> 01:34:37.100
[Amit Varma]: makes you feel more virtuous, because you're automatically on a pedestal if you're passing

01:34:37.100 --> 01:34:38.640
[Amit Varma]: judgment on others.

01:34:38.640 --> 01:34:40.960
[Amit Varma]: And that's like a toxic face of Twitter.

01:34:40.960 --> 01:34:45.440
[Amit Varma]: Now, by and large, I love Twitter, because it's a great if you curate your feet, well,

01:34:45.440 --> 01:34:50.280
[Amit Varma]: we feed well, you have access to the finest minds in the world thinking aloud every day

01:34:50.280 --> 01:34:51.280
[Amit Varma]: for your benefit.

01:34:51.280 --> 01:34:55.000
[Amit Varma]: This is such a bloody privilege, unimaginable 40 years ago, right?

01:34:55.000 --> 01:35:02.080
[Amit Varma]: Now, what I see you as doing is that on the one hand, you're talking about the things

01:35:02.080 --> 01:35:05.440
[Amit Varma]: that you've learned and the research that you've done all of which is very rigorous,

01:35:05.440 --> 01:35:07.040
[Amit Varma]: which has come through reading many books.

01:35:07.040 --> 01:35:11.580
[Amit Varma]: In fact, whenever one reads a blog post by you clicking the links is, you know, a source

01:35:11.580 --> 01:35:13.080
[Amit Varma]: of learning by itself.

01:35:13.080 --> 01:35:16.060
[Amit Varma]: So on the one hand, you're doing that you're presenting all of that.

01:35:16.060 --> 01:35:19.760
[Amit Varma]: On the other hand, you're thinking aloud, you know, you're walking through a town, you're

01:35:19.760 --> 01:35:22.760
[Amit Varma]: talking to the bus driver, you're talking to this person, you go to a wedding, you talk

01:35:22.760 --> 01:35:25.600
[Amit Varma]: to three people, and you're putting that out there, right?

01:35:25.600 --> 01:35:26.880
[Amit Varma]: And you're thinking aloud.

01:35:26.880 --> 01:35:30.300
[Amit Varma]: And it's a very open source kind of way of thinking.

01:35:30.300 --> 01:35:32.120
[Amit Varma]: And these two are happening in the same account.

01:35:32.120 --> 01:35:35.960
[Amit Varma]: And even if they weren't, it wouldn't matter because, you know, people could still get

01:35:35.960 --> 01:35:36.960
[Amit Varma]: after you.

01:35:36.960 --> 01:35:41.160
[Amit Varma]: And the thing is, this is not a space where everybody is going to give you the benefit

01:35:41.160 --> 01:35:43.800
[Amit Varma]: of the doubt and figure out that, oh, this is what she's doing.

01:35:43.800 --> 01:35:51.080
[Amit Varma]: And most people and I believe that the silent majority out there has goodwill, you know,

01:35:51.080 --> 01:35:54.800
[Amit Varma]: it's this process of seeking knowledge and refining knowledge.

01:35:54.800 --> 01:35:56.920
[Amit Varma]: Most people are like that most people are good.

01:35:56.920 --> 01:36:01.720
[Amit Varma]: But you know, mobs will randomly form when somebody will interpret something you said

01:36:01.720 --> 01:36:03.160
[Amit Varma]: in bad faith.

01:36:03.160 --> 01:36:08.360
[Amit Varma]: And we'll and you know, we won't go too much into detail because I just find it unpleasant

01:36:08.360 --> 01:36:09.360
[Amit Varma]: to think about it.

01:36:09.360 --> 01:36:12.560
[Amit Varma]: But you've been at the receiving end of a mob like this recently, I have a number of

01:36:12.560 --> 01:36:14.920
[Amit Varma]: times in the past as well, right?

01:36:14.920 --> 01:36:16.600
[Amit Varma]: So how do you get passes?

01:36:16.600 --> 01:36:21.320
[Amit Varma]: How do you like what you do on Twitter by having opening the space for dialogue, where

01:36:21.320 --> 01:36:24.920
[Amit Varma]: you're essentially telling everybody that, hey, I'm thinking aloud, I could be wrong,

01:36:24.920 --> 01:36:25.920
[Amit Varma]: tell me how I'm wrong.

01:36:25.920 --> 01:36:29.480
[Amit Varma]: I learned from that I'll incorporate it, which is not just posturing because you actually

01:36:29.480 --> 01:36:30.480
[Amit Varma]: do that.

01:36:30.480 --> 01:36:34.160
[Amit Varma]: It's very obvious from your blog post that you're engaging with everything that kind

01:36:34.160 --> 01:36:35.640
[Amit Varma]: of comes at you.

01:36:35.640 --> 01:36:38.880
[Amit Varma]: But how do you sort of then deal with this kind of toxicity?

01:36:38.880 --> 01:36:43.480
[Amit Varma]: Because you know, you can't and I remember having this conversation once with our mutual

01:36:43.480 --> 01:36:49.000
[Amit Varma]: friend Shruti Rajgopalan, and you know, and I was kind of telling her that everyone's

01:36:49.000 --> 01:36:50.360
[Amit Varma]: looking at you so closely.

01:36:50.360 --> 01:36:54.640
[Amit Varma]: They're so determined to misinterpret every damn thing that you say, that you almost have

01:36:54.640 --> 01:36:56.240
[Amit Varma]: to be idiot proof.

01:36:56.240 --> 01:37:00.560
[Amit Varma]: And her argument was and I now feel she was right.

01:37:00.560 --> 01:37:03.480
[Amit Varma]: And her argument was that you can't be idiot proof all the time.

01:37:03.480 --> 01:37:05.640
[Amit Varma]: If they want to find something, they'll find something.

01:37:05.640 --> 01:37:09.520
[Amit Varma]: All you can do is be intellectually honest and say what you have to say.

01:37:09.520 --> 01:37:15.720
[Amit Varma]: So what are your feelings on this, given that it's such an important part of your process

01:37:15.720 --> 01:37:17.840
[Amit Varma]: of active learning, like you pointed out?

01:37:17.840 --> 01:37:18.840
[Guest]: Thank you.

01:37:18.840 --> 01:37:25.600
[Guest]: So one, I would raise another way in which Twitter has been incredibly useful, is that

01:37:25.600 --> 01:37:31.080
[Guest]: so many people, knowing that I'm traveling through India have contacted me saying, Hey,

01:37:31.080 --> 01:37:34.720
[Guest]: Alice, would you like to meet up and they've been incredibly kind to the other day, let

01:37:34.720 --> 01:37:36.080
[Guest]: me give you a story.

01:37:36.080 --> 01:37:40.440
[Guest]: So I, and I'll come to answer any of your questions in due course, but I received a

01:37:40.440 --> 01:37:46.800
[Guest]: message from this anonymous account with the name of a white male European.

01:37:46.800 --> 01:37:50.320
[Guest]: And they said, Hi, Alice, I'm in Jaipur, do you want to meet up?

01:37:50.320 --> 01:37:55.480
[Guest]: And I was like, sorry, not to be rude, but who are you?

01:37:55.480 --> 01:37:58.440
[Guest]: It's just like this anonymous account.

01:37:58.440 --> 01:38:02.280
[Guest]: And they said, Oh, I'm 23, I'm an MPhil student at JNU.

01:38:02.280 --> 01:38:06.840
[Guest]: I was like, so you're female, you know, because I have, you know, I need to be a little bit

01:38:06.840 --> 01:38:11.280
[Guest]: careful before, you know, jumping, jumping on every opportunity.

01:38:11.280 --> 01:38:12.280
[Guest]: And they say, yes, yes, yes.

01:38:12.280 --> 01:38:13.280
[Guest]: And so we met.

01:38:13.280 --> 01:38:15.200
[Guest]: And she was tremendously fast.

01:38:15.200 --> 01:38:17.440
[Guest]: So she came from a Hindu Muslim family.

01:38:17.440 --> 01:38:20.440
[Guest]: She told me all about her life, her student politics at JNU.

01:38:20.440 --> 01:38:24.440
[Guest]: And the following day, which she invited me to meet her family, and they were incredibly

01:38:24.440 --> 01:38:25.440
[Guest]: warm and welcoming.

01:38:25.440 --> 01:38:29.240
[Guest]: Then we went to the village the day after that, and we met many of their extended Muslim

01:38:29.240 --> 01:38:30.760
[Guest]: relatives.

01:38:30.760 --> 01:38:32.360
[Guest]: And so I learned so much.

01:38:32.360 --> 01:38:36.560
[Guest]: And we were traveling together and we're meeting up, I think tomorrow, in fact.

01:38:36.560 --> 01:38:37.960
[Guest]: And so I learned a great deal from her.

01:38:37.960 --> 01:38:40.160
[Guest]: And there have been so many other interactions like that.

01:38:40.160 --> 01:38:45.520
[Guest]: So just yesterday for breakfast, a guy who was involved in JNU student politics around

01:38:45.520 --> 01:38:52.600
[Guest]: the time of the 2012 gang rapes, and how he became involved in the protests for, you know,

01:38:52.600 --> 01:38:54.860
[Guest]: resisting impunity for male violence.

01:38:54.860 --> 01:38:57.200
[Guest]: So many people have contacted me through Twitter.

01:38:57.200 --> 01:38:59.240
[Guest]: So many Indians have invited me to their home.

01:38:59.240 --> 01:39:03.760
[Guest]: So for example, I posted data on Ahmedabad asking, you know, why is the rate of female

01:39:03.760 --> 01:39:06.320
[Guest]: labor force participation so low, 13%?

01:39:06.320 --> 01:39:08.160
[Guest]: And then someone contacted me.

01:39:08.160 --> 01:39:11.160
[Guest]: She said, Oh, I live in Ahmedabad, would you like to visit?

01:39:11.160 --> 01:39:14.880
[Guest]: So and people have asked me to, invited me to Calcutta, you know, I'll raise the question,

01:39:14.880 --> 01:39:15.880
[Guest]: well, what's going on here?

01:39:15.880 --> 01:39:17.480
[Guest]: And people invite me to their homes.

01:39:17.480 --> 01:39:19.200
[Guest]: And so that's great.

01:39:19.200 --> 01:39:24.840
[Guest]: And so Twitter has enabled me, a total outsider, because of people's warmth and their generosity

01:39:24.840 --> 01:39:28.040
[Guest]: and their kindness and their support and understanding for this project.

01:39:28.040 --> 01:39:31.160
[Guest]: You know, that would not be possible without Twitter.

01:39:31.160 --> 01:39:35.680
[Guest]: And so I'm so grateful that Twitter has enabled so many different people.

01:39:35.680 --> 01:39:42.240
[Guest]: Now, I, of course, grant that many of those people using Twitter are enormously privileged,

01:39:42.240 --> 01:39:44.480
[Guest]: economically privileged, often Brahmin.

01:39:44.480 --> 01:39:49.680
[Guest]: But also, through Twitter, people see that I have a, they see my profile, they know who

01:39:49.680 --> 01:39:50.680
[Guest]: I am.

01:39:50.680 --> 01:39:54.400
[Guest]: So I've also been able to contact Dalit journalists, Dalit politicians, so you know, it's having

01:39:54.400 --> 01:39:56.600
[Guest]: your name people saying, Oh, that's that person they've been tweeting.

01:39:56.600 --> 01:39:58.060
[Guest]: So that gives you that helps.

01:39:58.060 --> 01:40:01.560
[Guest]: And also through the many of the people that I meet, I'm able to expand their network.

01:40:01.560 --> 01:40:05.800
[Guest]: So for example, the woman I met from the Hindu Muslim family, it was her who invited invited

01:40:05.800 --> 01:40:11.040
[Guest]: me to the villages where people were living in a state of, you know, not, you know, prosperity.

01:40:11.040 --> 01:40:15.000
[Guest]: So I'm, I am able to use these networks to access more and different people.

01:40:15.000 --> 01:40:20.640
[Guest]: So one is, Twitter has been enormously beneficial, and maybe let's say in several ways, one reaching

01:40:20.640 --> 01:40:26.320
[Guest]: different people learning from them to the critique.

01:40:26.320 --> 01:40:32.280
[Guest]: So that and because Twitter is so enormously valuable for something that I privilege, which

01:40:32.280 --> 01:40:35.720
[Guest]: is learning that almost any cost is worth it.

01:40:35.720 --> 01:40:42.720
[Guest]: So after the after the, a couple of Twitter mobs, I did protect my account.

01:40:42.720 --> 01:40:45.480
[Guest]: And I did lock it, but I unlocked it for two reasons.

01:40:45.480 --> 01:40:49.620
[Guest]: One is I saw someone celebrating the fact they cancelled me.

01:40:49.620 --> 01:40:52.120
[Guest]: And I thought that was so disgusting.

01:40:52.120 --> 01:40:58.200
[Guest]: And I thought if someone is celebrating gleefully, suppressing my speech, that I thought was

01:40:58.200 --> 01:40:59.480
[Guest]: dangerous for other people.

01:40:59.480 --> 01:41:03.440
[Guest]: I did not want to perpetuate an environment that someone thought, yes, we've cancelled

01:41:03.440 --> 01:41:06.840
[Guest]: her primarily because I was worried about I thought I don't want to be part of that

01:41:06.840 --> 01:41:08.980
[Guest]: if they think they're going to know let's not.

01:41:08.980 --> 01:41:14.440
[Guest]: But I also realize I also because I privilege my research, because I privilege, because

01:41:14.440 --> 01:41:19.400
[Guest]: I prioritize learning, and because I realized the gains to Twitter, I wanted to unlock my

01:41:19.400 --> 01:41:20.920
[Guest]: account to allow some abuse.

01:41:20.920 --> 01:41:22.840
[Guest]: You know, that's a trade off, right?

01:41:22.840 --> 01:41:28.760
[Guest]: I was willing to endure some abuse, because the gains to my learning is so huge from Twitter.

01:41:28.760 --> 01:41:34.160
[Unknown]: So that's, so that's, so that's the second point to the third point that enables me to

01:41:34.160 --> 01:41:40.860
[Guest]: third point is that I have been very lucky that I have many kind friends, that when they

01:41:40.860 --> 01:41:43.880
[Guest]: do see nastiness, they reach out.

01:41:43.880 --> 01:41:50.000
[Guest]: So and they express kindness, and that helps me realize, you know, that gives me some support

01:41:50.000 --> 01:41:55.560
[Guest]: and feeling that, you know, it's very upsetting when people say hateful things, that's hurtful.

01:41:55.560 --> 01:41:59.760
[Guest]: And when people, when friends reach out, and they say they understand, and they and they

01:41:59.760 --> 01:42:06.480
[Guest]: and they think that it that it's unfair, that legitimizes us and that actually relates to

01:42:06.480 --> 01:42:11.640
[Guest]: a broader point in terms of feminist consciousness and the consciousness of marginalized groups

01:42:11.640 --> 01:42:16.700
[Guest]: more broadly, that many people may be privately critical of something, but they can be emboldened

01:42:16.700 --> 01:42:19.680
[Guest]: to resist once they have the support and encouragement of others.

01:42:19.680 --> 01:42:23.560
[Guest]: And so that's why I always emphasize this point of friendship and peer support.

01:42:23.560 --> 01:42:26.560
[Guest]: And Shruti has always given me support, and you did too.

01:42:26.560 --> 01:42:28.240
[Guest]: And I'm grateful for that.

01:42:28.240 --> 01:42:36.400
[Unknown]: And then a final point, so to say, yeah, so I think those and so how do I, but I won't

01:42:36.400 --> 01:42:41.480
[Guest]: deny that I won't deny that these things are hurtful, but particularly because I would

01:42:41.480 --> 01:42:44.320
[Guest]: never I would never want to hurt people.

01:42:44.320 --> 01:42:49.280
[Guest]: Like I would never want to upset people, like I care, I do care about people's feelings.

01:42:49.280 --> 01:42:51.960
[Guest]: So I wouldn't want people to feel hurt by things.

01:42:51.960 --> 01:42:57.800
[Guest]: And I also need to learn, I need to learn to be more careful in how I present things.

01:42:57.800 --> 01:43:00.240
[Guest]: So I'm not going to blame trolls for getting it wrong.

01:43:00.240 --> 01:43:02.440
[Guest]: You know, I wouldn't even I shouldn't even call them trolls.

01:43:02.440 --> 01:43:05.280
[Guest]: I should be more careful in how I present my research.

01:43:05.280 --> 01:43:07.240
[Guest]: And that's absolutely on me.

01:43:07.240 --> 01:43:13.480
[Guest]: And that's something that I learned through trial and error, and occasional trolling.

01:43:13.480 --> 01:43:16.560
[Amit Varma]: You know, I'll push back a little bit of that very last thing you said, because the truth

01:43:16.560 --> 01:43:20.760
[Amit Varma]: is, no matter how careful you are, if people want to come after you, they'll find a reason

01:43:20.760 --> 01:43:21.760
[Amit Varma]: to come after you.

01:43:21.760 --> 01:43:25.720
[Amit Varma]: I mean, a lot of what has been said about you has really been said in bad faith.

01:43:25.720 --> 01:43:31.600
[Amit Varma]: And if bad faith is your starting point, then it doesn't matter specifically what you say.

01:43:31.600 --> 01:43:37.640
[Amit Varma]: But but yeah, I mean, sort of I kind of get what you're where you're coming from.

01:43:37.640 --> 01:43:44.080
[Amit Varma]: And it's always disturbing, like my, my way of dealing with it also, you know, is a way

01:43:44.080 --> 01:43:45.840
[Amit Varma]: of providing dopamine to myself.

01:43:45.840 --> 01:43:50.480
[Amit Varma]: In the sense, I realized at one point, and this was a right wing mob, which attacked

01:43:50.480 --> 01:43:56.040
[Amit Varma]: me after I criticized demonetization, that one, my strategy was just to block everyone,

01:43:56.040 --> 01:43:59.640
[Amit Varma]: not just block people who were trolling me or abusing me, but block anyone who was being

01:43:59.640 --> 01:44:00.640
[Amit Varma]: rude.

01:44:00.640 --> 01:44:04.200
[Amit Varma]: So my habit is block anyone who's being rude, who's engaging in bad faith, either with me

01:44:04.200 --> 01:44:06.240
[Amit Varma]: or with a friend, just block.

01:44:06.240 --> 01:44:11.640
[Amit Varma]: And after a point, I realized that days which were quiet, I was sort of missing the dopamine

01:44:11.640 --> 01:44:13.760
[Amit Varma]: hits that each block gave me.

01:44:13.760 --> 01:44:17.640
[Amit Varma]: You know, you could say I was being addicted to blocking people.

01:44:17.640 --> 01:44:21.560
[Amit Varma]: But once I became aware of this, I successfully fought this addiction.

01:44:21.560 --> 01:44:26.640
[Amit Varma]: Otherwise, I could have, you know, been deliberately provocative just to be able to block people.

01:44:26.640 --> 01:44:29.760
[Amit Varma]: But anyway, thankfully, I haven't gone down, down that road.

01:44:29.760 --> 01:44:32.480
[Amit Varma]: So you know, let's take a quick commercial break now.

01:44:32.480 --> 01:44:36.640
[Amit Varma]: And on the other side of the break, we'll, you know, continue talking about your life,

01:44:36.640 --> 01:44:39.760
[Amit Varma]: but also actually get to your work, the great gender divergence.

01:44:39.760 --> 01:44:44.040
[Unknown]: So thank you so much.

01:44:44.040 --> 01:44:46.680
[Amit Varma]: Long before I was a podcaster, I was a writer.

01:44:46.680 --> 01:44:51.800
[Amit Varma]: In fact, chances are that many of you first heard of me because of my blog India Uncut,

01:44:51.800 --> 01:44:56.640
[Amit Varma]: which was active between 2003 and 2009 and became somewhat popular at the time.

01:44:56.640 --> 01:44:58.920
[Amit Varma]: I love the freedom the form gave me.

01:44:58.920 --> 01:45:01.680
[Amit Varma]: And I feel I was shaped by it in many ways.

01:45:01.680 --> 01:45:06.600
[Amit Varma]: I exercise my writing muscle every day and was forced to think about many different things

01:45:06.600 --> 01:45:08.840
[Amit Varma]: because I wrote about many different things.

01:45:08.840 --> 01:45:12.160
[Amit Varma]: Well, that phase in my life ended for various reasons.

01:45:12.160 --> 01:45:13.840
[Amit Varma]: And now it is time to revive it.

01:45:13.840 --> 01:45:16.640
[Amit Varma]: Only now, I'm doing it through a newsletter.

01:45:16.640 --> 01:45:22.800
[Amit Varma]: I have started the India Uncut newsletter at indiancut.substack.com, where I will write

01:45:22.800 --> 01:45:25.280
[Amit Varma]: regularly about whatever catches my fancy.

01:45:25.280 --> 01:45:29.920
[Amit Varma]: I'll write about some of the themes I cover in this podcast and about much else.

01:45:29.920 --> 01:45:34.520
[Amit Varma]: So please do head on over to indiancut.substack.com and subscribe.

01:45:34.520 --> 01:45:35.520
[Amit Varma]: It is free.

01:45:35.520 --> 01:45:40.000
[Amit Varma]: Once you sign up, each new installment that I write will land up in your email inbox.

01:45:40.000 --> 01:45:41.800
[Amit Varma]: You don't need to go anywhere.

01:45:41.800 --> 01:45:43.840
[Amit Varma]: So subscribe now for free.

01:45:43.840 --> 01:45:48.160
[Amit Varma]: The India Uncut newsletter at indiancut.substack.com.

01:45:48.160 --> 01:45:51.200
[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

01:45:51.200 --> 01:45:52.560
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the Unseen.

01:45:52.560 --> 01:45:57.840
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Alice Evans about her great work on gender, specifically her forthcoming

01:45:57.840 --> 01:46:01.700
[Amit Varma]: book called The Great Gender Divergence, which we're all waiting for, which even Princeton

01:46:01.700 --> 01:46:03.680
[Amit Varma]: is waiting for, though they are pretty patient.

01:46:03.680 --> 01:46:07.360
[Amit Varma]: I don't feel like waiting another eight or nine years for it.

01:46:07.360 --> 01:46:11.200
[Amit Varma]: So here's the thing, you know, I right when I began my research for this, obviously, the

01:46:11.200 --> 01:46:14.840
[Amit Varma]: first step is you Google somebody's name, and there's an actress by the name of Alice

01:46:14.840 --> 01:46:15.840
[Amit Varma]: Evans.

01:46:15.840 --> 01:46:16.840
[Amit Varma]: And I was like, what is this?

01:46:16.840 --> 01:46:22.720
[Amit Varma]: We must make sure that our Alice is the first Google search result and this other person,

01:46:22.720 --> 01:46:23.720
[Amit Varma]: it's just intolerable.

01:46:23.720 --> 01:46:30.560
[Amit Varma]: But leaving that aside, tell me a little bit about how you arrived at this subject in terms

01:46:30.560 --> 01:46:34.600
[Amit Varma]: of this is what I'm interested in, and this is what I want to do.

01:46:34.600 --> 01:46:39.920
[Amit Varma]: Like you already spoke about going to Zambia and doing that, you know, the narrow study

01:46:39.920 --> 01:46:41.120
[Amit Varma]: that you did.

01:46:41.120 --> 01:46:45.040
[Amit Varma]: But how did that process take place where you kind of broadened your view and you said

01:46:45.040 --> 01:46:50.360
[Amit Varma]: that no, I don't just want to study A or B or C, I want to study the whole damn alphabet.

01:46:50.360 --> 01:46:52.080
[Amit Varma]: How did that come about?

01:46:52.080 --> 01:46:58.120
[Guest]: Well, I was always interested in these long term comparative studies.

01:46:58.120 --> 01:47:02.440
[Guest]: I've seen that through my rural urban contrast, my Cambodia, Zambia contrast, so I really

01:47:02.440 --> 01:47:03.440
[Guest]: enjoyed that.

01:47:03.440 --> 01:47:09.320
[Guest]: And I've always been interested in examining the causes of how the world came to be.

01:47:09.320 --> 01:47:13.320
[Guest]: So some, for example, economists or political scientists might examine the effects of some

01:47:13.320 --> 01:47:14.720
[Guest]: intervention or some shock.

01:47:14.720 --> 01:47:19.560
[Guest]: I've always been interested in why is our world like as it is.

01:47:19.560 --> 01:47:25.600
[Guest]: So that was my prior disposition, though, I tell you, I actually stopped researching

01:47:25.600 --> 01:47:36.480
[Guest]: gender in about 2017, no, 2016, 17, because as I was saying earlier, there really were,

01:47:36.480 --> 01:47:40.760
[Guest]: even though I was publishing fine in very nice journals, no one was really that interested

01:47:40.760 --> 01:47:41.760
[Guest]: in my research.

01:47:41.760 --> 01:47:44.440
[Guest]: And there just wasn't the environment.

01:47:44.440 --> 01:47:46.280
[Guest]: People just, they weren't bothered.

01:47:46.280 --> 01:47:47.920
[Guest]: No one else was doing what I was doing.

01:47:47.920 --> 01:47:48.920
[Guest]: So I stopped it.

01:47:48.920 --> 01:47:52.040
[Guest]: And I did labour repression and global supply chains.

01:47:52.040 --> 01:47:54.960
[Guest]: And I went on a total tangent of looking at corporate accountability.

01:47:54.960 --> 01:48:00.640
[Guest]: I compared the political, the politics of labour repression in Bangladesh and Vietnam.

01:48:00.640 --> 01:48:06.880
[Guest]: So I was, I'd even given up on gender because there was so many, you know, for example,

01:48:06.880 --> 01:48:10.960
[Guest]: you know, in gender theory, there's often a lot of understanding gender identities and

01:48:10.960 --> 01:48:14.360
[Guest]: gender fluidity and performances of gender, whereas you have these other, economists might

01:48:14.360 --> 01:48:17.480
[Guest]: be looking at smaller processes, you know, RCTs.

01:48:17.480 --> 01:48:20.440
[Guest]: So no one was doing these big comparative studies.

01:48:20.440 --> 01:48:28.040
[Guest]: And I think I was a little bit lonely in the sense that I just, there wasn't anyone who

01:48:28.040 --> 01:48:30.640
[Guest]: saw value in what I was doing.

01:48:30.640 --> 01:48:34.560
[Guest]: And so I thought, well, you know, let me not do, let me, so I didn't have enough self-belief

01:48:34.560 --> 01:48:35.960
[Guest]: to, to continue it.

01:48:35.960 --> 01:48:42.200
[Guest]: And then as I was saying, I encountered economic history on the great gender divergence, how

01:48:42.200 --> 01:48:43.200
[Guest]: the West became rich.

01:48:43.200 --> 01:48:49.360
[Guest]: And I, I loved this for the big comparative questions, you know, striking at the heart

01:48:49.360 --> 01:48:56.240
[Guest]: of the differences in our global society, and also using interdisciplinary methods.

01:48:56.240 --> 01:49:02.800
[Guest]: So drawing on also economics and understanding geography, so drawing or marshalling every

01:49:02.800 --> 01:49:05.200
[Guest]: method to work out what's going on.

01:49:05.200 --> 01:49:06.960
[Guest]: And so I really loved that.

01:49:06.960 --> 01:49:11.840
[Guest]: And so that's how I came to look at the great gender divergence.

01:49:11.840 --> 01:49:18.560
[Guest]: Now in terms of my methodology, when I start a new region, first of all, I remember when

01:49:18.560 --> 01:49:22.840
[Guest]: I started studying South Asia or the Middle East, I mean, I was totally overwhelmed, you

01:49:22.840 --> 01:49:24.440
[Guest]: know, I'm a total outsider, right?

01:49:24.440 --> 01:49:28.880
[Guest]: I know Zambia and Cambodia, what did I know about India?

01:49:28.880 --> 01:49:31.880
[Guest]: And that's incredibly overwhelming.

01:49:31.880 --> 01:49:37.280
[Guest]: And I, and I accept, you know, it may seem mad that I even embarked on trying to understand

01:49:37.280 --> 01:49:39.120
[Guest]: the history of gender in India.

01:49:39.120 --> 01:49:46.280
[Guest]: I mean, to be clear, no one has written a history of gender, or an explanation of how

01:49:46.280 --> 01:49:49.480
[Guest]: countries became so patriarchal in any one country.

01:49:49.480 --> 01:49:53.000
[Guest]: So I'm trying to do in every single country, what has not been done as an explanation of

01:49:53.000 --> 01:49:54.000
[Guest]: it.

01:49:54.000 --> 01:49:58.400
[Guest]: And how I do that is one, first of all, start with some broad overview history.

01:49:58.400 --> 01:50:01.960
[Guest]: So let me understand South Asian history, or let me understand history in Morocco.

01:50:01.960 --> 01:50:04.220
[Guest]: And then I piece together that jigsaw.

01:50:04.220 --> 01:50:08.740
[Guest]: So I go further back, I look at population movements by looking at genetic data of who

01:50:08.740 --> 01:50:14.560
[Guest]: moved in where, I look at archaeology, I read histories from medieval period, I read more

01:50:14.560 --> 01:50:18.120
[Guest]: recent studies from economics, sociology, anthropology.

01:50:18.120 --> 01:50:23.880
[Guest]: So all this time, I'm always piecing together little different parts of the jigsaw, definitely

01:50:23.880 --> 01:50:29.120
[Guest]: learning from all these disciplines, and iteratively building.

01:50:29.120 --> 01:50:35.440
[Guest]: So I think one difference that distinguishes my methodology from some of the big books

01:50:35.440 --> 01:50:41.560
[Guest]: on the rise of the Westwood, they often have their theory.

01:50:41.560 --> 01:50:44.040
[Guest]: But it's not necessarily developed from the ground up.

01:50:44.040 --> 01:50:49.080
[Guest]: What I'm really trying to do is study every single society and not go in with any priors,

01:50:49.080 --> 01:50:54.160
[Guest]: not go in with any priors at all, but try to assemble it from the bottom up.

01:50:54.160 --> 01:50:58.680
[Guest]: So we can use big studies in economics, for example, there's a famous paper by Alessina

01:50:58.680 --> 01:51:02.800
[Guest]: and others, showing that countries that had a history of the plough, typically have lower

01:51:02.800 --> 01:51:04.480
[Guest]: female labor force participation.

01:51:04.480 --> 01:51:10.200
[Guest]: And then we can try to use anthropology to trace changes over time to understand or archaeology

01:51:10.200 --> 01:51:16.800
[Guest]: or sociology to understand why that might be important and to do when you study each

01:51:16.800 --> 01:51:22.000
[Guest]: society in depth, you can try to understand why might the plough be associated with lower

01:51:22.000 --> 01:51:23.800
[Guest]: female labor force participation.

01:51:23.800 --> 01:51:31.280
[Guest]: So it's all a sort of, it's an act of assembly, it's an act of working with a 4D jigsaw that's

01:51:31.280 --> 01:51:34.440
[Guest]: continually in flux, and everything should be up for grabs.

01:51:34.440 --> 01:51:39.600
[Guest]: And this goes back to my philosophical training that there are no sacred truths that I should

01:51:39.600 --> 01:51:43.680
[Guest]: be questioning everything, and that I should be rigorously interrogating things.

01:51:43.680 --> 01:51:49.440
[Guest]: So for example, yeah, so there are many, there are many beliefs that I now hold that I didn't

01:51:49.440 --> 01:51:50.440
[Guest]: go in with.

01:51:50.440 --> 01:52:01.560
[Guest]: So for example, as a very secular atheist nihilist, you know, sort of left leaning,

01:52:01.560 --> 01:52:06.000
[Guest]: my prior was not that, you know, Christianity was some great force for the world, right?

01:52:06.000 --> 01:52:09.000
[Guest]: That's a position that would be taken by a centre-right who I definitely do not agree

01:52:09.000 --> 01:52:10.000
[Guest]: with.

01:52:10.000 --> 01:52:17.560
[Guest]: And so one of the arguments is that it was the Christian church that promoted the European

01:52:17.560 --> 01:52:21.480
[Guest]: marriage pattern, that is nuclear families, and that might, and it's the church that meant

01:52:21.480 --> 01:52:27.280
[Guest]: the church that Europe has these nuclear families, I was so opposed to that idea, I really did

01:52:27.280 --> 01:52:31.440
[Guest]: not want to accept the idea that there was something good in Christianity.

01:52:31.440 --> 01:52:38.920
[Guest]: You know, there are so many patriarchal aspects to the Christianity, and I associated it with

01:52:38.920 --> 01:52:41.800
[Guest]: the right that I just didn't like.

01:52:41.800 --> 01:52:47.040
[Guest]: And so I, and so I really studied all the literature on medieval Europe, I considered

01:52:47.040 --> 01:52:50.040
[Guest]: all the different hypotheses, I looked at the evidence.

01:52:50.040 --> 01:52:53.400
[Guest]: And then I think one thing that really changed it for me, I was reading this book, fantastic

01:52:53.400 --> 01:52:56.920
[Guest]: book called Ties That Bind by Barbara Hanawalt.

01:52:56.920 --> 01:53:02.800
[Guest]: And she looks at coroner's reports from before the Black Death.

01:53:02.800 --> 01:53:09.320
[Guest]: So in the 11th century, and what she finds is that even before the Black Death, these

01:53:09.320 --> 01:53:15.160
[Guest]: peasant families in England were cooperating outside their kinship group, they lived in

01:53:15.160 --> 01:53:20.920
[Guest]: nuclear families, women were working, and she shows that the nuclear family existed

01:53:20.920 --> 01:53:22.120
[Guest]: long before the Black Death.

01:53:22.120 --> 01:53:27.400
[Guest]: So it can, so the other geographical theories that the Black Death led to a far deeper labour

01:53:27.400 --> 01:53:31.720
[Guest]: market, and it was that those jobs in service that enabled people to live apart from their

01:53:31.720 --> 01:53:34.160
[Guest]: families and that broke down these kinship groups.

01:53:34.160 --> 01:53:37.680
[Guest]: But she's showing actually, all this existed long before the Black Death.

01:53:37.680 --> 01:53:43.560
[Guest]: And she also found that people were refusing cousin marriage, they were refusing, they

01:53:43.560 --> 01:53:49.320
[Guest]: were abiding by many, many of the prescriptions of the church.

01:53:49.320 --> 01:53:52.480
[Guest]: And so I realized, and she doesn't use her book to relate to the nuclear family pattern,

01:53:52.480 --> 01:53:58.320
[Guest]: but I realized that actually, the church was incredibly draconian, the church was interfering

01:53:58.320 --> 01:54:00.100
[Guest]: in people's private lives.

01:54:00.100 --> 01:54:04.800
[Guest]: And I realized that nobles were leveraging those incest prohibitions in order to stop

01:54:04.800 --> 01:54:07.080
[Guest]: their rivals for consolidating wealth.

01:54:07.080 --> 01:54:13.360
[Guest]: And so against my own priors, against what I consider to be my better judgment, I increasingly

01:54:13.360 --> 01:54:17.800
[Guest]: realized that there was an important role for the church in that they stamped out cousin

01:54:17.800 --> 01:54:18.800
[Guest]: marriage.

01:54:18.800 --> 01:54:23.320
[Guest]: And then as a result of that, couples were expected to form nuclear households, and you

01:54:23.320 --> 01:54:27.200
[Guest]: could only form a nuclear household when you'd acquired sufficient resources.

01:54:27.200 --> 01:54:31.760
[Guest]: And that meant that both men and women often worked in service on very, very low wages.

01:54:31.760 --> 01:54:35.000
[Guest]: And that meant a rather late age of marriage, because you had to acquire enough wealth before

01:54:35.000 --> 01:54:36.000
[Guest]: marrying.

01:54:36.000 --> 01:54:39.820
[Guest]: And then women continued to work after marriage in medieval Europe.

01:54:39.820 --> 01:54:43.400
[Guest]: And as a result of that, husbands and wives often cooperated.

01:54:43.400 --> 01:54:48.160
[Guest]: Now that's not to say that Europe was gender equal, far from it, it was incredibly patriarchal,

01:54:48.160 --> 01:54:54.400
[Guest]: men dominated the judiciary, the courts, the medicine, health, parliament, etc, religion.

01:54:54.400 --> 01:54:57.480
[Guest]: But at least there was that, that at least women were working.

01:54:57.480 --> 01:55:03.600
[Guest]: And so there are so many things that I've been, it's really this continually testing

01:55:03.600 --> 01:55:08.520
[Guest]: my hypotheses, that sort of, and you know, studying all sorts of bits together that's

01:55:08.520 --> 01:55:09.840
[Guest]: helped me work out what's going on.

01:55:09.840 --> 01:55:12.440
[Guest]: And the comparative aspect is really helpful too.

01:55:12.440 --> 01:55:13.440
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:55:13.440 --> 01:55:17.800
[Amit Varma]: And that seems almost radical, given the context of academia, like one lamin that historians

01:55:17.800 --> 01:55:23.660
[Amit Varma]: who've been on the show have, is that within academic history, you're always expected to

01:55:23.660 --> 01:55:25.600
[Amit Varma]: have some lens or the other, right?

01:55:25.600 --> 01:55:30.000
[Amit Varma]: So you'd imagine that what is history, history is you're talking about what happened.

01:55:30.000 --> 01:55:33.760
[Amit Varma]: But actually, you look at academic history, and there'll be Marxist historians who'll

01:55:33.760 --> 01:55:36.960
[Amit Varma]: always have that specific lens, and they'll apply that to everything.

01:55:36.960 --> 01:55:42.680
[Amit Varma]: And within all the humanities, you know, it becomes, you know, as much a propagation of

01:55:42.680 --> 01:55:47.080
[Amit Varma]: a particular political ideology as much as it is a pursuit of truth.

01:55:47.080 --> 01:55:51.440
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, the approach that, you know, you've taken with this book is that I will

01:55:51.440 --> 01:55:55.880
[Amit Varma]: have no priors, and I will just, you know, bring in frames from everywhere to look at

01:55:55.880 --> 01:55:59.480
[Amit Varma]: this seems almost radical and also brave.

01:55:59.480 --> 01:56:06.040
[Amit Varma]: So what's sort of been the reaction from within academia, for example, for something like

01:56:06.040 --> 01:56:07.040
[Amit Varma]: this?

01:56:07.040 --> 01:56:12.440
[Amit Varma]: So like, this is a big book, Princeton has commissioned it, it's a huge project, you

01:56:12.440 --> 01:56:18.520
[Amit Varma]: know, do you get pushback from your academic peers and colleagues and so on and so forth?

01:56:18.520 --> 01:56:24.280
[Amit Varma]: And is there jealousy, how does all of that play itself out?

01:56:24.280 --> 01:56:25.280
[Guest]: Let me say two things.

01:56:25.280 --> 01:56:31.400
[Guest]: I think that academics often talk about positionality, that our background experiences will shape

01:56:31.400 --> 01:56:34.320
[Guest]: the kinds of questions and research we pursue.

01:56:34.320 --> 01:56:37.720
[Guest]: And maybe listening to this podcast, some people might think, oh, she had an abusive

01:56:37.720 --> 01:56:42.520
[Guest]: partner, she had an abusive father, she was born without a vagina, of course, she ends

01:56:42.520 --> 01:56:43.520
[Guest]: up studying gender.

01:56:43.520 --> 01:56:45.080
[Guest]: And I would like to say two things.

01:56:45.080 --> 01:56:48.360
[Guest]: Number one, none of those experiences led me to gender, it was actually just because

01:56:48.360 --> 01:56:51.760
[Guest]: I knew the supervisor who was studying the Gambia.

01:56:51.760 --> 01:57:00.480
[Guest]: Secondly, I think my background experiences made me, I think through overcoming adversity

01:57:00.480 --> 01:57:04.560
[Guest]: and iteratively travelling the world gave me the confidence and the ambition to take

01:57:04.560 --> 01:57:05.920
[Guest]: on a big project.

01:57:05.920 --> 01:57:11.440
[Guest]: But what I would hope and what I aspire to, is that anyone else who studied the exact

01:57:11.440 --> 01:57:14.960
[Guest]: same question who looked at the same data would come to the same conclusion.

01:57:14.960 --> 01:57:19.720
[Guest]: So it may be my background experiences that led me to take on this big project.

01:57:19.720 --> 01:57:23.960
[Guest]: But I am, I think that there is an objective truth, which others could also reach out.

01:57:23.960 --> 01:57:25.440
[Guest]: And if I get something wrong, they should correct me.

01:57:25.440 --> 01:57:29.040
[Guest]: So that's my point about background positionality.

01:57:29.040 --> 01:57:34.280
[Guest]: So I don't, I'm, you know, all my research is going to be influenced by my priors, but

01:57:34.280 --> 01:57:39.720
[Guest]: I should try to challenge them and read work that challenges them.

01:57:39.720 --> 01:57:48.360
[Guest]: I also need to be careful about how I present my research, because to some, for example,

01:57:48.360 --> 01:57:53.160
[Guest]: it might be seen like I'm, I might be seen in various ways.

01:57:53.160 --> 01:57:59.160
[Guest]: So for example, when I talk about economic growth, my, I need to be quite emphatic that

01:57:59.160 --> 01:58:01.440
[Guest]: my point is, that my points are twofold.

01:58:01.440 --> 01:58:05.560
[Guest]: One is on job creating economic growth, not worshipping GDP in itself.

01:58:05.560 --> 01:58:11.000
[Guest]: And two, that job creation enables female solidarity, and the real point is this friendship

01:58:11.000 --> 01:58:13.680
[Guest]: and exposure and questioning and challenging.

01:58:13.680 --> 01:58:18.040
[Guest]: And I need to make that clear, because if I'm not sufficiently nuanced, someone might

01:58:18.040 --> 01:58:23.360
[Guest]: think Alice is this neoliberal defending GDP, for example.

01:58:23.360 --> 01:58:27.320
[Guest]: So it's partly about how I phrase and present my research.

01:58:27.320 --> 01:58:29.560
[Guest]: I think that's important.

01:58:29.560 --> 01:58:38.760
[Guest]: Yeah, I, I, it's difficult to know at that, at this stage, how everyone feels about it.

01:58:38.760 --> 01:58:43.480
[Guest]: I'm sure there is some resistance, I mean, in some groups might not like the point of

01:58:43.480 --> 01:58:44.480
[Guest]: regional comparisons.

01:58:44.480 --> 01:58:48.320
[Guest]: You know, gender research is often very specific about a very specific place.

01:58:48.320 --> 01:58:52.280
[Guest]: Some people don't even like the idea that I'm doing big regional comparisons.

01:58:52.280 --> 01:58:56.580
[Guest]: So anyone who knows India will say, well, there's huge heterogeneity within India.

01:58:56.580 --> 01:59:05.640
[Guest]: And that's absolutely true, but across India as a whole, men represent 89% of its leaders,

01:59:05.640 --> 01:59:07.440
[Guest]: of its political representatives.

01:59:07.440 --> 01:59:12.120
[Guest]: Across India as a whole, pretty much every state has a female labour force participation

01:59:12.120 --> 01:59:15.900
[Guest]: rate and certainly an urban female labour force participation rate of below 20%.

01:59:15.900 --> 01:59:21.480
[Guest]: So although there's this heterogeneity, and that's well below the global average in terms

01:59:21.480 --> 01:59:24.840
[Guest]: of both female employment and political representation.

01:59:24.840 --> 01:59:30.240
[Guest]: So for example, if you look at the World Economic Forum Gender Gap Index, where they look at

01:59:30.240 --> 01:59:36.120
[Guest]: these different objective nationally representative data on gender inequality, we do see that

01:59:36.120 --> 01:59:41.700
[Guest]: North Africa, the Middle East and South Asia are different from the global average.

01:59:41.700 --> 01:59:45.720
[Guest]: So some people, but some people would see my analysis as far too sweeping by ignoring

01:59:45.720 --> 01:59:46.800
[Guest]: that heterogeneity in it.

01:59:46.800 --> 01:59:53.720
[Guest]: So I think, so there are some people who have reservations with even asking the question

01:59:53.720 --> 01:59:57.000
[Guest]: that I'm asking, for sure, for sure.

01:59:57.000 --> 01:59:58.000
[Guest]: And that's okay.

01:59:58.000 --> 01:59:59.000
[Guest]: We all ask different questions.

01:59:59.000 --> 02:00:03.680
[Guest]: And I can, you know, let a thousand flowers bloom, let other people do their own research.

02:00:03.680 --> 02:00:07.480
[Guest]: But I think this is important and let me try for all those who are interested.

02:00:07.480 --> 02:00:10.320
[Amit Varma]: Let a thousand flowers bloom, indeed.

02:00:10.320 --> 02:00:12.680
[Amit Varma]: Let's sort of get to the topic at hand.

02:00:12.680 --> 02:00:17.680
[Amit Varma]: And one of the essays I like the most is one that's titled 10,000 Years of Patriarchy Updated,

02:00:17.680 --> 02:00:18.680
[Amit Varma]: right?

02:00:18.680 --> 02:00:24.760
[Amit Varma]: And it's such a sweeping look at, as the title suggests, the broad history, you know, what

02:00:24.760 --> 02:00:25.760
[Amit Varma]: is patriarchy?

02:00:25.760 --> 02:00:26.760
[Amit Varma]: Where did it come from?

02:00:26.760 --> 02:00:28.480
[Amit Varma]: What are the different factors that led to its rise?

02:00:28.480 --> 02:00:34.240
[Amit Varma]: And before we actually get to that final sort of meta question, which is that, were there

02:00:34.240 --> 02:00:39.240
[Amit Varma]: any role models you had in terms of either researchers or writers who have attempted

02:00:39.240 --> 02:00:45.160
[Amit Varma]: similar things in different fields, obviously, not this one, like within, for example, popular

02:00:45.160 --> 02:00:49.120
[Unknown]: nonfiction, you have people like Jared Diamond, who wrote his books on, you know, why countries

02:00:49.120 --> 02:00:52.760
[Amit Varma]: turn out the way they do, the importance of geography, and so on.

02:00:52.760 --> 02:00:57.920
[Amit Varma]: There's Paul Collier, who's also looked at why nations have developed the way they have.

02:00:57.920 --> 02:01:01.760
[Amit Varma]: Were there models you have where you said that, yes, this person is great, they're bringing

02:01:01.760 --> 02:01:05.720
[Amit Varma]: this frame and that frame, and there's something new happening here?

02:01:05.720 --> 02:01:10.000
[Amit Varma]: Who were your influences in that sense?

02:01:10.000 --> 02:01:11.920
[Guest]: That's a great question.

02:01:11.920 --> 02:01:18.080
[Guest]: I think in terms of introducing me to economic history, Pseudo Erasmus, who's an economic

02:01:18.080 --> 02:01:23.200
[Guest]: historian blogger, he was enormously influential, and the rigor through which he looks at different

02:01:23.200 --> 02:01:26.960
[Guest]: theories and exploring evidence, that was hugely influential.

02:01:26.960 --> 02:01:33.600
[Guest]: I also have a really great friend who's really supported me, and I share many of my hypotheses

02:01:33.600 --> 02:01:40.360
[Guest]: with him, Professor Daron Adjemoglu at MIT, and he's written a number of big books.

02:01:40.360 --> 02:01:46.240
[Guest]: I don't have so many friends with whom I can discuss my research, but he's one person who's

02:01:46.240 --> 02:01:50.800
[Guest]: really supported me, and I share ideas, and we talk about it a lot together, so he's really

02:01:50.800 --> 02:01:51.800
[Guest]: supported me.

02:01:51.800 --> 02:01:55.680
[Guest]: I think that, yeah, there are a number, I mean, you mentioned all those big names, those

02:01:55.680 --> 02:02:02.560
[Guest]: big books, those big sweeping books were great and fascinating, all of those were written

02:02:02.560 --> 02:02:07.800
[Guest]: by men, all of those big ambitious books were written by men.

02:02:07.800 --> 02:02:13.080
[Guest]: Men tend to be much more focused, much more specific, and among those, I would highlight

02:02:13.080 --> 02:02:14.960
[Guest]: the work of Professor Naila Kabir.

02:02:14.960 --> 02:02:16.760
[Guest]: She's a brilliant scholar.

02:02:16.760 --> 02:02:20.280
[Guest]: So there are many scholars, also Professor Sylvia Chant, my supervisor.

02:02:20.280 --> 02:02:22.400
[Guest]: So there are many, many brilliant scholarship.

02:02:22.400 --> 02:02:29.040
[Guest]: Also another person who I have greatly admired, and her insights are hugely important, Professor

02:02:29.040 --> 02:02:34.760
[Guest]: Claudia Golden, an economist at Harvard, and by analyzing the US labor market, she drew

02:02:34.760 --> 02:02:41.560
[Guest]: the importance of tightening labor demand, that initially firms would impose marriage

02:02:41.560 --> 02:02:46.400
[Guest]: bars, that women had to lose their jobs when they got married, but when demand tightened,

02:02:46.400 --> 02:02:49.760
[Guest]: when firms and factories needed women, they abandoned these marriage bars.

02:02:49.760 --> 02:02:52.840
[Guest]: And I see that, and I've seen that pattern repeated across the world, that when you have

02:02:52.840 --> 02:02:57.600
[Guest]: tight labor markets, then firms increasingly want to hire women, and we can talk about

02:02:57.600 --> 02:02:58.920
[Guest]: that in the case of Taiwan.

02:02:58.920 --> 02:03:03.600
[Guest]: So there are so many scholars whose work has greatly enriched me, greatly enriched my understanding

02:03:03.600 --> 02:03:08.400
[Guest]: and improved my analysis, and it really is a collective project.

02:03:08.400 --> 02:03:14.480
[Guest]: It really is a collective project of me learning from other people, and I'm always very, very

02:03:14.480 --> 02:03:20.800
[Guest]: grateful when people message me again on Twitter, sharing their papers, sharing their research,

02:03:20.800 --> 02:03:22.360
[Guest]: because that really, yeah, that really helps me.

02:03:22.360 --> 02:03:27.000
[Guest]: It's absolutely, you know, improving our knowledge is absolutely a collective project.

02:03:27.000 --> 02:03:31.720
[Guest]: I don't want to give the impression that I think I'm this one maverick going at it by

02:03:31.720 --> 02:03:33.120
[Guest]: myself or alone.

02:03:33.120 --> 02:03:38.040
[Guest]: It's very much through learning from other people's brilliant research.

02:03:38.040 --> 02:03:43.960
[Amit Varma]: Let's talk about the history of gender now, and you've written about three major waves

02:03:43.960 --> 02:03:46.240
[Amit Varma]: of patriarchalism, as it were.

02:03:46.240 --> 02:03:48.280
[Unknown]: Why do you academics use such big words?

02:03:48.280 --> 02:03:49.280
[Unknown]: It makes it so difficult for me.

02:03:49.280 --> 02:03:50.280
[Unknown]: What's a better word?

02:03:50.280 --> 02:03:51.280
[Unknown]: What's a better word?

02:03:51.280 --> 02:03:52.280
[Amit Varma]: I can't think of a better word for this.

02:03:52.280 --> 02:03:57.800
[Amit Varma]: Three major waves of, I mean, I'd just break it up, you know, male domination or something

02:03:57.800 --> 02:03:58.800
[Unknown]: of that sort.

02:03:58.800 --> 02:03:59.800
[Unknown]: Patriarchy.

02:03:59.800 --> 02:04:00.800
[Unknown]: Patriarchy is fine.

02:04:00.800 --> 02:04:03.200
[Unknown]: Actually, patriarchy is better than patriarchalism.

02:04:03.200 --> 02:04:05.560
[Amit Varma]: No, no, I'm just kidding.

02:04:05.560 --> 02:04:06.560
[Amit Varma]: No, no, it's fine.

02:04:06.560 --> 02:04:07.560
[Unknown]: I'm just pulling your leg.

02:04:07.560 --> 02:04:10.440
[Amit Varma]: So you can't offend me.

02:04:10.440 --> 02:04:13.880
[Amit Varma]: That's great, because that's what I tell people about me as well, that you can't offend me,

02:04:13.880 --> 02:04:14.880
[Unknown]: but sadly.

02:04:14.880 --> 02:04:15.880
[Unknown]: You really can't.

02:04:15.880 --> 02:04:18.120
[Unknown]: I mean, there's nothing you could say that would offend me.

02:04:18.120 --> 02:04:21.240
[Amit Varma]: OK, I'm not even going to try to test that.

02:04:21.240 --> 02:04:27.320
[Amit Varma]: So, yeah, I'm not interested in offending others either, but no doubt others will test

02:04:27.320 --> 02:04:28.600
[Amit Varma]: it out.

02:04:28.600 --> 02:04:35.720
[Amit Varma]: So give me a broad sweep version of how patriarchy grows everywhere in the world.

02:04:35.720 --> 02:04:37.760
[Amit Varma]: What are the factors that bring it about?

02:04:37.760 --> 02:04:41.440
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, what are the traditional kind of explanations?

02:04:41.440 --> 02:04:44.000
[Amit Varma]: And I know you've, you know, come up with seven explanations.

02:04:44.000 --> 02:04:47.240
[Amit Varma]: I'm from, you know, I'm familiar with two or three of them.

02:04:47.240 --> 02:04:50.640
[Amit Varma]: I knew the evolutionary one pretty well because I knew all of that literature.

02:04:50.640 --> 02:04:55.320
[Amit Varma]: But what you've sort of done is that you've synthesized all of that.

02:04:55.320 --> 02:05:00.120
[Amit Varma]: And this is, you know, beautiful sweeping narrative, which takes us all the way through

02:05:00.120 --> 02:05:02.440
[Amit Varma]: 10,000 years to the present day.

02:05:02.440 --> 02:05:06.120
[Amit Varma]: So let's start at the very beginning, as it were.

02:05:06.120 --> 02:05:07.120
[Unknown]: I'm ready.

02:05:07.120 --> 02:05:08.120
[Amit Varma]: Are you ready for this?

02:05:08.120 --> 02:05:09.120
[Guest]: I'm ready for this.

02:05:09.120 --> 02:05:10.120
[Guest]: Hardcore patriarchy.

02:05:10.120 --> 02:05:11.120
[Guest]: OK.

02:05:11.120 --> 02:05:17.200
[Guest]: So for the 100,000 years in which we are hunter gatherers, the evidence is pretty threadbare

02:05:17.200 --> 02:05:20.960
[Guest]: because, you know, they didn't leave that much stuff.

02:05:20.960 --> 02:05:25.920
[Guest]: But I think if we look, if contemporary studies of foragers and hunter gatherers over the

02:05:25.920 --> 02:05:32.880
[Guest]: past 200,000 years, over the past 200 years or any guide, usually women in forager economies

02:05:32.880 --> 02:05:37.900
[Guest]: are not secluded, though I don't think we should expect any kind of feminist utopia.

02:05:37.900 --> 02:05:43.600
[Guest]: Women may still be beaten, raped, forced into polygamous and arranged marriage.

02:05:43.600 --> 02:05:51.160
[Guest]: I think the real step changes, the three major drives of patriarchy were the plough, nomadic

02:05:51.160 --> 02:05:55.120
[Guest]: pastoralism and male dominated religions.

02:05:55.120 --> 02:06:01.640
[Guest]: So the Neolithic revolution, the advent of agriculture did not enormous, did not necessarily

02:06:01.640 --> 02:06:02.720
[Guest]: entail patriarchy.

02:06:02.720 --> 02:06:07.640
[Guest]: So if we look at cattle hayuk in Turkey, we see that men and women appear to have lived

02:06:07.640 --> 02:06:08.760
[Guest]: very similar lives.

02:06:08.760 --> 02:06:13.640
[Guest]: So bones and burials suggest no difference in stature, status or how they spend their

02:06:13.640 --> 02:06:14.640
[Guest]: time.

02:06:14.640 --> 02:06:17.520
[Guest]: We've seen like equal amounts of soot on both men and women, suggesting they spent similar

02:06:17.520 --> 02:06:18.520
[Guest]: time indoors.

02:06:18.520 --> 02:06:24.080
[Guest]: Similarly, if we look at Bronze Age Thailand, we don't see big differences in graves.

02:06:24.080 --> 02:06:28.760
[Guest]: Likewise, ancient Egypt, women had equal rights under law.

02:06:28.760 --> 02:06:30.260
[Guest]: They weren't veiled.

02:06:30.260 --> 02:06:33.360
[Guest]: Women were priestesses to the cults of goddesses.

02:06:33.360 --> 02:06:37.680
[Guest]: Women, women were managers in workshops, especially in the Old Kingdom.

02:06:37.680 --> 02:06:42.320
[Guest]: So women exercised status and had equal rights under the law.

02:06:42.320 --> 02:06:51.200
[Guest]: The major step change is one, the advent of the plough, irrigation and the advent of cereals.

02:06:51.200 --> 02:06:57.040
[Guest]: Now what I think occurred is that this raised the value of land because this increased crop

02:06:57.040 --> 02:06:58.100
[Guest]: yields.

02:06:58.100 --> 02:07:03.440
[Guest]: Now suddenly land became an important resource that could be inherited and bequeathed down

02:07:03.440 --> 02:07:05.000
[Guest]: the generations.

02:07:05.000 --> 02:07:13.160
[Guest]: Now a man who inherits land is able to attract or otherwise conquer many wives and concubines.

02:07:13.160 --> 02:07:18.880
[Guest]: So once you have inherited wealth, there's a selective advantage for patrilineal.

02:07:18.880 --> 02:07:23.640
[Guest]: That land can also become under threat because other people might want to raid and attack

02:07:23.640 --> 02:07:24.640
[Guest]: you.

02:07:24.640 --> 02:07:28.720
[Guest]: So groups will be more likely to survive and flourish if they're what we call patrilocal,

02:07:28.720 --> 02:07:32.120
[Guest]: if men band together with our cousins and uncles.

02:07:32.120 --> 02:07:34.360
[Guest]: So that seems to encourage patrilocality.

02:07:34.360 --> 02:07:39.680
[Guest]: So if you look at wherever there was a plough, irrigation, cereals, we tend to see the emergence

02:07:39.680 --> 02:07:47.520
[Guest]: of patrilocality in which those tight knit clans cooperate and share honour collectively.

02:07:47.520 --> 02:07:52.960
[Guest]: Now another important process is nomadic pastoralism.

02:07:52.960 --> 02:07:58.880
[Guest]: So 5,000 years ago, these gangs of young men erupted out of the Pontic steppes, so that's

02:07:58.880 --> 02:08:04.080
[Guest]: across Eurasia, and they were calling each other names of wolves and dogs.

02:08:04.080 --> 02:08:10.240
[Guest]: And if we look at the genetic data, we see that indigenous men were slaughtered and the

02:08:10.240 --> 02:08:13.720
[Guest]: steppe pastoralists raped or otherwise reproduced with women.

02:08:13.720 --> 02:08:18.160
[Guest]: And so from Spain to Korea, the male line harks back to the steppe, and what they did

02:08:18.160 --> 02:08:22.420
[Guest]: is institutionalise male dominance.

02:08:22.420 --> 02:08:29.520
[Guest]: So from both pastoralism and the introduction of the plough heightened, so we see patrilocality

02:08:29.520 --> 02:08:30.680
[Guest]: and patrilineal.

02:08:30.680 --> 02:08:36.840
[Guest]: Now as those societies expanded, as they flourished, as they became more socially, economically

02:08:36.840 --> 02:08:46.640
[Guest]: complex, getting to a population of 40,000 or 100,000, we also see, with the emergence

02:08:46.640 --> 02:08:53.600
[Guest]: of city-states, we also see the emergence of moralising supernatural punishment, religions.

02:08:53.600 --> 02:08:58.820
[Guest]: And there's been debates in academia where people are like, well, is it that socio-economic

02:08:58.820 --> 02:09:03.200
[Guest]: complexity led to religion, or was it vice versa, or is there a co-evolutionary process?

02:09:03.200 --> 02:09:08.020
[Guest]: And I think my general understanding of the literature is by religions often promoted

02:09:08.020 --> 02:09:11.360
[Guest]: social cooperation, like thou shall not kill, you know, there are a bunch of things that

02:09:11.360 --> 02:09:13.000
[Guest]: make people get along with each other.

02:09:13.000 --> 02:09:16.120
[Guest]: If you believe there's eternal damnation for not doing it, you're sort of a bit nicer to

02:09:16.120 --> 02:09:17.120
[Guest]: your neighbour.

02:09:17.120 --> 02:09:24.160
[Guest]: What some of that literature overlooks is another important driver of cooperation.

02:09:24.160 --> 02:09:31.240
[Guest]: So many of these religions, the Abrahamic religions across Eurasia, out-promoted female

02:09:31.240 --> 02:09:36.920
[Guest]: chastity, sexual segregation, veiling, virginity tests, keeping men and women apart.

02:09:36.920 --> 02:09:40.980
[Guest]: And I think that could be an important part of social cooperation and state expansion

02:09:40.980 --> 02:09:46.520
[Guest]: because it would have mitigated male sexual jealousy, or even female sexual jealousy.

02:09:46.520 --> 02:09:50.800
[Guest]: By keeping the sexes apart, people will be less jealous of other men, less likely to

02:09:50.800 --> 02:09:52.200
[Guest]: result in conflict.

02:09:52.200 --> 02:09:57.240
[Guest]: And so I think that patriarchy actually could have been, in inverted commas, good for social

02:09:57.240 --> 02:09:59.240
[Guest]: flourishing and cooperation.

02:09:59.240 --> 02:10:04.320
[Guest]: In addition to that, many of these ancient rulers often claimed divine authority.

02:10:04.320 --> 02:10:10.080
[Guest]: So in southern Mesopotamia, in Song China, in Herod, for example, they often claimed

02:10:10.080 --> 02:10:13.440
[Guest]: that we're backed up, the rulers claimed that they were backed up by God.

02:10:13.440 --> 02:10:18.120
[Guest]: Now if you're backed up by God, if God is with you, how on earth do you explain floods,

02:10:18.120 --> 02:10:19.320
[Guest]: disasters and famines?

02:10:19.320 --> 02:10:21.260
[Guest]: They blame disobedient women.

02:10:21.260 --> 02:10:27.720
[Guest]: So in 13th century, Mamluk Sultan Basbari, he blamed food price, food price hikes and

02:10:27.720 --> 02:10:32.560
[Guest]: floods and the rising bread prices on disobedient women and banished them from the city streets.

02:10:32.560 --> 02:10:38.000
[Guest]: So we do see the co-evolutionary process of male dominated societies, social expansion,

02:10:38.000 --> 02:10:41.520
[Guest]: and also these prescriptive social codes.

02:10:41.520 --> 02:10:43.520
[Guest]: And that's repeated across Eurasia.

02:10:43.520 --> 02:10:50.380
[Guest]: However, that process of cultural evolution was mediated by geography.

02:10:50.380 --> 02:10:57.560
[Guest]: So the plough, nomadic pastoralism could not spread in places where you have oceans, parasites

02:10:57.560 --> 02:10:59.080
[Guest]: or mountains.

02:10:59.080 --> 02:11:05.740
[Guest]: In those places like Southeast Asia, the Andes, the Gulf of Guinea, land never gained value.

02:11:05.740 --> 02:11:08.000
[Guest]: So in the Andes, the biggest animal was the llama.

02:11:08.000 --> 02:11:09.720
[Guest]: Like what can you plough with a llama?

02:11:09.720 --> 02:11:11.560
[Guest]: It's not much bigger than me.

02:11:11.560 --> 02:11:16.120
[Guest]: And so in those communities, land was not high value.

02:11:16.120 --> 02:11:19.520
[Guest]: So we don't see the patrilineal inheritance of wealth.

02:11:19.520 --> 02:11:21.520
[Guest]: Women were never tightly policed.

02:11:21.520 --> 02:11:27.040
[Guest]: There were no strict restrictions on female chastity or ideals of female virginity.

02:11:27.040 --> 02:11:32.880
[Guest]: Women continue to move freely and maintain their own social networks and political hierarchies,

02:11:32.880 --> 02:11:36.560
[Guest]: valorize women in folklore that recognize their authority.

02:11:36.560 --> 02:11:41.600
[Guest]: And they continue to contest men's attempts to check their authority and autonomy.

02:11:41.600 --> 02:11:42.920
[Guest]: So that's the broad story.

02:11:42.920 --> 02:11:48.800
[Guest]: So it's about the plough, pastoralism, male dominated religions spreading to places where

02:11:48.800 --> 02:11:51.800
[Guest]: possible or otherwise limited by geography.

02:11:51.800 --> 02:11:52.800
[Guest]: That's the sort of nutshell.

02:11:52.800 --> 02:11:53.800
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:11:53.800 --> 02:11:59.800
[Amit Varma]: And it's fascinating because we always assume that progress happens in one dimension, right?

02:11:59.800 --> 02:12:04.280
[Amit Varma]: And as you point out, you know, that's not the like just the Minoans and the Etruscans,

02:12:04.280 --> 02:12:08.360
[Amit Varma]: for example, you know, you point out that, you know, they of course predated the ancient

02:12:08.360 --> 02:12:10.280
[Amit Varma]: Greeks and the Romans and all of that.

02:12:10.280 --> 02:12:11.280
[Amit Varma]: And they were chill.

02:12:11.280 --> 02:12:12.280
[Amit Varma]: They were far more gender equal.

02:12:12.280 --> 02:12:16.200
[Amit Varma]: It wasn't like heaven on earth or something, but they were far more gender equal.

02:12:16.200 --> 02:12:18.040
[Amit Varma]: Women had a much better time and so on.

02:12:18.040 --> 02:12:22.360
[Amit Varma]: But then the invasions happened by the pastoral, the nomadic pastoralists.

02:12:22.360 --> 02:12:26.080
[Amit Varma]: I was about to say the pastoral nomadists, but whatever.

02:12:26.080 --> 02:12:28.400
[Amit Varma]: And everything kind of changes.

02:12:28.400 --> 02:12:34.480
[Amit Varma]: You also, I love this quote where you have from Mesopotamia, where you quote Uruk-Agina,

02:12:34.480 --> 02:12:39.520
[Amit Varma]: who is the king of Lagash in 2400 BC, who says, quote, the woman who has sinned by saying

02:12:39.520 --> 02:12:43.760
[Amit Varma]: something to a man which she should not have said must have her teeth crushed with burnt

02:12:43.760 --> 02:12:46.000
[Amit Varma]: bricks, stop quote.

02:12:46.000 --> 02:12:50.880
[Amit Varma]: And again, the whole pattern of controlling female sexuality, you know, where you write,

02:12:50.880 --> 02:12:56.560
[Amit Varma]: quote, I suggest that controlling female sexuality reduced male jealousy, enabled social cooperation

02:12:56.560 --> 02:12:57.760
[Amit Varma]: and flourishing commerce.

02:12:57.760 --> 02:13:00.380
[Amit Varma]: This long predated Islam, stop quote.

02:13:00.380 --> 02:13:06.600
[Amit Varma]: The point being that toxic as it was, there's a particular reason, an instrumental reason

02:13:06.600 --> 02:13:11.960
[Amit Varma]: why it came about at that particular time and why it spread.

02:13:11.960 --> 02:13:16.000
[Amit Varma]: Let's sort of talk about India, and I've done a couple of episodes, which kind of touch

02:13:16.000 --> 02:13:17.000
[Amit Varma]: on that early history.

02:13:17.000 --> 02:13:21.640
[Amit Varma]: I've done an episode with Tony Joseph, who wrote the great book, Early Indians, and with

02:13:21.640 --> 02:13:25.880
[Amit Varma]: Peggy Mohan, who essentially, again, looked at that early period, but through the prism

02:13:25.880 --> 02:13:26.880
[Amit Varma]: of languages.

02:13:26.880 --> 02:13:31.080
[Amit Varma]: So, whereas, you know, Tony looked at what genes can reveal about where we came from

02:13:31.080 --> 02:13:32.080
[Amit Varma]: and who we are.

02:13:32.080 --> 02:13:38.720
[Amit Varma]: Peggy looked at languages and it was incredibly fascinating because, you know, the Aryan migration,

02:13:38.720 --> 02:13:42.760
[Amit Varma]: as it were, happened around 4000 years ago, right?

02:13:42.760 --> 02:13:48.240
[Amit Varma]: And they come out here and the way Peggy describes it is exactly as you write about nomadic pastoralist

02:13:48.240 --> 02:13:51.780
[Amit Varma]: that it's troops of men just coming, marrying local women.

02:13:51.780 --> 02:13:54.840
[Amit Varma]: And it's very interesting because they have different languages at the start and those

02:13:54.840 --> 02:13:57.120
[Amit Varma]: different languages persist through generations.

02:13:57.120 --> 02:13:59.920
[Amit Varma]: And that's a fascinating narrative there.

02:13:59.920 --> 02:14:05.400
[Amit Varma]: But the revelation there and the turning point comes around 2000 years ago.

02:14:05.400 --> 02:14:10.000
[Amit Varma]: And there's a great quote by David Reich, where he talks about populations.

02:14:10.000 --> 02:14:14.520
[Amit Varma]: And he says that if you're looking for a large population, look at the Han Chinese, but in

02:14:14.520 --> 02:14:19.520
[Amit Varma]: India, you won't find large populations, you'll just find many, many, many, many small populations.

02:14:19.520 --> 02:14:24.880
[Amit Varma]: What he means by that is endogamy, where somehow 2000 years ago, and before that they partied

02:14:24.880 --> 02:14:29.880
[Amit Varma]: for 2000 years before that, after the Aryans came, everybody was mingling with everybody

02:14:29.880 --> 02:14:30.880
[Amit Varma]: else.

02:14:30.880 --> 02:14:37.800
[Amit Varma]: So a particular ideological or political strand kind of won over and you had caste and endogamy.

02:14:37.800 --> 02:14:43.040
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, you have sort of the India that we have today.

02:14:43.040 --> 02:14:47.840
[Amit Varma]: And that caste endogamy, obviously, then has this preference for female seclusion, as you

02:14:47.840 --> 02:14:48.840
[Amit Varma]: put it.

02:14:48.840 --> 02:14:52.960
[Amit Varma]: Because once you have this situation where everybody from any other caste is a threat

02:14:52.960 --> 02:14:57.840
[Amit Varma]: to your property, a threat to your women, so to say, then, you know, that increases

02:14:57.840 --> 02:15:01.760
[Amit Varma]: the incentives for keeping the women locked up at home for policing them for policing

02:15:01.760 --> 02:15:03.240
[Amit Varma]: their sexuality.

02:15:03.240 --> 02:15:04.680
[Amit Varma]: And it kind of gets worse and worse.

02:15:04.680 --> 02:15:09.080
[Amit Varma]: And it's a worse problem in South Asia and in India than in other parts of the world,

02:15:09.080 --> 02:15:14.040
[Amit Varma]: where, you know, that drive to female seclusion is not so high.

02:15:14.040 --> 02:15:20.220
[Amit Varma]: And you also talk about how this is further exacerbated in North India, as compared to

02:15:20.220 --> 02:15:27.820
[Amit Varma]: South India, when you have the constant invasions by, you know, Turkic Muslim empires, or the

02:15:27.820 --> 02:15:29.720
[Amit Varma]: Mughals as we would call them.

02:15:29.720 --> 02:15:34.460
[Amit Varma]: And you know, they come in bringing Islam and Islam is again, a male dominated sort

02:15:34.460 --> 02:15:35.460
[Amit Varma]: of religion.

02:15:35.460 --> 02:15:40.640
[Amit Varma]: They have their own regressive traditions like purdah and all of that, which for various

02:15:40.640 --> 02:15:45.160
[Amit Varma]: reasons, you know, it just exacerbates what is already happening out here.

02:15:45.160 --> 02:15:50.680
[Amit Varma]: So give me a little sense on how we can look at India in the light of all this broad sweep,

02:15:50.680 --> 02:15:55.760
[Amit Varma]: you know, I'd ask you to then turn your attention to India and sort of tell me a little bit

02:15:55.760 --> 02:15:59.960
[Amit Varma]: about this, because obviously very heterogeneous, a lot of local variations, there is so much

02:15:59.960 --> 02:16:03.200
[Amit Varma]: shit happening out there, you cannot generalise, all that is fair.

02:16:03.200 --> 02:16:09.320
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, you know, looking at it broadly can also make a lot of things clearer.

02:16:09.320 --> 02:16:10.320
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:16:10.320 --> 02:16:15.320
[Guest]: So, and again, I'm sure many of your listeners are more knowledgeable on this than I am,

02:16:15.320 --> 02:16:17.000
[Guest]: and they should correct me.

02:16:17.000 --> 02:16:21.720
[Guest]: So absolutely, yes, we know from the genetic data that caste has existed for at least 2000

02:16:21.720 --> 02:16:26.960
[Guest]: years, and that tight endogamy is only possible by strictly restricting women's mobility.

02:16:26.960 --> 02:16:32.720
[Guest]: So of course, women were used, women did participate in farm work, but that's within your, on your

02:16:32.720 --> 02:16:33.720
[Guest]: own farms.

02:16:33.720 --> 02:16:36.320
[Guest]: And so you can limit their contact with outsiders.

02:16:36.320 --> 02:16:41.800
[Guest]: Whereas when people gained wealth, women might retreat to the family courtyard.

02:16:41.800 --> 02:16:48.120
[Guest]: On top of that, I think another really important point is that there was ancestral pastoralism

02:16:48.120 --> 02:16:49.960
[Guest]: in Northwest India.

02:16:49.960 --> 02:16:55.200
[Guest]: Now ancestral pastoralism, as we know from work by Anke Becker, and also Nathan Nunn

02:16:55.200 --> 02:17:00.160
[Guest]: and others, is that this is typically associated with higher rates of female seclusion, and

02:17:00.160 --> 02:17:03.160
[Guest]: greater idealisation of male honour and violence.

02:17:03.160 --> 02:17:10.480
[Guest]: And I think a part of that is, if you have agriculture, cereal cultivation, then the

02:17:10.480 --> 02:17:15.680
[Guest]: harvest can be easily taxed and appropriated and stored, and that can enable the formation

02:17:15.680 --> 02:17:19.320
[Guest]: of states and rule of law and imposition of rule of law.

02:17:19.320 --> 02:17:22.560
[Guest]: Whereas pastoralists can always easily evade the rule of law.

02:17:22.560 --> 02:17:30.360
[Guest]: And so that condition of anarchy can itself cultivate macho men, because you need to act

02:17:30.360 --> 02:17:34.040
[Guest]: just super tough so that no one dares fuck with you, right?

02:17:34.040 --> 02:17:40.760
[Guest]: You need to seem so tough, so violent, they need to anticipate that if they come to you,

02:17:40.760 --> 02:17:42.960
[Guest]: you will destroy their entire clan.

02:17:42.960 --> 02:17:50.440
[Guest]: So that itself may cultivate this ideology of clan sharing honour collectively, and protecting

02:17:50.440 --> 02:17:51.440
[Guest]: female clan.

02:17:51.440 --> 02:17:58.680
[Guest]: And it's especially a wonderful book on medieval Rajasthan, looks at how, you know, when one

02:17:58.680 --> 02:18:03.800
[Guest]: dominant group would take over another, they would often raid and take their women.

02:18:03.800 --> 02:18:07.740
[Guest]: And it was a way of humiliating their opponent and demonstrating one's mastery.

02:18:07.740 --> 02:18:12.600
[Guest]: And still today in Rajput weddings, for example, they take this, and I forget the precise term,

02:18:12.600 --> 02:18:18.360
[Guest]: but it's like a long silver sword type pole that they used to hit the banner that would

02:18:18.360 --> 02:18:20.360
[Guest]: go over the front of the house.

02:18:20.360 --> 02:18:25.800
[Guest]: And it's a way, and also in North India, there tends to be the bride givers have the subservient

02:18:25.800 --> 02:18:26.800
[Guest]: status.

02:18:26.800 --> 02:18:31.440
[Guest]: And I think that goes back to this history of the conquering clan, seizing the women

02:18:31.440 --> 02:18:35.160
[Guest]: from the others and using them as concubines, sex slaves, etc.

02:18:35.160 --> 02:18:40.840
[Guest]: So in that history, where we have caste endogamy, where we have ideals of purity and female

02:18:40.840 --> 02:18:46.040
[Guest]: seclusion, where male honour is contingent on female chastity.

02:18:46.040 --> 02:18:54.120
[Guest]: And that condition of conquest, then in came, one raids and slavery and taking our women,

02:18:54.120 --> 02:18:56.800
[Guest]: and that's an assault on male honour.

02:18:56.800 --> 02:19:02.280
[Guest]: And I think that may have exacerbated, that may have politicised religion.

02:19:02.280 --> 02:19:08.640
[Guest]: So still today, if you look at Pew data, their religion, people are much more religious in

02:19:08.640 --> 02:19:12.840
[Guest]: North India than the South, it's like 88% in the North, 35% in the South.

02:19:12.840 --> 02:19:16.920
[Guest]: There's also far greater opposition to inter-religious marriage in the North.

02:19:16.920 --> 02:19:21.960
[Guest]: And again, that may stem from this history of not wanting another community to take our

02:19:21.960 --> 02:19:22.960
[Guest]: women.

02:19:22.960 --> 02:19:26.360
[Guest]: And again, it's a sense of social policing, these are our women.

02:19:26.360 --> 02:19:32.080
[Guest]: Also, I think a really important point when we talk about Islam is to understand the cultural

02:19:32.080 --> 02:19:36.560
[Guest]: evolution of Islam, because this isn't about the Quran per se.

02:19:36.560 --> 02:19:42.040
[Guest]: Now the Quran per se has many egalitarian aspects addressing both men and women.

02:19:42.040 --> 02:19:48.680
[Guest]: Actually there was a step change in the 12th century when Iraq became the seat of the Sunni

02:19:48.680 --> 02:19:55.120
[Guest]: Muslim Empire and those rulers gained legitimacy through their close alliance with Persian

02:19:55.120 --> 02:20:00.240
[Guest]: theologians and Amit Kuru in his wonderful book calls this the Ulema state alliance.

02:20:00.240 --> 02:20:05.360
[Guest]: And as we were already discussing, Southern Mesopotamia was one of the most patriarchal

02:20:05.360 --> 02:20:06.360
[Guest]: places in the world.

02:20:06.360 --> 02:20:13.160
[Guest]: So now you have those Persian theologians, Tusi, Devani, Ghazali, they are empowered

02:20:13.160 --> 02:20:14.920
[Guest]: and emboldened to run these madrasas.

02:20:14.920 --> 02:20:20.920
[Guest]: And then those Persian texts, Udu texts, came to influence those Mughal courts.

02:20:20.920 --> 02:20:25.080
[Guest]: So I don't want us to say that we're talking about Islam in its original state.

02:20:25.080 --> 02:20:29.960
[Guest]: This is a process of cultural evolution influenced by some of those Persian ideas.

02:20:29.960 --> 02:20:38.680
[Guest]: And there were some aspects of the way that the influence of Arab tribes shaped the cultural

02:20:38.680 --> 02:20:39.680
[Guest]: evolution of Islam.

02:20:39.680 --> 02:20:46.080
[Guest]: So for example, to avoid the Jizya head tax, people had to learn the Quran, over in the

02:20:46.080 --> 02:20:51.560
[Guest]: Middle East had to gain an Arab patron and that fostered cousin marriage, because women

02:20:51.560 --> 02:20:55.680
[Guest]: under Islam, married women can own and maintain their own property.

02:20:55.680 --> 02:20:59.720
[Guest]: And that cultivated cousin marriage because people wanted to keep wealth in the family.

02:20:59.720 --> 02:21:06.520
[Guest]: So you see these strong kinship groups, these Persian theologians like Ghazali, and I'd

02:21:06.520 --> 02:21:10.720
[Guest]: recommend this wonderful book by Zahra Ayubi called Gendered Morality.

02:21:10.720 --> 02:21:17.840
[Guest]: She talks about how Ghazali and others promoted this idea that men are intellectually superior,

02:21:17.840 --> 02:21:24.960
[Guest]: men are uniquely capable of reason, and they gain piety by preventing fitna, that is moral

02:21:24.960 --> 02:21:25.960
[Guest]: corruption.

02:21:25.960 --> 02:21:29.320
[Guest]: So this isn't something in the Quran, this isn't something in Sharia law, and I want

02:21:29.320 --> 02:21:31.320
[Guest]: to be very explicit about that.

02:21:31.320 --> 02:21:40.240
[Guest]: So it's this cultural influence combined by slavery, which is exacerbated by history of

02:21:40.240 --> 02:21:46.520
[Guest]: male honor being contingent on female chastity, that I think may heighten some of these controls.

02:21:46.520 --> 02:21:52.560
[Guest]: But again, and I think that's part of the reason why women increasingly retreated into

02:21:52.560 --> 02:22:01.400
[Guest]: the family courtyard, and as families gained wealth, women were kept closer to the home.

02:22:01.400 --> 02:22:10.000
[Guest]: But all of this is also subject to flux and change.

02:22:10.000 --> 02:22:16.600
[Guest]: So I think that's my broad understanding of why North India generally tends to have higher

02:22:16.600 --> 02:22:18.520
[Guest]: rates of seclusion.

02:22:18.520 --> 02:22:23.240
[Guest]: So for example, if we look at Rajasthan, the rural rate of female labor force participation

02:22:23.240 --> 02:22:24.240
[Guest]: is 40%.

02:22:24.240 --> 02:22:28.040
[Guest]: But in urban areas, in towns and cities, it's 13%.

02:22:28.040 --> 02:22:34.200
[Guest]: And I think this is what I call the honor income trade off, in that families are perfectly

02:22:34.200 --> 02:22:38.800
[Guest]: happy for women to work in the fields because they're not mixing and mingling with outsiders.

02:22:38.800 --> 02:22:43.960
[Guest]: But in urban areas, families might be much more reluctant for women to be mixing and

02:22:43.960 --> 02:22:46.920
[Guest]: mingling in the streets, because then they could be mixing with outsiders.

02:22:46.920 --> 02:22:48.620
[Guest]: And that is a risk to male honor.

02:22:48.620 --> 02:22:53.040
[Guest]: So even though many women who I've spoken to in Rajasthan would like a job, it's principally

02:22:53.040 --> 02:22:57.400
[Guest]: a government job, because that's a respectable position, and there's less threat of mixing

02:22:57.400 --> 02:22:58.400
[Guest]: with outsiders.

02:22:58.400 --> 02:23:03.920
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit more about the honor income trade off, as you call it, because it's something

02:23:03.920 --> 02:23:08.560
[Amit Varma]: that's, I mean, we'll come back to history later, where I want to know about the rest

02:23:08.560 --> 02:23:13.240
[Amit Varma]: of the world as well, the way we've spoken about India over the last 2000 years, so to

02:23:13.240 --> 02:23:14.240
[Amit Varma]: say.

02:23:14.240 --> 02:23:20.480
[Amit Varma]: But the honor income trade off is something that seems especially to be a factor in India

02:23:20.480 --> 02:23:23.960
[Unknown]: and an impediment to gender equality.

02:23:23.960 --> 02:23:25.840
[Guest]: So tell me a bit about what that phrase means.

02:23:25.840 --> 02:23:31.760
[Guest]: So the honor income trade off is, in societies where male honor is contingent upon female

02:23:31.760 --> 02:23:40.080
[Guest]: chastity, then female labor supply only rises when female earnings are sufficiently high

02:23:40.080 --> 02:23:43.080
[Guest]: to compensate for that loss of male honor.

02:23:43.080 --> 02:23:47.680
[Guest]: And so that's precisely what we saw in East Asia.

02:23:47.680 --> 02:23:54.060
[Guest]: So for example, Taiwan had incredibly labor-intensive growth, job-creating economic growth, smaller

02:23:54.060 --> 02:23:58.600
[Guest]: medium enterprises from the 1980s really ran out of skilled labor.

02:23:58.600 --> 02:24:04.000
[Guest]: They couldn't hire enough men, so they increasingly recruited women, and the gender pay gap increasingly

02:24:04.000 --> 02:24:05.000
[Guest]: closed.

02:24:05.000 --> 02:24:09.840
[Guest]: And Taiwan now today has a smaller gender pay gap than the USA.

02:24:09.840 --> 02:24:14.960
[Guest]: Its legislature is 44% female, it has a twice-elected female president.

02:24:14.960 --> 02:24:19.720
[Guest]: And that's partly as a result of the income compensating for the loss of male honor.

02:24:19.720 --> 02:24:24.920
[Guest]: But let me nuance it a little for India, is that in Delhi today, not many people will

02:24:24.920 --> 02:24:26.560
[Guest]: talk about honor, right?

02:24:26.560 --> 02:24:29.680
[Guest]: That's not something that's so important, maybe in rural Rajasthan, but maybe not in

02:24:29.680 --> 02:24:30.680
[Guest]: Delhi today.

02:24:30.680 --> 02:24:36.200
[Guest]: But still, this history of male honor has profound repercussions for culture.

02:24:36.200 --> 02:24:43.640
[Guest]: And so the more that, so caste endogamy and ideals of seclusion were maintained by keeping

02:24:43.640 --> 02:24:45.360
[Guest]: women close to the home.

02:24:45.360 --> 02:24:52.160
[Guest]: And as women stay at home, they come to, we come to see the cultural celebration of female

02:24:52.160 --> 02:24:58.760
[Guest]: sacrifice for men, female sacrifice for men, and the ideal of male dominance.

02:24:58.760 --> 02:25:02.560
[Guest]: And that's ritualized and celebrated through culture.

02:25:02.560 --> 02:25:09.040
[Guest]: So the idea of women fasting for their husbands, the idea of women performing housework, feminist

02:25:09.040 --> 02:25:15.680
[Guest]: economists and sociologists often talk about housework as it's a tax on women's time.

02:25:15.680 --> 02:25:19.240
[Guest]: And this is an asymmetric tax and women are doing the lion's share of it and this is unfair

02:25:19.240 --> 02:25:21.720
[Guest]: and we need to reduce those time costs.

02:25:21.720 --> 02:25:26.340
[Guest]: And some people, for example, they look at data on India and they see that married women

02:25:26.340 --> 02:25:29.520
[Guest]: are spending a huge amount of time on housework.

02:25:29.520 --> 02:25:34.240
[Guest]: And they think that it's housework holding men back, holding women back rather.

02:25:34.240 --> 02:25:35.640
[Guest]: And that's true.

02:25:35.640 --> 02:25:40.480
[Guest]: But housework is also endogenous to our normative expectations.

02:25:40.480 --> 02:25:46.800
[Guest]: And the underlying idea, or at least as I understand it, is women performing their subservience

02:25:46.800 --> 02:25:51.580
[Guest]: to male dominance, that women doing things for men.

02:25:51.580 --> 02:25:57.080
[Guest]: So mothers doing all this housework for their sons and revering their sons and, you know,

02:25:57.080 --> 02:26:01.400
[Guest]: maybe treating their sons as small gods, right, or treating their husbands as small gods.

02:26:01.400 --> 02:26:03.640
[Guest]: And that itself has important repercussions.

02:26:03.640 --> 02:26:09.160
[Guest]: Because even if piped water supply, for example, would be able to reduce the absolute time

02:26:09.160 --> 02:26:15.720
[Guest]: burden of housework, that improved infrastructure, that development doesn't change the underlying

02:26:15.720 --> 02:26:20.320
[Guest]: cultural ideal that women are performing subservience to men.

02:26:20.320 --> 02:26:24.920
[Guest]: And as long as that's happening, then that cultural mindset persists that women are doing

02:26:24.920 --> 02:26:26.560
[Guest]: things for men.

02:26:26.560 --> 02:26:34.100
[Guest]: And I think that culture has emerged through this valorization of, you know, and the number

02:26:34.100 --> 02:26:35.320
[Guest]: of ways that culture persists.

02:26:35.320 --> 02:26:41.000
[Guest]: So for example, as long as you have this institution of patrilocality, that a woman leaves her

02:26:41.000 --> 02:26:44.160
[Guest]: household to join the groom's household, which, as I was saying, emerged through a number

02:26:44.160 --> 02:26:49.460
[Guest]: of traditions, then women are socialized to accept subservience.

02:26:49.460 --> 02:26:55.480
[Guest]: So for example, in my interviews with women, they talk about how one woman was saying how,

02:26:55.480 --> 02:26:58.120
[Guest]: you know, her mother would say, don't be stubborn.

02:26:58.120 --> 02:27:00.100
[Guest]: How on earth are you going to live with your in-laws?

02:27:00.100 --> 02:27:01.100
[Guest]: How will they manage?

02:27:01.100 --> 02:27:02.100
[Guest]: How will they?

02:27:02.100 --> 02:27:03.560
[Guest]: Well, they won't keep you if you're like this.

02:27:03.560 --> 02:27:05.840
[Guest]: So women are socialized.

02:27:05.840 --> 02:27:11.800
[Guest]: And I'd really recommend the book Chup on this, is women socialized, not some women,

02:27:11.800 --> 02:27:17.120
[Guest]: I should say, some women socialized not to have their own preferences, not to be independently

02:27:17.120 --> 02:27:18.520
[Guest]: evaluating things.

02:27:18.520 --> 02:27:22.520
[Guest]: Because if the expectation is that you have to leave to fit in with another household,

02:27:22.520 --> 02:27:28.800
[Guest]: to be subservient under another family, then women are socialized to take up less space,

02:27:28.800 --> 02:27:34.120
[Guest]: to adjust because they, because they're inculcated, some are inculcated with the fear that they

02:27:34.120 --> 02:27:37.920
[Guest]: are then dependent on that family's support and favor.

02:27:37.920 --> 02:27:44.280
[Guest]: And another important way in which this is institutionalized is through the mother-in-law

02:27:44.280 --> 02:27:45.480
[Guest]: relationship.

02:27:45.480 --> 02:27:51.440
[Guest]: And this is an important element of gender inequality that Anu Kriti has written about,

02:27:51.440 --> 02:27:57.440
[Guest]: for example, is that, you know, in poor patrilineal societies where female employment is very

02:27:57.440 --> 02:28:03.720
[Guest]: low and women lack economic independence, mother's prosperity and security is reliant

02:28:03.720 --> 02:28:05.240
[Guest]: on their sons, right?

02:28:05.240 --> 02:28:08.800
[Guest]: Women need sons to survive because the son is going to provide for her, to take care

02:28:08.800 --> 02:28:09.800
[Guest]: of her.

02:28:09.800 --> 02:28:13.480
[Guest]: So, you know, women have son preference and that's also encouraged through the cultural

02:28:13.480 --> 02:28:17.000
[Guest]: idealization that men continue the family lineage.

02:28:17.000 --> 02:28:24.640
[Guest]: But if a woman is economically dependent on her son, then she may resist and be resentful

02:28:24.640 --> 02:28:29.340
[Guest]: and be jealous of this incoming wife who's claiming an alternative alliance because she

02:28:29.340 --> 02:28:34.440
[Guest]: worries that that wife may destroy and fracture her relationship with her son and take him

02:28:34.440 --> 02:28:37.640
[Guest]: away and then she'll be left all alone and isolated.

02:28:37.640 --> 02:28:45.560
[Guest]: So that kind of female jealousy and animosity can lead to bullying and abuse between the

02:28:45.560 --> 02:28:46.560
[Guest]: women.

02:28:46.560 --> 02:28:52.800
[Guest]: For example, you were talking about marriage as a toxic institution or there are a number

02:28:52.800 --> 02:29:00.760
[Guest]: of other institutions and relationships between women that can also perpetuate patriarchy

02:29:00.760 --> 02:29:05.320
[Guest]: in a context of low female employment and dependence on men.

02:29:05.320 --> 02:29:11.080
[Guest]: And there's a combination of the way that economic dependence builds on the cultural

02:29:11.080 --> 02:29:15.280
[Unknown]: valorization of men, you know, men treated as a better example.

02:29:15.280 --> 02:29:20.600
[Amit Varma]: And an unintended consequence of this, you know, this mother-in-law daughter-in-law battles

02:29:20.600 --> 02:29:26.680
[Amit Varma]: also is a rash of terrible TV dramas, which we kind of suffered through in the aughties.

02:29:26.680 --> 02:29:31.040
[Amit Varma]: I mean, not that I watched any of them, but it crowds out better content.

02:29:31.040 --> 02:29:36.920
[Amit Varma]: But anyway, that is so one sort of common narrative about women's empowerment and you

02:29:36.920 --> 02:29:41.360
[Amit Varma]: mentioned it in your book in the context of other places is that household tech is a big

02:29:41.360 --> 02:29:42.360
[Amit Varma]: deal, right?

02:29:42.360 --> 02:29:46.240
[Amit Varma]: Because once you have a washing machine, once you have a dishwasher, your tasks become much

02:29:46.240 --> 02:29:47.240
[Amit Varma]: easier.

02:29:47.240 --> 02:29:48.360
[Amit Varma]: You have much more time.

02:29:48.360 --> 02:29:53.080
[Amit Varma]: But what you're saying is that it doesn't really matter so much that one of the one

02:29:53.080 --> 02:29:58.600
[Amit Varma]: of the key reasons why a woman is doing all of those is to express a subservience to the

02:29:58.600 --> 02:29:59.600
[Amit Varma]: man.

02:29:59.600 --> 02:30:02.800
[Amit Varma]: And she's got to do that anyway, if not this way, then some other way.

02:30:02.800 --> 02:30:08.720
[Amit Varma]: It doesn't mean that if she has more time, she's necessarily going to go out and work.

02:30:08.720 --> 02:30:13.760
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, at least in India, it's not as much of a panacea as one would think.

02:30:13.760 --> 02:30:14.760
[Guest]: Is that what you're saying?

02:30:14.760 --> 02:30:15.760
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:30:15.760 --> 02:30:16.760
[Guest]: So let me say two things.

02:30:16.760 --> 02:30:22.960
[Guest]: One, demand for so there's a lot of literature showing, for example, there are several papers

02:30:22.960 --> 02:30:27.640
[Guest]: in the USA that show the washing that suggests washing machines were engines of liberation.

02:30:27.640 --> 02:30:33.080
[Guest]: They reduce women's time burdens, but actually, that demand for washing machines may have

02:30:33.080 --> 02:30:34.080
[Guest]: been endogenous.

02:30:34.080 --> 02:30:37.800
[Guest]: It may have been that there was job creating economic growth.

02:30:37.800 --> 02:30:41.760
[Guest]: Women went out into the labor force and they were eager to pursue careers.

02:30:41.760 --> 02:30:45.220
[Guest]: And then they wanted washing machines to reduce their time burdens so that it could be the

02:30:45.220 --> 02:30:47.240
[Guest]: reverse relationship.

02:30:47.240 --> 02:30:52.940
[Guest]: And in India, we do see that even though fertility has fallen, which should have reduced women's

02:30:52.940 --> 02:30:58.600
[Guest]: time burdens, women remain laden with a number of domestic duties.

02:30:58.600 --> 02:31:02.580
[Guest]: And I think this is and I think this reflects a global trend.

02:31:02.580 --> 02:31:07.600
[Guest]: So if you look across national data, we see that in countries where the male breadwinner

02:31:07.600 --> 02:31:12.980
[Guest]: ideal is widely endorsed, women perform a larger volume of housework.

02:31:12.980 --> 02:31:19.560
[Guest]: So the actual volume of housework could actually stem from ideology and the child penalty,

02:31:19.560 --> 02:31:25.920
[Guest]: that is the cost of having a child when you compare European countries, where people believe

02:31:25.920 --> 02:31:30.640
[Guest]: that a mother should stay at home with their children, they do a lot.

02:31:30.640 --> 02:31:32.940
[Guest]: Then you see a larger child penalty.

02:31:32.940 --> 02:31:38.040
[Guest]: So the normative expectations that women should be performing this labor for men and for their

02:31:38.040 --> 02:31:44.200
[Guest]: children could be shaping women's responsiveness to economic opportunities.

02:31:44.200 --> 02:31:52.160
[Guest]: And so, for example, let me give a couple of examples that, you know, some rural families

02:31:52.160 --> 02:31:54.920
[Guest]: might want women to make fresh chapatis twice a day, right?

02:31:54.920 --> 02:31:59.920
[Guest]: The expectation or women should be preparing for Hindu festival and the absolute enormity

02:31:59.920 --> 02:32:04.860
[Guest]: of that work, whether it's making Ladoo or other things, right, the enormity of the expectations

02:32:04.860 --> 02:32:07.640
[Guest]: of all the things that mothers should do.

02:32:07.640 --> 02:32:12.180
[Guest]: So there's a nice paper, and I'll forget the name and terribly offend people, that they

02:32:12.180 --> 02:32:17.600
[Guest]: suggest that actually one reason that women might, educated women might even be limiting

02:32:17.600 --> 02:32:21.920
[Guest]: their labor supply might be so they can support their children's education.

02:32:21.920 --> 02:32:26.640
[Guest]: So prioritizing the family and putting their children first, putting their families first.

02:32:26.640 --> 02:32:34.520
[Guest]: And yeah, so there are a number of things that the idealization of serving men may persist

02:32:34.520 --> 02:32:37.280
[Guest]: and may increase the total burden of housework.

02:32:37.280 --> 02:32:43.700
[Guest]: And it's not just about housework, but it's the idea that, it's that these cultural ideals

02:32:43.700 --> 02:32:47.640
[Guest]: can persist alongside development.

02:32:47.640 --> 02:32:51.640
[Amit Varma]: You know, just the thought of women making Ladoos for everyone, it's a kind of, it's

02:32:51.640 --> 02:32:55.040
[Amit Varma]: a kind of sinister revenge, because sugar is poison, of course, so you're gradually

02:32:55.040 --> 02:33:00.320
[Amit Varma]: killing your whole family by making them sweets, pat on the back to all the women who do that.

02:33:00.320 --> 02:33:03.920
[Amit Varma]: And it reminds me of like Parkinson's law, which you could call the Parkinson's law for

02:33:03.920 --> 02:33:06.040
[Amit Varma]: women because it applies so well, right?

02:33:06.040 --> 02:33:08.340
[Amit Varma]: Work expands to fill the time available.

02:33:08.340 --> 02:33:13.920
[Amit Varma]: So you know, your point being that it isn't enough if time saving technology comes along.

02:33:13.920 --> 02:33:17.300
[Amit Varma]: The point is that, you know, there's something deeper at play here.

02:33:17.300 --> 02:33:22.920
[Amit Varma]: And just going back to the honor income trade off, you know, where the honor side of the

02:33:22.920 --> 02:33:26.800
[Unknown]: ledger is a bit weaker to begin with, for example, where there isn't such a preference

02:33:26.800 --> 02:33:31.060
[Amit Varma]: for female seclusion, it's much easier for women to go out there and work, all you need

02:33:31.060 --> 02:33:34.200
[Amit Varma]: is that the economic returns increase, and then it makes sense.

02:33:34.200 --> 02:33:37.780
[Amit Varma]: But here it's not just about the economic returns increasing, that is one way.

02:33:37.780 --> 02:33:42.680
[Amit Varma]: But the other way is, you know, as you've pointed out, if there are fewer concerns about

02:33:42.680 --> 02:33:46.920
[Amit Varma]: the honor, for example, there's less of an obstacle to women working in businesses owned

02:33:46.920 --> 02:33:51.600
[Unknown]: by other women, you've pointed out, because the assumption is that they're safer.

02:33:51.600 --> 02:33:53.400
[Guest]: And I should, yes, so absolutely.

02:33:53.400 --> 02:33:59.720
[Guest]: So when families are more confident that women's honor is protected, then they're generally

02:33:59.720 --> 02:34:02.200
[Guest]: much more supportive of female employment.

02:34:02.200 --> 02:34:03.560
[Guest]: And let me give you two examples.

02:34:03.560 --> 02:34:08.880
[Guest]: So earlier, I was mentioned, Soumya Dhanaraj and Vidya Mahambe's research that they point

02:34:08.880 --> 02:34:16.600
[Guest]: to family factories often assure rural families in Bihar that yes, we'll look after your daughters

02:34:16.600 --> 02:34:22.960
[Guest]: by keeping them in these incredibly surveilled, you know, basically prisons, you know, we're

02:34:22.960 --> 02:34:26.640
[Guest]: going to escort them to the market on the Sunday and return them back safely.

02:34:26.640 --> 02:34:32.880
[Guest]: So factories redouble their efforts to control and monitor women to reassure the families

02:34:32.880 --> 02:34:35.280
[Guest]: in Bihar so they can be assured of the labor supply.

02:34:35.280 --> 02:34:37.000
[Guest]: And the same was true in East Asia.

02:34:37.000 --> 02:34:44.160
[Guest]: I should also add, so absolutely, so when women's honor is secured, we do see generally

02:34:44.160 --> 02:34:47.520
[Guest]: higher rates of female labor force participation.

02:34:47.520 --> 02:34:54.960
[Guest]: Let me give one more example that I wanted to share that within India, 34% of people

02:34:54.960 --> 02:35:01.160
[Guest]: say that male, 34% of women say that male violence is justified, that men can beat their

02:35:01.160 --> 02:35:05.160
[Guest]: wives if she neglects the children or burns the food.

02:35:05.160 --> 02:35:10.400
[Guest]: So never mind men doing zero care work, if a woman does that care work inadequately,

02:35:10.400 --> 02:35:11.940
[Guest]: it's okay to beat her.

02:35:11.940 --> 02:35:15.400
[Guest]: So this is what I'm talking about, the normative expectations of housework.

02:35:15.400 --> 02:35:21.080
[Guest]: And again, going back to Soumya Dhanaraj and Vidya Mahamre, they show that in North India,

02:35:21.080 --> 02:35:25.160
[Guest]: when women who work, they're much more likely to be beaten by their husbands.

02:35:25.160 --> 02:35:29.560
[Guest]: So that in itself is another reason why women might be reluctant to step out.

02:35:29.560 --> 02:35:32.320
[Guest]: I mean, what, it's not so great.

02:35:32.320 --> 02:35:35.880
[Guest]: And Anu Kriti, whose work I was mentioning, she finds that in areas where you see higher

02:35:35.880 --> 02:35:40.600
[Guest]: rates of female political representation as a result of quotas, you see higher rates of

02:35:40.600 --> 02:35:41.800
[Guest]: gender based violence.

02:35:41.800 --> 02:35:45.980
[Guest]: And there are parallels in Bangladesh, women who work in garment factories or microcredit

02:35:45.980 --> 02:35:48.460
[Guest]: might be at higher risk of patriarchal backlash.

02:35:48.460 --> 02:35:53.240
[Guest]: So in societies where male honour is paramount, where men want to demonstrate their mastery

02:35:53.240 --> 02:35:57.000
[Guest]: over women, then they can respond negatively.

02:35:57.000 --> 02:36:04.840
[Guest]: But I also wanted to say, let me share why actually, but the way that this can be overcome

02:36:04.840 --> 02:36:06.720
[Guest]: is through job creating economic growth.

02:36:06.720 --> 02:36:10.120
[Guest]: And I want to share some data from the UK.

02:36:10.120 --> 02:36:14.460
[Guest]: So when Hindu Indian women come to the UK, they do work.

02:36:14.460 --> 02:36:18.280
[Guest]: So in the UK, the rate of female labour force participation among white British women is

02:36:18.280 --> 02:36:19.280
[Guest]: 74%.

02:36:19.280 --> 02:36:23.200
[Guest]: Among Hindu Indians, it's 69%.

02:36:23.200 --> 02:36:28.760
[Guest]: So when there are job creating economic opportunities, and when public safety is assured, women are

02:36:28.760 --> 02:36:29.760
[Guest]: working.

02:36:29.760 --> 02:36:36.640
[Guest]: I mean, and in India, in the UK today, Indian families are relatively wealthy and women

02:36:36.640 --> 02:36:42.600
[Guest]: are thriving, you know, as accountants, in finance, in myriad fields, in accountancy,

02:36:42.600 --> 02:36:44.640
[Guest]: many of our doctors are Indian women.

02:36:44.640 --> 02:36:49.360
[Guest]: So I think that really shows the honour income trade off, that when honour can be ensured,

02:36:49.360 --> 02:36:54.280
[Guest]: when their income returns are sufficiently high, so there's no fundamental, there's no

02:36:54.280 --> 02:36:58.720
[Guest]: fundamental bottleneck, you know, culture isn't set in stone, it's this trade off that

02:36:58.720 --> 02:37:00.760
[Guest]: I'm trying, that's what I want to communicate.

02:37:00.760 --> 02:37:05.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and I was also sort of fascinated by two other data points that you bring to bear.

02:37:05.920 --> 02:37:11.080
[Amit Varma]: And one of them is that Bangladesh is better in this respect, because there is lower endogamy

02:37:11.080 --> 02:37:12.080
[Guest]: there.

02:37:12.080 --> 02:37:13.080
[Guest]: Oh, yeah.

02:37:13.080 --> 02:37:14.080
[Guest]: So that's something I got wrong.

02:37:14.080 --> 02:37:15.080
[Guest]: That's something I got wrong.

02:37:15.080 --> 02:37:16.080
[Unknown]: That's something I changed my mind on.

02:37:16.080 --> 02:37:17.080
[Unknown]: Yes.

02:37:17.080 --> 02:37:18.080
[Unknown]: Excellent.

02:37:18.080 --> 02:37:19.080
[Guest]: Tell me about it.

02:37:19.080 --> 02:37:20.080
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:37:20.080 --> 02:37:25.560
[Guest]: So I, so I initially thought that, so right, so India has seen its rate of female labour

02:37:25.560 --> 02:37:30.720
[Guest]: force participation plummet, while Bangladesh has seen its rate of female labour force participation

02:37:30.720 --> 02:37:31.720
[Guest]: increase.

02:37:31.720 --> 02:37:36.240
[Guest]: And I think that fact alone is fascinating and deserves more research.

02:37:36.240 --> 02:37:37.440
[Guest]: Now why is this?

02:37:37.440 --> 02:37:38.760
[Guest]: And some people say, well, it's garments.

02:37:38.760 --> 02:37:43.200
[Guest]: But no, in a population of 160 million, garments are only employing 4 or 4.5 million.

02:37:43.200 --> 02:37:45.320
[Guest]: So that's not it.

02:37:45.320 --> 02:37:47.640
[Guest]: I also realised it's actually not culture.

02:37:47.640 --> 02:37:50.360
[Guest]: It's not that Bangladeshis care less about honour.

02:37:50.360 --> 02:37:54.080
[Guest]: If you look at early marriage, that's incredibly high in Bangladesh.

02:37:54.080 --> 02:37:57.200
[Guest]: Early marriage indicates huge concern for female virginity.

02:37:57.200 --> 02:38:02.360
[Guest]: We must marry our daughter early to preserve her virginity, to get to the right lineage.

02:38:02.360 --> 02:38:08.240
[Guest]: If you, Bangladesh had a history of purdah, a history of female veiling, which indicates

02:38:08.240 --> 02:38:10.720
[Guest]: a concern for female seclusion.

02:38:10.720 --> 02:38:16.200
[Guest]: Also when Bangladeshis go to the UK, their rate of female labour market participation

02:38:16.200 --> 02:38:18.640
[Guest]: is actually only 39%.

02:38:18.640 --> 02:38:24.760
[Guest]: So faced with those exact same economic opportunities, they're much less likely to seize them.

02:38:24.760 --> 02:38:29.200
[Guest]: The economic returns, the female employment are not high enough to compensate for male

02:38:29.200 --> 02:38:30.200
[Guest]: honour.

02:38:30.200 --> 02:38:34.440
[Guest]: Now, the Bangladeshi families also tend to be less educated and less wealthy than Indian

02:38:34.440 --> 02:38:36.760
[Guest]: families and that itself might suppress female employment.

02:38:36.760 --> 02:38:42.160
[Guest]: But even controlling for that, Muslim Bangladeshis, women are less likely to work.

02:38:42.160 --> 02:38:47.760
[Guest]: So again, so it's not that Bangladesh is actually more gender equal.

02:38:47.760 --> 02:38:55.000
[Guest]: What I suspect has gone on is, and this is going to sound controversial, and I need to

02:38:55.000 --> 02:39:00.680
[Guest]: be careful about how I put this, over the past 50 years, there has been massive labour

02:39:00.680 --> 02:39:02.440
[Guest]: repression in Bangladesh.

02:39:02.440 --> 02:39:06.640
[Guest]: So trade unions were banned ever since the 1970s.

02:39:06.640 --> 02:39:11.480
[Guest]: Successive governments co-opted trade unions and used patronage to control them and they

02:39:11.480 --> 02:39:16.600
[Guest]: became fairly defunct and weak and useless and people lost faith in trade unions.

02:39:16.600 --> 02:39:22.080
[Guest]: As a result of that weak activism, labour inspectorates were understaffed and fairly

02:39:22.080 --> 02:39:23.080
[Guest]: ineffective.

02:39:23.080 --> 02:39:26.040
[Guest]: They were even banned from export processing zones.

02:39:26.040 --> 02:39:28.760
[Guest]: National legislation around labour rights does not apply in those places.

02:39:28.760 --> 02:39:34.760
[Guest]: And that has enabled Bangladesh to, you know, compete on price for low end garment jobs.

02:39:34.760 --> 02:39:40.640
[Guest]: But more than that, with very weak labour protections, with huge labour repression,

02:39:40.640 --> 02:39:47.200
[Guest]: for example, in 2019, when there was a sporadic outburst of strikes, the police returned with

02:39:47.200 --> 02:39:50.240
[Guest]: water cannons and rubber bullets and 50 people died.

02:39:50.240 --> 02:39:57.240
[Guest]: So as a result of that labour repression, as a result of those weak labour protections,

02:39:57.240 --> 02:40:01.040
[Guest]: it's not enormously costly to hire more formal labour.

02:40:01.040 --> 02:40:05.880
[Guest]: So firms actually have a great economic incentive to hire more and more workers because it doesn't

02:40:05.880 --> 02:40:11.400
[Guest]: come with so many burdens of protections for the worker, for the formal worker.

02:40:11.400 --> 02:40:16.840
[Guest]: So Amit Basole over in Bangalore has a fantastic paper looking at the growth elasticity of

02:40:16.840 --> 02:40:21.840
[Guest]: employment and he finds that in Bangladesh compared to India, we see that growth generates

02:40:21.840 --> 02:40:22.880
[Guest]: more jobs.

02:40:22.880 --> 02:40:27.240
[Guest]: It generates more non-agricultural jobs and it generates more formal jobs, whereas the

02:40:27.240 --> 02:40:32.760
[Guest]: difference I think in India, and we could contrast West Bengal, for example, in West

02:40:32.760 --> 02:40:38.440
[Guest]: Bengal, as you know, there's been the left front and leftist agitation since the 1970s.

02:40:38.440 --> 02:40:42.240
[Guest]: And that raised the cost of labour relative to productivity.

02:40:42.240 --> 02:40:47.800
[Guest]: And if labour is more costly than productivity, factories closed and we saw de-industrialisation.

02:40:47.800 --> 02:40:51.240
[Guest]: That also occurred in Kerala in the 1970s.

02:40:51.240 --> 02:40:58.680
[Guest]: So while many of us may think it's a great thing to have formal labour protections that

02:40:58.680 --> 02:41:04.160
[Guest]: can actually protect a labour aristocracy while leading to the decimation of industry.

02:41:04.160 --> 02:41:09.440
[Guest]: So in the 1970s, many biddy factories actually closed down.

02:41:09.440 --> 02:41:15.260
[Guest]: They relocated to Tamil Nadu or they outsourced to home-based workers.

02:41:15.260 --> 02:41:19.920
[Guest]: Those women are working at home under the control of patriarchal guardians.

02:41:19.920 --> 02:41:25.120
[Guest]: So some of those labour protections, even though they're well intended, at least by

02:41:25.120 --> 02:41:31.320
[Guest]: the labour aristocracy, may actually be suppressing job-creating economic growth, may actually

02:41:31.320 --> 02:41:33.720
[Guest]: be compounding precarity.

02:41:33.720 --> 02:41:41.160
[Guest]: So for example, just yesterday I interviewed a female entrepreneur who has a printing business

02:41:41.160 --> 02:41:48.120
[Guest]: and she was saying that by staying small, she's actually able to avoid many of these

02:41:48.120 --> 02:41:52.200
[Guest]: bureaucratic controls, bureaucratic controls and labour regulations.

02:41:52.200 --> 02:41:57.360
[Guest]: So what she does has is a relatively small staff of formal workers and then she has an

02:41:57.360 --> 02:42:00.080
[Guest]: additional dozen contract labourers.

02:42:00.080 --> 02:42:04.400
[Guest]: So she keeps her formal workforce small in order to avoid some of the costs and that

02:42:04.400 --> 02:42:06.820
[Guest]: enables her to be much more productive.

02:42:06.820 --> 02:42:14.080
[Guest]: But there are major consequences and as a result, as our survey shows that 77% of Indians

02:42:14.080 --> 02:42:18.800
[Guest]: continue to work in firms employing less than 10 people and that has barely changed.

02:42:18.800 --> 02:42:22.120
[Guest]: And this has a number of consequences for gender relations.

02:42:22.120 --> 02:42:28.680
[Guest]: First of all, if people remain in informal, unorganised, precarious labour, then they

02:42:28.680 --> 02:42:34.240
[Guest]: remain incredibly precarious and there is very weak social security.

02:42:34.240 --> 02:42:37.360
[Guest]: No one wants to end up in a government hospital where you could be waiting four days or poor

02:42:37.360 --> 02:42:41.440
[Guest]: quality education or just the total lack of social security.

02:42:41.440 --> 02:42:47.680
[Guest]: And so that means to protect themselves, to mitigate health shocks and economic shocks,

02:42:47.680 --> 02:42:53.560
[Guest]: people cling closely to their caste and kinship networks, their jati, as shown by Munshi,

02:42:53.560 --> 02:42:54.600
[Guest]: among others.

02:42:54.600 --> 02:43:00.360
[Guest]: So that precarity tightens reliance on kin, that tightens the incentive, the economic

02:43:00.360 --> 02:43:01.520
[Guest]: incentive for endogamy.

02:43:01.520 --> 02:43:06.280
[Guest]: Now, of course, there are also cultural reasons, the ideals of purity, ideals that we should

02:43:06.280 --> 02:43:11.840
[Guest]: marry within our own kin, but it's also the nature of India's economic development that's

02:43:11.840 --> 02:43:14.200
[Guest]: reproducing some of those caste ideals.

02:43:14.200 --> 02:43:20.160
[Guest]: So if we look at caste-based residential segregation, we see that that is weakening slightly in

02:43:20.160 --> 02:43:23.280
[Guest]: thriving cities with more salaried employment.

02:43:23.280 --> 02:43:30.240
[Guest]: We also see that people are more likely to live in nuclear homes if they live, if they

02:43:30.240 --> 02:43:34.600
[Guest]: work for non-family businesses, if they have salaried employment.

02:43:34.600 --> 02:43:40.120
[Guest]: So if they're economically independent, then they're more likely to go at it alone.

02:43:40.120 --> 02:43:44.280
[Guest]: Whereas sons who think that they need to rely on their family business for inheritance,

02:43:44.280 --> 02:43:49.480
[Guest]: for their economic security, may feel they have little option but to challenged ideals

02:43:49.480 --> 02:43:51.480
[Guest]: of arranged marriages.

02:43:51.480 --> 02:43:56.280
[Guest]: But of course, there's cultural content too, like, for example, in North India, and I believe

02:43:56.280 --> 02:44:03.760
[Guest]: as a consequence of the history of close-knit clans banding together, the rate of joint

02:44:03.760 --> 02:44:05.880
[Guest]: families is four times higher.

02:44:05.880 --> 02:44:09.800
[Guest]: So there are cultural families, there are cultural factors, and the idea that people

02:44:09.800 --> 02:44:13.200
[Guest]: should revere and respect their parents and wanting to please their parents, and so that

02:44:13.200 --> 02:44:15.400
[Guest]: perpetuates arranged marriages.

02:44:15.400 --> 02:44:19.840
[Guest]: But this is exacerbated and perpetuated by economic development.

02:44:19.840 --> 02:44:24.840
[Guest]: So where you have precarity, that heightens reliance on kin, where you have a slow job

02:44:24.840 --> 02:44:30.240
[Guest]: creating economic growth, women remain under the control of patriarchal guardians.

02:44:30.240 --> 02:44:33.720
[Guest]: And it also suppresses economic opportunities.

02:44:33.720 --> 02:44:38.400
[Guest]: For example, if Dalit women cannot do, if there are no jobs in town, then Dalit women

02:44:38.400 --> 02:44:43.120
[Guest]: cannot escape the villages, so they remain under what Ambedkar referred to as what is

02:44:43.120 --> 02:44:48.160
[Guest]: the village, but the den of nepotism and ignorance and communism and narrow mindedness.

02:44:48.160 --> 02:44:53.320
[Guest]: So this job, so going back to your question, sorry, I should be more concise, is that the

02:44:53.320 --> 02:45:00.640
[Guest]: nature of India's economic development, with one factor among many, maybe being the extent

02:45:00.640 --> 02:45:06.120
[Guest]: of bureaucracy, the incentives for firms to stay small, and I should say, there could

02:45:06.120 --> 02:45:11.640
[Guest]: also be cultural incentives for firms to stay small, you know, as long as people trust their

02:45:11.640 --> 02:45:16.160
[Guest]: close knit kin, as long as people trust their family members, they may prefer just to stay

02:45:16.160 --> 02:45:18.280
[Guest]: small among themselves.

02:45:18.280 --> 02:45:22.280
[Guest]: But I don't think that can explain the Bangladeshi-India difference, because Bangladesh is also a close

02:45:22.280 --> 02:45:23.280
[Guest]: knit community.

02:45:23.280 --> 02:45:26.760
[Guest]: So to answer your question, why has female employment soared in Bangladesh, but not in

02:45:26.760 --> 02:45:27.760
[Guest]: India?

02:45:27.760 --> 02:45:33.840
[Guest]: I think, paradoxically, it might be labour repression, and labour protection, labour

02:45:33.840 --> 02:45:36.520
[Guest]: repression and labour protection, rather than cultural factors.

02:45:36.520 --> 02:45:38.600
[Guest]: I think that's the best way to explain it.

02:45:38.600 --> 02:45:41.720
[Guest]: But as and this goes back, so and I really like that comparison.

02:45:41.720 --> 02:45:48.000
[Guest]: I think that contrasting Bangladesh and India tells us actually more about India and about

02:45:48.000 --> 02:45:50.040
[Guest]: its race, about what's going on.

02:45:50.040 --> 02:45:51.760
[Guest]: So I find that intriguing.

02:45:51.760 --> 02:45:54.960
[Guest]: And I would, yeah, I like that.

02:45:54.960 --> 02:45:58.880
[Amit Varma]: You said at the start, this would, this, you know, borders on being a controversial explanation,

02:45:58.880 --> 02:46:00.760
[Amit Varma]: and you just called it paradoxical.

02:46:00.760 --> 02:46:05.680
[Amit Varma]: And I don't think it's either, because I think outside of left-leaning academia, it's well

02:46:05.680 --> 02:46:11.720
[Amit Varma]: accepted that most labour laws and most labour regulation harm workers rather than help them.

02:46:11.720 --> 02:46:12.720
[Amit Varma]: And we've seen that in India.

02:46:12.720 --> 02:46:18.400
[Amit Varma]: And this is a classic example of that, frankly, it's just an extremely cogent explanation,

02:46:18.400 --> 02:46:19.560
[Amit Varma]: which you just gave.

02:46:19.560 --> 02:46:24.080
[Amit Varma]: I want to pick up on another strand that you went down on when you mentioned Soumya and

02:46:24.080 --> 02:46:25.800
[Amit Varma]: Vidya's research.

02:46:25.800 --> 02:46:29.280
[Amit Varma]: And they'd be so happy, of course, to hear the name so many times.

02:46:29.280 --> 02:46:35.480
[Amit Varma]: But what you pointed out was how their research has shown that these factory workers, to alleviate

02:46:35.480 --> 02:46:40.200
[Amit Varma]: concerns about are the female workers safe, will, you know, herd them into safe spaces

02:46:40.200 --> 02:46:44.800
[Amit Varma]: and make sure they get back home, all right, and so on to fight some of that sort of urge

02:46:44.800 --> 02:46:47.000
[Amit Varma]: for female seclusion, as it were.

02:46:47.000 --> 02:46:53.520
[Amit Varma]: And my question is about sort of those spaces where these women are together, about those

02:46:53.520 --> 02:47:00.040
[Amit Varma]: spaces, not just in this context, but in any context where women talk to each other, they,

02:47:00.040 --> 02:47:03.800
[Amit Varma]: you know, earlier, you'd spoken about the Cambodia case where, you know, these women

02:47:03.800 --> 02:47:08.320
[Amit Varma]: are comparing notes and saying, oh, your husband helps out at home, mine doesn't.

02:47:08.320 --> 02:47:12.520
[Amit Varma]: And there's some kind of solidarity and empowerment happening there.

02:47:12.520 --> 02:47:17.080
[Amit Varma]: And this is something you've written pieces about, you've discussed on a podcast with

02:47:17.080 --> 02:47:20.400
[Amit Varma]: Shruti, all of which are linked from the show notes, of course.

02:47:20.400 --> 02:47:28.160
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit more about this, because part of the puzzle of figuring out where you

02:47:28.160 --> 02:47:33.320
[Amit Varma]: are, to begin with, and what is wrong with where you are, is just talking to others sort

02:47:33.320 --> 02:47:35.720
[Amit Varma]: of broadening those horizons.

02:47:35.720 --> 02:47:40.600
[Amit Varma]: And female friendships, therefore, play a huge part in female empowerment.

02:47:40.600 --> 02:47:45.480
[Amit Varma]: So you know, before we get back to the historical geographic narrative, let's talk a little

02:47:45.480 --> 02:47:46.760
[Guest]: bit more about that.

02:47:46.760 --> 02:47:47.760
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:47:47.760 --> 02:47:55.920
[Guest]: Shruti Mukherjee and others have found that in parts of Uttar Pradesh, 26% of women have

02:47:55.920 --> 02:47:59.000
[Guest]: no friends outside the home.

02:47:59.000 --> 02:48:02.440
[Guest]: And so their networks become limited.

02:48:02.440 --> 02:48:07.600
[Guest]: Also, there's a nice study of West Bengal looking at who people make phone calls to.

02:48:07.600 --> 02:48:12.240
[Guest]: And they find that women often make phone calls to their family or their husband's family.

02:48:12.240 --> 02:48:14.680
[Guest]: Whereas men have much wider networks.

02:48:14.680 --> 02:48:22.880
[Guest]: And if women are reliant and dependent on their husband's family, then they have narrow

02:48:22.880 --> 02:48:28.980
[Guest]: social circles, then they're less aware of alternative ideologies, and they might not

02:48:28.980 --> 02:48:34.880
[Guest]: necessarily have the support, the encouragement to transgress, to try new things.

02:48:34.880 --> 02:48:38.780
[Guest]: And so I think friendships are important in two ways.

02:48:38.780 --> 02:48:45.080
[Guest]: And it's also it's not just friends per se, but also a rich diversity of friends.

02:48:45.080 --> 02:48:49.320
[Guest]: So it's JNU women coming together, meeting people from Bengal, meeting people from all

02:48:49.320 --> 02:48:52.940
[Guest]: different parts of the country with different experiences and different ideologies.

02:48:52.940 --> 02:48:57.260
[Guest]: Because women in the village may have friends, but they might be similarly marginalised women

02:48:57.260 --> 02:49:01.760
[Guest]: with similarly economically dependent on their providers with little exit options.

02:49:01.760 --> 02:49:08.560
[Guest]: And instead, they themselves may practice Islamophobia, casteism, colourism, for example.

02:49:08.560 --> 02:49:13.440
[Guest]: So it's not just female friendships, but it's having this diverse networks with both economically

02:49:13.440 --> 02:49:17.980
[Guest]: privileged people who might help you with resources, but also people with greater ideas

02:49:17.980 --> 02:49:18.980
[Guest]: and exposure.

02:49:18.980 --> 02:49:21.680
[Guest]: So friendships are important in two ways.

02:49:21.680 --> 02:49:28.320
[Guest]: And in my analysis of gender, I try to differentiate between our internalised gender ideologies.

02:49:28.320 --> 02:49:33.420
[Guest]: So that is what I privately think is right or wrong, but also our norm perceptions, my

02:49:33.420 --> 02:49:38.620
[Guest]: perceptions of what is condemned or championed by others in my community.

02:49:38.620 --> 02:49:43.360
[Guest]: So within my internalised ideologies, we might look at my self belief, whether I have confidence

02:49:43.360 --> 02:49:48.580
[Guest]: in myself to speak out, whether I myself think women are more competent than men.

02:49:48.580 --> 02:49:56.100
[Guest]: But even if I myself am privately critical, I may nonetheless comply with gender inequalities

02:49:56.100 --> 02:50:01.760
[Guest]: and hierarchies, maybe because I'm not entirely confident in myself, or also because I anticipate

02:50:01.760 --> 02:50:07.180
[Guest]: backlash, whereas, so yesterday, I was at JNU, and I was talking to these women how

02:50:07.180 --> 02:50:12.140
[Guest]: they came to JNU, and they came to question all these patriarchal ideologies that women

02:50:12.140 --> 02:50:16.660
[Guest]: shouldn't date, or that women shouldn't choose for themselves, or that women shouldn't wear

02:50:16.660 --> 02:50:20.900
[Guest]: shorts or that women shouldn't do all these things, or that women should adhere to their

02:50:20.900 --> 02:50:22.980
[Guest]: parents choices in marriage.

02:50:22.980 --> 02:50:27.140
[Guest]: And it's friends, encouraging each other, emboldening each other.

02:50:27.140 --> 02:50:32.140
[Guest]: So one girl had travelled internationally, so she was from a slightly more economically-privileged

02:50:32.140 --> 02:50:33.140
[Guest]: background.

02:50:33.140 --> 02:50:37.860
[Guest]: Another girl had not travelled at all, but she'd managed to get a scholarship to go to

02:50:37.860 --> 02:50:38.860
[Guest]: a conference overseas.

02:50:38.860 --> 02:50:43.500
[Guest]: And those two friends encourage each other, they say, go for it, go for it, you do it.

02:50:43.500 --> 02:50:47.220
[Guest]: So even though families might be more conservative, even though families might be concerned for

02:50:47.220 --> 02:50:50.980
[Guest]: their honour, these women are supporting each other, encouraging each other.

02:50:50.980 --> 02:50:54.900
[Guest]: And it's these iterative transgressions.

02:50:54.900 --> 02:50:59.340
[Guest]: So for example, when I was in Cambodia, girls would see that other girls down their street

02:50:59.340 --> 02:51:01.340
[Guest]: were getting homework, and they were jealous.

02:51:01.340 --> 02:51:02.340
[Guest]: They wanted homework too.

02:51:02.340 --> 02:51:05.900
[Guest]: And so they were pushing their parents to take them to school and things like that.

02:51:05.900 --> 02:51:11.460
[Guest]: So it's absolutely what, and I say, and many of the women I've also spoken to who might

02:51:11.460 --> 02:51:17.500
[Guest]: be in abusive relationships and not recognising those harms.

02:51:17.500 --> 02:51:21.660
[Guest]: So thinking, for example, of this, you know, controlling your jealous practices because

02:51:21.660 --> 02:51:23.660
[Guest]: he loves me so much, for example.

02:51:23.660 --> 02:51:28.340
[Guest]: But friends can help each other to see that critically, to question some of those ideologies.

02:51:28.340 --> 02:51:34.500
[Guest]: So it's one about questioning, to question ideas, and two, to be supported, to be involved

02:51:34.500 --> 02:51:39.140
[Guest]: in, to be encouraged, that's really transformative.

02:51:39.140 --> 02:51:44.140
[Guest]: So this is why I say friendships are absolutely the foundation of both feminist consciousness

02:51:44.140 --> 02:51:46.780
[Guest]: and feminist activism.

02:51:46.780 --> 02:51:52.320
[Amit Varma]: One observation that I sometimes make is that, you know, India lives in sort of three centuries

02:51:52.320 --> 02:51:53.320
[Amit Varma]: at the same time, right?

02:51:53.320 --> 02:51:55.780
[Amit Varma]: So there's a 19th, 20th, 21st, right?

02:51:55.780 --> 02:52:00.020
[Amit Varma]: The girls you encountered in JNU, regardless of background, are pretty much firmly in the

02:52:00.020 --> 02:52:04.740
[Amit Varma]: 21st century, in that sense, where large parts of the country are in the 19th century.

02:52:04.740 --> 02:52:09.220
[Amit Varma]: And I think that's also something to keep in mind that it might seem to be the same

02:52:09.220 --> 02:52:15.220
[Amit Varma]: geography, but within that geography, there are these overlapping realities, as it were.

02:52:15.220 --> 02:52:19.020
[Amit Varma]: So you know, the drive to female seclusion would definitely be there, for example, from

02:52:19.020 --> 02:52:23.940
[Amit Varma]: those still in the 19th and 20th centuries, and not really so much in the 21st century.

02:52:23.940 --> 02:52:28.820
[Amit Varma]: But I'm struck by the distinction that you made between internalised ideologies and what

02:52:28.820 --> 02:52:30.380
[Amit Varma]: the social norms are, like...

02:52:30.380 --> 02:52:33.580
[Guest]: Or our norm perceptions, our perceptions of what...

02:52:33.580 --> 02:52:38.260
[Guest]: Because as Timur Kuran has highlighted, there can also be pluralistic ignorance.

02:52:38.260 --> 02:52:44.580
[Guest]: So we may underestimate wider support for disobedience and rebellion, and that itself

02:52:44.580 --> 02:52:48.660
[Guest]: can create a negative feedback loop, or what I call a despondency trap.

02:52:48.660 --> 02:52:54.980
[Guest]: So it may be that many other people are privately critical, but as long as they anticipate social

02:52:54.980 --> 02:53:00.140
[Guest]: disapproval, they won't actually stick their necks out and voice their concerns.

02:53:00.140 --> 02:53:05.460
[Guest]: And so that in itself traps people from thinking differently, which is like my vagina example.

02:53:05.460 --> 02:53:06.460
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:53:06.460 --> 02:53:11.300
[Amit Varma]: And I like Timur Kuran's term, preference falsification, where, I mean, the whole idea

02:53:11.300 --> 02:53:16.600
[Amit Varma]: is that you feel a certain way, which is your internalised ideology, but you perceive the

02:53:16.600 --> 02:53:20.940
[Amit Varma]: norm to be something else, and therefore you don't express yourself until eventually there

02:53:20.940 --> 02:53:25.060
[Amit Varma]: is what he calls a preference cascade, and then people feel emboldened to express themselves.

02:53:25.060 --> 02:53:30.580
[Amit Varma]: Now, classic example to go back to the Cambodia case would be that, you know, you could have

02:53:30.580 --> 02:53:35.220
[Amit Varma]: a woman who believes that it is a wife's job to do all the work at home, but then she meets

02:53:35.220 --> 02:53:37.620
[Amit Varma]: friends and her internalised ideology changes.

02:53:37.620 --> 02:53:40.660
[Amit Varma]: She thinks that, no, men should also share in it, right?

02:53:40.660 --> 02:53:45.540
[Amit Varma]: But she perceives a norm to be so patriarchal that she dare not question it, so she doesn't.

02:53:45.540 --> 02:53:50.020
[Amit Varma]: But here there's a sort of a third factor besides these female friendships, which kind

02:53:50.020 --> 02:53:56.940
[Amit Varma]: of comes into play, which is the way technology spreads a sort of globalised culture, where

02:53:56.940 --> 02:54:02.180
[Amit Varma]: you could be watching things on Netflix or Hotstar or whatever, where men are actually

02:54:02.180 --> 02:54:04.940
[Amit Varma]: cooking, where women are actually working outside.

02:54:04.940 --> 02:54:09.740
[Amit Varma]: So is that something that that is a source of hope for you as well in terms of the norms

02:54:09.740 --> 02:54:12.060
[Amit Varma]: themselves changing over time?

02:54:12.060 --> 02:54:16.300
[Amit Varma]: So if you have that internalised feeling that, hey, I shouldn't have to do all the housework,

02:54:16.300 --> 02:54:20.860
[Amit Varma]: but you're too scared to say it, because of all of that culture around you, you know,

02:54:20.860 --> 02:54:24.020
[Amit Varma]: does that change the culture at home as well gradually over a period of time?

02:54:24.020 --> 02:54:27.420
[Guest]: Okay, so let me make three points on that.

02:54:27.420 --> 02:54:33.780
[Guest]: One is that use and adoption of technology is itself endogenous to culture.

02:54:33.780 --> 02:54:38.420
[Guest]: So for example, in 2017, there was a cat panchayat that actually in Uttar Pradesh that banned

02:54:38.420 --> 02:54:40.300
[Guest]: women from having mobile phones.

02:54:40.300 --> 02:54:46.820
[Guest]: There are also instances of surveillance technology on mobile phones, mirroring women's phones,

02:54:46.820 --> 02:54:49.100
[Guest]: creating cameras to create their surveillance.

02:54:49.100 --> 02:54:52.520
[Guest]: So the kinds of technologies people use is endogenous to culture.

02:54:52.520 --> 02:54:58.500
[Guest]: My second point is that yes, on Instagram, people may see inspirational feminist messages,

02:54:58.500 --> 02:55:03.620
[Guest]: they may see Bollywood stars doing things differently, refusing dowry, for example.

02:55:03.620 --> 02:55:11.300
[Guest]: But what is equally important through my interviews is, and wait, and that is often contingent

02:55:11.300 --> 02:55:13.140
[Guest]: on a democratic environment.

02:55:13.140 --> 02:55:18.980
[Guest]: So for example, as I was saying in China, much of that is blacked out by the CCP.

02:55:18.980 --> 02:55:21.740
[Guest]: So the advantage of India that there's less surveillance on that.

02:55:21.740 --> 02:55:28.860
[Guest]: But still, even with the exposure to all those alternative ideologies, people often reflect

02:55:28.860 --> 02:55:33.740
[Guest]: on them in their friendship groups, and their ability to act them out is dependent on how

02:55:33.740 --> 02:55:36.620
[Guest]: they think they will be perceived and treated in their own communities.

02:55:36.620 --> 02:55:41.380
[Guest]: So earlier last year, there was the torn jean thing.

02:55:41.380 --> 02:55:44.380
[Guest]: So some guys said women shouldn't be wearing torn jeans, and then a bunch of women said,

02:55:44.380 --> 02:55:46.780
[Guest]: hey, I'm wearing my torn jeans, and I'm proud of it.

02:55:46.780 --> 02:55:52.420
[Guest]: But still, even if you saw that living in rural West Bengal, women might themselves

02:55:52.420 --> 02:55:54.180
[Guest]: not wear shorts in that environment.

02:55:54.180 --> 02:55:57.660
[Guest]: And so instead, JNU students, for example, were saying how excited they were to come

02:55:57.660 --> 02:56:02.460
[Guest]: to JNU, where they knew it would be possible to wear shorts in that environment.

02:56:02.460 --> 02:56:06.620
[Guest]: So it's not enough to see those Instagram inspirational messages.

02:56:06.620 --> 02:56:11.140
[Guest]: It's about the specific environment, how you think you'll be perceived and treated.

02:56:11.140 --> 02:56:15.140
[Guest]: So I would not say technology is inevitably emancipatory.

02:56:15.140 --> 02:56:22.580
[Guest]: And technology itself can spread hateful, casteist, Islamophobic, sexist, racist messages.

02:56:22.580 --> 02:56:27.940
[Guest]: So technology is always mediated by our culture, our institutions, etc.

02:56:27.940 --> 02:56:28.940
[Amit Varma]: Sure.

02:56:28.940 --> 02:56:32.420
[Amit Varma]: I mean, it's not a magic bullet, but at least you're aware another sort of world exists

02:56:32.420 --> 02:56:33.420
[Amit Varma]: out there.

02:56:33.420 --> 02:56:35.340
[Amit Varma]: Let's sort of go back to talking about global history.

02:56:35.340 --> 02:56:38.460
[Amit Varma]: We've looked at India and how India has evolved and so on and so forth.

02:56:38.460 --> 02:56:43.020
[Amit Varma]: Now, the rest of the world has evolved differently from India and differently from each other.

02:56:43.020 --> 02:56:48.820
[Amit Varma]: So give me a sense of that, you know, Europe, China, East Asia, Sub-Saharan Africa, you

02:56:48.820 --> 02:56:54.660
[Amit Varma]: know, Latin America, give me a sense of the sort of currents that are shaping patriarchy

02:56:54.660 --> 02:56:57.780
[Amit Varma]: or mitigating it in different ways in all of these places.

02:56:57.780 --> 02:57:03.220
[Guest]: Okay, well, perhaps let's start with East Asia, because I think that's one really important

02:57:03.220 --> 02:57:08.780
[Guest]: point in that I think it's important to understand how patriarchal it was historically, because

02:57:08.780 --> 02:57:12.460
[Guest]: I think that's a really great comparison with with South Asia.

02:57:12.460 --> 02:57:18.260
[Guest]: So the idea that men plough and women weave has this sort of gender division of labor

02:57:18.260 --> 02:57:23.940
[Guest]: has always been idealized in Chinese literature right through to antiquity.

02:57:23.940 --> 02:57:29.020
[Guest]: But the idea of the cult of chastity, the idea that the women should be confined to

02:57:29.020 --> 02:57:34.020
[Guest]: the inner quarters really took root when Confucianism was popular.

02:57:34.020 --> 02:57:41.820
[Guest]: So actually, after the collapse of the Han dynasty in 500 AD, 589 AD, when Confucianism

02:57:41.820 --> 02:57:47.660
[Guest]: lost power, lost favor, actually, we saw the flourishing of Daoism and women were recognized

02:57:47.660 --> 02:57:48.660
[Guest]: as scholars.

02:57:48.660 --> 02:57:53.740
[Guest]: Women were recognized as knowledgeable authorities as moral authorities.

02:57:53.740 --> 02:57:58.300
[Guest]: And yeah, women have exercised far greater freedoms and authority.

02:57:58.300 --> 02:58:05.580
[Guest]: So what changed the big step change in Chinese gender relations and patriarchy was the Song

02:58:05.580 --> 02:58:06.580
[Guest]: dynasty.

02:58:06.580 --> 02:58:14.260
[Guest]: So several things, they introduced a meritocratic civil service exam, and also widespread printing.

02:58:14.260 --> 02:58:20.380
[Guest]: And now what happened is the landed gentry was suddenly in a position of insecurity.

02:58:20.380 --> 02:58:24.300
[Guest]: And here I'm heavily borrowing from the work of Yuhan Wang, who's over at Harvard and he's

02:58:24.300 --> 02:58:25.660
[Guest]: got a new book out on this.

02:58:25.660 --> 02:58:29.540
[Guest]: And so meritocratic civil service exam means that you have to massively invest in your

02:58:29.540 --> 02:58:33.060
[Guest]: son's Confucian education in order to get that elite spot in the government.

02:58:33.060 --> 02:58:34.340
[Guest]: Everyone wants a government job, right?

02:58:34.340 --> 02:58:36.860
[Guest]: What's true in India today is also true in Song dynasty, right?

02:58:36.860 --> 02:58:39.980
[Guest]: That was your pathway to prestige and power, etc.

02:58:39.980 --> 02:58:45.260
[Guest]: So people heavily invested in their sons, but that also motivate, that also require,

02:58:45.260 --> 02:58:51.780
[Guest]: but people also, but people that heavy motivation to invest in sons cultivate a desire for intergenerational

02:58:51.780 --> 02:58:53.140
[Guest]: reciprocity.

02:58:53.140 --> 02:58:56.580
[Guest]: So if you massively investigate in your son's education, you need to make sure they pay

02:58:56.580 --> 02:59:02.740
[Guest]: back and you need these close-knit clans to cooperate to ensure basic survival, whether

02:59:02.740 --> 02:59:05.460
[Guest]: it's irrigation, social services, health.

02:59:05.460 --> 02:59:12.140
[Guest]: So close-knit clans are bonding closely together and they idealize the male lineage.

02:59:12.140 --> 02:59:16.820
[Guest]: We see the flourishing of genealogy books, the flourishing of ancestor worship, the idea

02:59:16.820 --> 02:59:19.820
[Guest]: of the, and that's preserved through the purity of the male line.

02:59:19.820 --> 02:59:24.660
[Guest]: And once you idealize the purity of the male line, then you need tighter restrictions on

02:59:24.660 --> 02:59:29.940
[Guest]: female ability, as was emphasized in Confucian literature and Confucian philosophy, which

02:59:29.940 --> 02:59:33.820
[Guest]: of course everyone is studying or many learned people are studying because they need to get

02:59:33.820 --> 02:59:35.460
[Guest]: into those state exams.

02:59:35.460 --> 02:59:39.940
[Guest]: So we see this emergence of the cult of genealogy, the emergence of the ideal of male purity

02:59:39.940 --> 02:59:42.980
[Guest]: and women increasingly retreat to the private sphere.

02:59:42.980 --> 02:59:48.220
[Guest]: So this is when we see the cult of chastity being idealized in song literature.

02:59:48.220 --> 02:59:54.760
[Guest]: Literature also emphasizes and celebrates female purity and celebrates women sacrificing

02:59:54.760 --> 02:59:56.340
[Guest]: themselves for their family.

02:59:56.340 --> 03:00:00.420
[Guest]: And I think this is such an important point that I previously didn't realize is that how

03:00:00.420 --> 03:00:06.420
[Guest]: our mental models are shaped by literature and how actually many women might comply with

03:00:06.420 --> 03:00:09.540
[Guest]: patriarchy because that is how you gain social esteem and praise.

03:00:09.540 --> 03:00:13.180
[Guest]: Like the greatest thing a woman can do is sacrifice herself for male honor.

03:00:13.180 --> 03:00:17.180
[Guest]: And we see parallels of that in India with Sati, for example, or Johar.

03:00:17.180 --> 03:00:23.760
[Guest]: And then another step change occurred with the Mongol invasion.

03:00:23.760 --> 03:00:28.920
[Guest]: So the Mongols came down to China, basically raiding, raping and pillaging, massive assault

03:00:28.920 --> 03:00:33.540
[Guest]: on male honor with close parallels with Northwest invasions in India.

03:00:33.540 --> 03:00:39.260
[Guest]: And then the Mongols tried to cultivate local legitimacy by adopting Confucian ideas.

03:00:39.260 --> 03:00:42.700
[Guest]: They tried to show, you know, we're just as Chinese as the Chinese and the Han officials

03:00:42.700 --> 03:00:45.580
[Guest]: underneath them also wanted to preserve their culture.

03:00:45.580 --> 03:00:48.620
[Guest]: So they closely cling to these Confucian ideas.

03:00:48.620 --> 03:00:53.220
[Guest]: And so then we see the ramping up of all these very patriarchal norms.

03:00:53.220 --> 03:00:57.340
[Guest]: So paintings of that era, you do not see women on city streets.

03:00:57.340 --> 03:01:03.780
[Guest]: So women are, their feet are bound and hobbled, especially in the North, less so in the South.

03:01:03.780 --> 03:01:04.780
[Guest]: And literature reflects it.

03:01:04.780 --> 03:01:08.920
[Guest]: So that's really the emergence of patriarchy in China.

03:01:08.920 --> 03:01:14.140
[Guest]: As I was saying, from ancient Greece to Mesopotamia to much of the Middle East and North Africa,

03:01:14.140 --> 03:01:17.500
[Guest]: also incredibly patriarchal.

03:01:17.500 --> 03:01:23.020
[Guest]: So the whole of Eurasia was incredibly patriarchal at that time.

03:01:23.020 --> 03:01:28.060
[Guest]: Now the areas that were different were places where you did not have nomadic pastoralism,

03:01:28.060 --> 03:01:33.260
[Guest]: where you did not have the plow and where male-dominated religions did not emerge.

03:01:33.260 --> 03:01:38.820
[Guest]: So for example, in the Philippines, where they didn't have plow agriculture, women traveled

03:01:38.820 --> 03:01:39.820
[Guest]: freely.

03:01:39.820 --> 03:01:43.900
[Guest]: So as we know from 10th century Chinese and European traders, they encountered Philippine

03:01:43.900 --> 03:01:47.900
[Guest]: Southeast Asian women trading, they traveled great distances.

03:01:47.900 --> 03:01:52.200
[Guest]: In the Philippines, it was women who acted as religious priestesses.

03:01:52.200 --> 03:01:56.740
[Guest]: If men wanted to be religious figures, they had to act effeminately.

03:01:56.740 --> 03:02:00.940
[Guest]: And if a woman wanted divorce, she could easily go and leave with half the shared slaves,

03:02:00.940 --> 03:02:01.940
[Guest]: half the assets, etc.

03:02:01.940 --> 03:02:07.100
[Guest]: And in fact, women were in such a position of authority and autonomy that they were in

03:02:07.100 --> 03:02:10.380
[Guest]: a position to prioritize their sexual pleasure.

03:02:10.380 --> 03:02:15.320
[Guest]: And so some asserted and demanded that men wear rather painful penis pins.

03:02:15.320 --> 03:02:18.740
[Guest]: So this is one country, to the best of my knowledge, where you have female sexual pleasure

