03:02:46.860 --> 03:02:47.860
[Guest]: Okay.

03:02:47.860 --> 03:02:51.860
[Guest]: I confess I have no ethnographic experience to comment in this regard.

03:02:51.860 --> 03:02:52.860
[Guest]: Okay.

03:02:52.860 --> 03:02:57.700
[Guest]: So Southeast Asia, relative weak restrictions on female mobility.

03:02:57.700 --> 03:02:59.180
[Guest]: The Andes also really interesting.

03:02:59.180 --> 03:03:05.100
[Guest]: So if we, although we don't have written scripts, so we have to be careful in inferring and

03:03:05.100 --> 03:03:06.940
[Guest]: understanding what these societies were like.

03:03:06.940 --> 03:03:11.860
[Guest]: If we look at iconography, if we look at art, if we look at artifacts, we see this strong

03:03:11.860 --> 03:03:16.180
[Guest]: ideology of gender complementarity, that we see men and women working together.

03:03:16.180 --> 03:03:20.900
[Guest]: And I suspect in the Andean civilization, well, they didn't have money and instead it

03:03:20.900 --> 03:03:26.220
[Guest]: was a tribute redistribution economy in that people paid service to the empire.

03:03:26.220 --> 03:03:29.300
[Guest]: So women contributed cloth, men contributed labor.

03:03:29.300 --> 03:03:32.140
[Guest]: And so women's work was recognized as equally valuable.

03:03:32.140 --> 03:03:36.660
[Guest]: And we did not see this patrilineal inheritance of wealth or relatively weak restrictions

03:03:36.660 --> 03:03:37.660
[Guest]: on women's mobility.

03:03:37.660 --> 03:03:42.680
[Guest]: They even recognized and celebrated trial marriage, premarital sexuality.

03:03:42.680 --> 03:03:47.340
[Guest]: They had this idea of bilateral descent so that women descended from women and ultimately

03:03:47.340 --> 03:03:49.080
[Guest]: from the moon goddess.

03:03:49.080 --> 03:03:53.420
[Guest]: So there's this idea of gender complementarity running right through the Americas with relatively

03:03:53.420 --> 03:03:54.420
[Guest]: weakened restrictions.

03:03:54.420 --> 03:03:57.660
[Guest]: And that's celebrated through folklore, et cetera.

03:03:57.660 --> 03:04:02.860
[Guest]: Now Africa is also incredibly fascinating and I think this is a great example of how

03:04:02.860 --> 03:04:05.140
[Guest]: geography mediates cultural evolution.

03:04:05.140 --> 03:04:12.540
[Guest]: So maybe 5,000 years ago, much of Sub-Saharan Africa might have been matrilineal, but this

03:04:12.540 --> 03:04:16.860
[Guest]: changed with cattle and pastoralism.

03:04:16.860 --> 03:04:21.500
[Guest]: So one, we have the Bantu expansion and that led to the spread of cattle.

03:04:21.500 --> 03:04:24.820
[Guest]: Cattle raises the value of land, patrilineal inheritance.

03:04:24.820 --> 03:04:26.880
[Guest]: Also we see nomadic pastoralism.

03:04:26.880 --> 03:04:33.140
[Guest]: So again, it's gangs of men, gangs of young men raiding, raping their way through the

03:04:33.140 --> 03:04:37.300
[Guest]: horn of Africa, down into Southern Africa, as we know through the genetic data.

03:04:37.300 --> 03:04:41.620
[Guest]: And they institutionalized patriarchal dominance and ideology.

03:04:41.620 --> 03:04:46.300
[Guest]: So if we look at the Maasai or Swana, these are male dominated village assemblies.

03:04:46.300 --> 03:04:48.220
[Guest]: Women are minors without the voice of their own.

03:04:48.220 --> 03:04:55.500
[Guest]: And there's also for the Swana, for example, men are revered, they are buried in the cattle

03:04:55.500 --> 03:04:56.500
[Guest]: corral.

03:04:56.500 --> 03:04:59.380
[Guest]: There are numerous sayings and proverbs saying, you know, women cannot lead, men are the ones

03:04:59.380 --> 03:05:02.300
[Guest]: who are autonomous, men are the ones who are the good leaders, et cetera.

03:05:02.300 --> 03:05:05.820
[Guest]: So that's the institution of patriarchy.

03:05:05.820 --> 03:05:12.900
[Guest]: But the spread of pastoralism and cattle was mediated by geography.

03:05:12.900 --> 03:05:18.220
[Guest]: So around the Gulf of Guinea, for example, they had the, I mispronounce this every time,

03:05:18.220 --> 03:05:19.220
[Guest]: setse fly.

03:05:19.220 --> 03:05:20.220
[Guest]: It's pronounced differently.

03:05:20.220 --> 03:05:22.360
[Guest]: I buggered it up, but you'll forgive me.

03:05:22.360 --> 03:05:25.620
[Guest]: This fly causes a sleeping sickness in cattle.

03:05:25.620 --> 03:05:28.160
[Guest]: And so it was not possible to have cattle there.

03:05:28.160 --> 03:05:32.460
[Guest]: So instead, land never became a valuable source of inheritance.

03:05:32.460 --> 03:05:37.780
[Guest]: So although many of the communities in the Gulf of Guinea had patrilineal succession,

03:05:37.780 --> 03:05:40.500
[Guest]: it was only men's control over the children.

03:05:40.500 --> 03:05:42.900
[Guest]: So through bride wealth, their men are getting the children.

03:05:42.900 --> 03:05:44.420
[Guest]: There's not about inherited wealth.

03:05:44.420 --> 03:05:49.180
[Guest]: So as a result, these communities, women are moving freely.

03:05:49.180 --> 03:05:51.620
[Guest]: Women have their own networks in the Yoruba and Igbo.

03:05:51.620 --> 03:05:56.700
[Guest]: And I especially recommend Professor Achebe Nwando, Professor Nwando Achebe's book on

03:05:56.700 --> 03:05:57.700
[Guest]: this.

03:05:57.700 --> 03:06:02.260
[Guest]: She highlights how there were women exercised authority and spirituality.

03:06:02.260 --> 03:06:06.060
[Guest]: So you see that Lesser, the name for God, is neither male or female.

03:06:06.060 --> 03:06:11.820
[Guest]: You see oracles and deities and women exercising spiritual authority.

03:06:11.820 --> 03:06:15.820
[Guest]: Queen Mothers also revered women across West Africa.

03:06:15.820 --> 03:06:20.060
[Guest]: Women are traders, they're merchants, they're running West African markets.

03:06:20.060 --> 03:06:25.220
[Guest]: And because they have this mobility, they were able to protect their own turf.

03:06:25.220 --> 03:06:31.980
[Guest]: Now on top of this, Islam spreads via networks of trade, but also amongst pastoralists.

03:06:31.980 --> 03:06:35.980
[Guest]: So there's another element in which geography mediates cultural evolution.

03:06:35.980 --> 03:06:40.700
[Guest]: And then fast forward a little bit to the 18th and 19th century, we have fuller jihads.

03:06:40.700 --> 03:06:44.780
[Guest]: And these fuller jihads are led by pastoralists in northern Nigeria, they institutionalize

03:06:44.780 --> 03:06:45.940
[Guest]: sharia law.

03:06:45.940 --> 03:06:50.820
[Guest]: And at that same time, we see the emergence of purdah.

03:06:50.820 --> 03:06:54.500
[Guest]: If you look at architecture, for example, that is when women are increasingly confined

03:06:54.500 --> 03:06:55.940
[Guest]: to the inner quarters.

03:06:55.940 --> 03:07:02.900
[Guest]: And families gain respectability by secluding their women and differentiating themselves

03:07:02.900 --> 03:07:05.420
[Guest]: from slaves used in labor.

03:07:05.420 --> 03:07:11.980
[Guest]: So it's this process of both geography and cultural evolution that's really important.

03:07:11.980 --> 03:07:20.220
[Guest]: So we have patrilineal, patrilocal Eurasia, and then we have these matrilineal and bilateral

03:07:20.220 --> 03:07:21.300
[Guest]: communities.

03:07:21.300 --> 03:07:27.540
[Guest]: Then there occurred an important divergence within Eurasia, and that is what I was talking

03:07:27.540 --> 03:07:31.900
[Guest]: about earlier, the emergence of nuclear families in Western Europe.

03:07:31.900 --> 03:07:34.340
[Guest]: And so that created a latent asset.

03:07:34.340 --> 03:07:38.340
[Guest]: So Europe was not gender equal, as I was saying, every institution was headed by men.

03:07:38.340 --> 03:07:42.060
[Guest]: I don't want anyone in the world to think that I'm saying that Europe was ahead, Europe

03:07:42.060 --> 03:07:44.260
[Guest]: was more gender equal, we had some great culture.

03:07:44.260 --> 03:07:46.020
[Guest]: No, no, no, no.

03:07:46.020 --> 03:07:52.580
[Guest]: In fact, women, so let me say, let me explain this, so one, even though women were working

03:07:52.580 --> 03:07:59.700
[Guest]: before the modern era, women spent 60% of their adult years either pregnant or nursing.

03:07:59.700 --> 03:08:05.900
[Guest]: So their mobility was hobbled, whereas men had far greater ability to capitalize on the

03:08:05.900 --> 03:08:09.420
[Guest]: transition from feudalism to commercialization.

03:08:09.420 --> 03:08:13.060
[Guest]: And as this occurred, men built guilds.

03:08:13.060 --> 03:08:18.480
[Guest]: So these are organizations that preserved existing privileges and locked out other groups.

03:08:18.480 --> 03:08:24.060
[Guest]: So they tried to disadvantage their competitors and prevent other groups for competing against

03:08:24.060 --> 03:08:25.700
[Guest]: them or undercutting them.

03:08:25.700 --> 03:08:30.100
[Guest]: So in places where there was weak economic growth and slow demand for labor, those were

03:08:30.100 --> 03:08:31.100
[Guest]: especially patriarchal.

03:08:31.100 --> 03:08:35.500
[Guest]: So for example, in Western Germany, women had no rights, they weren't allowed to use

03:08:35.500 --> 03:08:37.380
[Guest]: to compete with the girls at all.

03:08:37.380 --> 03:08:41.060
[Guest]: They also discriminated against immigrants for the exact same reason.

03:08:41.060 --> 03:08:46.780
[Guest]: But where you see greater prosperity, like the Netherlands and parts of France, Paris,

03:08:46.780 --> 03:08:48.780
[Guest]: then women could actually be included in guilds.

03:08:48.780 --> 03:08:49.780
[Guest]: So there was less.

03:08:49.780 --> 03:08:53.580
[Guest]: So when the pie was a little bit bigger, people might be a bit more prepared to share.

03:08:53.580 --> 03:08:55.460
[Guest]: So the girls discriminated against women.

03:08:55.460 --> 03:09:00.180
[Guest]: So the discrimination in Europe was not coming from within the household.

03:09:00.180 --> 03:09:05.220
[Guest]: It was primarily coming from outsiders who didn't want women competing against them.

03:09:05.220 --> 03:09:08.500
[Guest]: But women still had very weak social capital.

03:09:08.500 --> 03:09:13.420
[Guest]: So when Protestant and Catholic churches competed in the counter-reformation and their struggle

03:09:13.420 --> 03:09:18.640
[Guest]: for bums on seats or pews, they wanted to demonstrate their superior power to vanquish

03:09:18.640 --> 03:09:19.760
[Guest]: the devil.

03:09:19.760 --> 03:09:23.180
[Guest]: And they did so by burning witches, primarily women.

03:09:23.180 --> 03:09:25.780
[Guest]: So women's social capital was weak.

03:09:25.780 --> 03:09:28.780
[Guest]: Now let's fast forward to the Enlightenment.

03:09:28.780 --> 03:09:32.580
[Guest]: Now the Enlightenment was an age of great innovation and discovery.

03:09:32.580 --> 03:09:40.940
[Guest]: And men, whether they're engineers, scientists, entrepreneurs, they gather together to hear

03:09:40.940 --> 03:09:44.300
[Guest]: the latest innovations, to hear about scientific advances.

03:09:44.300 --> 03:09:47.100
[Guest]: And this enables collaborative creativity.

03:09:47.100 --> 03:09:50.940
[Guest]: The brilliant people, like when we went to our conference in Udaipur, brilliant people

03:09:50.940 --> 03:09:54.980
[Guest]: come together, share ideas, encourage each other, support each other.

03:09:54.980 --> 03:09:59.020
[Guest]: And Joel Mokia has a wonderful book on the enlightened economy, talking about why collaborative

03:09:59.020 --> 03:10:01.260
[Guest]: creativity is so important.

03:10:01.260 --> 03:10:05.500
[Guest]: And these groups are amplifying each other, they're supporting each other, they're amplifying

03:10:05.500 --> 03:10:07.860
[Guest]: each other's ideas on megaphones.

03:10:07.860 --> 03:10:12.860
[Guest]: Freemasons go to court to protect each other's reputations.

03:10:12.860 --> 03:10:19.220
[Guest]: Whereas in the English speaking world, 95% of these associations are male, discriminating

03:10:19.220 --> 03:10:20.220
[Guest]: against women.

03:10:20.220 --> 03:10:23.660
[Guest]: And so there were brilliant women, but they're toiling in solitude.

03:10:23.660 --> 03:10:30.740
[Guest]: I mean, there were a few Dutch Masonic lodges, London had a few women debating societies.

03:10:30.740 --> 03:10:33.220
[Guest]: But for the most part, women were locked out.

03:10:33.220 --> 03:10:37.300
[Guest]: So they're not getting that kind of support and encouragement and peer feedback, etc.

03:10:37.300 --> 03:10:41.180
[Guest]: So they're not able to benefit from this enlightenment.

03:10:41.180 --> 03:10:47.540
[Guest]: That said, we do see slightly higher rates of female writing in Protestant countries.

03:10:47.540 --> 03:10:51.460
[Guest]: And that's partly as a result of solar scripture, the idea that every person should understand

03:10:51.460 --> 03:10:53.100
[Guest]: the Bible for themselves.

03:10:53.100 --> 03:10:56.460
[Guest]: And that led to a reduction in gender gaps.

03:10:56.460 --> 03:11:00.100
[Guest]: So we did have a little bit of women's writing, especially in Protestant countries.

03:11:00.100 --> 03:11:05.140
[Guest]: But still, all the institutions are predominantly male, are male dominated.

03:11:05.140 --> 03:11:10.900
[Guest]: So now, okay, let's make it so Europe, patriarchal, but with this latent asset of participatory

03:11:10.900 --> 03:11:14.420
[Guest]: institutions, nuclear families and state institutions.

03:11:14.420 --> 03:11:19.580
[Guest]: Contrast that with the Middle East and North Africa, and these Ottoman towns are much more

03:11:19.580 --> 03:11:21.940
[Guest]: gender segregated.

03:11:21.940 --> 03:11:24.980
[Guest]: But women were by no means passive.

03:11:24.980 --> 03:11:28.980
[Guest]: So because married women had these property rights, if you look at court records, if you

03:11:28.980 --> 03:11:35.060
[Guest]: look at court records from Ain Tab, from Cairo, Damascus, you see women litigating in court,

03:11:35.060 --> 03:11:39.660
[Guest]: they're pursuing thieves, they're hounding, they're hounding people, they're pressing

03:11:39.660 --> 03:11:44.020
[Guest]: for their inheritance rights, they're pressing for their claims on property, they're owning

03:11:44.020 --> 03:11:49.500
[Guest]: various houses, assets, gardens, orchards, donkeys, etc.

03:11:49.500 --> 03:11:55.420
[Guest]: However, we tend not to see, but we tend to not, but elite and wealthy women tended to

03:11:55.420 --> 03:12:01.100
[Guest]: send emissaries on their behalf, so they could maintain seclusion because that was respectable.

03:12:01.100 --> 03:12:08.500
[Guest]: But again, we don't see, I still would not say that the Middle East was especially patriarchal

03:12:08.500 --> 03:12:13.540
[Guest]: at that time, because at that time, the vast majority of people across the world are peasants.

03:12:13.540 --> 03:12:17.660
[Guest]: Pretty much most women are working in peasants in family farms, where again, you don't have

03:12:17.660 --> 03:12:18.660
[Guest]: many exit options.

03:12:18.660 --> 03:12:21.360
[Guest]: So again, you're vulnerable to male violence, etc.

03:12:21.360 --> 03:12:25.780
[Guest]: And you probably internalize all the, and many people would have internalized patriarchal

03:12:25.780 --> 03:12:26.780
[Guest]: traditions.

03:12:26.780 --> 03:12:30.500
[Guest]: So Ottoman towns, more gender segregated, but much of Eurasia is very patriarchal.

03:12:30.500 --> 03:12:36.660
[Guest]: We just have this latent divergence that would appear much more important later on in the

03:12:36.660 --> 03:12:37.660
[Guest]: 20th century.

03:12:37.660 --> 03:12:41.460
[Guest]: Another important issue I should highlight, sorry, skipping over to Song China, is Song

03:12:41.460 --> 03:12:47.180
[Guest]: China actually outlawed cousin marriage, so you're not allowed to marry anyone with your

03:12:47.180 --> 03:12:48.940
[Guest]: same surname.

03:12:48.940 --> 03:12:53.460
[Guest]: So that would have led to weaker clans, so far weaker kinship intensity, which would

03:12:53.460 --> 03:12:54.820
[Guest]: prove important later on.

03:12:54.820 --> 03:12:55.820
[Guest]: Right.

03:12:55.820 --> 03:12:57.900
[Guest]: So now we have the main map of the world.

03:12:57.900 --> 03:12:59.900
[Guest]: Oh, I should also talk about colonialism.

03:12:59.900 --> 03:13:02.940
[Guest]: So the impact of colonialism.

03:13:02.940 --> 03:13:09.220
[Guest]: So many scholars raise concerns that colonialism could have perpetuated patriarchy, because

03:13:09.220 --> 03:13:16.020
[Guest]: of course, the Europeans were incredibly patriarchal at that time, undeniably.

03:13:16.020 --> 03:13:23.580
[Guest]: And they often emphasize, but I do not think that colonialism is responsible for the contemporary

03:13:23.580 --> 03:13:28.100
[Guest]: divergence in outcomes by pressing for their patriarchal beliefs.

03:13:28.100 --> 03:13:32.020
[Guest]: So let me give you the example, let's, but we have to take each region in turn.

03:13:32.020 --> 03:13:38.860
[Guest]: So if we look at colonialism in Latin America, where colonialism was horrifically impressive,

03:13:38.860 --> 03:13:43.540
[Guest]: they, they spawned disease, millions of people died.

03:13:43.540 --> 03:13:51.780
[Guest]: They also butchered and enslaved Native Americans, and there was horrific violence, rapes, etc.

03:13:51.780 --> 03:13:56.860
[Guest]: That said, indigenous people fiercely maintained their own traditions.

03:13:56.860 --> 03:14:02.980
[Guest]: So while Catholics might call trial marriage diabolical, Andean civilizations often continue

03:14:02.980 --> 03:14:03.980
[Guest]: to practice it.

03:14:03.980 --> 03:14:09.100
[Guest]: In fact, in 1789, there was an indigenous people's rebellion, 44% of those leaders were

03:14:09.100 --> 03:14:10.100
[Guest]: women.

03:14:10.100 --> 03:14:13.580
[Guest]: So they continue to practice their ideal, and still today, Peru has very high rates

03:14:13.580 --> 03:14:15.900
[Guest]: of female labor force participation.

03:14:15.900 --> 03:14:22.660
[Guest]: And for the most part, across Latin America, they had fairly weak ties of kinship in that

03:14:22.660 --> 03:14:31.180
[Guest]: there are fairly weak, fairly weak bond, fairly weak marital bonds in that in Sao Paulo in

03:14:31.180 --> 03:14:36.820
[Guest]: the 17th century in Mexico City in the 19th century, you'll find lots of single women

03:14:36.820 --> 03:14:38.860
[Guest]: working by themselves independently.

03:14:38.860 --> 03:14:44.260
[Guest]: It was really only the very, very tiny elites, landowners, that would practice cousin marriage

03:14:44.260 --> 03:14:49.580
[Guest]: and female seclusion and chastity and confinement in order to preserve their important landholding.

03:14:49.580 --> 03:14:57.180
[Guest]: So Latin America, though, I'd say one more important aspect there is the spread of Catholicism.

03:14:57.180 --> 03:15:02.620
[Guest]: Catholicism promoted this idea of the cult of virginity, the idea of shame.

03:15:02.620 --> 03:15:09.540
[Guest]: So yeah, so Catholicism, definitely, definitely, definitely a regressive religion for the most

03:15:09.540 --> 03:15:10.540
[Guest]: part.

03:15:10.540 --> 03:15:13.980
[Guest]: But there's, you know, the way that people adopt that and how they adopt it is mediated

03:15:13.980 --> 03:15:17.140
[Guest]: by their indigenous culture.

03:15:17.140 --> 03:15:22.540
[Guest]: Now I think, let me talk, I want to, I'll come back, I want to talk more, let me put

03:15:22.540 --> 03:15:25.860
[Guest]: colonialism on hold, because I'll come back to it in the case of Africa.

03:15:25.860 --> 03:15:28.340
[Guest]: But I can talk about colonialism for any reason.

03:15:28.340 --> 03:15:30.300
[Guest]: Yeah, so I'll come back to that.

03:15:30.300 --> 03:15:31.300
[Guest]: Okay.

03:15:31.300 --> 03:15:35.540
[Guest]: The next thing I want to do is to talk about industrialization in the 20th century.

03:15:35.540 --> 03:15:38.020
[Guest]: Now this was phenomenally important.

03:15:38.020 --> 03:15:42.420
[Guest]: And this is where we see the honor income trade-off taking off, because with technological

03:15:42.420 --> 03:15:48.620
[Guest]: change, reducing the domestic drudgery, and also job-creating economic growth, means that

03:15:48.620 --> 03:15:54.540
[Guest]: employers who might initially prefer to hire men, eventually run out of men.

03:15:54.540 --> 03:15:58.780
[Guest]: And here I'm borrowing work by Professor Claudia Goldin, and they run out of men.

03:15:58.780 --> 03:16:01.720
[Guest]: So they run out of men and increasingly hire women.

03:16:01.720 --> 03:16:04.140
[Guest]: And so we see this in every single country.

03:16:04.140 --> 03:16:08.860
[Guest]: Even more recently in Turkey, where we have strong job-creating economic growth, at least

03:16:08.860 --> 03:16:12.300
[Guest]: before 2018, then we see rising female labor force participation.

03:16:12.300 --> 03:16:14.780
[Guest]: Same in East Asia, Taiwan, and much of Europe.

03:16:14.780 --> 03:16:21.100
[Guest]: So in Europe, where the constraints, where the restrictions on female mobility are relatively

03:16:21.100 --> 03:16:26.740
[Guest]: weak, then when you get higher female education, then when fertility goes down, women seize

03:16:26.740 --> 03:16:29.140
[Guest]: economic opportunities in their droves.

03:16:29.140 --> 03:16:33.860
[Guest]: And this is because of the latent asset of nuclear families, where there is this weaker

03:16:33.860 --> 03:16:38.080
[Guest]: concern for honor, and where families really, where a woman's earnings make a massive difference

03:16:38.080 --> 03:16:39.080
[Guest]: to household survival.

03:16:39.080 --> 03:16:44.260
[Guest]: Then we see in the 1970s, there's liberalization of divorce laws, both in the USA and Europe,

03:16:44.260 --> 03:16:48.340
[Guest]: and women cease to believe that marriage offers decent security and insurance.

03:16:48.340 --> 03:16:51.140
[Guest]: So they become much more committed to the labor market.

03:16:51.140 --> 03:16:54.980
[Guest]: They pursue careers, and they become much more independently minded.

03:16:54.980 --> 03:16:57.740
[Guest]: And through that, they generate friendships.

03:16:57.740 --> 03:17:01.580
[Guest]: So that's the really important, that's why the great gender divergence occurred in the

03:17:01.580 --> 03:17:07.900
[Guest]: 20th century, because it's this economic, the culture is responding to economic changes.

03:17:07.900 --> 03:17:12.740
[Guest]: Now another really important dimension is communism.

03:17:12.740 --> 03:17:21.460
[Guest]: And here again, I can say something controversial, that I think communism, totalitarian communism,

03:17:21.460 --> 03:17:27.260
[Guest]: may be the world's greatest intervention for women's economic empowerment.

03:17:27.260 --> 03:17:28.700
[Guest]: And let me explain.

03:17:28.700 --> 03:17:35.180
[Guest]: So communism is run on, totalitarianism, totalitarian communism, is run on a model of extensive

03:17:35.180 --> 03:17:42.520
[Guest]: growth, that central planners set wages low, and demanded very high productivity targets.

03:17:42.520 --> 03:17:47.740
[Guest]: So consider yourself in the position of each firm, it's very cheap to hire in labor, and

03:17:47.740 --> 03:17:51.940
[Guest]: you want to get as much labor as possible in order to meet your production target.

03:17:51.940 --> 03:17:52.940
[Guest]: So what do you do?

03:17:52.940 --> 03:17:55.620
[Guest]: You recruit lots of men, and you also recruit women.

03:17:55.620 --> 03:18:00.660
[Guest]: And women themselves have a strong incentive to seek those jobs, because male wages are

03:18:00.660 --> 03:18:04.740
[Guest]: very low, they cannot, the male breadwinner model would not exist, because male earnings

03:18:04.740 --> 03:18:05.820
[Guest]: were so low.

03:18:05.820 --> 03:18:11.540
[Guest]: And also that jobs with a passport to social security, social services, holidays, amenities,

03:18:11.540 --> 03:18:12.980
[Guest]: everything, apartments.

03:18:12.980 --> 03:18:18.180
[Guest]: So post-communist countries have very high rates of female employment.

03:18:18.180 --> 03:18:21.220
[Guest]: It's not just that women are working, but also labor market advancement.

03:18:21.220 --> 03:18:24.820
[Guest]: So in Russia, 44% of economists are women.

03:18:24.820 --> 03:18:30.500
[Guest]: We see much smaller gender gaps in business ownership, business management, in post-communist

03:18:30.500 --> 03:18:31.500
[Guest]: countries.

03:18:31.500 --> 03:18:35.900
[Guest]: Also, post-communist countries have very small, and well, they're the smallest gender gaps

03:18:35.900 --> 03:18:37.140
[Guest]: in competitive chess.

03:18:37.140 --> 03:18:41.980
[Guest]: So in terms of the economy, yeah, the gender gaps are smaller.

03:18:41.980 --> 03:18:48.420
[Guest]: However, because totalitarian communism suffocated activism, we do not see the emergence of feminist

03:18:48.420 --> 03:18:50.900
[Guest]: activism, as I mentioned earlier.

03:18:50.900 --> 03:18:56.140
[Guest]: So we don't see strong pressure for reforms in government, for female representation,

03:18:56.140 --> 03:18:58.260
[Guest]: and also protections for male violence.

03:18:58.260 --> 03:19:02.620
[Guest]: However, and this is where my comparative lens is important.

03:19:02.620 --> 03:19:07.600
[Guest]: If you look, if you compare post-communist countries, their peers, you see that generally

03:19:07.600 --> 03:19:09.980
[Guest]: people in post-communist countries are more sexist.

03:19:09.980 --> 03:19:12.300
[Guest]: But there's one exception, Central Asia.

03:19:12.300 --> 03:19:16.220
[Guest]: So Central Asia, we're talking about Uzbekistan, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan.

03:19:16.220 --> 03:19:23.660
[Guest]: Now, in Uzbekistan, in Fergana Valley in the 1920s, women were marrying at 13.

03:19:23.660 --> 03:19:29.140
[Guest]: They're fully veiled, their faces are covered, they're clinging closely to the walls.

03:19:29.140 --> 03:19:35.560
[Guest]: What then happens is that the Soviet Union was incredibly brutal.

03:19:35.560 --> 03:19:42.140
[Guest]: They butchered, decimated and destroyed traditional institutions, just as they did in Russia.

03:19:42.140 --> 03:19:47.460
[Guest]: This destroyed indigenous resistance, so it's harder to preserve indigenous traditions.

03:19:47.460 --> 03:19:52.220
[Guest]: They also forced collectivization, now millions of people and also animals died.

03:19:52.220 --> 03:19:57.140
[Guest]: But it also made that the Soviets were able to assert their ideology.

03:19:57.140 --> 03:20:02.500
[Guest]: So they imposed secular schools where women were taught and prepared for a life in the

03:20:02.500 --> 03:20:06.140
[Guest]: public sphere, so taught drama and sports, etc.

03:20:06.140 --> 03:20:11.900
[Guest]: And also because they ramped up industrialization, they created hydroelectric power, they had

03:20:11.900 --> 03:20:16.280
[Guest]: factories, those factories needed women, and they also provide nurseries and creches.

03:20:16.280 --> 03:20:20.860
[Guest]: So we see a rapid increase in female labor force participation.

03:20:20.860 --> 03:20:26.900
[Guest]: Now I'm not trying to say that Uzbekistan is some feminist utopia, but if you listen

03:20:26.900 --> 03:20:34.020
[Guest]: to women's narratives, you listen to women who are postgraduate researchers in science

03:20:34.020 --> 03:20:40.480
[Guest]: and technology, and their work is being celebrated, even beetroot farmers are celebrated as heroes

03:20:40.480 --> 03:20:41.660
[Guest]: of socialist labor.

03:20:41.660 --> 03:20:46.100
[Guest]: And they'll say, you know, compared to my mother, when my mother was secluded, my mother

03:20:46.100 --> 03:20:49.580
[Guest]: was treated as a slave, and here I am as an independent career woman.

03:20:49.580 --> 03:20:53.140
[Guest]: Of course, feminist activism is suppressed, of course.

03:20:53.140 --> 03:20:58.780
[Guest]: But if you compare those countries to the relevant counterfactuals, which might be Afghanistan

03:20:58.780 --> 03:21:03.140
[Guest]: and Pakistan, then you see an enormous divergence in outcomes.

03:21:03.140 --> 03:21:09.200
[Guest]: So in that respect, those post-communist Central Asian countries are actually much more gender

03:21:09.200 --> 03:21:10.740
[Guest]: equal as a result of communism.

03:21:10.740 --> 03:21:17.340
[Guest]: So communism's impact on gender equality in gender relations differs on its domain, economy

03:21:17.340 --> 03:21:20.600
[Guest]: versus the political environment, and it's also media.

03:21:20.600 --> 03:21:24.220
[Guest]: And I would say, so I would say that for China and Russia, and those countries where there

03:21:24.220 --> 03:21:29.660
[Guest]: are relatively weak constraints on female mobility, communism actually took gender equality

03:21:29.660 --> 03:21:32.660
[Guest]: backwards or is worse than it would have been because female employment could have risen

03:21:32.660 --> 03:21:34.620
[Guest]: anyway with growth.

03:21:34.620 --> 03:21:39.340
[Guest]: And communism made a step, made it more patriarchal by suffocating activism, which is incredibly

03:21:39.340 --> 03:21:40.340
[Guest]: important.

03:21:40.340 --> 03:21:46.460
[Guest]: Now, I think the lesson from communism is that high female employment is no guard against

03:21:46.460 --> 03:21:47.460
[Guest]: misogyny.

03:21:47.460 --> 03:21:52.140
[Guest]: You know, you can still have incredibly high rates of male violence, persistence of sexist

03:21:52.140 --> 03:21:53.140
[Guest]: ideologies.

03:21:53.140 --> 03:21:57.820
[Guest]: You know, in Russia, the Orthodox Church champions very patriarchal ideologies.

03:21:57.820 --> 03:22:00.260
[Guest]: So what's incredibly important is feminist activism.

03:22:00.260 --> 03:22:03.060
[Guest]: And I think a great example there is Latin America.

03:22:03.060 --> 03:22:08.580
[Guest]: So this was a patriarchal region, partly thanks to Catholicism.

03:22:08.580 --> 03:22:14.620
[Guest]: For example, in Chile in the 1990s, the cabinet, parliament, almost entirely male, but women

03:22:14.620 --> 03:22:16.180
[Guest]: have increasingly organized.

03:22:16.180 --> 03:22:23.300
[Guest]: So one through relatively weak, with relatively weak kinship intensity, relatively weak concerns

03:22:23.300 --> 03:22:24.700
[Guest]: for honor.

03:22:24.700 --> 03:22:27.020
[Guest]: Women increasingly seize the economic opportunities.

03:22:27.020 --> 03:22:29.340
[Guest]: They increasingly gathered in the public sphere.

03:22:29.340 --> 03:22:30.980
[Guest]: They organized collectively.

03:22:30.980 --> 03:22:34.820
[Guest]: Women were at the forefront of many of the protests for democratization, protesting the

03:22:34.820 --> 03:22:35.820
[Guest]: disappeared.

03:22:35.820 --> 03:22:39.100
[Guest]: Then those women are organizing, sharing and learning from each other across the region.

03:22:39.100 --> 03:22:43.780
[Guest]: And this, I think, is a really important point about activism, but it's by seeing that people

03:22:43.780 --> 03:22:47.780
[Guest]: who we think are in a similar position as us or as our relevant peers, if we can see

03:22:47.780 --> 03:22:52.820
[Guest]: people we think are like us gaining something through successful activism, then we may become

03:22:52.820 --> 03:22:53.820
[Guest]: emboldened.

03:22:53.820 --> 03:22:58.020
[Guest]: So as Latin American feminists saw that a neighboring country could mobilize and gain

03:22:58.020 --> 03:23:02.500
[Guest]: some returns, that emboldens hope and that encourages relentless activism.

03:23:02.500 --> 03:23:07.820
[Guest]: And so we see these encuentros across Latin America, whereby women are increased.

03:23:07.820 --> 03:23:14.020
[Guest]: So in 2015, one woman tweeted, ni una menos, and that means not one woman less, not one

03:23:14.020 --> 03:23:17.580
[Guest]: woman less should die from male violence and femicide.

03:23:17.580 --> 03:23:20.820
[Guest]: And so 200,000 women took to the streets of Buenos Aires.

03:23:20.820 --> 03:23:26.000
[Guest]: So now in an environment of democratization, urbanization, social media, these ideas can

03:23:26.000 --> 03:23:29.180
[Guest]: spread like wildfire and they're celebrated in street murals.

03:23:29.180 --> 03:23:35.140
[Guest]: And people are, you know, challenging ideas of shame, challenging the idea that if a woman

03:23:35.140 --> 03:23:38.780
[Guest]: is raped, then it's her burden, it's her shame and her stigma and she should keep it to herself

03:23:38.780 --> 03:23:40.020
[Guest]: and she should be quiet.

03:23:40.020 --> 03:23:45.060
[Guest]: And so there was a Chilean protest anthem saying, you know, the problem, the problem

03:23:45.060 --> 03:23:46.060
[Guest]: is with the rapist.

03:23:46.060 --> 03:23:48.000
[Guest]: The problem is not with me.

03:23:48.000 --> 03:23:51.220
[Guest]: And so those ideas reverberate and women become emboldened.

03:23:51.220 --> 03:23:57.940
[Guest]: So we see massive campaigns for women's political representation and across Latin America, gender

03:23:57.940 --> 03:24:03.200
[Guest]: parity, not gender quotas, but parity is seen as part of human rights and democracy.

03:24:03.200 --> 03:24:09.780
[Guest]: So we see huge struggles for domestic workers' rights, for protections against male violence,

03:24:09.780 --> 03:24:12.260
[Guest]: for political representation.

03:24:12.260 --> 03:24:16.060
[Guest]: And this builds on a culture where there's been massive resistance, where there's been

03:24:16.060 --> 03:24:21.020
[Guest]: indigenous people's movements, where there's been piqueteros in Argentina, for example,

03:24:21.020 --> 03:24:23.700
[Guest]: the gas wars in Bolivia, the water wars in Bolivia.

03:24:23.700 --> 03:24:29.940
[Guest]: So that environment of resistance seen by mobilizing people can change the laws of the

03:24:29.940 --> 03:24:32.020
[Guest]: land also emboldens feminist activism.

03:24:32.020 --> 03:24:35.580
[Guest]: So feminist activism is endogenous to that culture of resistance.

03:24:35.580 --> 03:24:39.300
[Guest]: So that's Latin America as an example of feminist activism.

03:24:39.300 --> 03:24:41.460
[Guest]: And that's true for the whole world.

03:24:41.460 --> 03:24:45.260
[Guest]: Now this is where I want to come back to colonialism.

03:24:45.260 --> 03:24:52.940
[Guest]: So Sub-Saharan Africa has also seen many feminist movements pushing for greater women's representation.

03:24:52.940 --> 03:24:59.620
[Guest]: And we especially see those in periods of transition, regime transition, or after post-conflict

03:24:59.620 --> 03:25:06.220
[Guest]: women's movements mobilized and organized for better representation and gender quotas.

03:25:06.220 --> 03:25:13.540
[Guest]: However, one part of Africa remains especially patriarchal in terms of governance.

03:25:13.540 --> 03:25:17.940
[Guest]: And that surprisingly is the Gulf of Guinea, which I previously said was very, very gender

03:25:17.940 --> 03:25:18.940
[Guest]: equal, right?

03:25:18.940 --> 03:25:20.500
[Guest]: So what's happened there?

03:25:20.500 --> 03:25:24.380
[Guest]: Now this is my hypothesis.

03:25:24.380 --> 03:25:29.020
[Guest]: So yeah, we have this conundrum that there was this, we have definite evidence of traditions

03:25:29.020 --> 03:25:34.540
[Guest]: of women exercising authority and being respected as positions of authority across the Gulf

03:25:34.540 --> 03:25:35.540
[Guest]: of Guinea.

03:25:35.540 --> 03:25:39.220
[Guest]: But now, this is one of the most patriarchal regions of the world.

03:25:39.220 --> 03:25:42.580
[Guest]: So Nigeria's parliament is 94% male.

03:25:42.580 --> 03:25:47.540
[Guest]: And it's true across the Gulf of Guinea, all those parliaments are very, very patriarchal.

03:25:47.540 --> 03:25:50.100
[Guest]: And why is that?

03:25:50.100 --> 03:25:55.780
[Guest]: So my hypothesis is, and this is borrowing heavily on the work of Nathan Nunn and Leonard

03:25:55.780 --> 03:26:00.780
[Guest]: Wanchekon, is that this is the area that was heavily hit by slave raiding.

03:26:00.780 --> 03:26:06.940
[Guest]: So as there was slave raiding, indigenous Africans tried to protect themselves often

03:26:06.940 --> 03:26:10.660
[Guest]: through this weapons and slaves vicious cycle.

03:26:10.660 --> 03:26:14.620
[Guest]: So to protect themselves against raiders, they sought to actually raid other slaves

03:26:14.620 --> 03:26:19.020
[Guest]: and sell them to Europeans in order to buy the weapons that they needed to protect themselves.

03:26:19.020 --> 03:26:24.860
[Guest]: And this cycle of violence and conquest and slave raiding may have exacerbated distrust,

03:26:24.860 --> 03:26:26.820
[Guest]: may have exacerbated ethnic division.

03:26:26.820 --> 03:26:30.860
[Guest]: So if we look at West Africa today, we see that ethnic divisions and stratification are

03:26:30.860 --> 03:26:34.220
[Guest]: especially politicised in West Africa.

03:26:34.220 --> 03:26:38.580
[Guest]: Now why might that be correlated with this patriarchal governance?

03:26:38.580 --> 03:26:44.340
[Guest]: My suggestion is that, well, colonial borders were imposed arbitrarily across ethnic groups.

03:26:44.340 --> 03:26:46.940
[Guest]: So you've got a bunch of ethnic groups grouped together.

03:26:46.940 --> 03:26:51.580
[Guest]: And because of that history of slave raiding, we have this culture of distrust and animosity

03:26:51.580 --> 03:26:53.420
[Guest]: and ethnic divisions.

03:26:53.420 --> 03:27:00.740
[Guest]: So what I think has happened is that if your ethnic identity is primary, you may prefer

03:27:00.740 --> 03:27:03.180
[Guest]: to be represented by someone from your group.

03:27:03.180 --> 03:27:05.220
[Guest]: A Yoruba wants a Yoruba leader.

03:27:05.220 --> 03:27:09.420
[Guest]: It doesn't matter for a Yoruba, hey, here's a woman and she's Hausa, but that's Hausa,

03:27:09.420 --> 03:27:13.900
[Guest]: that's Northern Nigeria, that's a different religion, that's a different ethnicity.

03:27:13.900 --> 03:27:20.940
[Guest]: So I think where ethnicity is primary, that may weaken the strong, sustained nationwide

03:27:20.940 --> 03:27:28.060
[Guest]: feminist mobilisation that is necessary for strong campaigns for women's political representation.

03:27:28.060 --> 03:27:33.260
[Guest]: So as a result of that, as a result of arbitrary colonial borders and also slave raiding, I

03:27:33.260 --> 03:27:38.260
[Guest]: think that's why West Africa and especially the Gulf of Guinea is so patriarchal.

03:27:38.260 --> 03:27:44.380
[Guest]: Now, for the rest of Africa, I think the impact of colonialism would have been more indirect.

03:27:44.380 --> 03:27:50.220
[Guest]: So to the extent that colonialism exacerbated corruption, to the extent that colonialism

03:27:50.220 --> 03:27:56.100
[Guest]: exacerbated authoritarianism or stunted development, all that stuff is bad for gender equality.

03:27:56.100 --> 03:27:58.460
[Guest]: But I don't think the mechanism was that.

03:27:58.460 --> 03:28:03.460
[Guest]: So lots of gender scholars think that the mechanism is the male bias in colonial institutions,

03:28:03.460 --> 03:28:07.500
[Guest]: like patriarchal colonisers go in there spreading their ideologies.

03:28:07.500 --> 03:28:08.820
[Guest]: I don't think that's it.

03:28:08.820 --> 03:28:10.980
[Guest]: I think it's slightly different mechanisms.

03:28:10.980 --> 03:28:11.980
[Guest]: Yeah.

03:28:11.980 --> 03:28:12.980
[Guest]: So, right.

03:28:12.980 --> 03:28:14.980
[Guest]: So that was the feminist activism case.

03:28:14.980 --> 03:28:18.260
[Guest]: So I think we've pretty much covered most regions.

03:28:18.260 --> 03:28:19.260
[Guest]: Yeah.

03:28:19.260 --> 03:28:25.220
[Guest]: So the big story, the three main drivers of patriarchy are the plough, nomadic pastoralism

03:28:25.220 --> 03:28:27.340
[Guest]: and male dominated religions.

03:28:27.340 --> 03:28:31.900
[Guest]: But their spread, that cultural evolution is mediated by geography.

03:28:31.900 --> 03:28:39.540
[Guest]: And then it's and that that story explains why some cultures and why in some cultures

03:28:39.540 --> 03:28:42.420
[Guest]: male honour is contingent upon female chastity.

03:28:42.420 --> 03:28:47.580
[Guest]: And that explains why in some places like South Asia, the Middle East and North Africa,

03:28:47.580 --> 03:28:51.980
[Guest]: male earnings need to be sufficiently high to compensate for that loss of male honour.

03:28:51.980 --> 03:28:55.740
[Guest]: And if the earnings remain low, if you have a situation of jobless growth or indeed no

03:28:55.740 --> 03:29:01.540
[Guest]: growth at all, then women remain trapped in their homes, dependent on patriarchal guardians,

03:29:01.540 --> 03:29:05.660
[Guest]: lacking the exposure or friendships to challenge some of those patriarchal ideologies.

03:29:05.660 --> 03:29:09.180
[Unknown]: So that I think is the story of the great gender divergence.

03:29:09.180 --> 03:29:12.020
[Amit Varma]: Oh, I feel like you just gave me such a masterclass.

03:29:12.020 --> 03:29:13.180
[Amit Varma]: So thank you for that.

03:29:13.180 --> 03:29:17.620
[Amit Varma]: And by the way, on the point of the gender gap between chess players, I think today the

03:29:17.620 --> 03:29:21.260
[Amit Varma]: countries where the gender gap is the least is perhaps China.

03:29:21.260 --> 03:29:26.100
[Amit Varma]: But having said that, you know, the former Soviet countries are closed, India is closed.

03:29:26.100 --> 03:29:31.780
[Amit Varma]: And there are so few women who are above 2600 that it's really, you know, it's hard to tell

03:29:31.780 --> 03:29:33.340
[Amit Varma]: between these.

03:29:33.340 --> 03:29:37.420
[Amit Varma]: But certainly the gender gap has reduced in all of these places.

03:29:37.420 --> 03:29:42.100
[Amit Varma]: And I'd say overall, and by the way, we had a coffee break just before this, and I'm sure

03:29:42.100 --> 03:29:46.260
[Amit Varma]: you know this, but the coffee break happened because of a woman's labor movement.

03:29:46.260 --> 03:29:47.260
[Amit Varma]: Are you aware of this?

03:29:47.260 --> 03:29:48.260
[Amit Varma]: Tell me.

03:29:48.260 --> 03:29:50.420
[Amit Varma]: So there's a video by Michael Pollan on this.

03:29:50.420 --> 03:29:53.540
[Amit Varma]: I think he came on the Joe Rogan show, and it's about coffee.

03:29:53.540 --> 03:29:55.580
[Amit Varma]: And I'll share that in the show notes.

03:29:55.580 --> 03:30:00.860
[Amit Varma]: And Pollan's essential point was that both the Enlightenment and the Industrial Revolution,

03:30:00.860 --> 03:30:06.180
[Amit Varma]: as per him, were enabled by coffee, because caffeine helped people work longer hours and

03:30:06.180 --> 03:30:07.180
[Amit Varma]: better.

03:30:07.180 --> 03:30:11.820
[Amit Varma]: So what happened, and I think this was perhaps in the 1860s or 1870s, whatever, I'm sure

03:30:11.820 --> 03:30:15.700
[Amit Varma]: I'll get the details wrong, but the link is in the show notes, you can see it there, is

03:30:15.700 --> 03:30:19.820
[Amit Varma]: that in that second half of the 19th century, there were factories which were replacing

03:30:19.820 --> 03:30:24.100
[Amit Varma]: male workers with female workers, because the female workers were more diligent and

03:30:24.100 --> 03:30:27.460
[Amit Varma]: could focus on the work and so on and so forth, no surprise there.

03:30:27.460 --> 03:30:31.220
[Amit Varma]: But even they would run out of energy towards the middle of the day.

03:30:31.220 --> 03:30:37.100
[Amit Varma]: So then the female workers got together and they went on strike, and their union or whatever

03:30:37.100 --> 03:30:41.900
[Amit Varma]: it was, they had exactly one demand, and that demand was for a coffee break, because they

03:30:41.900 --> 03:30:46.580
[Amit Varma]: felt correctly, as it turned out, that coffee would give them energy and they would be able

03:30:46.580 --> 03:30:49.260
[Amit Varma]: to work longer hours and therefore make more money.

03:30:49.260 --> 03:30:51.500
[Amit Varma]: So yeah, so that's where the coffee break comes.

03:30:51.500 --> 03:30:56.140
[Amit Varma]: So every man who ever takes a coffee break, you owe it to a woman.

03:30:56.140 --> 03:31:03.180
[Amit Varma]: So the interesting part of this entire history that you've shared, and you've obviously,

03:31:03.180 --> 03:31:09.260
[Amit Varma]: you know, to make it fittable into this podcast, you've also sort of painted broad strokes.

03:31:09.260 --> 03:31:13.420
[Amit Varma]: If you wanted to, I'm sure you could, you know, break up the continents into countries

03:31:13.420 --> 03:31:14.420
[Amit Varma]: and into regions and so on.

03:31:14.420 --> 03:31:18.460
[Guest]: Yeah, so for example, if you wanted to, I could explain the difference between the USA

03:31:18.460 --> 03:31:22.660
[Guest]: and Europe, for example, and the US's recent restrictions on abortion.

03:31:22.660 --> 03:31:23.660
[Guest]: That's one thing we could discuss.

03:31:23.660 --> 03:31:25.660
[Amit Varma]: You can pick any country and I can talk about it really.

03:31:25.660 --> 03:31:31.940
[Amit Varma]: We'll come to the US, but my larger question first was that, while we can look at the different

03:31:31.940 --> 03:31:37.300
[Amit Varma]: ways in which, you know, the divergence has taken place, we see a host of reasons that

03:31:37.300 --> 03:31:38.820
[Amit Varma]: are deeply complicated.

03:31:38.820 --> 03:31:43.060
[Amit Varma]: But when we speak about coming out of it, about women getting empowered, it seems that

03:31:43.060 --> 03:31:45.180
[Amit Varma]: there the story is fairly simple.

03:31:45.180 --> 03:31:47.700
[Amit Varma]: Economic growth is a big part of the job creating.

03:31:47.700 --> 03:31:51.220
[Amit Varma]: Job creating economic growth is a big part of the solution and structural transformations

03:31:51.220 --> 03:31:55.340
[Amit Varma]: are a big part of the solution in terms of getting rid of some of these incentives towards

03:31:55.340 --> 03:31:59.480
[Amit Varma]: female seclusion, as you point out, which are strong in some places and not so strong

03:31:59.480 --> 03:32:00.480
[Amit Varma]: in others.

03:32:00.480 --> 03:32:07.140
[Amit Varma]: So broadly, tell me about, you know, if we look at job creating economic growth and the

03:32:07.140 --> 03:32:12.420
[Amit Varma]: social changes that lead to a change of incentives, therefore being the way out of this for everybody,

03:32:12.420 --> 03:32:16.300
[Amit Varma]: then it seems to me that it's a cause for great hope that sooner or later it will happen.

03:32:16.300 --> 03:32:20.140
[Amit Varma]: Now, I know at the start of this episode, you said that no, no, you know, there is climate

03:32:20.140 --> 03:32:25.900
[Amit Varma]: change and there is automation and there are authoritarian dictatorships and all those

03:32:25.900 --> 03:32:27.140
[Amit Varma]: worries are there.

03:32:27.140 --> 03:32:33.980
[Amit Varma]: But assuming we get past those worries and there is, you know, growth, then, you know,

03:32:33.980 --> 03:32:37.340
[Amit Varma]: even if we regressed in different ways, we can progress in the same ways.

03:32:37.340 --> 03:32:38.340
[Unknown]: What are your thoughts?

03:32:38.340 --> 03:32:39.340
[Unknown]: Yes.

03:32:39.340 --> 03:32:43.020
[Unknown]: So my model is, if there's job creating economic growth, then we should anticipate rising female

03:32:43.020 --> 03:32:44.020
[Unknown]: labor force participation.

03:32:44.020 --> 03:32:45.020
[Unknown]: Yes.

03:32:45.020 --> 03:32:48.420
[Amit Varma]: That's, that's the, it's as simple as that.

03:32:48.420 --> 03:32:49.420
[Unknown]: Yes.

03:32:49.420 --> 03:32:50.420
[Amit Varma]: Okay.

03:32:50.420 --> 03:32:51.420
[Amit Varma]: Let's talk about the US now.

03:32:51.420 --> 03:32:52.420
[Amit Varma]: Right.

03:32:52.420 --> 03:32:53.420
[Amit Varma]: Why is the US going backwards?

03:32:53.420 --> 03:32:54.420
[Amit Varma]: Why don't women own their own bodies anymore?

03:32:54.420 --> 03:33:04.620
[Guest]: Okay, so I think my, so the US, so it was persecuted religious minorities who fled Europe

03:33:04.620 --> 03:33:06.280
[Guest]: and went to the USA.

03:33:06.280 --> 03:33:10.540
[Guest]: So people for whom religion was so important that they would travel across a massive ocean

03:33:10.540 --> 03:33:12.740
[Guest]: at a time of incredible proscurity.

03:33:12.740 --> 03:33:15.220
[Guest]: Those are the people who landed up in the USA.

03:33:15.220 --> 03:33:19.180
[Guest]: And so those people then socialized their children to care much more about religion.

03:33:19.180 --> 03:33:23.380
[Guest]: And we also know that the USA had a sort of more open marketplace for different religions

03:33:23.380 --> 03:33:25.340
[Guest]: that led to competition, that led to innovation.

03:33:25.340 --> 03:33:29.220
[Guest]: So, you know, churches are cultivating and attracting more members.

03:33:29.220 --> 03:33:35.340
[Guest]: So one is we see greater religiosity and that's associated with far higher support for abortion

03:33:35.340 --> 03:33:36.700
[Guest]: restrictions.

03:33:36.700 --> 03:33:44.620
[Guest]: On top of that, the US is, another patriarchal aspect, patriarchal also varies by class within

03:33:44.620 --> 03:33:46.060
[Guest]: the USA.

03:33:46.060 --> 03:33:53.580
[Guest]: So because of the history of enslaving African Americans, that ethnic diversity appears to

03:33:53.580 --> 03:33:57.020
[Guest]: be associated with lower contributions to public goods.

03:33:57.020 --> 03:34:01.160
[Guest]: And here I'm drawing on a paper by Bill Easterly and others, and they find that in ethnically

03:34:01.160 --> 03:34:05.780
[Guest]: diverse places, people don't, people may not be as likely to associate with the other,

03:34:05.780 --> 03:34:08.220
[Guest]: not wanting to share or pool resources.

03:34:08.220 --> 03:34:12.840
[Guest]: So in that context, that might explain why Americans may be privately wealthy, but don't

03:34:12.840 --> 03:34:16.260
[Guest]: have great public goods and don't have great public infrastructure.

03:34:16.260 --> 03:34:22.620
[Guest]: And so that means that we see weaker protections and support for working for families and working

03:34:22.620 --> 03:34:28.260
[Guest]: class women struggle to get the support they need to manage work and employment.

03:34:28.260 --> 03:34:32.060
[Guest]: So we see large gender wage gaps for working class women.

03:34:32.060 --> 03:34:36.380
[Guest]: That said, in a more liberalized economy, we tend to see women doing better in managerial

03:34:36.380 --> 03:34:37.380
[Guest]: roles.

03:34:37.380 --> 03:34:40.780
[Guest]: So in the US, it's the elite professional women who are thriving in a more liberalized

03:34:40.780 --> 03:34:41.780
[Guest]: environment.

03:34:41.780 --> 03:34:48.700
[Guest]: So the gender, the USA also suffers from the majoritarian first post, the post system,

03:34:48.700 --> 03:34:54.740
[Guest]: which India also shares now that and is inherited by the colonial English.

03:34:54.740 --> 03:34:58.640
[Guest]: And that is associated with lower rates of women's political representation.

03:34:58.640 --> 03:35:03.580
[Guest]: So that I think is another thing Indians can blame the UK for in terms of colonialism,

03:35:03.580 --> 03:35:09.020
[Guest]: that had they adopted proportional representation by much of continental Europe and the Scandinavians,

03:35:09.020 --> 03:35:11.820
[Guest]: then we'd expect higher rates of female political representation.

03:35:11.820 --> 03:35:15.780
[Guest]: And when women are in positions of power, they're more able to assert and push for more

03:35:15.780 --> 03:35:17.300
[Guest]: gender equal governance.

03:35:17.300 --> 03:35:22.900
[Guest]: The other thing that I wanted to discuss in relation to India is fear of crime.

03:35:22.900 --> 03:35:24.780
[Amit Varma]: Should we talk about that?

03:35:24.780 --> 03:35:25.780
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, totally.

03:35:25.780 --> 03:35:26.780
[Amit Varma]: Okay.

03:35:26.780 --> 03:35:31.020
[Amit Varma]: But about the US, my specific question was, why does it seem like we're going backwards

03:35:31.020 --> 03:35:32.020
[Amit Varma]: from 20 years ago?

03:35:32.020 --> 03:35:37.560
[Amit Varma]: So I'm not looking at the broad swath of history and how, you know, the original immigrants

03:35:37.560 --> 03:35:39.540
[Unknown]: got there.

03:35:39.540 --> 03:35:45.620
[Guest]: So I think this is, if you look at the data, there has been this persistent religiosity

03:35:45.620 --> 03:35:50.340
[Guest]: in some communities and where that religiosity is higher, then we see the strong support

03:35:50.340 --> 03:35:51.340
[Guest]: for abortion.

03:35:51.340 --> 03:35:56.500
[Guest]: We also see the rise of authoritarianism.

03:35:56.500 --> 03:36:01.980
[Guest]: So where Republicans feel that they are under threat, they've increasingly restricted people's

03:36:01.980 --> 03:36:08.020
[Guest]: right to vote, increasingly punishing and restricting people of colour.

03:36:08.020 --> 03:36:12.300
[Guest]: So that's the rise of authoritarianism to entrench, entrench their dominance.

03:36:12.300 --> 03:36:14.040
[Guest]: There's a great book called Entrenchment.

03:36:14.040 --> 03:36:19.140
[Guest]: So yes, it's part of that counter struggle to entrench the religious right.

03:36:19.140 --> 03:36:20.140
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely.

03:36:20.140 --> 03:36:24.460
[Guest]: Let's go back to India and talk about the fear of crime.

03:36:24.460 --> 03:36:25.460
[Guest]: Okay.

03:36:25.460 --> 03:36:26.460
[Guest]: Right.

03:36:26.460 --> 03:36:30.100
[Guest]: So we've agreed that job creating economic growth is incredibly important for gender

03:36:30.100 --> 03:36:39.060
[Guest]: equality, equally important is public safety for women and ending male impunity for violence,

03:36:39.060 --> 03:36:40.820
[Guest]: assault and harassment.

03:36:40.820 --> 03:36:44.700
[Guest]: And I explicitly want to centre on ending men's impunity rather than women's safety

03:36:44.700 --> 03:36:49.220
[Guest]: because it's absolutely about ending men's impunity for violence.

03:36:49.220 --> 03:36:55.020
[Guest]: And this, this works, I think, in four ways that restrict women's freedoms and restrict

03:36:55.020 --> 03:36:56.800
[Guest]: women's movements.

03:36:56.800 --> 03:37:02.820
[Guest]: So one is fear of crime leads to tighter restrictions on women's mobility.

03:37:02.820 --> 03:37:08.660
[Guest]: So when families are concerned that women may be assaulted or it's unsafe, they restrict

03:37:08.660 --> 03:37:11.180
[Guest]: their girls from going out.

03:37:11.180 --> 03:37:14.260
[Guest]: And I've had numerous interviews about this.

03:37:14.260 --> 03:37:18.980
[Guest]: And there's also a bunch of papers about when women fear or anticipate crime, they choose

03:37:18.980 --> 03:37:22.540
[Guest]: worse colleges that affects their employment options.

03:37:22.540 --> 03:37:26.060
[Guest]: And let me also stress, there's a religious element to this.

03:37:26.060 --> 03:37:32.940
[Guest]: So after the horrific riots in Gujarat, many Muslim women feared violence and so restricted

03:37:32.940 --> 03:37:37.540
[Guest]: themselves to Muslim ghettos because they were so afraid.

03:37:37.540 --> 03:37:43.820
[Guest]: So that inter-religious violence and intimidation actually thwarts gender equality because women

03:37:43.820 --> 03:37:49.960
[Guest]: choose inferior, less good colleges and worse than their labour market options because they're

03:37:49.960 --> 03:37:51.820
[Guest]: so fearful of violence.

03:37:51.820 --> 03:37:55.900
[Guest]: So the inter-religious violence is absolutely going to suppress female labour force participation

03:37:55.900 --> 03:37:57.640
[Guest]: in Muslim communities.

03:37:57.640 --> 03:37:58.640
[Guest]: So I wanted to stress that.

03:37:58.640 --> 03:38:00.900
[Guest]: So female safety is really important there.

03:38:00.900 --> 03:38:07.140
[Guest]: So the fear of violence and also media reports of violence may fuel these concerns about

03:38:07.140 --> 03:38:09.040
[Guest]: the city is unsafe.

03:38:09.040 --> 03:38:15.660
[Guest]: So for example, I interviewed a woman recently, she has a job in Delhi, but her mother drives

03:38:15.660 --> 03:38:19.660
[Guest]: her to and from work because she doesn't think the stations are safe.

03:38:19.660 --> 03:38:25.700
[Guest]: Now this is also this fear of crime is exacerbated by traditions of female seclusion.

03:38:25.700 --> 03:38:29.420
[Guest]: So the more that women are kept closely to the home, the more that their freedoms are

03:38:29.420 --> 03:38:34.220
[Guest]: restricted, the less they gain the capacity to independently navigate and explore the

03:38:34.220 --> 03:38:38.580
[Guest]: cities for themselves and the more their families continue to be protective because they do

03:38:38.580 --> 03:38:42.860
[Guest]: not see women being competent in exploring their cities for themselves.

03:38:42.860 --> 03:38:45.540
[Guest]: And the more that women themselves may be fearful.

03:38:45.540 --> 03:38:50.780
[Guest]: And here's one hypothesis that other researchers might test and it's come up in my own interviews.

03:38:50.780 --> 03:38:57.900
[Guest]: I was talking to a woman from Bangalore and she was 17 at the time of the 2012 horrific

03:38:57.900 --> 03:38:59.340
[Guest]: gang rape in Delhi.

03:38:59.340 --> 03:39:03.780
[Guest]: And at that time she did not want to come to Delhi because she perceived Delhi as violent.

03:39:03.780 --> 03:39:07.780
[Guest]: So she chose to study in Bangalore because of her fear of crime.

03:39:07.780 --> 03:39:12.660
[Guest]: And I think here's one area whereby, I mean, if you read any Indian newspaper at least

03:39:12.660 --> 03:39:19.420
[Guest]: once a week, you'll be continually reading stories about horrific gang rapes, violence.

03:39:19.420 --> 03:39:24.580
[Guest]: And I think that's partly a consequence of a huge population.

03:39:24.580 --> 03:39:31.540
[Guest]: In a country of 1.3 billion, you're bound to hear something about horrific violence.

03:39:31.540 --> 03:39:34.020
[Guest]: So it's partly about objective dangers.

03:39:34.020 --> 03:39:38.720
[Guest]: But also the media is continually perpetrating this idea that streets are unsafe.

03:39:38.720 --> 03:39:42.860
[Guest]: And also the way these stories are reported, and you're a journalist, so you know this

03:39:42.860 --> 03:39:47.860
[Guest]: better than me, but often the emphasis on the horrific violence against women, the images

03:39:47.860 --> 03:39:56.260
[Guest]: themselves often are cartoons or sort of animations visualizing gang rape.

03:39:56.260 --> 03:39:59.140
[Guest]: And often the perpetrator is still on the loose.

03:39:59.140 --> 03:40:04.900
[Guest]: The story is not about this man has been imprisoned, this man has been held to account, this man

03:40:04.900 --> 03:40:06.540
[Guest]: is now behind bars.

03:40:06.540 --> 03:40:11.980
[Guest]: The story is always there are these horrific things happening in your neighborhood.

03:40:11.980 --> 03:40:16.700
[Guest]: And so I think that itself may be inculcating fear among women.

03:40:16.700 --> 03:40:23.180
[Guest]: So it's one, the fear of crime, exacerbated by this media reporting, and the more that

03:40:23.180 --> 03:40:26.700
[Guest]: families fear that, the more they restrict women, the more that women never gain those

03:40:26.700 --> 03:40:27.700
[Guest]: opportunities.

03:40:27.700 --> 03:40:31.020
[Guest]: And we know those opportunities for independent mobility are so important.

03:40:31.020 --> 03:40:37.460
[Guest]: So in my interviews here in India, when I talk to entrepreneurial go-getting independent

03:40:37.460 --> 03:40:44.420
[Guest]: women, the way they've developed their autonomy and confidence is through iterative exploration.

03:40:44.420 --> 03:40:48.740
[Guest]: You know, the more that women travel independently, the more they explore different areas, they

03:40:48.740 --> 03:40:49.940
[Guest]: realize they can do it myself.

03:40:49.940 --> 03:40:53.660
[Guest]: You know, Indian women's story is just the same story that I told you, right?

03:40:53.660 --> 03:40:57.300
[Guest]: It's about trying stuff out, seeing you can do it and gaining confidence and parents gaining

03:40:57.300 --> 03:40:58.540
[Guest]: confidence in you.

03:40:58.540 --> 03:41:02.300
[Guest]: And let me draw a comparison with a woman I interviewed in Marrakesh.

03:41:02.300 --> 03:41:06.940
[Guest]: Her family was initially reluctant to her about her working in tourism because they

03:41:06.940 --> 03:41:10.460
[Guest]: perceived this is unsafe for women because she had to deal with so many different men.

03:41:10.460 --> 03:41:13.480
[Guest]: But she persuaded her father and she said, you know, let me try this out.

03:41:13.480 --> 03:41:17.060
[Guest]: And her father agreed and she showed him that she could do it.

03:41:17.060 --> 03:41:19.220
[Guest]: She showed him that she could independently navigate.

03:41:19.220 --> 03:41:21.920
[Guest]: So she set up a shop selling argan oil.

03:41:21.920 --> 03:41:27.780
[Guest]: She set up a tour guide operation and her father saw that she could handle herself independently.

03:41:27.780 --> 03:41:32.980
[Guest]: And he increasingly granted her more and more freedoms because he saw that she could manage.

03:41:32.980 --> 03:41:34.780
[Guest]: So we do see this positive feedback loop.

03:41:34.780 --> 03:41:40.820
[Guest]: The more the parents loosen those restrictions, the more they gain confidence in women's skills

03:41:40.820 --> 03:41:42.460
[Guest]: to navigate alone.

03:41:42.460 --> 03:41:45.860
[Guest]: So it's a matter of being shifting between two equilibrium.

03:41:45.860 --> 03:41:49.940
[Guest]: Added to this, I think there are two more important factors in how fear of crime comes

03:41:49.940 --> 03:41:50.940
[Guest]: out.

03:41:50.940 --> 03:41:52.780
[Guest]: It's not just about fear of crime.

03:41:52.780 --> 03:41:58.700
[Guest]: It's the idea that if a sexual assault were to happen, it would be the absolute worst

03:41:58.700 --> 03:42:00.300
[Guest]: thing in the world.

03:42:00.300 --> 03:42:01.940
[Guest]: Her life would be over.

03:42:01.940 --> 03:42:07.980
[Guest]: And this plays out both in terms of internalised ideologies of shame and the woman feeling

03:42:07.980 --> 03:42:12.080
[Guest]: horrific and that this is the worst thing ever because purity is so important.

03:42:12.080 --> 03:42:14.660
[Guest]: And also, what will others think?

03:42:14.660 --> 03:42:17.540
[Guest]: And the idea that, you know, what was she wearing, the blame on the victim, the idea

03:42:17.540 --> 03:42:18.540
[Guest]: that she is loose.

03:42:18.540 --> 03:42:21.460
[Guest]: And then the entire family's name could be jeopardised.

03:42:21.460 --> 03:42:23.580
[Guest]: Her sisters could be seen as unmarriable.

03:42:23.580 --> 03:42:24.860
[Guest]: So I think it's four mechanisms.

03:42:24.860 --> 03:42:26.260
[Guest]: One, it's fear of crime.

03:42:26.260 --> 03:42:30.420
[Guest]: Two, it's the belief that women are incapable of navigating alone.

03:42:30.420 --> 03:42:33.660
[Guest]: And that's reinforced and that follows a history of seclusion.

03:42:33.660 --> 03:42:40.460
[Guest]: Three, it's the idea that sexual assault is a fate worse than death.

03:42:40.460 --> 03:42:43.060
[Guest]: And four, it's the concern that what will other people think?

03:42:43.060 --> 03:42:47.660
[Guest]: And the way that three and four work, or the way that they can be overturned, is absolutely

03:42:47.660 --> 03:42:49.420
[Guest]: through feminist activism.

03:42:49.420 --> 03:42:52.340
[Guest]: Feminist activism to challenge ideologies of shame.

03:42:52.340 --> 03:42:54.180
[Guest]: Feminist ideologies to...

03:42:54.180 --> 03:42:59.380
[Guest]: And because the more that women speak out, you know, because you have to counter the

03:42:59.380 --> 03:43:03.040
[Guest]: shame, you have to counter the sexual, the social policing in order for women to even

03:43:03.040 --> 03:43:04.040
[Guest]: come forward.

03:43:04.040 --> 03:43:05.820
[Guest]: So again, to give another example from JNU.

03:43:05.820 --> 03:43:13.020
[Guest]: So JNU has these boards against sexual harassment with representation from NGOs and students.

03:43:13.020 --> 03:43:18.140
[Guest]: But if women fear social condemnation from their own communities, they may not even report

03:43:18.140 --> 03:43:19.140
[Guest]: sexual harassment.

03:43:19.140 --> 03:43:25.380
[Guest]: You know, if you think your parents will be furious from you having any kind of altercation

03:43:25.380 --> 03:43:28.220
[Guest]: or interaction with men, then you might not want to press a claim.

03:43:28.220 --> 03:43:32.100
[Guest]: So no matter how good that institution is, women might not want to become public.

03:43:32.100 --> 03:43:34.060
[Guest]: I mean, the same thing happened in Japan.

03:43:34.060 --> 03:43:38.820
[Guest]: Japan had no Me Too movement because all the women, most, the vast majority of women remained

03:43:38.820 --> 03:43:41.980
[Guest]: too ashamed, too fearful to come out.

03:43:41.980 --> 03:43:45.620
[Guest]: Let me add a further important point about fear of crime.

03:43:45.620 --> 03:43:52.460
[Guest]: If Muslim women anticipate violence from Hindu men, like horrific rapes, and if the state

03:43:52.460 --> 03:43:57.700
[Guest]: allows male impunity for that violence, as we've recently seen, then Muslim women may

03:43:57.700 --> 03:44:02.660
[Guest]: be increasingly fearful, remaining increasingly close to their own communities, not seizing

03:44:02.660 --> 03:44:09.820
[Guest]: educational or employment opportunities, and then remaining more dependent on patriarchal

03:44:09.820 --> 03:44:10.820
[Guest]: guardians.

03:44:10.820 --> 03:44:17.380
[Guest]: So, yeah, the best thing, so if the government really wants to support gender equality in

03:44:17.380 --> 03:44:21.700
[Guest]: Muslim communities, then the main drivers are absolutely the same universally, is job

03:44:21.700 --> 03:44:27.100
[Guest]: creating economic growth, enabling communities to flourish, to seize economic opportunities,

03:44:27.100 --> 03:44:32.140
[Guest]: to prosper, and also to ensure families of safety, so that women can seize these economic

03:44:32.140 --> 03:44:33.140
[Guest]: opportunities.

03:44:33.140 --> 03:44:39.020
[Amit Varma]: A lot of great points, and I'm especially struck by the tragic vicious cycle that women

03:44:39.020 --> 03:44:43.100
[Amit Varma]: can get trapped in, where they feel that, hey, you know, it's not safe outside because

03:44:43.100 --> 03:44:46.300
[Amit Varma]: there's so much news of crimes, and therefore they don't go out, and because they don't

03:44:46.300 --> 03:44:51.180
[Amit Varma]: go out, they don't develop the capacity to deal with whatever might be out there, nor

03:44:51.180 --> 03:44:55.500
[Amit Varma]: the recognition that perhaps what is out there is not quite as bad as the news makes it out

03:44:55.500 --> 03:44:59.900
[Amit Varma]: to be, and they just get stuck in that equilibrium, as you pointed out.

03:44:59.900 --> 03:45:03.540
[Amit Varma]: And also there is, you know, when you speak of the media, I mean, that's again a dilemma,

03:45:03.540 --> 03:45:04.540
[Amit Varma]: right?

03:45:04.540 --> 03:45:07.820
[Amit Varma]: Because as Steven Pinker has put it, we have a bias for bad news, right?

03:45:07.820 --> 03:45:12.620
[Amit Varma]: Man bites dog is always news, dog licks man isn't news, you know, some horrific thing

03:45:12.620 --> 03:45:16.740
[Amit Varma]: happened to a woman somewhere is news, and at the same time, you know, millions of women

03:45:16.740 --> 03:45:21.260
[Amit Varma]: travel to and from office to home and nothing happened, that's obviously not news.

03:45:21.260 --> 03:45:28.420
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, I think it's also a responsibility of journalists to report this

03:45:28.420 --> 03:45:29.420
[Amit Varma]: kind of news.

03:45:29.420 --> 03:45:32.140
[Amit Varma]: And that's why the outrage around Nirbhaya happened.

03:45:32.140 --> 03:45:34.060
[Amit Varma]: That's why the laws got changed.

03:45:34.060 --> 03:45:37.980
[Amit Varma]: That's why there was a flip to the feminist movement around that time, because the media

03:45:37.980 --> 03:45:40.540
[Amit Varma]: made a big deal out of it.

03:45:40.540 --> 03:45:42.060
[Amit Varma]: So you know, so that is a dilemma.

03:45:42.060 --> 03:45:49.780
[Amit Varma]: I think in this particular case, while I recognize the role that this kind of reporting can make

03:45:49.780 --> 03:45:54.380
[Amit Varma]: in giving people the impression that the world is more violent than it actually is, I still

03:45:54.380 --> 03:45:58.660
[Amit Varma]: think this kind of reporting is important, because, hey, you know, that's, that's a journalist

03:45:58.660 --> 03:46:01.020
[Amit Varma]: job, you have to point out what's wrong with the world.

03:46:01.020 --> 03:46:05.980
[Amit Varma]: So I guess that's just one of those dilemmas in this kind of...

03:46:05.980 --> 03:46:09.340
[Guest]: Yes, that's a great point.

03:46:09.340 --> 03:46:12.840
[Guest]: Let me caveat, I don't want to give the impression that I think fear of crime is entirely in

03:46:12.840 --> 03:46:13.840
[Guest]: people's own minds.

03:46:13.840 --> 03:46:19.660
[Guest]: What I want to say is how it leads to heightened restrictions on women, and then fewer women

03:46:19.660 --> 03:46:23.220
[Guest]: in the streets, then those streets feel increasingly unsafe.

03:46:23.220 --> 03:46:26.340
[Guest]: So if you're the only woman in the street, then you feel much more frightened, then you're

03:46:26.340 --> 03:46:30.780
[Guest]: much more afraid, because you don't have that solidarity, and that support from other women.

03:46:30.780 --> 03:46:37.020
[Guest]: Now, what's the best way, and I also, you know, there are also cases, and I want to

03:46:37.020 --> 03:46:43.940
[Guest]: also give another example of why silence is, can be so, can trap people.

03:46:43.940 --> 03:46:48.700
[Guest]: So for example, I was talking to one woman who grew up in Mumbai, and she was telling

03:46:48.700 --> 03:46:55.660
[Guest]: me that very frequently, on the bus to school, when she was a schoolgirl, when those crowded

03:46:55.660 --> 03:46:59.220
[Guest]: buses she was getting groped by much older men.

03:46:59.220 --> 03:47:04.340
[Guest]: So this is absolutely a real phenomenon, and in many ways, it'll be underreported.

03:47:04.340 --> 03:47:08.060
[Guest]: You know, most victims of sexual assault do not tell anyone.

03:47:08.060 --> 03:47:12.740
[Guest]: So sexual crimes are absolutely going to be underreported.

03:47:12.740 --> 03:47:14.540
[Guest]: And so I'm not saying they're overreported.

03:47:14.540 --> 03:47:16.420
[Guest]: My point is that there's this daily deluge.

03:47:16.420 --> 03:47:26.700
[Guest]: Now the question is, what, if we want to challenge impunity for male violence, what's the most

03:47:26.700 --> 03:47:29.020
[Guest]: effective way of doing that?

03:47:29.020 --> 03:47:36.740
[Guest]: Now you're totally right, that outrage around the 2012, 2012 attacks did lead to changes

03:47:36.740 --> 03:47:44.620
[Guest]: in legislation, but it's not like fear of crime has radically reduced.

03:47:44.620 --> 03:47:53.060
[Guest]: So the legislation was changed, yes, but given relatively weak state capacity and enforcement,

03:47:53.060 --> 03:47:57.380
[Guest]: that hasn't actually made people perceive the streets as any safer, at least that's

03:47:57.380 --> 03:47:59.300
[Guest]: not my impression.

03:47:59.300 --> 03:48:02.300
[Guest]: And so I would be careful of celebrating that victory in itself.

03:48:02.300 --> 03:48:05.660
[Guest]: What I think is much more important is sustained feminist activism.

03:48:05.660 --> 03:48:10.420
[Guest]: So feminist activism is important, but not in itself, because some of the women I interview

03:48:10.420 --> 03:48:13.820
[Guest]: and also the men, they say, yes, we protested, but then nothing happened.

03:48:13.820 --> 03:48:15.620
[Guest]: Delhi is still very unsafe.

03:48:15.620 --> 03:48:19.740
[Guest]: And that itself can be dangerous because then people can become trapped in this despondency

03:48:19.740 --> 03:48:20.740
[Guest]: trap.

03:48:20.740 --> 03:48:25.420
[Guest]: That what's the, you know, to change the world, you need to have a sense of collective self-efficacy

03:48:25.420 --> 03:48:29.900
[Guest]: that if you invest in mobilisation, if you continually march and mobilise, then the state

03:48:29.900 --> 03:48:34.340
[Guest]: will respond and enact better enforcement, better policing.

03:48:34.340 --> 03:48:39.160
[Guest]: And for some, they don't think that's happened and they can even become disheartened.

03:48:39.160 --> 03:48:43.540
[Guest]: So the question is what can cultivate relentless mobilisation?

03:48:43.540 --> 03:48:49.940
[Guest]: And there, I would actually say what's really important is that seeing that mobilisation

03:48:49.940 --> 03:48:54.580
[Guest]: results in better law enforcement and actually ends impunity for male violence.

03:48:54.580 --> 03:48:57.580
[Guest]: And Gabby Crooks Wisner has done great work on this in Rajasthan.

03:48:57.580 --> 03:49:03.020
[Guest]: So, for example, she shows that people in rural Rajasthan are much more likely to mobilise

03:49:03.020 --> 03:49:07.860
[Guest]: for public goods when they see and believe that the state will respond to their petitions.

03:49:07.860 --> 03:49:10.600
[Guest]: And the same is true for domestic, for violence.

03:49:10.600 --> 03:49:15.580
[Guest]: So I think it's that you can create a greater, a stronger positive feedback loop, but showing

03:49:15.580 --> 03:49:21.340
[Guest]: that feminist activism leads to greater government responsiveness, because then that can in itself

03:49:21.340 --> 03:49:23.340
[Guest]: encourage more feminist activism.

03:49:23.340 --> 03:49:29.180
[Guest]: So I think it's showing that activism works and results in impunity for male violence.

03:49:29.180 --> 03:49:35.100
[Guest]: I think sending the message, it's incredibly important for organisations to publicise zero

03:49:35.100 --> 03:49:41.060
[Guest]: tolerance because perpetrators will continue if they think they can get away with it.

03:49:41.060 --> 03:49:46.520
[Guest]: And victims or survivors will be less likely to report if they think nothing will happen.

03:49:46.520 --> 03:49:50.820
[Guest]: If they think that by far, by, you know, many, very few victims tell anyone, let alone the

03:49:50.820 --> 03:49:51.820
[Guest]: police.

03:49:51.820 --> 03:49:56.180
[Guest]: Many, and there's a wonderful book by Pulumi Roy Chowdhury called Capable Women, Incapable

03:49:56.180 --> 03:49:57.180
[Guest]: States.

03:49:57.180 --> 03:50:00.500
[Guest]: And she talks about, you know, women may be fearful of going to the police or don't anticipate

03:50:00.500 --> 03:50:02.780
[Guest]: any favours at all from going to the police.

03:50:02.780 --> 03:50:08.820
[Guest]: They, you know, the police may be reluctant, they may not even file the FRI.

03:50:08.820 --> 03:50:13.380
[Guest]: So it's really about building state capacity and feminist activism, the two need to work

03:50:13.380 --> 03:50:19.420
[Guest]: together to change, to build this ideology that people can end impunity for male violence.

03:50:19.420 --> 03:50:23.780
[Amit Varma]: I think feminist activism is a solution to a different problem, the problem of the rule

03:50:23.780 --> 03:50:24.780
[Amit Varma]: of law.

03:50:24.780 --> 03:50:28.340
[Amit Varma]: And I agree that the post Nirbhaya laws haven't really made the streets of Delhi safer.

03:50:28.340 --> 03:50:32.900
[Amit Varma]: But that's an issue, as you put it, of the rule of law and of state capacity, and the

03:50:32.900 --> 03:50:38.260
[Amit Varma]: solutions are deeply complicated and activism, feminist or otherwise, doesn't seem likely

03:50:38.260 --> 03:50:39.260
[Amit Varma]: to change that.

03:50:39.260 --> 03:50:40.740
[Amit Varma]: It's a deep structural problem.

03:50:40.740 --> 03:50:45.460
[Amit Varma]: But what I would be wary of is shooting the messenger, I think, if the state of crime

03:50:45.460 --> 03:50:51.060
[Amit Varma]: against women is bad, it's got to be reported as bad, you know, there's sort of no way around

03:50:51.060 --> 03:50:52.060
[Amit Varma]: that.

03:50:52.060 --> 03:50:53.420
[Amit Varma]: So all these to me are in different domains.

03:50:53.420 --> 03:50:57.420
[Amit Varma]: The journalists are doing what they must, the rule of law is utterly broken.

03:50:57.420 --> 03:51:01.180
[Amit Varma]: And you know, I've just come back from a conference where a bunch of us, where a bunch of people

03:51:01.180 --> 03:51:07.420
[Amit Varma]: rather spoke or spoke, I mean, it almost seems like an unfixable problem on some margins.

03:51:07.420 --> 03:51:10.100
[Amit Varma]: Mayor activism isn't going to solve this particular issue.

03:51:10.100 --> 03:51:16.060
[Amit Varma]: But mayor, but activism, feminist activism, especially can make a huge dent when it comes

03:51:16.060 --> 03:51:18.180
[Amit Varma]: to the mindsets of people.

03:51:18.180 --> 03:51:22.780
[Amit Varma]: You know, I think some social change has to come from within society.

03:51:22.780 --> 03:51:24.300
[Amit Varma]: And then the state has its own function.

03:51:24.300 --> 03:51:29.180
[Amit Varma]: Now, we happen to have a dysfunctional state, and it is the way it is, and that's a much

03:51:29.180 --> 03:51:30.180
[Amit Varma]: deeper problem.

03:51:30.180 --> 03:51:36.380
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, I think, I do not know, and I'll be open and honest about this, I do not

03:51:36.380 --> 03:51:38.740
[Guest]: know what would make Delhi safer.

03:51:38.740 --> 03:51:39.740
[Guest]: Right.

03:51:39.740 --> 03:51:43.820
[Guest]: But I, I remain sceptical.

03:51:43.820 --> 03:51:51.340
[Guest]: And I want to say that I don't know if just repeating that sexual assaults happen, necessarily

03:51:51.340 --> 03:51:57.940
[Guest]: cultivates activism in a context of relatively low rates of female employment, where women

03:51:57.940 --> 03:52:01.780
[Guest]: might not be gathering together, because instead, you might just be cultivating hopelessness,

03:52:01.780 --> 03:52:06.060
[Guest]: learned hopelessness, that all these bad things are happening, and nothing's changing and

03:52:06.060 --> 03:52:07.260
[Guest]: nothing we can do about them.

03:52:07.260 --> 03:52:08.460
[Guest]: So I don't know the solution.

03:52:08.460 --> 03:52:11.140
[Guest]: I'm not saying the media shouldn't report.

03:52:11.140 --> 03:52:18.300
[Guest]: All I'm saying is this deluge, the reality of violence may just, you know, if it's on

03:52:18.300 --> 03:52:22.700
[Guest]: the forefront, if a father is coming to breakfast, and he's reading the newspaper, and he reads

03:52:22.700 --> 03:52:26.460
[Guest]: about the gang rape, and then his daughter asks if she can have a sleepover at a friend's

03:52:26.460 --> 03:52:28.980
[Guest]: house, he may say no.

03:52:28.980 --> 03:52:32.140
[Guest]: Now, so that's the only thing I'm trying to highlight.

03:52:32.140 --> 03:52:34.020
[Guest]: I don't have any, I don't have the solution.

03:52:34.020 --> 03:52:35.020
[Guest]: I don't know.

03:52:35.020 --> 03:52:38.580
[Guest]: You know, so I don't know what would be the better way of doing everything.

03:52:38.580 --> 03:52:42.940
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, I don't think a journalist's job is to make society feel this way or that

03:52:42.940 --> 03:52:43.940
[Amit Varma]: way.

03:52:43.940 --> 03:52:47.460
[Amit Varma]: A journalist's job is just to report the news as a journalist sees it.

03:52:47.460 --> 03:52:51.980
[Amit Varma]: So the fact of the matter is Delhi is an unsafe place for women.

03:52:51.980 --> 03:52:53.260
[Amit Varma]: I mean, it is what it is.

03:52:53.260 --> 03:52:56.220
[Amit Varma]: So but I think we're both in agreement about that.

03:52:56.220 --> 03:52:59.460
[Amit Varma]: This is just a deeply sort of complicated problem.

03:52:59.460 --> 03:53:00.460
[Amit Varma]: Great.

03:53:00.460 --> 03:53:03.900
[Amit Varma]: So you've kind of given me so much of your time, and I'm deeply grateful for that.

03:53:03.900 --> 03:53:07.880
[Amit Varma]: And I will, of course, be listening to the episode for once at half speed so I can kind

03:53:07.880 --> 03:53:13.920
[Amit Varma]: of absorb all the useful lessons you've shared with me and all my listeners.

03:53:13.920 --> 03:53:18.980
[Amit Varma]: Some closing questions, one, in the course of all the work that you've done, and this

03:53:18.980 --> 03:53:25.140
[Amit Varma]: is particularly a relevant question, because you came into this work questioning your priors,

03:53:25.140 --> 03:53:27.140
[Amit Varma]: happy to rock your priors, as it were.

03:53:27.140 --> 03:53:32.140
[Amit Varma]: So in the course of all your work, what is the biggest thing that you learned that really

03:53:32.140 --> 03:53:37.140
[Unknown]: surprised you?

03:53:37.140 --> 03:53:43.140
[Unknown]: I think the importance of culture, the importance of ideology and how that shapes what we do.

03:53:43.140 --> 03:53:48.460
[Guest]: And I underestimated that, I underestimated the importance of religion.

03:53:48.460 --> 03:53:54.100
[Guest]: And as I've written about before, you know, me coming in with my sort of atheist, secular,

03:53:54.100 --> 03:54:02.180
[Guest]: empiricist mindset, I didn't appreciate how much people might be fearful of eternal damnation,

03:54:02.180 --> 03:54:07.260
[Guest]: how much people might buy into certain ideologies, and how that might shape and how those beliefs

03:54:07.260 --> 03:54:10.780
[Guest]: and desires shape how they respond to economic opportunities.

03:54:10.780 --> 03:54:13.220
[Guest]: And that's really key to the great gender divergence.

03:54:13.220 --> 03:54:21.020
[Amit Varma]: Okay, so I understand why religion can be a negative force in terms of codifying social

03:54:21.020 --> 03:54:24.620
[Amit Varma]: norms that keep women back.

03:54:24.620 --> 03:54:28.700
[Amit Varma]: But fear of eternal damnation, I'm not so sure.

03:54:28.700 --> 03:54:32.660
[Amit Varma]: I mean, the economist Stephen Landsberg had a great book called Big Questions.

03:54:32.660 --> 03:54:38.460
[Amit Varma]: And one of the questions in that, which was quite provocative, but which I think and you

03:54:38.460 --> 03:54:42.140
[Amit Varma]: know, fans of Landsberg will forgive me if I don't articulate it properly, because I

03:54:42.140 --> 03:54:46.340
[Amit Varma]: don't remember the exact sort of terms in which he put it.

03:54:46.340 --> 03:54:50.060
[Amit Varma]: But his point was no one believes in God, that people say they believe in God, but when

03:54:50.060 --> 03:54:54.060
[Amit Varma]: push comes to shove, their revealed preferences will show that they don't really believe in

03:54:54.060 --> 03:54:55.060
[Amit Varma]: God.

03:54:55.060 --> 03:54:59.140
[Amit Varma]: So my belief in that sense from what I see, and I'm of course an atheist, but from what

03:54:59.140 --> 03:55:03.500
[Amit Varma]: I see of religious people around me, is that they don't really believe either, that they

03:55:03.500 --> 03:55:08.060
[Amit Varma]: might follow certain customs and social mores and so on and so forth.

03:55:08.060 --> 03:55:12.300
[Amit Varma]: But you know, ultimately, if they are in an incredibly sort of drastic spot, they won't

03:55:12.300 --> 03:55:16.580
[Amit Varma]: be praying to God, they'll be going to a doctor or trying to figure out another way to solve

03:55:16.580 --> 03:55:18.460
[Amit Varma]: whatever other problem they have.

03:55:18.460 --> 03:55:20.380
[Amit Varma]: And they have blind faith in other domains.

03:55:20.380 --> 03:55:24.060
[Amit Varma]: For example, some people believe in homeopathy and try to cure themselves with it, which

03:55:24.060 --> 03:55:28.020
[Amit Varma]: is a different kind of blind faith and a different kind of false God.

03:55:28.020 --> 03:55:33.780
[Amit Varma]: But the toxic thing that religion does is it codifies many of these backward values.

03:55:33.780 --> 03:55:34.780
[Amit Varma]: And that's a problem.

03:55:34.780 --> 03:55:36.300
[Amit Varma]: And that's why it's a danger.

03:55:36.300 --> 03:55:39.500
[Amit Varma]: But does fear of eternal damnation really come into it?

03:55:39.500 --> 03:55:40.500
[Guest]: I mean,

03:55:40.500 --> 03:55:41.500
[Guest]: Yeah, I believe that it does.

03:55:41.500 --> 03:55:45.380
[Guest]: So there's a nice book called Honour and Shame in Iraq.

03:55:45.380 --> 03:55:53.580
[Guest]: And it's about how women might acquiesce to their husband's demands, and try to please

03:55:53.580 --> 03:55:57.620
[Guest]: them and do everything, you know, even if their husbands are incredibly abusive, even

03:55:57.620 --> 03:56:04.060
[Guest]: if their husbands are violent, even if they force sex or rape their wives, you know, many

03:56:04.060 --> 03:56:08.460
[Guest]: of these women genuinely believe, according to this excellent ethnography, that, you know,

03:56:08.460 --> 03:56:12.420
[Guest]: if they don't have sex with their husbands, then they will be punished by angels that,

03:56:12.420 --> 03:56:13.420
[Guest]: you know, they will have.

03:56:13.420 --> 03:56:17.860
[Guest]: And they're even in Christianity, also in early Christianity, there were these tours

03:56:17.860 --> 03:56:22.620
[Guest]: of hell where people talked about the torment, the way that sinners would be tormented in

03:56:22.620 --> 03:56:23.620
[Guest]: the afterlife.

03:56:23.620 --> 03:56:28.380
[Guest]: So I think, and if you look at data, there's a great variety, there's, I mean, there's

03:56:28.380 --> 03:56:32.420
[Guest]: far stronger belief in eternal damnation in Egypt, for example, people are more likely

03:56:32.420 --> 03:56:35.860
[Guest]: to believe in hell, actually, than God, there's much stronger belief in hell.

03:56:35.860 --> 03:56:40.660
[Guest]: The belief that if you do wrong, then that will affect what happens to you in the afterlife,

03:56:40.660 --> 03:56:42.660
[Guest]: I think is quite powerful.

03:56:42.660 --> 03:56:46.300
[Guest]: And that's one of the, and I think, so one, I think is the fear of hell, that you're doing

03:56:46.300 --> 03:56:48.820
[Guest]: something terrible, and there will be condemnation.

03:56:48.820 --> 03:56:53.580
[Guest]: And we see that across the world, not just in Europe, not just in Southern Mesopotamia,

03:56:53.580 --> 03:56:59.660
[Guest]: also in Chinese literature, how disobedient women were upset in cosmic harmony, and then

03:56:59.660 --> 03:57:02.260
[Guest]: they were challenged and chastised.

03:57:02.260 --> 03:57:04.740
[Guest]: And then we have also see the element of social policing, right?

03:57:04.740 --> 03:57:08.180
[Guest]: So the social policing, the institutions are important.

03:57:08.180 --> 03:57:17.100
[Guest]: The other way in which I think religion can be a major blockage and bottleneck to critical

03:57:17.100 --> 03:57:22.940
[Guest]: debate if people, because religion can be elevated to a specific plane that people want

03:57:22.940 --> 03:57:27.300
[Guest]: to be a good person, they want to be the good and dutiful person, especially the ideologies

03:57:27.300 --> 03:57:31.540
[Guest]: of shame and stigma around female chastity and virginity.

03:57:31.540 --> 03:57:38.020
[Guest]: The idea that these are the pure, these are the ideals that which we must strive for.

03:57:38.020 --> 03:57:43.100
[Guest]: I think ethnographies do point to that being incredibly important and incredibly powerful

03:57:43.100 --> 03:57:44.100
[Guest]: for us.

03:57:44.100 --> 03:57:47.940
[Guest]: I stay, I strive strongly on, and I would say, let me caveat it, it's not just religion

03:57:47.940 --> 03:57:56.300
[Guest]: per se, but it's this male dominated religions that have been incredibly patriarchal.

03:57:56.300 --> 03:58:00.140
[Amit Varma]: I would imagine that women who are in that situation and who do whatever their husband

03:58:00.140 --> 03:58:03.460
[Amit Varma]: wants to do it because they feel they just don't have a choice, they're just trapped

03:58:03.460 --> 03:58:04.860
[Amit Varma]: in a terrible situation.

03:58:04.860 --> 03:58:07.260
[Amit Varma]: But yeah, I mean, and that could be one way of rationalising it.

03:58:07.260 --> 03:58:10.620
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, I do have a bit of a rational bias.

03:58:10.620 --> 03:58:12.500
[Amit Varma]: So maybe I am wrong here.

03:58:12.500 --> 03:58:16.860
[Amit Varma]: And maybe people do fear literal eternal damnation, who is to say.

03:58:16.860 --> 03:58:24.780
[Amit Varma]: My next closing question is, what broad consensus narrative do you disagree with or is wrong?

03:58:24.780 --> 03:58:31.340
[Amit Varma]: Like, what broad conventional belief is there, which you feel is wrong?

03:58:31.340 --> 03:58:34.500
[Guest]: Okay, how controversial do I want to be on your podcast?

03:58:34.500 --> 03:58:36.020
[Amit Varma]: I just want you to be honest.

03:58:36.020 --> 03:58:37.020
[Amit Varma]: Don't worry.

03:58:37.020 --> 03:58:39.820
[Unknown]: The, you know, the toxic internet trolls haven't gotten so far.

03:58:39.820 --> 03:58:41.620
[Amit Varma]: Will you protect me from the trolls?

03:58:41.620 --> 03:58:42.620
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely.

03:58:42.620 --> 03:58:44.380
[Amit Varma]: Though you don't need protection, but I will protect you.

03:58:44.380 --> 03:58:46.020
[Amit Varma]: You promise you'll protect me on this one?

03:58:46.020 --> 03:58:47.020
[Amit Varma]: You don't need protection.

03:58:47.020 --> 03:58:50.580
[Amit Varma]: I want you to say you'll protect me.

03:58:50.580 --> 03:58:52.060
[Amit Varma]: How can I protect you from the trolls?

03:58:52.060 --> 03:58:54.060
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I can take your phone away.

03:58:54.060 --> 03:58:55.060
[Unknown]: Sure.

03:58:55.060 --> 03:58:56.780
[Guest]: Okay, listen.

03:58:56.780 --> 03:59:02.700
[Guest]: So I have argued that the major drivers of gender equality are job creating growth and

03:59:02.700 --> 03:59:05.020
[Guest]: feminist activism.

03:59:05.020 --> 03:59:13.540
[Guest]: Some people push for an alternative and we see social policing of discourse, that it

03:59:13.540 --> 03:59:17.140
[Guest]: matters what we say, like how we refer to each other people.

03:59:17.140 --> 03:59:21.340
[Guest]: So this might be referred to in pejorative terms as woke.

03:59:21.340 --> 03:59:27.300
[Guest]: So using the right inclusive terminology, and I think the importance of discourse there

03:59:27.300 --> 03:59:30.260
[Guest]: is overrated.

03:59:30.260 --> 03:59:34.860
[Guest]: And we actually don't have strong empirical evidence to say that if people use slightly

03:59:34.860 --> 03:59:38.980
[Guest]: different terminology, then we would see greater gender equality.

03:59:38.980 --> 03:59:42.980
[Guest]: So that I think would be, and I think it's mainly that we see that we see that in.

03:59:42.980 --> 03:59:48.380
[Guest]: So we see a lot of self righteous social policing in the USA, for example.

03:59:48.380 --> 03:59:51.260
[Guest]: These people absolutely committed to equality.

03:59:51.260 --> 03:59:56.540
[Guest]: They believe, many of them believe the best way to do that is by changing discourse, etc.

03:59:56.540 --> 03:59:58.340
[Guest]: And I don't think that's empirically supported.

03:59:58.340 --> 04:00:02.660
[Guest]: So I think that would be the major way in which I, yeah, disagree with something that's

04:00:02.660 --> 04:00:04.580
[Guest]: quite popular in that environment.

04:00:04.580 --> 04:00:05.580
[Amit Varma]: Fair enough.

04:00:05.580 --> 04:00:07.180
[Amit Varma]: And I think I agree with you.

04:00:07.180 --> 04:00:08.180
[Amit Varma]: So my last question.

04:00:08.180 --> 04:00:10.420
[Unknown]: Will you protect me if people attack me on that point?

04:00:10.420 --> 04:00:11.540
[Amit Varma]: Why do you need protection?

04:00:11.540 --> 04:00:13.540
[Amit Varma]: This is such a non feminist thing to say.

04:00:13.540 --> 04:00:14.540
[Unknown]: Come on.

04:00:14.540 --> 04:00:18.020
[Unknown]: Right, I'm asking for the Rakhi thread, right, right, right.

04:00:18.020 --> 04:00:21.540
[Amit Varma]: Rakhi, you should be promising to protect me if I get into trouble because of what you

04:00:21.540 --> 04:00:22.540
[Amit Varma]: said.

04:00:22.540 --> 04:00:23.540
[Amit Varma]: Like, come on.

04:00:23.540 --> 04:00:28.940
[Amit Varma]: I didn't expect this from you, it's very sad, very sad.

04:00:28.940 --> 04:00:30.260
[Amit Varma]: So all right.

04:00:30.260 --> 04:00:34.380
[Amit Varma]: So yeah, so final question, and you probably would expect this by now.

04:00:34.380 --> 04:00:38.960
[Amit Varma]: But you know, one of the things that sort of awes me when I read your work, and something

04:00:38.960 --> 04:00:44.460
[Amit Varma]: that I deeply love, is how many rabbit holes you provide to all of us to go down on in

04:00:44.460 --> 04:00:48.820
[Amit Varma]: terms of all the links, all the books, every day you're on Twitter posting about three

04:00:48.820 --> 04:00:52.440
[Amit Varma]: or four or eight or nine different books, depending on what the day is.

04:00:52.440 --> 04:00:55.660
[Amit Varma]: And that's fantastic, because I've picked up a whole bunch of books just reading about

04:00:55.660 --> 04:00:59.540
[Amit Varma]: it on your Twitter thread, and it's been an education.

04:00:59.540 --> 04:01:04.420
[Amit Varma]: So what are the books that have meant the most to you?

04:01:04.420 --> 04:01:08.740
[Amit Varma]: And you know, I asked this question about films, music, so if you want to talk about

04:01:08.740 --> 04:01:12.060
[Amit Varma]: that as well, but what would you take with you to a desert island?

04:01:12.060 --> 04:01:15.260
[Amit Varma]: What is, you know, really, really dear to you, and it doesn't even have to be something

04:01:15.260 --> 04:01:17.780
[Amit Varma]: to do with your work or your research or whatever.

04:01:17.780 --> 04:01:21.460
[Amit Varma]: But whatever means the most to you and that you absolutely love.

04:01:21.460 --> 04:01:24.340
[Unknown]: I would take to a desert island would be a motorboat.

04:01:24.340 --> 04:01:25.340
[Unknown]: What?

04:01:25.340 --> 04:01:29.380
[Amit Varma]: I asked you to recommend books for my readers.

04:01:29.380 --> 04:01:32.620
[Amit Varma]: And you've just said what I will take to a desert island will be a motorboat.

04:01:32.620 --> 04:01:33.620
[Unknown]: What is this?

04:01:33.620 --> 04:01:36.620
[Unknown]: I don't want to be trapped on a desert island where I'll die.

04:01:36.620 --> 04:01:37.620
[Unknown]: So I can escape.

04:01:37.620 --> 04:01:47.540
[Unknown]: A fully fuelled motorboat, I don't want to be trapped on your desert island.

04:01:47.540 --> 04:01:48.540
[Unknown]: I'm gonna die.

04:01:48.540 --> 04:01:49.940
[Amit Varma]: I don't want to die.

04:01:49.940 --> 04:01:52.820
[Amit Varma]: And then Component, what's the last good book you read?

04:01:52.820 --> 04:01:53.820
[Amit Varma]: Fine.

04:01:53.820 --> 04:01:54.820
[Guest]: Give us something.

04:01:54.820 --> 04:01:55.820
[Guest]: Throw us a straw.

04:01:55.820 --> 04:02:00.940
[Guest]: The last excellent book I read, I really liked Shrayana's book, Desperately Seeking Shahrukh.

04:02:00.940 --> 04:02:03.380
[Guest]: I think it's fantastic.

04:02:03.380 --> 04:02:04.380
[Guest]: Yeah.

04:02:04.380 --> 04:02:10.220
[Guest]: I think that adds another element that we haven't really discussed is about love and

04:02:10.220 --> 04:02:15.660
[Guest]: how women's desire for love, and especially from one person, especially in places where

04:02:15.660 --> 04:02:19.660
[Guest]: monogamous marriage is highly valorised, as we discussed earlier, can trap them in abusive

04:02:19.660 --> 04:02:23.700
[Guest]: relationships because they're constantly trying to please that person and cultivate their

04:02:23.700 --> 04:02:24.940
[Guest]: favours.

04:02:24.940 --> 04:02:27.980
[Guest]: And this goes back to our earlier conversation.

04:02:27.980 --> 04:02:35.980
[Guest]: If the desire for love and the desire to be loved is the primary thing and there are fewer

04:02:35.980 --> 04:02:40.860
[Guest]: alternative ways in which women can flourish and be rewarded and respected, then they can

04:02:40.860 --> 04:02:43.220
[Guest]: be trapped in very abusive relationships.

04:02:43.220 --> 04:02:48.980
[Guest]: So love has the potential to trap women in patriarchal relationships.

04:02:48.980 --> 04:02:56.860
[Guest]: And I think Shrayana's book is so fantastic because it explores Indian gender relations

04:02:56.860 --> 04:03:03.780
[Guest]: through another lens, and it's saying, you know, all these women navigating elements

04:03:03.780 --> 04:03:12.180
[Guest]: of patriarchy, they see in Shahrukh Khan this idea of this gentle, nurturing, appreciating,

04:03:12.180 --> 04:03:15.900
[Guest]: affectionate, care, compassion, listening to women.

04:03:15.900 --> 04:03:22.100
[Guest]: And I think that's such an amazing way of understanding gender relations, then that

04:03:22.100 --> 04:03:25.140
[Guest]: that's what people might aspire for, but not getting.

04:03:25.140 --> 04:03:30.500
[Guest]: And I think that's a fantastic way of understanding gender relations, distinguishing between our

04:03:30.500 --> 04:03:32.820
[Guest]: internalised ideologies, our norm perceptions.

04:03:32.820 --> 04:03:35.500
[Guest]: And the idea is that many women would like to be appreciated.

04:03:35.500 --> 04:03:37.820
[Guest]: They would like all their care labour.

04:03:37.820 --> 04:03:42.900
[Guest]: So there's an interesting excerpt in that book where they talk about, in one of Shahrukh's

04:03:42.900 --> 04:03:45.580
[Guest]: films, where he sings in appreciation of the tiffin.

04:03:45.580 --> 04:03:49.820
[Guest]: He sings in appreciation of his wife's care work, and that so often across the world,

04:03:49.820 --> 04:03:53.980
[Guest]: and this is not unique to India, women's care work is neglected and devalued.

04:03:53.980 --> 04:03:56.020
[Guest]: And here he appreciates her labour.

04:03:56.020 --> 04:04:02.180
[Guest]: And one woman talks about how nice and how wonderful that might be, just to be appreciated.

04:04:02.180 --> 04:04:05.020
[Guest]: And so, yeah, I would, I'd really recommend Shrayana's book.

04:04:05.020 --> 04:04:06.020
[Guest]: It's really wonderful.

04:04:06.020 --> 04:04:07.020
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

04:04:07.020 --> 04:04:10.940
[Amit Varma]: And she's, my most downloaded episode, in fact, is with Shrayana, it's called The Loneliness

04:04:10.940 --> 04:04:11.940
[Amit Varma]: of the Indian Women.

04:04:11.940 --> 04:04:13.440
[Amit Varma]: We'll link it from the show notes.

04:04:13.440 --> 04:04:18.540
[Amit Varma]: And since you mentioned the element of love, sort of a final, final question for you, which

04:04:18.540 --> 04:04:24.620
[Amit Varma]: is, while what you're studying is really social norms, social currents, so on and so forth,

04:04:24.620 --> 04:04:26.500
[Amit Varma]: and on the surface, it can seem dry.

04:04:26.500 --> 04:04:31.380
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, you've spent a lot of time talking to people, living with people,

04:04:31.380 --> 04:04:38.300
[Amit Varma]: being a witness to their experiences, being a confidant for, you know, whatever is happening

04:04:38.300 --> 04:04:39.660
[Amit Varma]: in their lives.

04:04:39.660 --> 04:04:44.260
[Amit Varma]: And you've had sort of a unique glimpse of their interior lives as well, and sort of

04:04:44.260 --> 04:04:45.260
[Amit Varma]: their lives as people.

04:04:45.260 --> 04:04:51.420
[Amit Varma]: And at some level, does it also make a part of your research, not just the intellectual

04:04:51.420 --> 04:04:55.780
[Amit Varma]: work that you put into it, but also a certain emotional work?

04:04:55.780 --> 04:04:59.660
[Amit Varma]: You know, how do you sort of then kind of navigate that?

04:04:59.660 --> 04:05:03.860
[Amit Varma]: Because you go in with these people as your subjects, in a sense, and they've been kind

04:05:03.860 --> 04:05:05.740
[Amit Varma]: enough to offer you the friendship.

04:05:05.740 --> 04:05:08.820
[Amit Varma]: But as you come out, it's obviously more than that.

04:05:08.820 --> 04:05:13.660
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about that aspect of things, that human aspect of connecting.

04:05:13.660 --> 04:05:19.740
[Unknown]: Yeah, that's such a great question, because in the process of getting to know people,

04:05:19.740 --> 04:05:24.980
[Guest]: in the process of understanding their stories, their aspirations, their struggles, we do

04:05:24.980 --> 04:05:28.500
[Guest]: form these wonderful friendships.

04:05:28.500 --> 04:05:35.820
[Guest]: You know, maybe this will sound insincere and fake, but I really do connect.

04:05:35.820 --> 04:05:41.540
[Guest]: You know, I have such strong emotional ties, really great bonds of friendship with so many

04:05:41.540 --> 04:05:46.260
[Guest]: people who've looked after me, who've welcomed me into their homes.

04:05:46.260 --> 04:05:50.300
[Guest]: And I stay in touch with so many of them, whether it's through WhatsApp or Instagram.

04:05:50.300 --> 04:05:55.700
[Guest]: You know, the Bemba mother who I stayed with, she often chats with me on Facebook or Instagram

04:05:55.700 --> 04:05:59.580
[Guest]: in Bemba, of course, whereas Moroccan women follow me on Instagram.

04:05:59.580 --> 04:06:03.260
[Guest]: And it's fun because on Instagram, they can see me traveling through each different country.

04:06:03.260 --> 04:06:08.020
[Guest]: So the Moroccan men and women see that I go to Italy and interview people there, etc.

04:06:08.020 --> 04:06:14.060
[Guest]: So they get to follow my travels, and that's a really nice way that I'm able to stay in

04:06:14.060 --> 04:06:21.540
[Guest]: touch with these people that are incredibly dear to my heart, really and truly.

04:06:21.540 --> 04:06:26.740
[Guest]: I have, you know, friendships all over the world that are incredibly important to me.

04:06:26.740 --> 04:06:33.500
[Guest]: And I just really, I'm so grateful for learning about their lives, understanding each individual

04:06:33.500 --> 04:06:38.220
[Guest]: struggle, their story, their perspectives, their individuality, and that goes back to

04:06:38.220 --> 04:06:41.340
[Guest]: your question on depth and breadth.

04:06:41.340 --> 04:06:45.100
[Guest]: And I think that, yeah, I really appreciate it.

04:06:45.100 --> 04:06:48.940
[Guest]: I really, really enjoy what I do.

04:06:48.940 --> 04:06:52.300
[Amit Varma]: That's I think, a wonderful note to end on, because even if the world doesn't change,

04:06:52.300 --> 04:06:53.780
[Amit Varma]: you'll always have that.

